<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUTO-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW BARRING INSURERS' TIPS ON CAR SHOPS IS TOSSED OUT
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a decision that could affect all drivers in New
York state, a federal judge in Manhattan ruled this week that state
regulators could not prevent two insurance companies from
recommending specific auto repair shops to their policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, filed Friday in U.S. District Court, involves a
state law prohibiting insurance companies from providing lists of
repair shops unless customers specifically ask for a
recommendation. In his decision, issued Thursday, Judge Richard
Casey found that the law violated the companies' constitutional
right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Although Casey's decision was written to apply to the two
companies that had sued the state, Allstate and Geico, an industry
trade group said the decision would probably apply to all insurers
that write policies in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision should be interpreted broadly, not just for
Allstate and Geico,'' said Robert P. Hartwig, chief economist for
the Insurance Information Institute, the industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwig said insurers' repair policies were basically the same.
He said the companies wanted to be able to recommend repair shops
that provided cheap and reliable service to minimize their costs.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer who represented the State Insurance Department in the
case said he had not had time to review the judge's ruling and
could not say whether the state would appeal, or whether the ruling
would affect other insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibiting referrals, enacted in 1974, was intended to
protect consumers' ability to choose their own repair shop. It was
amended in 1983 to allow insurance companies to recommend auto
glass repair shops, although the change was not extended to general
repairs. The judge said the Insurance Department approved the 1983
amendment in expectation that it would result in lower claim costs
and premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The state law also prohibits insurance companies from requiring
policyholders to use certain shops. Geico and Allstate did not
challenge that part of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate writes the most auto insurance policies in New York
state, insuring 1.6 million cars, or 20 percent of the market,
according to the Insurance Department. Geico insures about 7
percent of the market, or 560,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict began in 1992, after state regulators threatened to
fine Allstate for posting a sign at offices informing customers:
``If you have no shop preference, your adjuster is prepared to
recommend several conveniently located repair shops.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators said the sign, erected as part of a company program
to evaluate approved repair shops, violated the prohibition on
recommending shops to policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   But Casey found that policyholders were not denied the ability
to select their own repair shops. He also said the state law
deprived customers of important information by barring insurance
companies from telling their customers which shops had a proven
track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the state does have a legitimate interest in
protecting consumers,'' he wrote, ``the court does not accept the
notion that consumers' lack of intelligence requires the state to
deprive them of options or limit their choices to those which the
state thinks are acceptable. The court finds that the programs
offered to Allstate's and Geico's insureds afford them additional
opportunities, protection and truthful information. The speech at
issue is not deceptive, misleading or illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce E. Clark, a lawyer for Allstate, said the company was
``gratified'' by the decision, but he declined to comment further
until he had reviewed the ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
