<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ABC-BLACKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES REFUSE TO GUARANTEE ABC ON CABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Executives of Time Warner and ABC told City Council
members Friday that they could not guarantee that ABC programming
would not be disrupted again as they proceed with bitter contract
negotiations in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Rosenblum, president of Time Warner Cable of New York
City, and Thomas P. Kane, president of WABC, ABC's New York
station, had been called before the new Select Committee on Media
Services and Consumer Rights by Council Speaker Peter F. Vallone
under threat of subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   And while the media executives appeared contrite, acknowledging
that the blackout of ABC on Monday and Tuesday had provoked
widespread anger among their viewers and subscribers, both balked
at repeated attempts by Vallone to obtain their assurances that it
would not be repeated by either company in an effort to gain
leverage in their contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious to me that eight million New Yorkers are not
party to this dispute, and they have a right to watch their
televisions,'' Vallone said. ``Is it asking so much to just shake
hands and get this over with?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult to do that,'' responded Rosenblum, whose
company the Federal Communications Commission's Cable Bureau found
at fault in the blackout and said might face fines. He said legal
questions hanging over the company's negotiations with ABC and its
parent, the Disney Co., prevented him from offering any guarantees.
But he added that he found another service interruption ``hard to
fathom.''
</P>
<P>
   Kane, referring to the complex negotiations taking place,
responded to Vallone's request of a public handshake by the two
sides by saying, ``We'd need 100 people on each side of the table
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the outcry after the blackout has encouraged both sides
to resolve their differences quickly, he said, ``I can offer no
guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the corporate standoff is an attempt by ABC and
Disney to obtain commitments from Time Warner of more widespread
and profitable distribution of Disney programming on Time Warner
Cable. For its part, Time Warner is pressuring Disney to revise its
contractual agreements, made under 1992 federal guidelines, to
arrangements that would require the cable operator to provide
uninterrupted ABC programming but would weaken Disney's hand in
other negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblum testified Friday that Time Warner had decided to cut
off the ABC signal in the New York area and in six other broadcast
markets only after Disney had repeatedly insisted on short-term,
interim operating agreements, forcing Time Warner, under federal
law, to repeatedly warn its viewers that ABC service might be
permanently dropped.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, ABC complained that Time Warner launched a
surprise attack by cutting its signal during ``sweeps,'' a ratings
period of special importance to advertisers and broadcasters. The
network's charge was upheld by the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   When Time Warner restored ABC's signal on Tuesday, the two
companies agreed to resume contract negotiations, which had halted,
until at least July 15 if the issue is not resolved sooner. The
public protest provoked by the blackout centered on what many
called the near monopolistic powers of the conglomerates, and could
prove most damaging to Time Warner because its pending merger with
America Online requires federal approval.
</P>
<P>
   To placate critics and compensate its subscribers, Time Warner
said on Thursday that each of its affected customers would receive
a rebate for two days of basic cable service and 30 days of an
additional premium cable channel free. Rosenblum told the Council
committee that the rebate would be worth about $1, based on Time
Warner's basic service cost of $15 a month, and the 30 days of
service with a free premium channel would be worth an average of
$13.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
