<SLUG> BC-GM-FAIRFAX-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MOTORS TO UPDATE FAIRFAX PLANT, CHANGE PRODUCT LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER and STEVE NICELY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ General Motors Corp.
announced Friday that it would build a new generation of passenger
cars at its Fairfax plant beginning in 2003, providing job security
to 3,500 area GM employees for the foreseeable future.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plant manager Paul Marr, along with leaders of United Auto
Workers Local 31, made the announcement to the Fairfax workers at a
quarterly meeting held in a plant auditorium, said Tara
Condon-Tullier, a plant spokeswoman. The meeting also was broadcast
via closed-circuit television to the production floor.
</P>
<P>
   GM plans to invest more than $500 million in the facility to
build cars under the Epsilon platform, the company's worldwide
building process for its next generation of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Although GM declined to identify which models would be built at
Fairfax, union officials said the Chevrolet Malibu and Pontiac
Grand Am were the vehicles assigned to the plant. Those models
would replace the Pontiac Grand Prix and the Oldsmobile Intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   GM is the second automaker in recent years to make a sizable
reinvestment in an area plant. Ford Motor Co. has been retooling
and expanding its Claycomo facility for nearly two years to prepare
to launch a new compact sport utility vehicle later this month.
Ford reportedly spent $750 million to adapt the plant.
</P>
<P>
   GM's announcement Friday pleased union officials at Fairfax,
particularly after a bill in the Kansas Legislature to give GM tax
relief for the Epsilon project failed to gain the support of key
area legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful we've been approved for the new product,'' said
Jim Russell, president of UAW Local 31. ``It's good for our
membership, and it ensures that our younger people will have a
future here.''
</P>
<P>
   Both GM and the UAW credited the plant's employees for the
automaker's decision to bring the new product line to Fairfax
despite the lack of a tax-incentive package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got the Epsilon because of a great work force and
good labor-management relations,'' Russell said. ``I know it wasn't
because of the Unified Government (of Wyandotte County and Kansas
City, Kan). They flat knocked us down.''
</P>
<P>
   GM's Condon-Tullier agreed. ``The significant factors were the
(plant's) excellent work force, safety record and the quality,''
she said. ``But the tax climate will weigh heavily on future
program allocations and investment decisions at Fairfax.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite GM's concerns about the tax climate, the company's
decision was welcome news in Wyandotte County, where the plant is
the largest taxpayer. GM currently pays about $10 million a year in
property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's excellent news,'' said Dan Schenkein, president of the
Kansas City, Kan., Area Chamber of Commerce. ``It's a testament to
this production facility's...ability to produce a quality
product.''
</P>
<P>
   Unified Government Mayor Carol Marinovich said General Motors
was a major corporate citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Epsilon project will provide stability to this business
and the jobs it provides,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   GM announced its plans for the Fairfax plant before it concluded
negotiations for tax breaks with the Unified Government, which
surprised some officials.
</P>
<P>
   GM's push for a bill granting permanent tax abatement on tools
and dies did not pass the Legislature, partly because it lacked
solid support among lawmakers from Wyandotte County and their
constituents. The Fairfax plant had received total property tax
breaks on its current plant for 10 years and had resumed normal
payments three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But GM did not strike out completely during the recently
completed legislative session. A bill passed exempting GM from
sales taxes on new machinery and equipment and the cost of
installing it. Another bill also makes the plant eligible for $1.5
million in training aid for its work force.
</P>
<P>
   The Unified Government also has the authority to grant property
tax breaks of as much as 100 percent for 10 years. It routinely
grants breaks equal to 50 percent of property taxes for 10 years
for major plant expansions and new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Unified Government Administrator Dennis Hays said there had been
no discussions about taxes with GM since the Legislature adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to work with GM with all licenses and permits
for them to move forward,'' Hays said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   GM plans to continue building the Pontiac Grand Prix at Fairfax
through 2002. Grand Prix assembly then is expected to be
transferred to a GM plant in Canada. The Oldsmobile Intrigue, which
has suffered slow sales after an impressive debut, will be
discontinued sometime in 2003, according to the union's Russell.
</P>
<P>
   GM will begin preparing the Fairfax plant for the Epsilon
platform as early as this summer, when U.S. automakers
traditionally shut down for two weeks, Condon-Tullier said. It is
too early to tell whether unscheduled shutdowns will be necessary
for construction at the facility over the next 2 years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Malibu will move to Fairfax from GM's plant in Oklahoma
City. The Fairfax plant mainly will produce Malibus, but it also
will supplement production of the Grand Ams, which primarily will
be made in Lansing, Mich., according to Russell.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfax plant currently employs about 3,000 hourly workers
on two shifts. Russell said GM is hoping to reduce the hourly work
force to about 2,500 through attrition and retirements over the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
   However, both company and union officials said a third shift
could be added if the new Epsilon cars do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have hopes for a third-shift operation, but that
depends on how well the car does,'' Russell said. ``If there's
strong demand when GM kicks off the Epsilon, naturally they'd look
for a way to meet that demand by adding another shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said a third shift could boost the number of hourly
workers by 700 to 800 people.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Fairfax plant's gaining the Chevrolet Malibu and
losing the Pontiac Grand Prix, one auto analyst called it ``an even
swap.''
</P>
<P>
   Annual production of the Malibu is normally between 200,000 and
250,000 units, said George Magliano, director of automotive
research for the WEFA Group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume numbers are roughly the same. But you can build a
few more units of the Malibu, because it's easier to make than the
Grand Prix,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Malibu has an advantage over both the Grand Prix and the
Grand Am, according to Magliano.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Malibu is a volume-car sold more to consumers than to
rental fleets, unlike the Grand Am,'' he said. ``The Grand Prix has
become an enigma; it's lost some of the positioning in the market
that it used to have. Are you better off having the Malibu instead
of the Grand Prix? You probably are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Malibu generally sells more units than the Grand Prix.
Through April of this year, GM reported Malibu sales of 73,528, an
increase of 10.2 percent over the same time last year. The Grand
Prix has sold 51,793 units through April, a 3 percent gain from
last year. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
