<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEARWASTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECT OF SHIPPING NUCLEAR WASTE VIA I-70 STIRS UP MISSOURI
SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Ashcroft and Gov.
Mel Carnahan, who is running against Ashcroft for the Senate, are
at odds over who is more opposed to having hazardous waste shipped
across Missouri on Interstate 70.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ashcroft voted this week to override President Clinton's veto of
a bill that would have placed a nuclear-waste storage site at Yucca
Mountain, Nev. Waste from temporary storage sites in the East was
to move to Nevada by rail and by truck, with some of it crossing
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The veto stood after a 64-35 override vote fell short, but
Carnahan thinks Ashcroft's support for the Nevada site runs
contrary to statements he made at a Missouri news conference two
weeks ago that waste shouldn't be shipped on Interstate 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to give the appearance he opposes it,'' said Tony
Wyche, communications director of the Carnahan for Senate
committee. ``It's a flip, flop, flip.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft appeared at a news conference in Jefferson City, Mo.,
on April 19 and held up a chunk of broken pavement from I-70 to
demonstrate that shipping nuclear waste on such a deteriorated
highway would be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's remarks that day were not related to the Yucca
Mountain bill but to plans by the Department of Energy to ship a
truckload of spent nuclear fuel from South Carolina to a storage
site in Idaho later this year. He called on the Energy Department
to find another route.
</P>
<P>
   David James, communications director for the Ashcroft 2000
committee, said that the Yucca Mountain bill dealt with storage,
not shipment, and that the senator's support of it did not mean he
was willing to have waste sent across Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Energy decides the shipping routes,'' James
said. ``If Mel Carnahan wants to get this material off the
dilapidated, crowded roadbed of I-70, he needs to call his friend
Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department has determined I-70 would be among routes
used for shipments to Nevada. Carnahan doesn't want the highway
used for any shipments, Wyche said, and has written the Energy
Department to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft wrote a letter to Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on
April 18 to suggest transporting any radioactive waste shipments
through alternative routes in Iowa, which he said experienced four
to five times fewer accidents than I-70 in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Wyche said Carnahan agreed that other routes would be better,
especially because I-70 passes through the major population centers
of St. Louis and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Ozark chapter of the Sierra Club is among environmental
groups strongly opposed to shipping waste across Missouri. The
chapter opposed the Yucca Mountain site partly for that reason and
thinks shipping waste anywhere is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the states are unequipped to deal with high-level
radioactive waste accidents,'' said Ken Midkiff, director of the
Ozark chapter. Nuclear storage plants, not the U.S. government,
should be responsible for safe storage and shipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Midkiff criticized Ashcroft for backing the Yucca Mountain site
while at the same time coming out against shipping waste across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just political hypocrisy _ a finger-in-the-wind
gesture,'' Midkiff said. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
