<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASD DIRECTOR RETIRES AFTER 30 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ After 30 years, Jack
Rosenfield is a citizen again. He has spent three decades, more
than half of it in Kansas City, as a cop on the stock market beat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He retired Friday as vice president and district director for
the National Association of Securities Dealers. His start came May
4, 1970, as an NASD examiner in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD is the industry's self-regulatory arm that polices
brokers and brokerages. It operates under the watch of the federal
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield, 60, recalled on Wednesday that an examination in
1970 meant stopping by with ``a pad, a pencil and a 100-page
questionaire.'' Today, examiners carry laptop computers, tap into
databases and tailor audits to fit each firm's activities.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield has witnessed the creation of the Nasdaq Stock
Market, industry computerization, the advent of online trading and
day trading, a surge of public participation in the stock market
and the seamy side of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a regulator you have to hurt someone for doing wrong,''
Rosenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also was praised by some of the area NASD members whom he
has regulated for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point in time, everybody in town had some contact with
Jack and most of it was good,'' said William H. Coughlin, president
of George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City. ``He's been good for the
business and I think he's been good for Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield helped to bring a delegation of top Japanese
securities dealers to Kansas City in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He unwittingly had laid the groundwork in the late 1970s in New
York. He had been tapped to serve as host to a visiting group of
Japanese dealers and stayed in touch with one of the lower-level
visitors. That official rose through the ranks until becoming
secretary general of Japan's version of the NASD.
</P>
<P>
   When the group toured the U.S. securities industry four years
ago, its top delegates, including the secretary general, started
with a visit to Kansas City and Rosenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield had transferred here in November 1981 to become
director of the NASD's District 4 office. The promotion meant he
was the chief NASD regulator in Missouri, Kansas, Nebraska and
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival closed what had been something of a revolving door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, before he got here, we had maybe four other guys in
a span of a few years,'' said Bob Smart, chairman of the Perkins,
Smart &AMP; Boyd Inc. investment firm in Fairway.
</P>
<P>
   A reorganization in 1991 expanded Rosenfield's District 4
territory to seven states in the Midwest. The district's staff has
grown to 47, from 16 when he arrived in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the industry recognized Rosenfield's 30 years
of service with a good-natured roasting of their retired-that-day
regulator. The send-off by about 150 industry members at the Kansas
City Club also raised nearly $30,000 that will go to charities of
Rosenfield's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get a very warm send-off,'' Smart said early in
the week.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosenfield said the idea of a roast was intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   He is decidely low key. Despite his post and tenure in it,
Rosenfield rarely has appeared in The Kansas City Star. He said
that was by design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the type of person who, in the morning, opens the paper
very slowly lest, on the back page, my name might be there
somewhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had hoped to say a few goodbyes. But Brent Weisenborn,
chairman of Security Investment Co. of Kansas City, organized the
roast to Rosenfield's surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Weisenborn also serves as chairman of the NASD member committee
that hears charges against NASD members in the district. He
credited Rosenfield not only for keeping members in compliance but
also for serving them.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Weisenborn said, Rosenfield began visits with
chief executive officers and compliance officers at NASD member
firms in the district. The group sessions were aimed at preventing
problems rather than issuing sanctions for them after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Weisenborn said other NASD districts have taken up the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield said retirement won't mean ending his long
involvement with the stock market or an exit from Kansas City. He
plans to take a couple of months to rest and update his resume,
then he plans to job hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than photography, my life is the stock market,'' he
said. ``I really don't go anywhere without my Wall Street Journal,
New York Times, CNBC and Bloomberg.'' (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 0010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
