<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LASORDA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA NAMED U.S. OLYMPIC TEAM COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Give Tom Lasorda five minutes and he can motivate
a rock to roll up hill. Give him 25 young players, send him to
another country, and the hope is he can turn that to gold.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, widely recognized as baseball's grandest ambassador,
will step on an international stage of which even he hasn't been
on. The Los Angeles Dodgers senior vice president and Hall of Fame
manager was named manager of the 2000 United States Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was anticipated for the past month, but Lasorda
said that didn't lessen the luster when he found out Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of great thrills in my lifetime, and the 51
years I've been with the Dodgers, but something like this really is
something special to me,'' Lasorda, 72, said at a press conference
behind home plate at Dodger Stadium. ``I stood here in front of
this dugout many, many, many, many times, listening to the national
anthem, seeing the American flag up there and always saying at that
time, `Thank God I was born in the greatest country in the world.'
I would always say that every time I heard the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, to be able to represent our country, I think that's
really special. And let me tell you something. I am really inspired
by this. I want to do everything in my power to make this showing
over in Australia a great one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda's coaching staff could be named at a later date. The
members of Team USA won't be selected until August. Team USA will
compete in the Olympics in Sydney, Australia, Sept. 17-27. Team USA
will train in Brisbane, Australia, Sept. 2-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to represent our country, `Wow,'`' Lasorda said.
``I hope and pray everything will turn out right. I'm excited about
it. I want to get back in that uniform one more time, and, man, it
would be great to bring that gold medal back to the United States,
where it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Having accomplished everything else in his managing career,
including leading the Dodgers to two World Series titles, Lasorda
made it known he wanted to lead Team USA when the possibility was
first mentioned in March.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda was chosen ahead of Jim Lefebvre and Terry Collins by a
19-member panel of consisting of people from Major League Baseball
and USA Baseball. Lasorda was clearly the front-runner throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years and years and years I've known how important Tommy's
been to Major League Baseball in the United States,'' said Dodgers
president and chief operating officer Bob Graziano. ``But it wasn't
until I was walking through the streets of Seoul (Korea), Nagoya
(Japan) and Tokyo (Japan), and people of all different backgrounds
were walking up to Tommy and talking about baseball, that I
realized how much Tommy meant to baseball all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Darren Dreifort is the only member of the Dodgers
to play in the Olympics, competing in Barcelona, Spain, in 1992. He
said the selection of Lasorda is perfect. The Americans are yet to
win the gold medal since baseball was sanctioned for the 1992
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have probably the greatest ambassador to the game of
baseball there is, representing America's team, and that's not the
Atlanta Braves,''Dreifort said. ``They picked the best guy to send
over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Former USC and Olympic coach Rod Dedeaux presented Lasorda with
the Team USA cap he wore while coaching the Team USA in 1984 - when
baseball was a demonstration sport at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But before accepting the post, Lasorda spoke with Graziano,
general manager Kevin Malone and Dodgers managing general partner,
chairman and CEO Bob Daly about it since it will call for him to
leave his position for a few months. Nobody had a problem with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy Lasorda is one of the most accomplished managers in
baseball history and we are very fortunate to have him managing the
2000 Olympic Baseball Team,'' said Bob Watson, co-chairman of the
steering committee for USA Baseball. ``Tommy is a great motivator,
a great teacher and a great leader.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
