<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7451 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-GENOME-KAN &LR;      05-06 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC SOON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 COMPLETE SEQUENCE OF GENES LINKED WITH dOWN SYNDROME TO BE MADE (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The complete sequence
of genes associated with Down syndrome will be published soon, the
chief of the Human Genome Project announced Friday during a visit
to Kansas City.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This should be a big leg up for Down syndrome researchers,''
Francis Collins, director of the National Human Genome Research
Institute, told students and faculty at the University of Kansas
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a physician-geneticist, was in Kansas City at the
invitation of Republican Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas to meet with
local scientists and students and to visit research centers such as
KU Medical Center and the Stowers Institute for Medical Research.
</P>
<P>
   The Down syndrome chromosome, called chromosome 21, will be the
second chromosome sequence the government-sponsored Human Genome
Project has published since December.
</P>
<P>
   Chromosome 21 is also the site of genes that can cause Lou
Gehrig's disease, Alzheimer's disease and epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the Human Genome Project will be completing work on
additional chromosomes at an accelerating rate. He predicted the
gene sequences of all human chromosomes will be published within
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see chromosome after chromosome appearing,'' Collins
said. ``Then we'll have a full sequence (of genes) that will stand
the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   An international team of scientists is mapping the human genetic
code. The project will help scientists understand diseases at the
molecular level and to develop treatments and even cures.
</P>
<P>
   Down syndrome researchers hailed the completion of the
chromosome 21 gene sequence as a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a historic step for research,'' said geneticist
David Patterson, president of the Eleanor Roosevelt Institute in
Denver and chairman of the science advisory board of the National
Down Syndrome Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we'll know the genetic information on
chromosome 21. That will be critical to devising ways to help
people with Down syndrome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Every person has 23 pairs of chromosomes, for a total of 46. A
full set of chromosomes is contained in the nucleus of every body
cell.
</P>
<P>
   Each human chromosome holds thousands of genes, the bits of DNA
code that control the growth, repair and function of cells.
</P>
<P>
   Most research on genetic diseases focuses on locating defective
genes that cause disorders, such as cystic fibrosis, or make a
person more vulnerable to illnesses, such as certain cancers.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, doctors may be able to use this genetic
information in several ways. They may recommend risk-reducing
lifestyle changes to people with a genetic susceptibility to an
illness. They may provide tailor-made drugs to counter the effects
of a malfunctioning gene. Or they may be able replace defective
genes with healthy ones.
</P>
<P>
   Down syndrome researchers, however, face a different set of
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Down syndrome there is an overabundance of genes. Persons
with the disorder have three, rather than two, copies of chromosome
21, for a total of 47 chromosomes.
</P>
<P>
   Down syndrome, which occurs in about one in every 700
pregnancies, causes learning disabilities that range from mild to
severe, and other problems such as congenital heart disease and
Alzheimer's disease by age 40.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson is involved in research to identify the genes on
chromosome 21 that are associated with Down syndrome learning
disabilities. Once these genes are known, researchers may try to
use drugs to subdue the harmful effects of the extra set of genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that's going to ameliorate some of the learning
problems people with Down syndrome have,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson was among the researchers who discovered in 1993 the
defective gene on chromosome 21 that can cause Lou Gehrig's
disease, also called amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. In the late
1980s, other researchers discovered a chromosome 21 gene that can
cause Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of scientists around the world have been working on
(chromosome 21) for a long time,'' Patterson said. ``That made it
an attractive target for sequencing.'' (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
