<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGAND-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TOBACCO EXECUTIVES TELLS STUDENTS ABOUT HEALTH RISKS OF
SMOKING AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Students at Truman
High School in Independence, Mo., saw ``The Insider'' on Friday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not the movie _ the man.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Wigand, the subject of the Oscar-nominated movie, is the
former Brown &AMP; Williamson executive who broke the tobacco
industry's code of silence when he appeared on ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the now-famous interview with Mike Wallace, he told how toxic
chemicals were added to tobacco to enhance the addictive quality of
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Wigand's message to Truman students, however, went far beyond
the health risks of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   He told them about the bullet in the mailbox and the
middle-of-the-night death threats. He said Brown &AMP; Williamson
squashed the First Amendment by using courts to bully CBS into
postponing the ``60 Minutes'' segment.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry was desperate to shut him up, he said,
because he knew the secret of how cigarette companies hustled 3,000
teens each day into becoming habitual smokers. And he knew how they
ensured future sales with addictive, lethal additives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When used as intended, cigarettes kill you,'' Wigand told the
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider'' starred Russell Crowe as Wigand and Al Pacino as
a producer for ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   At the movie's start, in March 1993, Wigand is chief of research
and development for Brown &AMP; Williamson, earning more than $300,000
annually. He and his family live in an upscale home and drive
luxury cars. His children attend private school.
</P>
<P>
   When he refuses to toe the company line, he is fired.
</P>
<P>
   Death threats are called to his house. His wife leaves. He is
tailed. When Brown &AMP; Williamson threatens to sue CBS, the network
drops the Wigand interview and the story is leaked to newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   By movie's end, he'd been divorced, deemed unhireable in his
profession, sued by his former employer and made a target in a
national smear campaign. He was teaching at a trifle of his
previous income.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday at City Hall, where Kansas City Mayor
Kay Barnes presented a proclamation to him, Wigand looked back on
the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how the industry treated defectors,'' he said. ``It was
emotionally devastating, but was it worth it....
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I do it again?...Yes, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes'' eventually showed the interview with Wigand, and
in 1998, 46 states negotiated a $206 billion settlement with the
tobacco industry. The remaining four states settled for $40
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement put new restrictions on how tobacco companies
marketed and advertised cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson also agreed to drop its lawsuit against
Wigand.
</P>
<P>
   Since his ordeal, Wigand founded Smoke Free Kids, an
organization that advocates tobacco-use prevention. He was the
keynote speaker Friday at a World No Tobacco Day luncheon at
Rockhurst University and was scheduled to take part today in a
youth workshop at North Kansas City Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At Truman High on Friday, Wigand implored students not to be
deceived by ads that used sexuality, fun and athleticism to sell
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Girls, he said, are prime targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a sweet, you're going to get fat,'' he said. ``But
if you have a smoke, you will stay skinny.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Rebecca Walker said Wigand's message, because of the
movie, was stronger than most anti-smoking strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In a local angle Friday, Wigand said Kansas City's largest law
firm, Shook, Hardy &AMP; Bacon, played a role in his story by
instructing him _ when he was hired at Brown &AMP; Williamson _ how to
``interpret'' scientific research that concluded smoking was
unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to convince me the research was flawed,'' Wigand
told the students.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Cofer, a Shook, Hardy &AMP; Bacon partner who works on tobacco
cases, confirmed that the firm represented Brown &AMP; Williamson (and
still does) but said he could not comment because of
attorney-client confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what light we are put in, our lips are sealed,''
Cofer said.
</P>
<P>
   Not Wigand's. And he's getting some help.
</P>
<P>
   He said a few ``insiders'' at tobacco companies send him things
occasionally. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
