<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7453 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      05-06 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTOUCHERS GET RETORTS ON TERMS, TOILETS AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Apologies are due all the loyal
StarTouchers. They've been asking a lot of questions lately but
haven't been getting any answers from Uncle Fearless. The time has
come to end this benign neglect:
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they say the economy is growing at a (certain) annual rate,
what is that a percent of? I never know.
</P>
<P>
   The calculation process is simple. The gross domestic product
measures the value of all U.S. economic output. At the end of each
quarter the government estimates this value and compares it with
the previous quarter. If the economy is growing, the magnitude of
economic expansion will be quantified by subtracting the previous
quarter's lower number from the current quarter's higher number and
figuring the percentage increase on an annualized basis. If the
economy is in recession, the process is reversed. To adjust for
inflation, the current calculation is based on constant 1992
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   You should use the terms Kansas City and Kansas Citians to mean
the people of Kansas City, Mo. Whenever you talk about the metro
area, it should be stated specifically.
</P>
<P>
   Well, excuuuuse me!!! This has always seemed a distinction
without a difference. When traveling abroad in this fair land and
strangers ask, ``Where you from?'' the answer is Kansas City, not
Lenexa, Kan. New Yorkers are New Yorkers, regardless of which
borough they inhabit. Kansas City's suburbs may not be precisely
analogous, but they're close enough for column work. Besides, we're
all one big happy family, right?
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything we can do about our (1.6)-gallon flush
toilets?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, media types don't pay much attention to this
outrage, but the latest word isn't encouraging. A House
subcommittee, reports The Weekly Standard, took up the matter of
repealing the stingy-flush toilet mandate recently, but voted
narrowly to retain the current law. Critics contend no water is
saved by refusing to allow consumers to choose the old 3.5-gallon
model, as if saving water is necessary in the first place, because
the stingy-flush models often take two or three tries to get the
job done. Officious government, however, thinks it more important
to control such matters than allow average citizens to make
common-sense judgments about such private aspects of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   How will the economy benefit from paying down the national debt?
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't make much difference to average Americans.
Treasury has been paying down the publicly held marketable portion
of the debt, but as of April 30, the total debt was still $100
billion higher than a year ago. The problem is that Uncle Sam has
been spending excess revenues from Social Security taxes and money
collected for such things as highways and airports faster than he's
paying down the public portion of the debt. When trust funds for
Social Security and the like are credited with IOUs after the
surplus revenues are spent, these obligations are added to the
national debt. So, what we're seeing is a substituion of debt. The
amount we owe investors, institutions and foreign governments and
central banks shrinks, while the amount we owe future Social
Security recipients expands. Meantime, the shrinkage of marketable
Treasury securities may create problems for financiers everywhere.
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
