<HEADLINE>
WHITE'S STATUS UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers orthopedist Frank Jobe called
the tear in Devon White left rotator cuff ``slight'' on Friday but
added it would be two weeks before the team knows if season-ending
surgery is required for the switch-hitting center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   White, 37, was injured Tuesday night diving for a ball hit by
Atlanta's Brian Jordan. It is the same shoulder that required
surgery last winter, but Jobe said the new injury is in a different
location.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe said he was encouraged by White's range of motion during an
examination Friday. He added that because White's non-throwing
shoulder was injured, the recovery time probably is shorter. But he
stopped short of putting White back in the lineup anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best-case scenario is that he continues to get better
every day and starts to play in two weeks,'' Jobe said of White,
who was batting .289 in 22 games. ``The worst-case scenario would
be that he stops getting better and we have to operate on him. If
we do then it's a season-ending injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Cora returns: Alex Cora was devastated when he didn't make the
Dodgers out of spring training. The starting shortstop position was
his to lose and he lost it.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Cora is back in the big leagues, called up
Thursday when Kevin Elster was placed on the disabled list with a
strained groin. Cora started Friday night against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Cora did more than just catch a break. At the time of the
promotion, he was batting .394 (39 for 99) at Triple-A Albuquerque,
including a 13-game hitting streak, which prompted Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson to put him back in the everyday lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is up here to play,'' said Johnson, who kept veteran Jose
Vizcaino in the reserve role. ``He went down to the minors, did
what he had to do and persevered.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy at first.
</P>
<P>
   The adjustment to minor-league camp at the end of spring
training was difficult. Cora, who hit .176 with a club high four
errors, was unhappy and let everyone know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I realized that if I kept complaining and had my head
down, I was going to be in the minors a lot longer than I wanted to
be,'' said Cora, brother of former All-Star second baseman Joey
Cora. ``I had put too much pressure on myself in spring training.
The most important change for me was keeping things as simple as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cora, 24, recognized that people thought his spring average was
just more of the all-field, no-hit tag that had followed him since
he was selected in the third round of the 1996 draft out of the
University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past few years, Cora's numbers have improved.
Although he batted .121 and .167 in brief stops with the Dodgers,
Cora had a strong second half at Albuquerque in 1998 and batted
.308 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've had that tag on my head ``Defense'' for a long
time,'' he said. ``But I feel very comfortable at the plate right
now. This is a great opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
