<HEADLINE>
GORE OFFERS PLANS TO IMPROVE QUALITY AND PAY OF TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   (CLARIFIES Gore quote in 5th graf) 
 (SUBS to insert new material on Bush after 6th graf; new quotes
from teachers' union officials after original 11th graf) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. _ In a speech here outlining his proposals to
improve the quality of the nation's public school teachers, Vice
President Al Gore offered a spoonful of sugar to help the medicine
go down.
</P>
<P>
   He said that as president he would spend $8 billion over 10
years to recruit 1 million new teachers and another $8 billion over
10 years to increase teacher salaries if the states and teachers'
unions agreed that all new teachers submit to testing and meet
rigorous national standards and if teachers are hired on the basis
of expertise and not seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am entrusted with the presidency, I will ensure that
there is a fully qualified, well-trained teacher in every single
classroom, everywhere in this nation, before the next four years is
out,'' he declared in a speech here to the Michigan Education
Association.
</P>
<P>
   His proposals are based on the theory that the quality of
teachers is the most significant factor within a school's control
in improving student achievement. And education ranks near the top
of voter concerns, especially in important battleground states like
Michigan, where Gore conducted his fourth ``school day'' Friday,
spending an entire day at the high school in nearby Holt. (He also
conducted his first ``school day'' in Michigan, in McComb County.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In communities where schools, teachers, community groups and
lo- cal businesses agree on effective plans to raise teacher
quality, let's give every qualified teacher a $5,000 raise,'' the
vice president said here. Gore said that by 2004, he would require
states to make sure that teachers are fully qualified to teach the
subject they are teaching. As of now, he said, only 36 percent of
teachers consider themselves to be very well-prepared to meet the
standards of their state or school district. In high-poverty areas,
as many as 50 percent of the math teachers have not studied math.
</P>
<P>
   Education is an area to which Gore's Republican rival, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, has devoted considerable attention in
hopes of wooing swing voters. Polls show he has been successful in
this attempt, which is uncharacteristic for a Republican. The Gore
campaign is countering Bush's initiatives with proposals that do
not just allocate federal money but also make demands of teachers
and school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposes to require teachers to have majored in their
subject area in college or pass a competency test in it. And he
would reward outstanding teachers and help schools improve or
remove bad teachers quickly, within the academic year as opposed to
the three years that such a process can take now, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``While we absolutely must respect due process, we have to put
an end to endless delays in removing those few teachers who really
do need to be removed,'' Gore said. He also said principals should
be allowed to hire teachers for reasons other than seniority. ``No
teaching contract should be a lifetime job guarantee,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Teacher testing and seniority hiring are highly controversial
matters among educators and have been strongly resisted by the
teachers' unions, which believe that standardized testing does not
measure the intangibles of good teachers. Others object to
standardized testing of both teachers and students as a step toward
giving up local control of education.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the teachers' unions have heartily endorsed Gore's
presidential candidacy. Against that backdrop, his speech Friday
was intended to be seen as a daring, principled stand, the kind
that his political advisers have been eager for him to take to
demonstrate that, contrary to the popular impression as registered
in public opinion polls, Gore does not just blow with the political
winds and pander to every group he addresses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was what Gore aides called a ``Sister Souljah Moment,'' a
reference to Bill Clinton's tough speech during the 1992
presidential campaign when he took on the black singer face to face
for lyrics he said were offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech comes after the American Teachers Federation, the
nation's second-largest teachers' union, endorsed the idea last
week of toughening teacher standards.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory King, a spokesman for Sandra Feldman, the president of
the American Federation of Teachers, said Gore consulted with Ms.
Feldman on his proposals. He said that she was heartened that Mr.
Gore would cede some decisions on teacher hiring to ``principals
working with teams of teachers, and not just principals.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth Teasley, the director of government relations for
the nation's largest teachers' union, the National Education
Association, said her union was comfortable with Gore's suggestion
that seniority not be the only criterion in teacher hiring. She
emphasized that Gore was not dismissing seniority as a
qualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe what he is putting forth is the notion that we
should consider credentials and expertise, and that seniority could
be a factor, it's just not the only factor,'' she said. ``We can
work with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been trying to demonstrate his commitment to education
in multiple ways, including by spending a full day at a school
somewhere in the country every week or so. He spent Friday at Holt
High School after spending the night with Margot Strong, a computer
teacher, her husband, Jay, who teaches first grade, and their two
children, Nick, 10, and Anna, 6. Gore arrived at their house after
midnight Wednesday night and stayed up late enough to watch four of
the five overtimes in the hockey playoffs on television.
</P>
<P>
   Holt was the first high school Gore has visited during this
campaign, and the older age of the students was evident in some of
their by-play with the vice president. In a morning physics class,
when Gore asked the students what the most interesting thing was
they had learned, Tonia Van Every, 18, called out: ``About Mr.
Pulver's personal life,'' a reference to the teacher, Eric Pulver.
``I'm one of the sarcastic kids,'' she told a reporter later.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the school newspaper, Gore was asked about
abortion. He said he believed it was up to a woman to decide what
to do, but he said he also believed in abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   And he revealed that his glory moment in high school was
shooting _ and sinking _ a long shot at the final buzzer, but only
after the basketball hit the backboard. Asked to list his favorite
sports, he said: ``Football, basketball, track, art.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his most difficult moment as vice president has been,
he answered without much hesitation: ``The day our soldiers in
Somalia were killed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
