<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN, BUSH FINALLY TO CONFER LIKELY TO BE AMICABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 Republic Washington Bureau  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON - The Tuesday, May 9, long-awaited ``summit'' between
George W. Bush and John McCain is likely to produce smiles and
handshakes, but it is far less certain that the GOP rivals will
manage the sort of meaningful reconciliation that party regulars
are hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's top advisers have reportedly said the Arizona senator
will not formally endorse the Texas governor at the Pittsburgh
meeting, preferring to wait until later in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That apparent coyness on McCain's part is disturbing to some
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't endorse (Tuesday), I will not understand why,''
veteran Republican consultant Lyn Nofziger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, a guy who can go over and endorse the North Vietnamese
certainly ought to be able to endorse George Bush. He's had more
than a month since the primaries to get over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, during his eighth trip to Vietnam, McCain again told
reporters that he is not interested in being Bush's running mate -
a topic likely to come up Tuesday in one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I would want to talk to him about it,'' Bush said in an
ABC-TV interview broadcast Friday night. ``If he wants to talk
about it, I'd like to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said he'd prefer to play an active role in the
Senate, where he chairs the Commerce Committee, than to perform the
often ceremonial functions of a vice president. He has also said
that he and his wife, Cindy, would prefer to avoid an invasive
procedure in which the family's taxes and finances are scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is certain to make clear at Tuesday's summit that he
supports Bush and that the two share a common goal of defeating
Democratic Vice President Al Gore in November. McCain has said he's
been delaying his endorsement because he wanted to achieve a
``greater comfort level'' with Bush's positions and out of respect
for his own voters during the primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's problematic for the Bush campaign, because McCain does
have a unique appeal, and an outpouring of McCain support for Bush
would clearly be beneficial to Bush's hopes,'' said Frank Luntz, an
analyst for YROCK.com, a political Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Nofziger said the longer McCain waits, the greater the
opportunity will be for Democrats to say, ``See, Bush is so bad
that even McCain won't endorse.''
</P>
<P>
   Nofziger recently participated in a GOP strategy session
organized by the Bush campaign. Among the attendees was former
McCain adviser Ken Duberstein _ evidence, Nofziger said, that
McCain's ``people,'' if not McCain himself, have gotten over the
bad blood of the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   McCain suspended his campaign two days after decisive defeats in
the ``Super Tuesday'' balloting on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain had some memorable campaign squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   McCain complained when a Bush radio ad questioned his commitment
to breast-cancer research and when the Texas governor appeared with
a veteran in South Carolina attacking McCain's Senate voting
record.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush was outraged at negative phone calls suggesting
he was anti-Catholic and by a McCain ad comparing his level of
truthfulness to President Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Since the campaign, McCain and Bush have become reluctant
suitors. Bush would like to tap into the Independent and Democratic
voters who declared their allegiance to McCain during the
primaries. McCain wants to be seen as aiding Bush to avoid the
charge that he is a bad loser who is disloyal to his party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won't rule out seeking the White House again in 2004 if
the circumstances are right. His hero, Ronald Reagan, lost his bid
for the nomination to Gerald Ford in 1976 but won the presidency
four years later.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who labeled himself the reform candidate, says he wants
to ask Bush at their meeting about his specific proposals for
overhauling campaign-finance reform, Medicare and the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told Gannett News Service that ``the agenda is going to be
how do we work together, to fight for and campaign on personal
savings accounts in Social Security, or campaign-funding reform.
John and I have a lot of agreements.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Jeff.Barker(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at
(202) 662-7264. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
