<HEADER>
A7460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELEGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-06 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELEGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE? LIBERAL? ONE BISHOP PROCEEDS WITH AN EFFORT THAT'S
JUST IMPORTANT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were two Roman Catholic priests from New York and one
out-of-town bishop sitting in front of the audience. The priests
were the ones in black clerical garb. The bishop was the one in a
pale blue sweater and a sports shirt.
</P>
<P>
   This was three weeks ago in the parish hall of St. Paul the
Apostle Church on Manhattan's West Side. Bishop Kenneth Untener of
the diocese of Saginaw, Mich., was there to address several hundred
people at a one-day conference on spirituality and social justice.
</P>
<P>
   Untener is considered one of the more liberal members of the
Catholic hierarchy, and not just because he shows up casually
dressed at events like this. Although he is anything but a
firebrand, from time to time he says things out loud, on topics
like birth control and the ordination of women, that a number of
other Catholic bishops say only privately.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular morning, however, Untener said nothing that
Pope John Paul II would not heartily endorse, and he said it all in
an easy, direct, enormously good-humored manner that totally won
his audience's attention and trust.
</P>
<P>
   He did not delve into specific social or political injustices,
about which his audience probably needed little education. Instead,
he stuck to basic theology and spirituality. He unselfconsciously
made passing references to life after death that could have come
from the most old-fashioned pastor. The ultimate focus of his
remarks was the Sunday Eucharist.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when New Yorkers are scanning the horizon for the
successor to Cardinal John O'Connor, Untener's remarks, and an
interview with him later that day, are a reminder of the limits of
the categories often used to describe church leaders, and not only
Catholic ones.
</P>
<P>
   The terms ``liberal'' and ``conservative,'' for example, are
notoriously slippery, depending on whether one is talking theology
or politics. A little better is the tool kit of familiar types: the
political churchman joining in civic debates, the doctrinal
churchman teaching from the pulpit, the administrator making church
agencies run smoothly or the comforter offering solace and
performing good deeds.
</P>
<P>
   These stereotypes are not completely useless; nor are the
categories of ideology, ethnicity and fund-raising abilities that
the news media, as in their reporting on prospective archbishops of
New York, readily import from the arena of party politics and
presidential tickets. But they are all seriously insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   What Untener was eager to talk about, for example, didn't fit
any of these categories, and yet, more than doctrine, sex, politics
or finances, it may be the key to Catholicism's future in this
country. His concern was the quality of Sunday worship.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Untener began meeting with his priests and
deacons in groups of five to review and improve their preaching.
Each person, including the bishop, was asked to record a live
sermon, and the six tapes were sent to the whole group for
listening before the gathering. Transcripts of these homilies, to
use the more current term, were also made, and a veteran journalist
working for the bishop marked them up the way a tough-minded editor
would.
</P>
<P>
   Each group engaged in this process for four meetings. More
recently, Untener has initiated a similar process, but this time
with the videotaping of entire Sunday liturgies (again, his own
included). Priests can review their manner of presiding, the degree
and nature of congregants' participation and the effect of the
music. The meetings will begin, say, with analyzing how one priest
or another conducted the opening prayers or the Eucharistic prayer.
Always keeping the church's liturgical theology in mind, the
participants discuss what ``worked,'' and what did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conversations can get very spiritual,'' Untener said,
``for example how hard it is to pray, really pray, in front of
other people _ not just performing prayer _ so that when Ken
Untener says, `O God,' it is really talking to God. And there's no
one single way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the tapes reveal general problems of congregational
participation, for instance, the bishop has authorized limited
liturgical experiments in a few parishes, although not in search of
``a hokey gimmick for each week.''
</P>
<P>
   One key to this whole process is honesty, he said. For priests,
the gatherings can be ``a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to hear
some straight talk from a cross section of experienced peers,'' he
wrote in ``Preaching Better'' (Paulist Press, 1999), a practical
little book he has written for preachers.
</P>
<P>
   Another key, of course, is that the bishop is part of the same
process as his priests. ``Once the priests found out it's not top
down but helping each other,'' he said on his New York visit, ``it
wasn't threatening. It was welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   That may all sound egalitarian and liberal. But another key to
the process, Untener said, is that it is mandatory. Is that
hierarchical and conservative?
</P>
<P>
   Other dioceses, including New York's, have set up liturgical
teams that are ready to attend and analyze parish liturgies at a
pastor's invitation, but by all reports relatively few parishes
avail themselves of this kind of critique.
</P>
<P>
   Untener works through the diocesan roster of priests in
alphabetical order. ``We make financial reports mandatory,'' he
pointed out, so why be any less insistent about the quality of
worship? Church people say that ``liturgy is the most important
thing in a parish,'' he said, ``but that's not where we invest our
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   No archbishop of New York could exercise leadership in the way
that a bishop of Saginaw can. The New York archdiocese has 15 times
the number of Catholics, four times the number of parishes and
perhaps 10 times the number of priests in them. A New York
archbishop would have to find and appoint perhaps half a dozen
liturgical mentors like Untener.
</P>
<P>
   But the real point is not the applicability of a ``Saginaw
plan'' to New York. It is that this kind of pastoral strategy and
creativity, although it touches on the very heart of church life,
escapes virtually all the categories and labels tossed around in
descriptions of future church leadership here or just about
anyplace else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
