<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-OBRIEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER S. O'BRIEN, 70, SCHOOL UNION LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., Mich.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter S. O'Brien, a founder and former president of
the Council of Supervisors and Administrators, a New York school
union, died on Wednesday at his home in Glen Rock, N.J. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   A native of New York and a graduate of St. John's University,
O'Brien spent 27 years in the Marine Corps and its reserve,
retiring as a lieutenant colonel.
</P>
<P>
   He served in the Korean War and was a specialist in flight
control.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien worked 34 years in the New York City public schools as a
teacher, an assistant principal, a principal and the superintendent
of Community School District 30. He retired in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the council, which was founded in 1966, he
supported a strike by the United Federation of Teachers in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He also helped found a national group, the American Federation
of School Administrators, and served as its president.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is survived by his wife of 49 years, Bernadette
Castronuovo O'Brien; four sons, Peter, of Glen Rock; Michael, of
Vernon, Conn.; Christopher, of Oakland, N.J., and Stephen, of New
York; a daughter, Bernadette O'Brien of New York; two sisters,
Eileen Burke of Clawson, Mich., and Sister Ann Michael of Syracuse;
a brother, Shawn, of Saratoga; and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
