<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-DEVILRAYS-REDSOX-BOS     05-06 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX BEAT RAYS
</HEADLINE>
 RAYS-RED SOX-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention the last-place Devil Rays to the Red Sox, and you don't
get the reaction you would expect.
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. Tampa Bay may have won only 69 games a year
ago, and may be in the basement in the American League East, but it
beat the devil out of the Red Sox last season, winning 9 of 13
games. It was only one of three AL teams to have such an advantage
on the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay came to Fenway Friday night for the opening of a
three-game weekend series, expecting to pick up where it left off
last season.
</P>
<P>
   But on an 80-degree evening, the Red Sox showed a sellout crowd
of 32,479 and the Devil Rays a combination of things in posting a
5-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Begin with starting pitcher Ramon Martinez, who gave a solid
five-inning (plus two batters) effort (eight hits, three runs)
before giving way to Rich Garces and Derek Lowe, who closed down
the Devil Rays the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Move over to a balanced offense that produced 10 hits, including
a pair of doubles by designated hitter Brian Daubach; a two-hit
effort by right fielder Trot Nixon, who also made a marvelous
run-saving catch in the sixth; another home run by center fielder
Carl Everett, who appears just as hot in the first week of May as
he was in April when he blasted seven home runs and had 23 RBIs;
and a three-hit effort by second baseman Jose Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good, clean game,'' said Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams. ``If you give yourself a good, clean game, good pitching,
good hitting, good fielding, you give yourself a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere Williams looked Friday night, he had reason to smile.
Martinez, for example, turned in what Williams said was his best
effort of the season. ``He had probably his best stuff,'' said
Williams. ``Maybe it was the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who threw 99 pitches, didn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt nice,'' he said. ``This is the kind of weather I
like.''
</P>
<P>
   But as has been the case in almost all of his starts, it took
him awhile to get going.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up a leadoff triple to center fielder Gerald Williams,
which turned into a quick run when left fielder Greg Vaughn lined a
single to right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always takes me awhile to get started,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (2-2) also got considerable support; the most the Sox
have given him since a 13-4 romp over Minnesota in the home opener
April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach drove in a run in the first following another Nixon
double (his fifth in the last three games), and back-to-back
doubles in the fourth by Jason Varitek and Wilton Veras (following
the Everett home run) highlighted a three-run inning that gave the
Sox a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they do against everybody else,'' said Jimy
Williams. ``But they do a lot of good things against us. Hit good,
pitch good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays chipped away at Martinez with a run in the fifth,
and then picked up another run in the sixth when Jose Canseco hit a
moon shot over the left-field screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit a few homers in this park,'' said Canseco, whose shot
carried an estimated 415 feet. ``But we still lost. I told myself
to be aggressive on anything around the plate, and I got a ball I
could drive.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all for Martinez. Garces came in and threw two shutout,
hitless innings, aided greatly by a marvelous running catch by
Nixon on the warning track in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep your eye on the ball, you get a feeling of where you
are on the field, where you are on the warning track,'' said Nixon.
``You keep an eye on the ball until it gets into your glove. If you
hit the wall, you hit the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon didn't, and Tampa Bay did when Lowe came in and closed the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone did a great job,'' said shortstop Nomar Garciaparra.
``Ramon did a great job settling down after the first inning, the
bullpen did its job, and we did the job behind them as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Jimy Williams said. A good, clean game that turned out
the way the Red Sox had hoped against the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
