<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LOCKERBIE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE LOCKERBIE BOMBING TRIAL  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 6:
</P>
<P>
   There may never be a full accounting of the terror plot that
brought down Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, just
before Christmas in 1988. But the trial of two suspects that began
this week in the Netherlands offers the best chance so far to
establish at least a measure of responsibility for the attack,
which killed 270 people. That the case has come to court at all is
a tribute to the persistence of British investigators and some
skillful diplomacy by Kofi Annan, the secretary-general of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The two Libyan defendants, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen
Khalifa Fhimah, were indicted nine years ago in the United States
after one of the most intensive manhunts in history. They are
accused of packing plastic explosives inside a Toshiba boombox and
shipping the device in a suitcase from Malta to Frankfurt to
London, where it was placed aboard the Pan Am flight, which was
headed to New York. Investigators say the two men, who have denied
any role in the attack, were Libyan intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
   The trial reflects the diplomatic maneuvering that made it
possible. The site is a former NATO airbase in the Netherlands, but
the trial is being conducted under Scottish law before three
Scottish judges, who will render the verdict. This satisfies Libyan
demands for a neutral location without compromising prosecution of
the case. Annan was helpful in making these arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives of some of the 189 Americans killed in the attack
fear the prosecution is misguided because it failed to implicate
others who may have ordered the bombing, including top Libyan
officials. Some relatives also believe that Syria and Iran may have
played a central role in the plot. These concerns are valid, but
they ought not to diminish the importance of the trial. If the
guilt of the two Libyans is established by hundreds of witnesses
who will testify and the thousands of bits of evidence that will be
introduced, they should be convicted and sentenced to life in
prison in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfortunate that the Clinton administration seems ready to
consider a thaw in relations with Libya as the trial opens. Col.
Moammar Gadhafi, the Libyan leader, has behaved with greater
moderation in recent months, and Britain re-established diplomatic
relations with Libya last summer. But it is far from clear that
Gadhafi has made a full conversion after years of promoting
terrorism around the world. As part of the compromise arrangements
for the trial, U.N. sanctions against Libyan air travel and imports
of vital industrial equipment have been lifted. That is sufficient
relief for now. Separate U.S. sanctions against Libya should remain
in place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
