<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7488 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX     05-06 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITING BACK: STARS TAKE 3-1 SERIES LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Joe Nieuwendyk spoke quietly about missed
chances and frustration before Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't scored since Game 1. Not good since scoring is what
the Stars expect him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he said, ``you are judged on what you put in the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   What Nieuwendyk put in the net Friday night were the Stars'
final two goals, including the game-winner, in their 5-4 victory
against the San Jose Sharks in Game 4 of the Western Conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good obviously,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I look forward
from here on in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are one victory away from a rematch of last season's
Western Conference Finals with the Colorado Avalanche, who defeated
the Detroit Red Wings in five games. The Stars could do so with a
victory in Game 5, scheduled for Sunday in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   To do so Friday night, the Stars had to survive four blown
leads, more ill-advised penalties, another gritty performance by
the Sharks' Owen Nolan and a mini-meltdown by goalie Ed Belfour in
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   They did so with excellent penalty killing, another superb
performance by center Mike Modano, and Belfour bailing himself out
of his own jam. He finished with 31 saves, nine of them after his
meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he composed himself really well,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``What really settled him down is when they were on
the power play he made some big saves. ... A couple of years ago,
we would've had a pretty good mess on our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Referees whistled Belfour for roughing at 3:03 of the third
period. Thirty-seven seconds later, he did it again. The Sharks had
one minute and 23 seconds of a 4-on-3 power play. They didn't get a
shot. They had 37 seconds of 5-on-4 with Belfour making great saves
on Patrick Marleau and Alexander Korolyuk to preserve the Stars'
5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might have been the best thing for him,'' Stars captain
Derian Hatcher said. ``(Belfour) told me before the game he didn't
feel great. So maybe it was good. He was great in the third
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Belfour: ``Sometimes you need that (something like the
penalties). It gets you into the game a little more. I've always
been that way when things aren't going that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Four times before, the Stars took leads. Four times, they lost
them.
</P>
<P>
   The last lead, the one they didn't lose, came on a pretty play
between Jamie Langenbrunner and Nieuwendyk, who beat everybody up
the ice, took a pass from Langenbrunner in the circle and put the
puck past Sharks goalie Steve Shields at 18:07 of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said before the game that he thought Nieuwendyk was
due to break out and be make a difference in the series.
</P>
<P>
   But not even he could've predicted this.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a smart guy,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I was pushing hard, and
it paid off with a couple of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   In a game Hitchcock called ``pivotal'' and ``as big of a game as
we've played for a while,'' the Stars' best players _ for the most
part _ delivered. In a series in which scoring goals had been a
problem, the Stars' forwards solved it.
</P>
<P>
   The lead they all followed, though, was once again Modano's.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 68 seconds into the first period to extend his streak
of playoff games with a point streak to a career-high eight, the
longest current streak in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   So began the back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   See if you can keep up.
</P>
<P>
   With Nieuwendyk and Hatcher both in the penalty box, a flashback
to Game 3, Sharks center Vincent Damphousse scored at 8:52 of the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' penalty kill answered when Guy Carbonneau took a pass
from Mike Keane on a 2-on-1 to give the Stars a 2-1 lead at 10:21
of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks tied the score with two minutes and 26 seconds left
in the first period as Sharks center Mike Ricci scored from the
edge of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars responded with another short-handed goal. It was
defenseman Sergei Zubov this time. He took a pass from Modano and
pumped it in 56 seconds into the second period with Hatcher in the
box. The Sharks were 2-for-7 with a man advantage Friday night, but
allowed the Stars two short-handed goals as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks tied the game at 3-all with a short-handed goal of
their own. Nolan beat Hatcher in a foot race down the ice and put
the puck into the far corner of the net at 7:48 of the second
period. No lead, however, was safe. Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk took a shot from the point that Hull tipped, Morrow took
a swipe, and Nieuwendyk buried at 10:52 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks finally scored a non 5-on-3 power play goal at 14:08
of the second period when former Stars winger Todd Harvey snuck
behind the Stars players and went five-hole on Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be better defensively,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``And we
certainly don't want to come back here for Game 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Nieuwendyk's game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say he'd score it. Nieuwendyk doesn't have any Joe
Namath in him. All he said before Game 4 was he'd be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's putting the puck in the net, it makes our team go,''
Stars winger Blake Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Which, in the end, is how he really should be judged. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
