<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7489 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     05-06 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT-OF-CHARACTER STYLE SUITS STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ What the heck was that? Instead of a Dallas
Stars' kind of playoff game, it might as well have been Arena
League football. Or maybe the Roller Derby. Hully-gully hockey is a
foreign factor in the Ken Hitchcock scheme. Showtime is almost
never dough-time for the button-downed Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ...
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night on the West Coast, step out in the yard this
morning, and look due northwest from any vantage point in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That jagged outline way off in the distance, it has to be the
Rocky Mountains. The Western Conference finals are coming, and the
Colorado Avalanche earned the right to be there again Friday night,
completing a surprising quick kill of the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   And now, despite being totally out of character in this Game 4,
the Stars are all but ready for a rematch of last year's thrilling
head-knocker with the Avalanche. San Jose, which never goes easy,
is on the verge of going away.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-4 victory by the Stars tells the story, just by the goal
count. These two clubs are 1-0, 2-1 kind of outfits.
</P>
<P>
   But as Joe Nieuwendyk welcomed himself back to the playoffs with
two goals, the Stars never trailed nor led by more than one goal.
You want defensive breakdowns, stupid penalties, and even almost a
return to Eddie Belfour's old ways of coming unglued in crunch time
... well, Belfour and the Stars were guilty of all that.
</P>
<P>
   But Nieuwendyk gave Mike Modano an offensive alternative, and in
the end that was the most important difference. Many goals were
needed, many were scored.
</P>
<P>
   And for an added bonus, there's not a Stars fan alive who
couldn't appreciate one special first period moment. Bryan
Marchment, in great pain, was unable to make it to the San Jose
bench, and also unable to slow Mike Keane, who was going to dump
the puck on a penalty kill, only to spot the wounded Marchment.
</P>
<P>
   Keane wheeled around the big lug, as two other Sharks rushed to
cover for Marchment. That left Guy Carbonneau free to whistle
unchecked down the other side of the San Jose zone. Keane's feed
was perfect, and Guy nailed a hummer past Steve Shields, the
short-handed goal giving the Stars a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, a disgusted and hurting Marchment stumbled toward
the bench after the goal, tried to leave for the dressing room, but
collapsed next to a water cooler. He wouldn't return. While
Marchment appeared to be dragging a knee, the Sharks announced a
groin injury. Whatever, something was hurting, and bad. In all
North Texas precincts, that's a beautiful thing.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes, however, to Hitchcock's version of a beautiful
thing, he wants a tight-checking, defensively sound performance for
82 regular season games. In the playoffs, you can double that
Hitchcock command.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are normally so good at following this Hitchcock game
plan, they wear the national label of boring. They also wear
Stanley Cup championship rings because of that style..
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, none of it applied. Not the discipline of
Hitchcock's system, and certainly not the label of boring.
Everything the Stars aren't supposed to do, they did. But the one
thing the Stars wanted most of all, they also did. Nothing else
mattered as long as there was a win in Game 4, meaning a big tilt
in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took the chartered flight home in the wee hours,
winging all the way back to Texas with a 3-1 advantage, and gunning
for the close-out of San Jose on Sunday night at Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the Stars don't win when the two best defensemen,
Derian Hatcher and Sergei Zubov, commit critical turnovers that
lead to goals. At least, however, when Zubov lost the puck behind
the Dallas net Friday night, it was a forced error and a good
defensive play by the Sharks' Marco Strum. Hatcher, who had his
worst playoff game in a while, simply bobbled the puck at the blue
line, and the always persistent Owen Nolan scooped it up, beating
Belfour while the Sharks were shorthanded.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Stars' penalty kill unit had two short-handed
goals of its own, as San Jose also went into an unusual defensive
funk.
</P>
<P>
   But the goal that counted the most came from Nieuwendyk late in
the second period, and while it was 5-on-5, the Sharks again were a
defensive mess. Kirk Muller carried the puck across the blue line,
got it to Jamie Langenbrunner in the circle and Jamie slid it to
Nieuwendyk, who rolled in unchecked on Shields.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday night's game, Nieuwendyk doubled his goal total for
the playoffs, and now has three.
</P>
<P>
   A hairy moment for the Stars came in the third period when
Belfour was twice called for roughing penalties. Nolan was
pestering Eddie all night, verbally and otherwise, and it appeared
to be taking a toll on Belfour. But Eddie responded on those power
plays, and was in total control of both himself and the Sharks down
the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   `'It was wild,'' said a smiling Hitchcock afterward. But with
the win, he could actually accept wild, at least for one night. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
