<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, May 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-U.N. (Dateline to come)_ On the challenges faced by the
U.N. peacekeeping mission to Congo, including the need to build a
town in one area to support a regional peacekeeping headquarters.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTISM-SCHOOLS (West Windsor, N.J.) _ One family came from
India, others from Greece and Italy and Israel. Compared to those
migrations, Rob and Anne Mandel had it pretty easy, giving up his
medical practice and a life they loved in Indiana to get their son,
Sam, the help he needed in New Jersey. Sam is autistic, and his
parents' move here made the Mandels part of the phenomenon of
families that, desperate for the most sophisticated special
education services for their disabled children, move from other
states and even other nations in search of care. But increasingly,
the needs of parents with autistic children are clashing with the
bottom lines of school districts. By Iver Peterson. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT25 was sent on 4-27 to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-DAMS (Lower Granite Dam, Wash.) _ The fate of the
hydroelectric dams on the Snake River, and of the endangered salmon
there, may hinge on the effectiveness of a program to bring
millions of the fish on barges around dams. Its success or failure
is the likely key to a momentous decision that will ultimately come
before the U.S. Congress: whether to take down the Snake River dams
altogether. That once-unthinkable idea has emerged in several
federal studies as the single action with the best chance of
restoring healthy salmon runs. But many people bitterly oppose that
plan as an assault on the area's agricultural economy. By Sam Howe
Verhovek. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 14,15,16,17, were sent on 5-4 to NYT photo
clients and map was sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KANSASCITY-SCHOOLS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Public lives on Benjamin
Demps Jr., Kansas City Schools superintendent, who faces the task
of bringing a district on its knees back up on its feet. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEDGE-FUNDS (Undated) _ Money managers George Soros and Julian
H. Robertson Jr., who once rattled world financial markets with
mere hints of their actions, have lost much of their punch. But
hedge funds, the investment vehicles for the wealthy that these
prominent investors epitomized, are by no means on the ropes; the
unregulated hedge fund industry continues to grow. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-RAIL (St. Augustine, Fla.) _ Henry Flagler came to Florida
in 1883 to build grand hotels in what was sparsely populated
coastal scrub. Using wealth amassed as one of the Standard Oil
Co.'s founders, he began cobbling together a railroad down the
length of the state. By 1896, he had built 350 miles of track from
Jacksonville to Miami. Now Florida East Coast Industries, the
holding company controlling the Flagler railroad, is using the
right of way to establish itself in the new economy. Since last
May, the company's subsidiary, Epik Communications, has been
selling capacity to move digital information through fiber optic
cables that run alongside chugging train cars piled high with
crushed stone, building materials and vehicles. By Jane Tanner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-OIL (Almaty, Kazakhstan) _ A consortium of nine oil
companies says it is encouraged by drilling in a potentially huge
Caspian Sea oil field. By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich writes about Bill Clinton's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (KENT, Ohio_ Anthony Lewis on Kent State.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUTNAM-CIVIC-MALAISE (Undated) _ Five years ago, Robert Putnam's
article, ``Bowling Alone,'' about the decline of civic engagement,
touched a public nerve and became a metaphor for a much larger
national malaise. He suddenly found himself profiled in People
Magazine, appearing on talk shows and getting an invite from
President Clinton to Camp David. Now he's back with a new book and
new evidence for his thesis, and a somewhat more optimistic outlook
for the future. By Louis Uchitelle. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 was sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY-REINTERPRETED (Undated) _ As an ideal, beauty has been
taking quite a beating. It has been viewed as an ideology that is
culture-bound, and it has come to seem irrelevant to art works
preoccupied with race and gender. Yet, there has also been a
movement in the other direction. The philosopher and classicist
Alexander Nehamas has suggested that beauty is once again becoming
an academic obsession, as philosophers and critics resuscitate the
beautiful, recasting old philosophical arguments and forecasting
new variants. By Edward Rothstein. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-CANTATA (Washington) _ The balmy spring night belied
the occasion of sad memorial, and, as the cantata played out around
the capital on the radio, listeners paused at the very idea of a
spirited tango composed by some forgotten Buchenwald prisoner, not
to mention the bold humor enduring beyond long gone lyricists at
the Auschwitz death camp. Listening to the Holocaust Cantata, a
choral pastiche of authentic music and song from inmates translated
from the Polish and premiered two years ago by the chorale's
chamber singers. By Francis X. Clines. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-PHILHARMONIC (Berlin) _ The controversy over plans to
have the the Vienna Philharmonic play Beethoven's Ninth Symphony at
the site of the former Nazi concentration camp in Mauthausen,
Austria. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BALANCHINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Balanchine Lives.''
Reviewed by Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   TV-JASON-REVIEW (Undated) _ On NBC, ``Jason and the Argonauts,''
a mini-series. Reviewed by Neil Genzlinger.
</P>
