<P>
   &UR; YIPPEE! FINALLY, THE CANDIDATES TALK ABOUT FOREIGN POLICY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOREBUSH-FRGNPOLICY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It has been a strange week in the playroom of
American presidential politics. Foreign policy has not just been
mentioned, but actually debated. Naturally nobody expects this to
last. Why should the American electorate consider anything so
tedious as global security, free trade or missile defense? This
attitude is perhaps understandable, but it is still wrong and _ as
President George Bush might have put it _ getting wronger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE NEEDS MORE IMMIGRANTS _ THAT'S RIGHT, MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAIL-EURO-IMMIGRANTS-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Europeans, it seems, are gripped by panic about
foreigners: that there are too many of them pouring in, that there
is certainly no need for any more. In short, that Europe is ``full
up.'' Alas, we beg to differ... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 850 words; 1,050 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ANGLO-SAXONS ARE BACK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANGLO-SAXON-RETURN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The Anglo-Saxons are back. For nearly a thousand
years, no one gave them much thought. Now, however, the
Anglo-Saxons are everywhere. They pop up in the context of stock
options, shareholder value and neo-American capitalism, or rather
(here's a clue) les stock options, la shareholder value et le
capitalisme neo-americain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
