<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN 15-7, RANGERS' RALLY SETS CLUB RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers pitcher John Wetteland has 299
saves in major-league baseball games. Friday night he got his first
victory in a major-league slow-pitch softball game.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland was the only pitcher left unscathed when Mike Lamb
lined a one-out bases-loaded single to deep center in the bottom of
the ninth to give the Rangers a 17-16 victory over the Oakland
Athletics at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb's base hit capped the biggest rally and one of the most
incredible games in Rangers history. By any standard _ American
League, juiced ball or otherwise _ this one defied belief.
</P>
<P>
   All the Rangers know is they rallied from being down 15-7 with
10 runs in the final three innings to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was crazy,'' Rangers starter Darren Oliver said.
``I've never seen a game like that. It was wild. The only thing you
can say is you're glad you won. If you score 16 runs and lost it
... wow.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis started the winning rally with a single to left
against losing pitcher Jeff Tam and was forced at second by Ivan
Rodriguez's grounder. Rafael Palmeiro then drew a walk, and Ruben
Mateo reached when Tam bobbled his grounder for an error.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and one out, Oakland manager Art Howe went
with a five-man infield, but Lamb foiled the strategy with a drive
to deep center beyond the reach of the remaining two outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those games, last one up, wins it,''
Palmeiro said. ``It would not have been a good one to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most amazing was both teams were playing with depleted
lineups. The Athletics were missing Matt Stairs, John Jaha and
Randy Velarde _ all injured _ and the Rangers had David Segui
(strained hip flexor) join their list of wounded that already
includes Rusty Greer, Gabe Kapler and Frank Catalanotto.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and Athletics even outdid one of the local
slow-pitch softball leagues. As of 10:30 p.m. Friday night,
Softball World in nearby Euless had completed 22 slow-pitch games
and the most scored in any one game was 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look up there and you just don't do that,'' manager Johnny
Oates said. ``I don't care how much fight you have in you, you just
don't come back from a deficit like that. But that's proof I lied
because we just did that.''
</P>
<P>
   All 18 starting offensive players scored at least one run, the
first time that's been done in American League history. It tied a
1996 26-7 victory over Baltimore for most runs scored by two teams
ever in a Rangers game. There were 37 hits and 13 walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exhausted,'' said first baseman Scott Sheldon, whose
single in the eighth scored two and tied it at 16-16. ``You hear
about teams that have done stuff like come back from being 10 runs
down but I've never been a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez started the comeback with a home run in the seventh
off Oakland reliever Luis Vizcaino. Run-scoring singles by Tom
Evans and Luis Alicea later in inning made it 15-10.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Zimmerman gave up a homer in the top of the eighth to
Terrance Long, but the Rangers were hardly daunted. They just came
back with six more in the bottom of the inning. They started the
inning with six straight singles and Jason McDonald's sacrifice
bunt then set up Sheldon's game-tying single.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pudge hit that homer, then Raffy got that single, I
thought, this game's not over,'' Sheldon said. ``Then, when we got
within four runs, I thought, we've got a shot to win this.''
</P>
<P>
   The unholy mess began with the starting pitchers, especially
Oliver who was given a 5-0 lead in the second inning and couldn't
hold it. Instead he gave up a three-run homer to No. 9 hitter Frank
Menechino in the fourth and a two-run homer to No. 8 hitter Ramon
Hernandez in the fifth, making it a 5-5 game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took a 7-5 lead in the bottom of the fifth but the
Athletics came back for 10 in two innings off reliever Matt
Perisho, who was pitching for the first time in nine days. The fans
showed their displeasure, hardly realizing the fun was only
beginning. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
