<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINFUL ANKLE KEEPS LEHTINEN OFF ICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Dallas Stars winger Jere Lehtinen is closer
than ever to returning to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Close, however, wasn't close enough for Game 4. He skated in the
pregame warmup, but didn't play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't dress, then he's not able to deal with the
discomfort that is going with the injury,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``The injury (right now) is can he deal with the
discomfort, and that's the area if you can deal with it and know
it's there and play. And if he can't deal with it, we just have to
buy more time.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Stars is Lehtinen's right ankle did feel
strong enough to skate yesterday after a vigorous practice on
Thursday. The Stars made the decision not to play him between the
morning skate and the pregame warmup.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Lehtinen's ankle, which caused him to miss all
but 17 regular-season games and the nine playoff games, ``is going
to be painful for the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can't perform (without worrying about it), we're better
putting somebody else in there,'' Hitchcock said. ``When people do
that, I usually find that's when people get hurt again in a
different area of body.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said they'll wait another day or two, which means
Lehtinen could be ready for Game 5 on Sunday. LANGENBRUNNER RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   While most of the talk of a returning forward focused on Jere
Lehtinen, who didn't play, another Stars forward did make his
return: winger Jamie Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   After missing Game 3 with a bruised shoulder suffered in Game 2,
Langenbrunner was back to his normal line spot, alongside Joe
Nieuwendyk and Scott Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What puts us over the edge in these games is forwards,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   It took a period, but after missing on a combined nine scoring
chances in Games 1 and 2, Langenbrunner cashed in. He had two
assists in the second period, including one on Nieuwendyk's goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my type of series,'' Langenbrunner said.''It's hard to
find ice, and I like those types of situations.''
</P>
<P>
   If Langenbrunner had any fears of hurting his shoulder again, it
didn't show. Through the first 40 minutes he had four hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I liked them a lot better without Langenbrunner,''
Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said. BELFOUR BOILS OVER
</P>
<P>
   Amid a cascade of taunts and Sharks crashing the crease, Stars
goalie Ed Belfour finally had enough, and in the third period he
let it show.
</P>
<P>
   With Sharks wingers Tony Granato and Dave Lowry establishing
position in front of the net, Belfour slammed his forearm into
Granato's face. Both Belfour and Lowry were given penalties at the
3:03 mark of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven seconds later, another scrum in front of Belfour
ensued, this time between Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk and
Sharks forward Owen Nolan. Belfour got into it again and was
awarded a hooking penalty, giving the Sharks a four-on-three, which
the Stars killed. TRIPLE-OT MEMORY
</P>
<P>
   The seven-hour playoff game between the Philadelphia Flyers and
Pittsburgh Penguins on Thursday night had the Stars' remembering
their late-night playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they won the Stanley Cup in triple overtime in Game 6
last season in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first overtime you go in and you got the bicycle pump
going and you are pumping up the rah-rah. After that, you don't
even go in the dressing room,'' Ken Hitchcock said. ``I talked to
the team in Buffalo after the second one, and there were six guys
in the dressing room. The rest of the guys were lying on tables out
in the hallways, sitting in the washroom. Your team just
evaporates.'' ANOTHER VOTE FOR BELFOUR
</P>
<P>
   Not that Stars general manager Bob Gainey needed the
reassurance, but Sharks coach Darryl Sutter likes Stars goalie Ed
Belfour better than St. Louis goalie Roman Turek.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks upset the No. 1-seeded Blues in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter was asked what differences he saw between the Stars and
Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depth, more experience definitely top to bottom,'' Sutter
said. ``Better goaltending is the biggest difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey had to decide which player to leave unprotected last
summer for the expansion draft. He ended up trading Turek to the
Blues right before the deadline. The move drew criticism as Turek
and the Blues went on to win the Presidents' Trophy this season.
THE SKINNY ON KEANE
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Mike Keane was teammates with Sharks center Mike
Ricci on the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Ricci remember about Keane?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dessert,'' Ricci said. ``The guy's a skinny little bone rack.
He eats a lot of dessert.'' ZUBOV'S VALUE
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock likes the way Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov has
played since returning to the lineup. He missed the first round
with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   There is one problem, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing that concerns you is he's made four or five
plays where, quite frankly, if everybody on the ice was awake we
could've scored without the goalie in the net,'' Hitchcock said.
``He surprises the hell out of us.'' MATTER OF POSITIONING
</P>
<P>
   The Stars learned a lesson in location during their Game 3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they had a lot of scoring chances. No, they didn't have
enough chances in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have to get more things around the net,'' Stars
center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``We've had some time in their end
where your face is up against the glass and you are holding the
puck in your feet. Somehow, we have to battle through that and get
the puck to the net and beat people off the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said the Stars changed up some things
strategically to help them get the puck to the front of the net.
The biggest change the Stars needed to make, he said, was work
harder. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
