r s BC-HKN-SHARKS-NOTES-TEX     05-06 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHARKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARKS KNOW LOSS AT HOME LEAVES THEM WITH A FORMIDABLE TASK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The San Jose Sharks had an opportunity to
return to Dallas with their Western Conference semifinal with the
Dallas Stars knotted at two games apiece. With Friday night's 5-4
loss, it's do-or-die for the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   The series has taken the same twists as the Stars' first-round
matchup against Edmonton. The Stars closed out that series in five
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the playoffs, it's the start,'' Sharks center Vincent
Damphousse said. ``If you can shut down the home team and silence
the crowd a little bit, that's usually when the home team plays the
best, early on when the juices are flowing and the crowd is getting
behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks are 2-4 on the road in the playoffs, but are no
strangers to big road victories. They took Game 2 and Game 7 in St.
Louis to win that first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the road you need to play good defense and that gives you a
chance to win,'' Sharks winger Todd Harvey said. ``If you play good
defense, get good gaoltending, then you have a chance to win on the
road. It's not a flashy game; it's a hard-working, grind-it-out
game when you're on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 4-0 at home in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've played well at home for a long time now so it
doesn't really change,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks now must win three consecutive games, including twice
in Dallas, to win the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had any doubts that we could beat Dallas,''
Damphousse said. ``It's up to us to make it very interesting.''
RISKY LINE
</P>
<P>
   Sharks coach Darryl Sutter kept his lines intact for the second
consecutive game, keeping left winger Jeff Friesen with Owen Nolan
and Vincent Damphousse.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter continued to use his speed lineup, which includes
20-year-old center Patrick Marleau and young Russian Alexander
Korolyuk on the same line with winger Niklas Sundstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little riskier line,'' Sutter said. ``You can probably
get away with it a little more at home.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Sutter has last change, meaning he has the advantage to
match up his lines with the Stars' defense. A SPECIAL GOAL
</P>
<P>
   As long as the Sharks are on a 5-on-3 power play, the
special-teams unit is fine. Vincent Damphousse scored his first
goal of the playoffs and the team's second 5-on-3 goal in as many
games. The goal tied the score at 1-1 at the 8:52 mark of the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration was short-lived. After the 5-on-3 expired, the
Stars had an odd-man rush and Mike Keane fed a cross-slot pass to
Guy Carbonneau, who beat Shields for a short-handed goal and a 2-1
lead at 10:21. AN EARLY TEST
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks' struggling penalty kill, which had allowed 10 goals
in 10 games, was put to the test early with the Stars already
leading, 1-0. With Bryan Marchment in the penalty box for four
minutes for high-sticking to Aaron Gavey, the Sharks killed the
first two minutes allowing no shots.
</P>
<P>
   After Joe Nieuwendyk got off a weak shot at the goal mouth that
was smothered by Sharks goalie Steve Shields, Nieuwendyk and Sharks
winger Owen Nolan tangled. Nieuwendyk was hauled off to the box for
roughing. The four-on-four ensued for 48 seconds and the Sharks
went on the power play for 1:12. ANOTHER FIRST GOAL
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth consecutive game, the Sharks allowed the Stars to
score the first goal. After surrendering a goal to Mike Modano at
the 3:35 mark of the first period in Game 3, Modano struck again
Friday night. On another assist from Brett Hull, Modano rifled a
one-timer past Steve Shields at the 1:08 mark of the opening
period. BOYS WILL BE BOYS
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman and captain Derian Hatcher and Sharks winger
and captain Owen Nolan didn't take long to rile each other. They
pushed and shoved, with Nolan winning the battles. Hatcher was
called for two penalties against Nolan in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher's first penalty, for high-sticking at the 8:31 mark of
the first period, gave the Sharks a five-on-three, resulting in a
Vincent Damphousse goal to tie the game at 1-1. The second, with
less than 10 seconds left in the period, allowed the Sharks to
begin the second period with the man advantage. MARCHMENT INJURED
</P>
<P>
   Sharks defenseman Bryan Marchment left the game with a groin
pull in the first period right after the Stars scored to make it
2-1 and did not return.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
