<HEADLINE>
STARS SHUFFLE LINES TRYING TO GIVE MODANO SCORING HELP
</HEADLINE>
 LINES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif._ This is what Stars winger Mike Keane wanted:
Moving with the puck toward the net and linemate Guy Carbonneau on
the opposite side.
</P>
<P>
   Keane threaded his pass by three San Jose Sharks to Carbonneau,
who sent a low wrister past Sharks goalie Steve Shields for the
short-handed goal.
</P>
<P>
   That goal, which came at the 10:21 mark of the first period in
Friday night's 5-4 Stars victory snapped a 148:33 streak where all
of the Stars' goals were either by center Mike Modano, or his
linemate, Brenden Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to just be this defensive-minded line,'' Keane
said. ``That's no good during the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Carbonneau's goal, Modano had scored the Stars past three
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The goal marked a degree of immediate success by the Stars
playing the line-shuffle in hopes of adding something that outside
of Modano's line was lacking: Offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you need the third and fourth lines producing,''
Keane said, ``to take a little pressure off. You score a couple
goals so Joe (Nieuwendyk) gets a little more loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk did finally shake loose, scoring two goals in the
second period, and for the first time since Game 1, the Stars
displayed scoring balance throughout their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we can get a line like Modano's that's playing
any better right now,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We've
played the whole playoffs and won a lot of games with different
people chipping in, but I think we've maxed with what were doing
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a different way to get other people to chip
in. Whether it's changing up the third and fourth lines and giving
them a different role, it's a fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Hitchcock's alterations began. Try to follow the
bouncing ball:
</P>
<P>
   Normal fourth-liner Kirk Muller to the checking line with
Carbonneau and Keane.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner to his normal spot on the second line with
Joe Nieuwendyk and Scott Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Blake Sloan to the fourth line with Roman Lyashenko and Aaron
Gavey, and scratching winger Grant Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate results? Carbonneau's goal, Keane's shot late in
the first period that narrowly missed going into the net, his
short-handed shot late in the second period, and more goals in the
first 32 minutes than they had scored in the previous 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine Stars scored points, including Langenbrunner, who
assisted on Sergei Zubov's short-handed goal and one of
Nieuwendyk's second goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would like to think that a good strength of our club is
depth,'' Muller said. ``Everyone knows they can chip in here and
there. No one line is going to carry you. It's important for a mix.
We have to do that and take a little pressure on Modano's line.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the pressure was off. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
