<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHARKS-RICCI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARKS' RICCI A PLAYER FANS LOVE TO HATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Mike Ricci showed Friday night why his
teammates love him and opposing fans hate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night he's getting into traffic areas, battling in front
of their net, helmet off, hair all over his face,'' teammate Jeff
Norton said of Ricci, always consistent, but suddenly the Sharks'
hottest player in this increasingly heated conference semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just consistency, every night,'' Norton said. ``It's an
82-game season, but it seems like he's always in the middle of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricci, easily identifiable by the long locks of black hair
flowing out the back of his helmet, was again in the middle of
nearly everything Friday night in Game 4 at San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci, selected Wednesday a Selke Trophy finalist _ awarded to
the league's top defensive forward _ is continuing his best
offensive season (20 goals, 24 assists) since 1993-94 when he had
51 points (30 goals) with Quebec. He scored his second goal in as
many games Friday night to tie a wild, high-energy affair at 2-2 at
the 17:54 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Where was he? Positioned perfectly at the left side of the
crease when Niklas Sundstrom looked off Stars goalie Ed Belfour in
the slot and assisted Ricci, who flipped the puck into the open
left side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci's name won't be in the box score on the Sharks' first
goal, but his tough work in the crease shielded Belfour and gave
center Vincent Damphousse a shooting lane on a 5-on-3 power play at
the 8:52 mark. That goal tied the game at 1-1. It was almost
identical to Ricci's first goal of the series in Game 3 when he
camped in the crease and redirected a Gary Suter slap shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``His biggest strength is he is always in position with his feet
to play the puck,'' Damphousse said. ``He keeps the other player
always in a defensive position. He is a very smart player out
there; he is always thinking and he knows where all the other guys
are on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharks coach Darryl Sutter called the 1998 trade that brought
Ricci to the Sharks from Colorado, where he won a Stanley Cup in
1996 along with Stars winger Mike Keane, ``the greatest trade the
organization ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken veteran of 10 years, Ricci is a player opposing
fans love to hate. He's a close second in that distinct category to
Sharks villain Bryan Marchment. Much of that has to do with Ricci's
long hair and scruffy, bad-boy look. Mostly, though, it's his
everyday grittiness and commitment to doing the hard-hat work in
all the difficult places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to be myself,'' said Ricci, who has five goals in
the playoffs. ``I think people like me when I'm off the ice. On the
ice, I'm not trying to make many friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricci, 28, broke into the NHL with the Philadelphia Flyers in
1991, a team that had Stars coach Ken Hitchcock as an assistant. He
played two seasons with the Flyers before being traded to Quebec,
along with current Avalanche star Peter Forsberg, in exchange for
Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a passionate guy; he wears it on his sleeve,'' Hitchcock
said. ``He's a heck of a player.''
</P>
<P>
   He's doing everything he can to keep the Sharks alive. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
