<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS FORCED TO SETTLE FOR MORAL VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Sometimes, a team just gets beat.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, more complicated explanations are thrown about at
season's end.
</P>
<P>
   This guy screwed up. That coach blew a decision. Somebody
choked. And, of course, the referees botched the big calls.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. Not Game 5 between the Seattle Sonics and Utah
Jazz Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   This went exactly according to form. Two good teams that split
eight previous games in the 1999-2000 season played well, hard and
close. Stars shone, role players were heroic, every play mattered
and the excruciating drama in a vibrating Delta Center drew down to
the final shot.
</P>
<P>
   Boink.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz 96, Sonics 93.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the season. G'night, everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask them,'' said Sonics coach Paul Westphal of his
team, ``to give any more than they gave.''
</P>
<P>
   As his Utah counterpart, Jerry Sloan, put it: ``The homecourt
advantage was obviously the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are coaching clich &UR; gfacute &LR; es, but the thoughts become
clich &UR; gfacute &LR; es because they are true. And sometimes there is
nothing more complicated about a basketball came than the plain
truth.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics did not falter from pressure, lapse from the game
plan, or make more than the standard number of mistakes. After five
games over two weeks that included collapse and resurrection, they
were three points short.
</P>
<P>
   As Gary Payton said: ``Shots that didn't fall for them in our
building fell in their building.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Jazz get the anticipated victory, and the Sonics, as the
underdog seventh seed, get the moral victory.
</P>
<P>
   The jock world always likes to say that moral victories don't
mean anything, but the Sonics won something over this fortnight _
credibility and even admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire that in people, when everybody thinks the world is
against them and they fought back,'' said Sloan of the Sonics. ``To
me, that's one of the most important things you can do in sports:
Show that kind of ability to be able to fight, when everybody wants
to take a foot and just step on top of your head.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had sneaker prints all over their noggins following
losses in the first two games here. They deserved most of them. The
had lost 13 of their past 18 games, and Westphal seemed to be
deriving his lineups from a dartboard.
</P>
<P>
   But in five days off, they fixed a lot of problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when we left here after Game 2, they were reeling a
bit, didn't quite know what it was that made them a good team,''
said Utah's John Stockton, with whom Payton conducted a splendid
battle between true warriors. ``They were a very good team
throughout the rest of the series.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter Friday, the game appeared to get away from
the Sonics. When the Jazz lead ballooned to 72-59 and the Jazz
fans' mocking chant of ``Ga-ry! Ga-ry!'' rocked the joint, the
Sonics went on a 24-12 run to make it a game the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of watching the Sonics disintegrate during that stretch,
it was the Jazz who got emotional and foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was driving Jerry crazy,'' said Stockton. ``When we got
excited about the lead, we forced the issue and missed some fast
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Jazz had no killer instinct, there was one development
that broke form and turned the game: Olden Polynice.
</P>
<P>
   Olden Polynice!
</P>
<P>
   The two-time ex-Sonic, the guy who would be voted least likely
to do a worthwhile thing, was the hero. The center with the worst
hands in the NBA did the unexpected: He caught the ball and put in
in the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Six times, ending up with 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sonics' two-game turnaround, the newly installed trapping
defense largely counted on the ball ending up in the hands of
Polynice or his backup, the often-befuddled Greg Ostertag.
Typically, they would heave the ball into the Great Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Said Westphal: ``They found a fifth player in Olden.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, however, how it often happens in the NBA postseason: A
minor miracle from an unheralded player. The Sonics received solid
games from nearly everyone, but didn't get the unexpected
contribution, something from somewhere that would negate homecourt
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If that is their biggest shortcoming, the Sonics can consider
their return to the playoffs after a one-year absence a relative
success. Some will argue with the selection of Chuck Person for the
final shot, given that he hadn't played for the Sonics since he
weighed under 270 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that he ended up with a clean, undefended shot from
straight on, and missed the game-tying trey by about three inches,
suggested that not much better could have been achieved, since the
entire state of Utah was stationed beyond the arc.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics did not resolve all their woes in one week. But they
did make matters exciting, and offered a glimpse of a future that
includes contention.
</P>
<P>
   Given where they were 12 days ago, the turnaround is nearly as
amazing as the vision of Polynice the Conqueror.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 0252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
