<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' BATS COME ALIVE TOO LATE AGAINST ANAHEIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners had no shortage of fall guys Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a 6-5 loss to Anaheim that dropped the Mariners
into a tie with the Angels for the AL West lead, starting pitcher
Aaron Sele and center fielder Mike Cameron kicked themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won that game,'' Sele said. ``You don't have to
look any further than the starting pitcher for a reason why we
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   For seven innings, Sele allowed just two runs, and although the
Mariners were behind, 2-0, they weren't out of the game. Then, with
two out and a man on second base, Sele faltered.
</P>
<P>
   He threw a 2-2 fastball so fat the ball needed extra stitching.
He threw it to exactly the wrong guy. Tim Salmon had doubled twice
on similar pitches early in the game. This time, Salmon homered,
and the Angels went on to score three two-out runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make it very difficult for him at all,'' Sele said.
``I gave him a good pitch to hit. I pitched a good game for seven
innings, but you can't give up three runs in the eighth after two
men are out.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, after the Mariners had scratched out four runs in the
bottom of the eighth, Cameron got fooled, then felled, by a
catchable Darin Erstad line drive in the top of the ninth. Erstad
wound up with a triple and eventually scored what would prove to be
the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was hit right to me, and I froze,'' Cameron said.
``Those are the hardest balls to know where they're going. I still
thought I had it, but I lost my footing. And that hurt. That was a
big ol' run.''
</P>
<P>
   That it was. But the run needn't have been so crucial if the
Mariners had flexed a little of their offensive muscle _ five runs
in the final two innings _ in the first seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the second and in the seventh, the Mariners loaded the bases.
In the second, Carlos Guillen popped out to end the inning, and in
the seventh, Mark McLemore grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Both Guillen and McLemore have underachieving batting averages,
.122 and .204, respectively. The Mariners are particularly
concerned about Guillen, who also made the final out of the eighth
inning, grounding out with Cameron standing on second base as the
potential tying run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guillen had a big hit (Tuesday) in Minnesota that helped us
win a game,'' batting coach Gerald Perry said. ``I was hoping that
would help him catch fire, build his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hit here or there tonight would have helped. It's been a
tough go for him. He started slow, then he got injured. He's
struggling now, and (lack of) confidence has a lot to do with it.
He's working hard, though, trying to get it together. It's not for
lack of work that he's struggling. He's out there working every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners need Guillen. And McLemore. And David Bell (.132).
Seattle has a good offense, but the power that was in evidence in
the 1990s isn't there. To get big offense, Seattle needs lots of
hits and walks. One or two an inning won't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   The final two Anaheim runs _ a two-out blooper for an RBI single
by Troy Glaus in the eighth and the Erstad triple that set up a run
in the ninth _ were particularly galling to Seattle manager Lou
Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the year, we weren't giving up add-on runs,''
Piniella said. ``Lately we've been doing it a lot. We've got to
stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Mariners never gave up Friday. Down 5-0, their
engine turned over, with Javier proving to be the ignition switch.
Javier opened the eighth inning with his first home run of the
season. It didn't seem like much at the time, but it was the start
of big doings.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez singled, and one out later, Edgar Martinez
singled to right. Rodriguez steamed around to third, and when
Salmon blew the pickup, Martinez took second.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lampkin doubled home both those runners, Cameron doubled
home Lampkin, and suddenly the Mariners were one hit away from
being tied.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get it. Raul Ibanez lined out and Guillen grounded
out, meaning the Mariners would have to come back against
flame-throwing reliever Troy Percival _ if they were to come back
at all.
</P>
<P>
   They would have made it as John Olerud drove in a run in the
ninth. But by then it was a two-run game, thanks to Erstad's liner
tricking Cameron for a triple, followed by Adam Kennedy's RBI
single, good for Anaheim's sixth run.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Mariners' third in four games and came as
Seattle is beginning a 10-day stretch against AL West teams.
</P>
<P>
   Games Saturday and Sunday against the Angels will be followed by
three games in Texas and four in Oakland, and the Mariners, shut
out for seven innings, can only hope that last night was not an
omen of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got five runs the last two innings,'' Piniella said.
``Let's hope that's a portent of things to come.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
