<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF BY A NOTE: SONICS TAKE UPSET BID DOWN TO FINAL SECONDS AGAINST
JAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ In so many ways, the final ride was a microcosm
of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But despite taking the Utah Jazz through every possible twist,
dip and hairpin turn, the roller coaster that was this Sonics
season came to a halt Friday night in a hard-fought, 96-93 Game 5
loss in the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics failed in an attempt to become just the sixth team in
NBA history to come back from an 0-2 deficit and win a first-round
playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Losing 3-2 in the best-of-five series, however, did not diminish
the scare the seventh-seeded Sonics threw into the No. 2 Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sonics clearly walked away with a sense of pride, Utah
took a case of whiplash into its Western Conference semifinal
matchup with Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept getting better and better, and tougher and tougher
to deal with,'' Utah coach Jerry Sloan said of the Sonics. ``That's
a credit to them. They went through a little turmoil, according to
what everyone was saying. It's really kind of aggravating, because
Paul Westphal did a great job to get his team back in a tough time,
to put them in a situation to compete like they did. They were just
that close to winning tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing the resilience they displayed throughout the series, the
Sonics came within inches of stealing the decisive road game
several times.
</P>
<P>
   Their last opportunity to extend the season came with nine
seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics controlled the ball for the game's final play after
Utah's John Stockton sank a pair of free throws. Following a
timeout, Westphal inserted Chuck Person into the lineup with
Rashard Lewis, Brent Barry, Vin Baker and Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   When Payton received the ball after the inbounds pass, he ran
around a Person screen at the top of the key. Stockton and Malone
followed Payton, who whipped a pass back to Person.
</P>
<P>
   Person pump-faked as a defender flew by before launching a
three-point attempt to tie the game. The ball bounced off the front
of the rim and time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some players don't relish the opportunity,'' said Person, whom
Westphal called the ``designated shooter'' in those situations.
``But, for me, it was easy to go in and to get the shot. I just
missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Person, a 36 percent shooter from 3-point range over his 13-year
career, dialed just 25 percent from long distance this season but
hit the game-winning 3-pointer Jan. 26 against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal, not wavering from the strategy that forced a Game 5,
played a hunch, played the odds and played to the unpredictability
of his team.
</P>
<P>
   That is how everyone wanted to go down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were going to double me,'' said Payton, who
finished with 27 points, nine assists and six rebounds. ``It was a
good shot by Chuck. I don't regret not taking that shot. I'd rather
for us to get a good look than for me to force something over two
people.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... It hurts a little bit. But I'm proud of this team and the
way they played. With a young team like we've got, we came into a
place that's really hard to win and had a chance to win. I take my
hat off to all the young guys. They came here and played really
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics used the same trapping defense that was successful in
Games 3 and 4. This time, though, Stockton was more active in
fending off the double teams. Stockton had his best game of the
series, countering Payton with 17 points, 15 assists and seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we left here after Game 2, they were reeling a little
bit,'' Stockton said. ``They didn't quite know what it was that
made them a good team and they figured it out early in the third
game. They were a very good team throughout the rest of the series.
So we feel real fortunate for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton said Utah's execution finally won out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew what was going on,'' Payton said. ``They were
running their plays, and it was just a matter of us trying to stop
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics knew they had to also deal with an emotional,
pumped-up Delta Center crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Payton and Lewis (20 points, 7 rebounds) were the starters
visibly immune to the hostile environment created by Jazz fans.
Ruben Patterson brought his usual energy and added 15 points off
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   That trio was mostly responsible for not allowing the Sonics to
wilt after Utah took a 72-59 lead late in the third quarter. Lewis'
3-pointer at the end of the third got the Sonics to 79-70.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has a lot of character,'' said Baker, who finished
with 17 points but had just two rebounds. ``We were supposed to be
done 1{ weeks ago. But we fought. I'll take this team in a dogfight
any day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics remained in a game in which they were outshot,
outrebounded and led just once (by three points in the second
quarter), and Westphal was pleased with the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got beat by a great team,'' said Westphal. ``I think we
could have finished it, except for a couple of little things. They
got a lot of second shots in the last four minutes. We played good
defense, and somehow they came up with the rebound. And then if
Chuck makes that shot ... I think we would have won in overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
