r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-LA     05-06 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN, BUT BROWN DOESN'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jeff Shaw is winning games, but he's not making
friends.
</P>
<P>
   One out from a save Friday night, Shaw allowed a home run to
Houston's Lance Berkman that tied the game and overshadowed an
outstanding performance by Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Los Angeles Dodgers scored in the bottom of the
ninth to beat the Astros 3-2, the boos of 45,428 fans turned to
cheers and the club had its fifth victory in seven games on the
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   And Shaw had another win.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems as if Shaw, who saved 34 games last year, has been
in this spot before, he has. Last Saturday he allowed a game-tying
ninth-inning home run to Florida's Derrek Lee only to get the
victory when the Dodgers scored in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going out there with a same gameplan every time out; it
never changes,'' said Shaw (2-1), who has three blown saves in 10
opportunities. ``The home runs don't change my perspective any
because I'm out to do my job, which is to save ballgames. And if I
don't save it, I try to put my team in a position to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Shaw gave up a home run to Berkman, who came to the
plate with one hit in 12 at-bats this season. But Shaw wound up
with the victory after Todd Hollandsworth singled past a drawn-in
infield to score Alex Cora with the winning run against reliever
Doug Henry (0-2).
</P>
<P>
   Cora, in his first game since being called up to replaced
injured shortstop Kevin Elster, opened the inning with a double.
</P>
<P>
   Cora was sacrificed to third and Hollandsworth, now the starting
center fielder with Devon White (torn rotator cuff) gone for at
least two weeks, made enough contact to get the game winning RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers opened the Houston series as a team in transition,
activating the rookie Cora and relief pitcher Antonio Osuna after
Elster (groin) and White were placed on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Cora started at short and Dave Hansen replaced Adrian Beltre
(tight hamstring) at third.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who has missed most of the past two seasons with elbow
trouble, technically gave the Dodgers 12 pitchers, but reliever
Mike Fetters was unavailable because of elbow soreness.
</P>
<P>
   Until the ninth, the only Dodger that mattered was Brown, who
limited the Astros to three hits and one run in eight innings. He
needed just 103 pitches to get that far, but getting his third
victory in four decisions would prove far more elusive.
</P>
<P>
   He was given the lead with a fourth-inning home run by Todd
Hundley, but never did figure out Jeff Bagwell, who had a
fourth-inning home run and a seventh-inning single.
</P>
<P>
   Brown got his revenge later that inning when the Astros loaded
the bases with two outs. With Tim Bogar at the plate, Brown threw a
breaking ball in the dirt that skipped past Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, that would have been a run. This year, the backstop
has been moved in from 83 feet to 58 feet to accommodate new seats.
As Bagwell broke for home, Hundley hustled for the ball and threw
to Brown covering the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Brown made a sweeping tag. Bagwell was out and Brown's 2-1 lead
was intact until turning the game over to Shaw in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play at home plate was a tough situation with the bases
loaded,'' Brown said. ``Instead of tying the game, we stopped a
run. The tag is not something you think about. It's just
instinct.''
</P>
</TEXT>
