<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 03:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7516 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-L     05-06 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS EDGE MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While other scores around the American League more
closely resembled those found in T-ball, Kent Bottenfield brought a
National League-like flavor to the Northwest on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield, an 18-game winner with the Cardinals last season,
threw 6 scoreless innings and the Anaheim Angels rode the hot bat
of Tim Salmon to beat the Seattle Mariners 6-5 before 38,307 at
Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield (3-3) allowed four hits while striking out seven and
walking three, but had to watch as the Angels bullpen hung on -
barely. He left the game with two on and one out in the seventh
inning but was saved by reliever Mark Petkovsek, who got out of the
inning with the Angels still leading, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored three times in the top of the eighth inning -
two coming in on Salmon's eighth home run of the year - and it
turned out they needed every one. Petkovsek got hit hard in the
bottom of the eighth, giving up four runs in the inning before
Shigetoshi Hasegawa got the final two outs of the inning with the
potential tying run at second base and the Angels clinging to a 5-4
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy's RBI single in the top of the ninth made it 6-4,
which turned out to be big. Troy Percival gave up a run in the
ninth but closed it out with the tying run on third for his eighth
save.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have won three in a row and trail the Mariners in the
AL West by percentage points (.538 to .533).
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck yes,'' Percival said when asked if the win was big.
``Bottenfield did a good job of holding them down. And any time you
hold 'em under six runs, I don't care when they score 'em, that's a
good win for us. Everybody's not going to be sharp every day. As
long as we win, I don't care if it's 20-19.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival got the first two batters in the ninth, including a
line drive by Stan Javier that hit the base of his palm and caromed
to shortstop Benji Gil, who made the play at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia ran out to check on Percival, who waved
him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to be rude, but it hit me pretty good and I
wanted to hurry up and get it over with before my elbow locked
up,'' Percival said.
</P>
<P>
   Percival, who had the imprint of the baseball's seams on his
hand after the game, said he felt stinging all the way up to his
elbow. But X-rays taken after the game were negative.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners then strung together a walk by Alex Rodriguez, a
single by John Olerud and an RBI single by Edgar Martinez to make
it 6-5. With pinch-runner Charles Gipson at third, Percival got Tom
Lampkin on a fly to right to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mark of two clubs that aren't going to quit,'' Scioscia
said. ``We're going to see games like this all year. These two
teams match up well.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon had three hits, including two doubles and the home run.
On the current road trip, Salmon is hitting .533 (8 for 15) with
three homers and six RBI.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Bottenfield's third consecutive quality start that
set the tone Friday. Since he got ripped in Toronto on April 20,
Bottenfield has allowed only four earned runs in 21 innings
covering three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was textbook Kent Bottenfield,'' Scioscia said. ``He has
command, he moves the ball around, he's an intelligent pitcher.
He's at a point where his last three starts he's about as good as
he can get.''
</P>
<P>
   A noticeable addition to Bottenfield's game is added velocity.
He hits the low 90's on the radar gun, where he used to be in the
high 80's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing a lot of long toss between starts, extending
the muscles and getting my shoulder stretched out,'' explained
Bottenfield.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been 16 strikeouts in his past two starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
