<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 03:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7517 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     05-06 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINE FEAST FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It remains an indisputable fact of life in the
NBA: When Godzilla wants to snack on a small city, you stay out of
the way of his fork.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers' Godzilla, Shaquille O'Neal, dined on the state
capital of California Friday night at Staples Center. In the first
half of a game the Lakers never expected to play, a deciding Game 5
of their first-round playoff series with Sacramento, O'Neal scored
20 points and outrebounded the Kings all by himself, 14-12.
</P>
<P>
   His line after the 113-86 win, a game that was anti-climactic
after the first quarter, was exactly what one would expect in a
must-win game by the NBA's MVP-to-be -- 32 points, 18 rebounds, 3
blocks, 4 assists, and total domination regardless of what
combination of players the Kings threw at him, quite literally on
some occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq turned to me right before the start and said `let me
start this game off,' '' said Lakers coach Phil Jackson. ``He
wanted to display his dominance. It means a lot to him. He's going
to be named the MVP in a few weeks, and he wants to prove to
everybody that he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But truly, Shaq Fu had nothing to prove Friday, and neither did
No. 1-A in the Lakers entry, Kobe Bryant, who contributed the kind
of poised, totally-in-control game we now have come to expect (17
points, 6 assists, 3 blocks, 1 turnover). They weren't the source
of the two losses in Sacramento that created Friday's must-win
game, and while the result bore their imprint, it was what everyone
else did that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   The best two-man team in the NBA today, or even the best duo of
the league's past, is incapable of winning a NBA playoff series if
everyone else decides to spectate. (Please note that the phrase
``two-man'' does not include the retired Michael Jordan and anyone
else).
</P>
<P>
   That was the Lakers' problem in the state capital. Glen Rice,
A.C. Green, Robert Horry and friends were all inanimate objects.
They didn't play poorly, they just didn't play. In the 148 minutes
of Game 4 played by those not named Shaq or Kobe, they contributed
just 10 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, they all played. In the first quarter, the choir made
6-of-13 field goals, including three baskets by the oft-invisible
Rice. In the second quarter, they made 6-of-10, five of them coming
off the bench, from Horry and Derek Fisher. The Lakers had more
assists in the first half Friday (18) than they had in all of Game
4 (12).
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and played the kind of game we talked about,''
Jackson said. ``The bench was very good. I didn't even tell Derek
before the game that he'd play. The minutes Travis Knight and Rick
Fox were also important within the context of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also came out and told the refs to watch the Kings'
illegal defense, a source of complaint in the two games in
Sacramento. It was the last words Shaq said before tipoff, and the
Kings were called for a zone three times in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame we have to play to that rule and demonstrate the
obvious,'' said Jackson. ``What it did was keep them from playing
so compacted on Shaq. They had to bring (Chris) Webber out, and it
gave us much better spacing.'' So at least for the moment, the
upset-o-meter can be set aside. Being forced to the max in the
first round recalled the miseries of the last three seasons, with
the added cloud of a league-best 67-15 regular season record. The
tale of the 1981 season was often told, that first round loss to
Houston in an idiotic best-of-three three series.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmists now can harken back to 1990, when the Lakers went
63-19 in the regular season and lost their second round match to
Phoenix, the same franchise that is on-deck. All this history
matters not at all to Jackson, but it is interesting to note that
this is new territory for the man who directed the AME Church -- as
in Air Michael Entertainment -- in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In nine previous seasons as a head coach, Jackson never faced a
series-deciding final game in the first round. His record in first
round games before the Sacramento series was 27-2, including seven
3-0 sweeps. His only first-round losses were by his first Bulls
team (1990) and one without Jordan (1995).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Kings series was only the fifth time in 32 series
that Jackson, owner of a NBA record 114-43 postseason mark, has
ever been forced to a deciding game. In nine seasons in Chicago,
the Bulls were forced to a Game 7 just four times, and Jackson went
2-2 -- losses in 1990 (Eastern finals to eventual champion Detroit)
and 1994 (second round to New York without Jordan), and wins in
1992 (round two, New York( and 1998 (Eastern finals, Indiana). For
someone who has done more in a decade of coaching than some coaches
do in three, it's sort of intriguing that there's actually some
unchartered territory here.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jackson was taking the same character test Friday night as
his players. ``Sacramento gave us a lot of push,'' he said. ``We
grew because of that. We learned a lot about ourselves. We needed a
trial by fire. We need to think as one. We are still a ways away
from that mental grip, but this is part of the process you have to
go through to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever sage advice or eastern philosophy he fed the team
Friday obviously worked. When we're all done with these playoffs,
and the Lakers have stapled another title flag to the wall, we may
look back on Game 5 Friday as a key moment. Then again, maybe we're
all just having a good time watching Godzilla eat his way across
America, and Jackson's true genius was getting invited to dinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 0354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 04:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7518 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN     05-06 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ROUT KINGS, SUNS NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A funny thing happened on the way to the greatest
upset in NBA history. A predictable thing, actually. The team that
was favored to win, the one on its home floor, the one with the two
superstars and the legend for a coach, the great record and even
greater expectations, made a stand.
</P>
<P>
   Just like 67-win teams are supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   One major stand, one major rout, and the Los Angeles Lakers had
snuffed out the upstart Sacramento Kings in a fabulously easy
113-86 victory Friday night before an energized sellout crowd of
18,997 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   After watching a 2-0 series lead slip to 2-2, the Lakers finally
finished off the Kings - and avoided becoming just the third No.1
seed ever to lose to a No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   They rediscovered their swagger, and perhaps restored their
standing as budding champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't really worried about anything,'' said Shaquille
O'Neal, who led the way with 32 points and 18 rebounds. ``We knew
if we didn't bring our `A' game, then we were going to make history
tonight. We didn't want to make history that way. So everybody
brought their `A' games, and my hat's off to my teammates. They
played well.''
</P>
<P>
   The first team in the regular-season standings became the last
team to clinch a second-round berth. And there will be little time
to savor the win - the Lakers open the second round Sunday
afternoon against the Phoenix Suns at Staples.
</P>
<P>
   They'll head into that series with renewed confidence after
holding the league's most potent offense to 86 points and 33.8
percent shooting. With O'Neal clicking early, Kobe Bryant and Glen
Rice contributing immediately and a rejuvenated bench, the Lakers
shot 52.2 percent and led wire-to-wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big performance by this team,'' said Lakers coach Phil
Jackson. ``They came out with a lot of guns and a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   And, having survived teetering on the brink of elimination, are
a better team for the experience, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to congratulate the Sacramento Kings on their effort,
their tremendous effort as a basketball club,'' he said. ``They
gave us a lot of push. And we needed that as a basketball team if
we're going to advance and continue on. And I think that we grew
because of that as a team. Hopefully, we learned a lot about
ourselves in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, who frustrated the Lakers throughout the season and
beat them convincingly just three nights earlier in Sacramento, had
nothing left. They watched the Lakers take a double-digit lead a
minute into the second quarter and never got closer than 15 points
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   There were no more chest-thumping heroics for Sacramento's Chris
Webber. After dominating the Lakers for most of the series, Webber
labored to get 20 points (on 7-of-21 shooting) and got no help from
his teammates. No other King scored in double digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hurt,'' Webber said. ``I'm very discouraged, mad, sad and
all those words.... Those guys were ready at home.''
</P>
<P>
   It all stood in stark contrast to the Lakers' two losses at Arco
Arena. But then, that's just what the Lakers said would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God,'' O'Neal said, ``for homecourt advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   As with any Lakers romp, everything began with O'Neal. After
struggling through two games in Sacramento - his ``Clark Kent
games'' - O'Neal brought back his Superman cape and made 15 of 24
field goals in 34 minutes of work. He also blocked three shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank my father for keeping me straight,'' O'Neal
said. ``I was kind of down on myself because I had two bad games at
Sacramento. He said, `You idiot, you always play bad at Sacramento.
Just play good at home.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant pitched in 17 points and six assists (his high for
the series), making 7 of 16 shots in 34 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Every move the Lakers might have scripted, every need Jackson
had identified, every hope they had for a turnaround, played out
perfectly in the first half, netting them a 59-44 lead by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   They needed O'Neal's aggression, and he opened the game with a
turnaround jumper over Vlade Divac to give the Lakers the only lead
they needed, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille turned to me before the game started and said, `Let
me start the game off first,''' Jackson said. ``It was a very good
indication.''
</P>
<P>
   They needed a resurgent bench, and Derek Fisher - who didn't
even play in Game 4 - hit all four of his field-goal attempts in
the first half, leading a bench effort that produced 14 points by
halftime and 36 in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was also clear from the outset that the officials intended to
end the ongoing debate over illegal defense. The Lakers were called
for their first violation 56 seconds into the game. The Kings got
tagged for a violation 69 seconds later - then got hit again six
seconds after that for a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   That got the Kings off of O'Neal's back, and the Lakers offense
did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had faith in the system,'' Bryant said. ``We knew it was
going to be tough for any team to beat us three times in a row.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
