<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 04:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KINGSIDE-LADN     05-06 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KINGSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS EXPECT MORE NEXT SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was different this time for the Sacramento
Kings, losing in the first round of the playoffs for the second
straight season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, success was such a new feeling it was an achievement
just to be playing the postseason. This year, getting there wasn't
enough, nor was pushing the top-seeded Lakers to a fifth and
deciding game before falling 113-86 at Staples Center on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento did the same thing a year ago against the heavily
favored Utah Jazz, losing in overtime in game five.
</P>
<P>
   That's getting old. Sacramento wants more now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being America's sweetheart team and playing on TV's not
enough,'' Chris Webber said.
</P>
<P>
   At times Webber seemed to be playing alone Friday, although he
finished with just 20 points on 7 of 21 shooting. But those numbers
were huge compared to Vlade Divac (four points ) and Jason
Williams, who had more gestures to the crowd than assists - he
finished with one.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Corliss Williamson (two points ) and Nick
Anderson (three points), who provided nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us on this team need to know that in order to make
names for ourselves we need to play big in big games,'' Webber
said.
</P>
<P>
   The blowout loss exposed the Kings for what they were this year:
A good home team that struggled on the road. That's enough to get
teams into the playoffs, but insufficient to advance.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied atmosphere at Sacramento's Arco Arena lifts the
emotional Kings to another level. On the road they're merely
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento was 30-11 at home this year and 14-27 everywhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast was especially evident Friday by the lack of
contributions Sacramento got from everyone else besides Webber,
especially reserves who played so well in two wins in Sacramento.
Pedrag Stojakovic, who had 19 and 12 points up north, had only
eight. Tony Delk, the steady backup point guard who broke the
Lakers' spirit the last two games, wasn't a factor with eight
points and one assist.
</P>
<P>
   It showed too in Sacramento's body language. The hard double and
triple teams that frustrated Shaquille O'Neal weren't nearly as
aggressive or sharp Friday, resulting in three illegal defense
violations and two technical fouls. O'Neal took full advantage,
ripping the Kings with 32 points and 18 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be a better team we've got to learn to play
on the road,'' Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said. ``We haven't
been that way this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the energy the Kings played with at home was absent
in Los Angeles, especially at key points. They couldn't close in on
the Lakers to end the first half, then collapsed in the third
quarter, falling behind 89-62.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the game right there,'' Adelman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 0401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
