<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 04:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7520 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN     05-06 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LONGER MISSING IN ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Imagine the Sacramento Kings' surprise. It turns
out the Los Angeles Lakers really do have more than three players.
Turns out - shock of shocks - they even have a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' stars came through in their stunning 113-86 victory
over the Kings in Game 5 on Friday night, but look who else showed
up.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!!off!Derek Fisher, a guy who couldn't even get off the
bench in Game 4,hit his first four shots and helped shut down
Sacramento sparkplug TonyDelk (2 for 9).
</P>
<P>
   --A.C. Green, who looked like he had little interest in playing
in the last game, scored 10 points and added six rebounds, three
assists and two steals.
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Horry, who hit but a lone field goal in Game 3, had
eight points, seven rebounds and teamed with Green to make the
Kings' Chris Webber (7 of 21) look very human.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally our supporting players showed up,'' Horry said. ``We'd
been missing. I think the key was Fish coming in and hitting his
first shots. That kind of got us going.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was an unexpected Friday star. This came after he never
left the bench Tuesday in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely bothered me,'' Fisher said. ``I'm not sure why I
didn't play. We fell behind and I guess (coach Phil Jackson) needed
Kobe (Bryant) in there most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely trying to help us get out to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much was going to go wrong for the Lakers on this night.
Diesel was refueled, Bryant was connecting, Glen Rice was a factor,
and for the first time, the Staples Center crowd had the arena
throbbing.
</P>
<P>
   And then all those background players got into the act. Suddenly
the Lakers were playing with energy, were more active, more
confident more like the team that won 67 games in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   A team that learned it could count on production from more than
their Big Three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not going to go down, not being aggressive,'' Green
said. ``I was looking for my shot. Phil wanted me to, and it's
going to be the same way against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one was ready tonight. Even little A.C. the Bear in my
pocket was trying to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers bench had been outscored 44-8 in Game 4, but Fisher
made it known quickly that would not happened again. He hit his
first four shots - including three jumpers from about 18 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sort of the way it worked out,'' Fisher said. ``You
know the three big guys are going to score, but it's been awhile
since several guys came off the bench and contributed
offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Aided by a fourth quarter that became an entire period of
garbage time, the Lakers bench scored 36 points. Six less than
Sacramento's, but a significant amount no less.
</P>
<P>
   The background players had caught a glimpse of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are professionals, they know what to do,'' Green
said. ``They wanted to win, and their competitiveness came out
tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 0405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 04:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7521 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-06 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ WAVES HIS MAGIC WAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If producing under pressure was easy, there'd be
as many players of the hour as there are hours in the day.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason the common fan doesn't cry out, ``You one of da
men!''or try to tug on Supermen's capes.
</P>
<P>
   The plain truth, one-time Laker Tom Hawkins has said, is more
players than not don't want the basketball in tight spots, their
fear of looking bad overriding their driving ambition.
</P>
<P>
   That goes for players big and really, really tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Wilt was that way,'' Hawkins once said, referring to
Wilt Chamberlain, his 7-foot-1 teammate on the 1968-69 Lakers,
``partly because he knew he'd be the first player to be blamed for
any defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain averaged an astonishing 50 points one season and
routinely led the league in rebounding. Yet it wasn't until he won
his first NBA title, in his eighth season, that he was able to lose
the underachiever label that others had pinned on him.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal found himself in Chamberlain's shoes Friday and
naturally everyone was straining to see, were they made of cement?
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' 7-foot-1 center was fresh off an exquisite regular
season in which he ranked in the top-three in the league in
scoring, rebounding, blocked shots and field goal percentage. The
NBA was his smorgasbord; all the other players were reduced to
begging for his scraps.
</P>
<P>
   Then came two bad playoff performances in Sacramento and in the
span of 48 hours O'Neal's detractors were flocking to his side to
apply the Heimlich maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Another uninspired performance in the Lakers' decisive Game 5 of
their first-round playoff series against the Kings and the six
sensational months that preceded it would have been forgotten
faster than yesterday's fad.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq's name would have been O'Heel.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Neal was Wilt-ing under the white-hot spotlight, he hid it
well from his teammates. He seemed his same old imperturbable self
before the game; indeed, he sidled up to Phil Jackson and
respectfully asked to be fed the ball for the first shot. Once the
game started, it was little wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal left little doubt that this year's league MVP was in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   And no, Sacramento fans, we aren't talking about Chris ``Call Me
Pained'' Webber.
</P>
<P>
   On the Lakers' first possession, O'Neal converted a feathery
hook over his nemesis Vlade Divac. He made five of his first six
shots, outrebounded the entire Kings team 14-12 in the first half,
blocked three shots and added four assists for the heck of it to
carry the Lakers past Sacramento, 113-86, and into the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's fast start (10 points and seven rebounds in the first
11 minutes) was so sweet, it seemed to give all his teammates a
sugar rush. Derek Fisher, who didn't play in Game 4, came off the
bench and contributed eight points in his first nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Another reserve, forward Robert Horry, made three of his first
four shots on his way to eight points. He also grabbed seven
rebounds, five of them on the defensive end. On the strength of
Fisher's moxie and Horry's muscle, the Lakers turned the benches on
the Kings; Sacramento's reserves had outscored their L.A.
counterparts 140-64 in the first four games but the Laker reserves
pretty much held their own on this night with 36 points.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was less a center than a symphony conductor, establishing
the tone and timbre of the Lakers' four-part harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were so helpless to stop O'Neal, they picked up three
illegal defense calls in the first quarter trying.
</P>
<P>
   The Staples Center sellout crowd was so relieved to see the
highlight reel O'Neal, it cheered loud enough that, for a change,
ears were ringing instead of cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq was ready to play,'' said Lakers forward A.C. Green. ``He
was motivated. He was hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for O'Neal and Co. is Phoenix, which was winless in four
games against the Lakers during the regular season. If O'Neal can
make the Suns set, his detractors will dwindle to an obstinate few.
</P>
<P>
   Despite everybody's nit-picking, O'Neal's championship plate
looks to be replenished and his appetite, again ravenous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like he gobbled up every defensive rebound,'' said
Fisher of O'Neal, who had 11 defensive boards. ``He can give us 30
points every night. But what he brings defensively makes us a great
team instead of a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   It also moves O'Neal ever closer to getting his due as a great
player instead of merely a very, very gifted one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 0408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7526 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TOYS-POLITICS-REVIEW-     05-06 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOY STORY: POLITICIANS `R' US 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By BRUCE KLUGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tempest is brewing in Washington, all because of an 11-inch
blonde bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel, in association with two nonprofit women's groups,
recently announced plans for a Barbie for President 2000 doll, a
power-suited, high-heeled White House hopeful who comes complete
with a pearl necklace and a Girls' Bill of Rights. Mattel says it
hopes the doll will ``broaden girls' vision of what's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately the protests sounded. Last week in an article
on the Op-Ed page of The New York Times, the former Colorado
congresswoman and one-time presidential candidate Patricia
Schroeder assailed the plastic politico as a giant leap backward
for womankind. ``Why should we feel great about a message that says
a woman can go to the White House if she looks like Barbie?''
Schroeder asked. ``I'm sorry, but I just can't get enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, why shouldn't American children learn about civics
and the virtues of public service via their favorite playthings?
Rather than jeer at this star-spangled Barbie, let's extend the
concept to other shelves at Toy Barn.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Potato Head
</P>
<P>
   What better way to teach the country's youth about the
versatility of the modern politician than by crossing a U.S.
senator with everybody's favorite synthetic spud? But instead of
the traditional plug-in eyes, nose, lips and limbs, Sen. Potato
Head (Independent of Idaho) comes equipped with interchangeable
position papers, a removable spine and a special ``two-face''
feature that allows the toy tater to talk out of both sides of its
mouth. (Manufacturer's note: On the Dan Quayle model of Sen.
Potatoe Head, the extra ``e'' is sold separately.)
</P>
<P>
   Tickle Me Reno
</P>
<P>
   The events of recent weeks have put a clearly beleaguered
Attorney General Janet Reno back in the national spotlight. Lest
children believe the job of AG is completely joyless, here comes a
fluffy, happy effigy of the nation's top cop that giggles and
chortles on command. This huggable toy was developed after several
failures, notably the ill-fated Tickle Me Zoe and Tickle Me Kimba
dolls, which, despite repeated efforts, never found anything to
laugh at.
</P>
<P>
   GI Joe Lockhart
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the battle fatigues, helmet and rifle. In their place a
tailored gray suit, briefing book and White House podium. Still, GI
Joe Lockhart, a pocket-sized version of the embattled press
secretary, is every bit as prepped for trench warfare as his
fox-holed predecessor _ he's the ultimate spin-controlling war
machine. Roll up his sleeves and let him slug it out with Sam
Donaldson; slip on his windbreaker and breeze him past reporters as
he boards the presidential chopper (not included). This is truly
one ``fighting Joe from head to toe.'' (Coming soon: A special
two-pack that includes a companion Helen Thomas doll.)
</P>
<P>
   Curious George Stephanapoulos
</P>
<P>
   Kids will love this video adaptation of the classic book series
starring the former White House aide as the mischievous monkey. The
first three releases: ``Curious George Goes to Washington,''
``Curious George Writes a Memoir'' and ``Curious George Can't Get
His Calls Returned.'' (James Carville co-stars as the Man in the
Yellow Hat.)
</P>
<P>
   Talking Head Teletubbies
</P>
<P>
   That colorful quartet of cuddlies with antennae on their heads
and TV screens in their bellies now features running political
commentary on the tummy monitors, courtesy of America's leading
pundits. Each Teletubbie is assigned its own talking head _ Tinky
Winky (Tim Russert), Dipsy (George Will), Laa-Laa (Cokie Roberts)
and Po (Matt Drudge) _ which means tykes can play in silence for
hours on end as their adorable Tubbies hash it out among
themselves. (Plans for the Charlie Rose Teletubbie were canceled
when manufacturers were unable to get the doll to stop talking.)
</P>
<P>
   Jujitsu Justices
</P>
<P>
   Step aside, Justice Scalia; take a powder, Justice O'Connor _
there's a new Supreme Court in town. The first Mighty Morphin Power
Rangers to sit on the high bench, this collector's set of robed
action figures metes out justice in ways the Rehnquist court can
only dream about. Miranda warning? Forget about it. First
Amendment? You've got to be kidding. This gang totes lasers, not
gavels. Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemonica
</P>
<P>
   And you thought Pikachu was the coolest member of the gang _
well, here comes the toughest pocket monster of them all. The only
Pokemon character to have survived battles with such nemeses as
Starrmander and Trippleypuff, Pokemonica is available in a variety
of sizes, comes with her own sports car and designer cell phone,
and boasts a wardrobe of more than two dozen dresses. None of them
blue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0654 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TOYS-POLITICS-REVIEW-     05-06 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOY STORY: POLITICIANS `R' US 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
