<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-MADCOW-ART-860     05-06 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MADCOW-ART-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE GOES ON THE OFFENSIVE AGAINST MAD COW DISEASE
</HEADLINE>
  By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUELLAS, France _ At first, the veterinarian said that it might
just be milk fever. Then the possibility of a brain tumor was
discussed. But as the laboratory took longer and longer to report
test results, Guy Jambon accepted the inevitable. It was mad cow
disease, although none had ever been detected in this southeast
region of France.
</P>
<P>
   The health department trucks came a few days later, on Feb. 18,
and in one morning all 670 of Jambon's cows were taken for
slaughter and incineration, leaving the barns, the pens, the
milking room and the fields empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part that got to you was how quiet it was,'' said Jambon,
who with his brother and two other partners had built up the herd
over 25 years. ``I was saying to myself: We don't really understand
anything. How did the cow get this disease? How did this happen
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Jambon is not alone in raising such questions. The number of
cases of mad cow disease discovered in France has been climbing
steadily. The totals are still minuscule compared with those in
Britain, which has reported 178,000 cases of the deadly
degenerative brain disease since 1986 and endured a ban on its beef
by European nations.
</P>
<P>
   But what is alarming in France is that the numbers are going up,
given that preventive measures were introduced in 1991 and even
stricter ones were ordered in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that mad cow disease continues to loom over
Europe like an advancing shadow, many experts say, with much about
it still a mystery. In the last few years, more and more countries
have reported cases of the disease, which is also known as bovine
spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE.
</P>
<P>
   It has now been discovered in native-born cows in 10 European
countries, including Belgium, the Netherlands, Denmark, Portugal,
Liechtenstein and Luxembourg. Switzerland, which began a testing
program a year ago, has discovered more than 350 cases so far. In
France, six cases were detected in 1997, 18 in 1998 and 30 in 1999.
In the first four months of this year, 16 cases have already been
detected, roughly one a week.
</P>
<P>
   Using newly developed tests, France intends to start a random
testing program of cows that have died after exhibiting suspicious
behavior. The program should look at as many as 50,000 of France's
21 million head of cattle each year. Martin Hirsch, the head of
France's new food safety agency, is, like many other officials
here, bracing himself for the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could certainly show that there is much more mad cow out
there than we have detected so far,'' Hirsch said. ``We just don't
know. There is so much we don't know about this disease, we can
hardly say with confidence that it is under control. We'll have to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   French scientists are not the only ones concerned. Earlier this
year, a group of scientists advising the European Union on the
issue warned that millions of Europeans may be at risk of catching
Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease, the fatal human version of BSE, despite
their governments' contentions that their countries are free of the
disease. The union has been urging broader preventive measures
throughout its 15 member countries. But some countries have
refused, maintaining that they do not have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see these measures taken,'' said Beate
Gminder, a spokeswoman for David Byrne, the European food safety
commissioner. ``The number of cases of mad cow may be much larger
than we know. It could be that cases exist much more extensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are still highly puzzled by the disease, which was
first recognized in cows in 1986. It appears that it is not a
bacteria, a virus or fungi, but stems from infectious particles
called prions, perhaps acting in concert with a virus or other
agent. The disease kills cells in the brain, leaving it full of
holes like a sponge.
</P>
<P>
   Since the human form of the disease was first recognized in
1995, more than 35 people have died of it in Britain. Estimates of
how many people are likely to be infected by the disease range
widely. Some British scientists have speculated that 75 more people
will die of the disease in the next 20 years. Others say 80,000,
depending on the incubation period and how the infection is passed
from animal to human.
</P>
<P>
   No one yet knows how much infected meat someone must eat before
the lethal brain-wasting disease takes hold, or if some other
factor must be present, too. Efforts to prevent the disease in cows
so far have centered on eliminating animal feed that is laced with
infected animal parts.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts believe that apart from foodstuffs and
cow-to-calf transmission, there may be a third, and yet unknown,
mode of transmission.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   France's agriculture minister, Jean Glavany, recently set off an
uproar here by merely mentioning that possibility in a newspaper
interview. But experts studying the disease said his speculation
was nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This disease is one of the great mysteries of the century,''
Hirsch said. ``We don't know exactly what is the nature of this
disease, so we don't know what steps to take to prevent it. We do
have many questions about modes of transmission. We are looking at
different things.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, France has taken perhaps the most conservative position
in Europe, refusing to even accept British beef despite assurances
by European Union officials that it is as safe as any other beef on
the market. (The union is currently moving forward with a lawsuit
against France over the matter.)
</P>
<P>
   But while the union may feel France has gone too far in trying
to protect itself from British meat, it is urging many European
countries to take more precautions against mad cow disease than
they have been willing to take so far.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven European Union countries, including Britain and
France, have taken the strictest preventive measures, Not only do
they control the animal feed, but they also prevent the parts of
the cattle most likely to carry prions, including the brain, spinal
material and intestines, from even entering the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission would like Austria, Denmark, Finland,
Germany, Greece, Sweden, Italy and Spain to do the same. (Italy and
Spain currently ban only the most infective parts of the beef from
countries with known cases of the disease.) The union is also
planning a monitoring program starting in 2001 that would test up
to 65,000 cows a year throughout the European Union to build a
realistic picture of a disease that many fear is underreported.
</P>
<P>
   Britain with its 178,000 cases has been hit hardest by the
disease. Ireland with 466 cases and Portugal with 371 have the next
highest number of cases. Then comes France with 92 cases detected
since 1991. Most of France's cases have been in the north, where
there is more likelihood of exchanges of feed and cattle with
Britain. But nowadays cases have begun to be detected in other
regions of France.
</P>
<P>
   French officials had predicted that because of their precautions
cases of the disease would be declining by now. Experts note that
it no doubt took a while for the 1996 regulations banning animal
parts from animal feed to take hold. And there may also be
instances in which regulations were ignored and the effects are now
being seen. A recent European Union report still noted incidents of
French feed with traces of meat and bone meal despite the ban. But
some experts say they are not sure such incidents can account for
the rise in numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Britain's Conservative Party has called for a
European ban on French beef. But the appeal has largely been
dismissed as a political tit-for-tat, as the numbers of infected
cattle are still very small. In addition to France, the United
States continues to ban British beef. But it does not have similar
restrictions on beef from elsewhere in Europe, Gminder said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, French farm unions and the government have stepped in
quickly to help the farmers who have had cattle with mad cow
disease. Within a week of losing his cows, Jambon had 30 calves
back on his farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was at least something to keep him busy,'' said Gilbert
Limandas, the president of the local farming union. ``There is no
question that this is a real trauma for the farmers. A herd like
Jambon's was built up over generations. Then, like that it is all
gone. ''
</P>
<P>
   Farm unions here have petitioned the government to spend more on
studying the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Eight weeks after his cows were carted away, Jambon had 520 new
cows, most donated by farms in the area near Lyon. He is pleased
with the quality of the animals. He has changed nothing about his
work, he says. ``There are no precautions to take because I had
already taken all the precautions I knew about. So, I'm back doing
the same thing and hoping it doesn't happen again. We are all
wondering: Who will it hit next?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7534 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-AFRICA-OBSTACLES-REVI     05-06 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-OBSTACLES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE U.S. AND AFRICA: EXTENDING A TREMBLING, HESITANT HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For most of a year now, the United States has been
proclaiming its intention to get more involved in the fate of
Africa _ in calming its wars, in building its economies.
</P>
<P>
   The 11,000 men of the U.N. peacekeeping force sent into Sierra
Leone, and the helicopter gunships reinforcing them, were the first
tangible sign that this intention would amount to more than words.
The soldiers were from third-world countries but their assignment
was being paid for in part with $70 million from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And another peacekeeping force has been waiting in the wings to
try to pacify the even more embattled Congo. The Clinton
administration has been hoping that these two forces together would
forever refute the notion that the international community has been
eager to right wrongs in Europe and Asia, but has another set of
rules for Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Sierra Leone mission is in trouble. By Friday night,
more than 300 of the force's troops were hostage, four were missing
and presumed dead and rebels were riding in captured U.N. armored
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   That debacle and the hesitant response to it in Washington _
several days of teleconferences among officials of the CIA, the
Pentagon and the National Security Council but no action, no
decisions _ demonstrate yet again that doing good in Africa takes
more than good intentions. Now the likelihood of deployment of even
the modest force for Congo _ 500 monitors protected by 5,000
soldiers _ looks more distant, despite a formal agreement last week
from the Congo leader, Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   The second track of the administration's Africa policy _
economic partnership _ was also delivering less than had been
promised. Even as the House of Representatives approved a trade
bill granting some new trading privileges to Africa, there were
doubts whether many countries on the continent have the economic
capacity to take advantage of it. And on the much-discussed subject
of AIDS, the bill sent a singular snub: In the final version,
bowing to American pharmaceutical companies, Congress dropped a
provision intended to make AIDS drugs more affordable by lowering
the licensing fees for African drug manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has experienced two defining moments
in Africa, barely six months apart. The first was the slaughter of
17 U.S. soldiers in Mogadishu, Somalia, in October 1993 and the
dragging of one of the bodies through the streets. The following
spring, the administration remained largely silent as a genocide
unfolded in Rwanda after the United States agreed to the removal of
a U.N. military force there.
</P>
<P>
   After Mogadishu, President Clinton chose to shy away from
risking such casualties or humiliation again; after Rwanda, he said
genocide could not be tolerated again.
</P>
<P>
   But those are incompatible goals, and in its twilight months,
the Clinton administration is strangled by its own constraints as
it contemplates the options in places like Sierra Leone, Congo,
Angola, Ethiopia, Eritrea and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   A collapse of the peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone could
portend far more than just the loss of a military effort in a
small, desperate West African country. At stake, some officials
argue, is the prestige of the United States within the United
Nations. The U.S. representative there, Richard C. Holbrooke, has
worked hard to fix the frayed U.N.-U.S. relationship, lobbying
Congress to restore funding and urging foreign diplomats to
understand the American political mood. Last week he was in Congo
with U.N. colleagues trying to assess whether it is peaceful enough
to send in the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, Holbrooke needs the 54 votes of African
nations, many of whom have been willing to suspend their
disillusionment with Washington if the Sierra Leone and Congo
peacekeeping missions can be made to work.
</P>
<P>
   But many also still resent the evident Western view that Africa
deserves to be marginalized because its problems run so deep. They
argue that some hope should be gleaned from democratic elections
here and there, from economic turn-arounds. They point to
Mozambique, strengthened by investment from neighboring South
Africa; to Kenya, where President Daniel arap Moi has taken steps
that could reduce corruption; to Nigeria, whose new president,
Olusegun Obasanjo, has assumed the mantle of a regional leader
(although his troops, which Western countries wouldn't finance,
pulled out of Sierra Leone after being roughed up by rebel thugs).
</P>
<P>
   Most important to hopes for peacekeeping, some African countries
now have armies that are willing to take part in international
forces on the continent. But it is also clear that African states
are not capable of dealing with big crises like Congo or Sierra
Leone. For these, they look to the United Nations, and thus the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in Sierra Leone is that the big powers on the
Security Council won't use their own forces, and this has left the
United Nations relying on frightened soldiers from less capable
armies _ the kind who sometimes give up their armored personnel
carriers when confronted by teen-agers with rifles at a roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   The minister of state for foreign affairs of Uganda, Amama
Mbabazi, put it this way earlier this year: ``When it is Kosovo you
are there in one minute and spend billions. When it's East Timor
you are there. When it is Africa, there are all sorts of excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   So the basic problem of what to do about Africa remains, despite
the administration's determination to get more involved. ``There
are huge stakes'' if the Sierra Leone operation fails, said one
official. ``We have to play pretty tough. Otherwise we are going to
walk away yet again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
