<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      05-06 1742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, May 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-DISARM (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ The Irish
Republican Army announced Saturday that it will soon begin
disarming. (Summary from wires.) By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Vladimir Kalamanov may have the
hardest job in Russia. As the Kremlin's special envoy for human
rights, his task is to persuade a skeptical West that Russia is
serious about ending human rights abuses in Chechnya. It is not
hard to see why it has been a hard sell. Despite numerous accounts
of pillaging, beatings and killings by Russian troops in Chechnya,
only a handful of cases have been investigated by military
prosecutors. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ROMAN-RUINS (Belkis, Turkey) _ Here, as in several parts
of southern Turkey, water is rising inexorably around a doomed
village as an artificial lake builds up behind a new dam, part of
the government's ambitious plans to generate electric power and
irrigate vast areas of dry land. But in Belkis, the swelling waters
are not just disrupting lives. In the last few months,
archaeologists have found that an ancient city that once stood here
holds what many experts are calling one of the world's richest
collections of Roman mosaics. Much of it is about to disappear
before anyone has a chance to see it. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-MADCOW (Buellas, France) _ The number of cases of mad cow
disease discovered in France has been climbing steadily. The totals
are still minuscule compared with those in Britain, which has
reported 178,000 cases of the deadly degenerative brain disease
since 1986. But what is alarming in France is that the numbers are
going up, even though preventive measures were introduced in 1991
and even stricter ones were ordered in 1996. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PUBLISHER (Washington) _ For all the problems of Kosovo
today, Veton Surroi, the publisher of the province's largest
newspaper, reminds himself that things could be much worse. ``We
could have well ended up like the Kurds and made good posters for
Amnesty International,'' he said. Instead, Surroi, who is viewed by
many diplomats as a voice of reason in a traumatized corner of
Europe, is trying to shape what he hopes will one day be a civil
society. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Ten months after they fled
the province in the face of revenge attacks from Kosovo Albanians,
the Serbs of Kosovo and other minorities are seeing international
political will swing in their favor. Preparations to help hundreds,
even thousands, of Serbs and Gypsies to return this summer are
gaining momentum and have sparked vigorous competition between
local Serbian leaders to reap the political rewards of bringing
people home. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   PEACEKEEPING-ZAMBIA (Lusaka, Zambia) _ The president of Zambia
said Saturday that the 200 Zambian peacekeepers taken hostage in
Sierra Leone had been deployed too quickly into unknown territory
with out of date maps and a shortage of other vital equipment. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS (Pretoria, South Africa) _ In a strikingly personal
speech, President Thabo Mbeki offered his first detailed
explanation of how he came to consult with two Americans who argue
that HIV does not cause AIDS. The decision, which became public two
months ago, quickly touched off a firestorm of criticism at home
and abroad. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Dateline TK) _ Developments in the U.N. hostage
crisis. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-U.N. (Kinshasa, Congo) _ Richard Holbrooke leads efforts
to set up a U.N. operation in Congo, a far huger nation than Sierra
Leone, which is to be patrolled by far fewer peacekeepers. By
Norimitsu Onishi and Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ In the shadowy world of Japanese
politics true turning points can be difficult to spot. But in the
last few weeks, after the incapacitating stroke suffered by a
sitting prime minister, and the retirement from politics of a
former prime minister who was his mentor, Japanese politicians and
commentators have begun to speak of the end of a style of factional
politics that has been in force for 45 years. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   PUTIN-ST.PETERSBURG (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ The first time
Vladimir Putin deserted Moscow and staged a meeting with a visiting
head of state here, Russians hardly noticed. That was in March,
when Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain came to the city that
Peter the Great built. But the second time it happened, when Putin
flew here to meet Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori of Japan, tongues
started wagging that Putin was raising the status of his hometown
in a manner that touched the historical chord of rivalry between
Moscow and St. Petersburg. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-SAVINGS (Undated) _ Americans took home some 2.8 billion
prescriptions last year. They bought many of those medications as
members of managed care drug plans run by pharmacy benefit
managers, companies that arrange discounts from retail drugstores
and often operate mail-order pharmacies on behalf of employer
health plans. Now the pharmacy benefit management companies, or
PBMs, which handle drug benefits for 200 million Americans, are
being assigned an important role in widely discussed proposals to
add a drug benefit to Medicare. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS-OVERNITE (Atlanta) _ The grueling Overnite
Transportation Co. strike has become James P. Hoffa's biggest labor
battle in his first year as Teamsters' president. It has become not
only one of the nation's most closely watched labor showdowns, but
also a brawl between a union renowned for its toughness and a
scrappy company that is showing just as much grit. Neither Hoffa
nor Overnite's parent company, Union Pacific, has offered the
slightest hint of blinking. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-MOM-MARCH (WESTMINSTER, Md.) _ After dealing with
exaggerated crowd estimates and warnings of disruption at the
recent World Bank protest in Washington, officials there are saying
the Million Mom March could prove the real sleeper protest of the
spring marching season. The multicity crowds from all manner of
family, kith and kin are determined to force the gun control issue
higher up the political agenda, led by mothers wheeling offspring
toward Capitol Hill in phalanxes of strollers. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-FRACAS (Undated) _ The 10-year project to decode the
human genome is entering its end game, but the high goal of
unlocking the secrets of human heredity is ending in a fractious
exchange of claims and countercharges. Within a few weeks, both
contestants in the genome race plan to declare victory, but on
different terms, each already judged imperfect by the rival team.
By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS (Washington) _ President Clinton has become a
crucial behind-the-scenes player in the 2000 campaign, serving as a
tactical adviser for House, Senate and gubernatorial candidates
around the country. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Abortion politics,
Pennsylvania-style; Assessing the field, West Virginia-style; A
money-back offer from an incumbent; The god of money and the god of
Ohio; A prayer of thanks, a prayer of humility. By B. Drummond
Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-LEGISLATION (Washington) _ This week, the Senate delved
into the year's most important education bill. Democrats fashioned
a ``war room,'' where senators conducted on-line chats about
education. Republicans countered with snazzy charts and a steady
flow of news conferences. But behind all the razzle-dazzle lies one
startling possibility: This could be the first time in 35 years
that an education bill so bogs down over partisan differences that
it is vetoed by a president, if it does not get yanked from the
Senate floor altogether. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, the
chief federal trial judge in Washington, has hired a lawyer to
represent her before judicial and congressional inquiries into why
she assigned several criminal cases involving President Clinton's
associates to judges Clinton had appointed. The first act of the
lawyer, Michael Madigan, was to tell a Republican-led congressional
investigation that his client would decline to testify at any
congressional committee hearing into her behavior. By Neil A.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON-HUMOR (Washington) _ Being funny at the annual
dinners of the Alfalfa Club, the Gridiron Club, and the
associations of White House and broadcast correspondents, has
become serious business in Washington. By John Files.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Escape from the East Wing. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Learning to live with limits. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
