<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TECH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMMING THE FLOW OF FREE INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing like a blank screen to spark one's imagination.
It is the Rorschach test of the information age. And never more so
than last week, when the ABC channel on Time Warner cable systems
in seven markets went blank.
</P>
<P>
   ABC devotees in 3.5 million homes, confronted with a blue screen
and scrolling Time Warner propaganda, may have thought about the
celebrities they would not see. Marketers of satellite dishes
probably contemplated fatter sales figures. And federal lawmakers
and regulators could ponder how to prevent the gatekeepers of the
information castle from pulling up the drawbridge and leaving the
public outside.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, for those who have believed in
technology's implied promise of an information utopia, in which
people can see or hear or read whatever they want (and show or tell
or write whatever they want), it was an uncomfortable reminder: the
more information available, the more places in which it is
available, the more the logic of economics and egos will come into
play to restrict it.
</P>
<P>
   As Floyd Abrams, the noted First Amendment lawyer, said in a
speech to the Mercer Law School in Georgia in March,
``paradoxically, the effect of more information becoming more
available more quickly may be less information being made public at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the evidence for Abrams' paradox. Last week, to gain
leverage in its contract dispute over the terms under which it
could carry ABC, which is owned by Walt Disney Co., Time Warner
pulled the plug on ABC's signal.
</P>
<P>
   During the negotiations _ Disney was seeking to make its Disney
Channel part of Time Warner's basic service and to get the cable
systems to carry its Toon Disney and Soap channels _ Disney
sometimes engaged in brinkmanship. In the Houston market, Disney
came within minutes of letting Time Warner's right to carry its
programming lapse. If it had done so, it would have pulled the plug
on itself.
</P>
<P>
   Disney was offering more programming (which in turn would bring
it more advertisements and more revenue). Time Warner's cable
system is capable of carrying scores of channels. But both media
giants, under the terms of the laws, regulations and contracts
governing their business, could serve as gatekeepers and black out
the signal. More information, or less? Or more information and more
choke points where it can be shut off?
</P>
<P>
   In other situations, the promise of open access to free
information has also produced a backlash:
</P>
<P>
   _ APBNews.com, a Web site specializing in covering crime stories
and the legal system, filed a Freedom of Information Act request
for all the financial disclosure statements filed by federal
judges. At first, the financial disclosure committee of the
Judicial Conference of the United States rejected the request,
citing judges' concerns that unstable or unsavory people could
obtain their addresses or the names of family members. In March,
the Judicial Conference ruled that the reports could not be
withheld ``simply because they are going to be placed on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Associated Press, Reuters and three other international
news agencies preparing to cover the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney
were asked in January if they would wait an hour before making
results available to commercial Web sites, including their own, and
if they would credit IBM and Swatch when reporting the results. The
AP argued that the results are raw data, not subject to copyright
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Servan-Schreiber, the director of communications and
new media for the International Olympic Committee, withdrew the
requests for the time being. He maintains that copyright
protections extend to ``the tabulation'' of results, if not the
results themselves. ``The agencies want to take the real-time
results and resend it, with no value added, to other Web sites _
and give us no compensation,'' he said. ``And those Web sites would
be competitive with our Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Association of Research Libraries and various teachers'
organizations are fighting legislation that would provide
electronic databases with copyright-like protections. Leslie
Harris, a lawyer who represents some teacher groups, said, ``You
want protections to encourage creation of intellectual property,
but you also want to encourage dissemination of information in a
free society.'' She added, ``As we migrate online, the traditional
ability of my clients to say, `Great article on Martin Luther King
Day; I'll make 15 copies for my class' may not be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, laws governing intellectual property and freedom
of information overlap with the laws governing information
distribution systems and the antitrust laws. Which is not
surprising, since a basic premise of the information age is that
information itself has economic value.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, it is a matter of civic interest if television viewers
are barred from receiving ABC News programming. The issue for the
Federal Communications Commission, though, was not the free flow of
information, but the fact that the plug was pulled during sweeps
month, when stations measure their audiences to determine what to
charge advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   If a city council wants to force a cable carrier to carry any
Internet service provider, it is a matter of business regulation.
(Federal judges in Oregon and Virginia have come to opposite
conclusions on the propriety of such actions.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it is a matter of copyright law if the
National Football League objects when a reporter from The St. Paul
Pioneer Press gives real-time coverage on a Vikings game via the
newspaper's Web site. And a matter of competition, since the NFL
also has its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article in Release 1.0, Esther Dyson's technology
newsletter, the Harvard law professor Lawrence Lessig said: ``The
original architecture of the Net gave great freedom to perfect
competition. But we're seeing an erosion of that freedom now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0682 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MEDIA-TECH-REVIEW-NYT     05-06 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TECH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMMING THE FLOW OF FREE INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing like a blank screen to spark one's imagination.
It is the Rorschach test of the information age. And never more so
than last week, when the ABC channel on Time Warner cable systems
in seven markets went blank.
</P>
<P>
   ABC devotees in 3.5 million homes, confronted with a blue screen
and scrolling Time Warner propaganda, may have thought about the
celebrities they would not see. Marketers of satellite dishes
probably contemplated fatter sales figures. And federal lawmakers
and regulators could ponder how to prevent the gatekeepers of the
information castle from pulling up the drawbridge and leaving the
public outside.
</P>
