giant Microsoft, became the subjects of antitrust inquiries by the
Justice Department, which accused them of price-fixing and
collusion. Heart-rending scenes from ``Antiques Roadshow'' were
revealed to be staged. The man who couldn't believe that his Civil
War-era sword was worth $35,000 and said he once carved a
watermelon with it was not the owner of the sword, but a friend of
the appraiser.
</P>
<P>
   The program's producers removed the appraiser from all reruns.
They also spliced out a woman who brought in a $250,000 helmet and
then mysteriously disappeared amid rumors that the helmet was not
hers. And eBay, the spiritual home of a nation of appraisers, is
now the subject of three local and federal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But the bidding continues. Aspiring analysts can play stock
games on Web sites, winning prizes for speculator of the month.
Aspiring appraisers can read trade secrets in Carol Prisant's
``Antiques Roadshow Primer'' and make estimates interactively on
the PBS Internet site. On the cable channel HGTV, they can watch
``Appraise It!'' or ``The Great Antiques Hunt,'' a program that
combines elements of roadshow and game show. Contestants choose
antiques at a fair and win points based on the value of their
selections. They also estimate the cost of estate jewelry, identify
furniture and guess the ages of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to ``The Price Is Right,'' where contestants pride
themselves on knowing what things actually cost, contestants on
``The Great Antiques Hunt'' revel in imagining what things might
bring.
</P>
<P>
   At first the fascination with old-world beauty seemed a reaction
to the high-technology revolution. Technophobes and neo-Victorians
alarmed by life in a cold electronic age grew nostalgic for the
comfort of physical design. Traditionalists perturbed by the mass
of paper wealth and new money yearned for the nobility of good
taste.
</P>
<P>
   The British, who originally gave America Christie's and
Sotheby's, also exported ``Antiques Roadshow,'' ``The Great
Antiques Hunt'' and (after making the questions easier) ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire,'' spreading the reassuring notion that riches
can flow from collecting or knowing arcana.
</P>
<P>
   But strangely enough this obsession with the old has also been
fueled by new technology: the Internet has given collectors novel
and ideal ways of interacting. By reaching mass audiences, the Net
has driven up the prices of some collectibles even as it has driven
down the prices of everyday items.
</P>
<P>
   On eBay, as contemporary alchemists turn Pez dispensers into
gold, those obsessed with the old and those obsessed with the new
exchange bric-a-brac. A Sumerian fertility amulet dating from 3000
B.C. can find new buyers in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger sense, the fascination with old and new are part of
the same mania. Both roller coasters promise accessibility,
immediacy and the wonder of hidden value. With the democratization
of investing, anyone can order shares of Qualcomm while sitting
home in a bathrobe. And the formerly insular antiques world has
come to the public, intimating that those with an eye for talent
can spot the value not only of the next Intel but of the tarnished
teapot in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Professional appraisers on television sometimes take up to
several hours off camera checking a research library. But the
viewers don't see the work involved, only the result, as a moldy
footstool morphs into a small fortune in a matter of seconds. This
is better than reality television: it's television edited to
celebrate reality. In a flash, the pompous owner of a fake Faberge
egg is humiliated; the unassuming bearer of a genuine Regency box
is exalted.
</P>
<P>
   The forces at work here are more poignant than mere greed. The
fantasy of ``Antiques Roadshow'' is that the chair you loved
because your Aunt Tillie gave it to you might also bring in six
figures. It is the fantasy that sentimental value can translate
into market value, that feelings and family bonds can matter in a
material world. It's the fantasy that our old stuff is worth
something and that, by extension, we are, too. Going on ``Antiques
Roadshow'' is like holding an emotional IPO for your garage _ an
expert can tell you that you're worth more than you previously
suspected.
</P>
<P>
   Such fantasies reveal how yet another British import, Harry
Potter, has become the best-selling fairy tale of the moment.
Readers cherish the idea that a boy neglected in the everyday world
has magical powers and fancy lineage in a parallel, enchanted
realm. There, eccentricities can turn out to be talents, weird
relatives can turn out to be brilliant wizards and the worthless
can become powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The public wants to be transported to that place, where the
money-losing start-up venture becomes a dot-com to watch and the
rickety armchair in the corner is transformed into a priceless
heirloom. Losers can become winners, not only of net worth but of
self-worth: by all accounts, a happy ending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
