<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7562 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-NATIONAL-SECURITY-REV     05-06 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-SECURITY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, NATIONAL SECURITY SAYS IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ten years after recapturing Europe, Dwight D.
Eisenhower calculated that the lessons of D-Day could be usefully
applied in persuading Congress to lace the land with highways. His
administration dreamed up the National System of Interstate and
Defense Highways and argued that these roads were not only about
economic development, they were about national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case of atomic attack on our key cities,'' he wrote in
1955, ``the road net must permit quick evacuation of target areas,
mobilization of defense forces and maintenance of every essential
economic function.''
</P>
<P>
   Half a century later, the highways he built can barely handle a
5 p.m. crush of commuters in their SUVs, much less a panicky
evacuation of the capital. But if he were alive today, the old
five-star might smile to hear the latest Clinton White House
strategy. The president and his national security adviser, Samuel
R. Berger, have taken up a mantra that granting permanent
``normal'' trading status to China isn't just about profit
opportunities, it's also about national security. At the same time,
the administration has labeled the AIDS crisis in Africa a threat
to national security, and Vice President Al Gore has raised similar
fears with his ``new security agenda,'' which includes global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   Without question there is a case to be made that economic chaos,
disease and climatic upheaval can all trigger political nastiness.
So all of this new labeling raises a question: Just when does a big
problem turn into a national security threat?
</P>
<P>
   On trade with China, the Clinton administration argument is that
granting normal trade status would reassure the Chinese that
America isn't trying to hem them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a national security point of view, it would in my view be
a very, very unwise and precarious move to say that the United
States doesn't care whether they're part of the world community or
not,'' President Clinton told an insurance group last week, a theme
he repeated nightly as he tried to win over 40 or so legislators
who were still undecided about the China bill.
</P>
<P>
   Only days before, the White House was arguing that the spread of
AIDS in Africa would lead to economic collapse, political
instability and civil wars that might eventually require American
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that we have a short list of national security
threats and East Timor is now off and AIDS is on it,'' Berger said
in an interview. But strife has many origins, he said: ``If it
creates instability, chaos, conflict and war, that has national
security implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, used a foreign policy speech last weekend to
argue for the need for ``forward engagement'' (presumably a
Gore-ism for trying to think ahead). He ticked off _ in no
particular order of priority _ pandemics, economic inequality,
global warming and the digital divide as potential security
problems that had to be nipped in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   In Gore's case, the political calculation is obvious: he is
trying to portray his opponent, George W. Bush, as a man caught in
what he termed a cold-war mindset that sees national security only
in the most conventional terms.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still unclear whether the new Democratic relabeling of
issues is just shrewd political marketing _ to Democrats who don't
like trade deals, and to Republicans who don't care for foreign
aid, particularly when it involves AIDS _ or a truly new agenda for
an age of new global threats.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell. As the Clinton presidency winds down, the
definition of national security threats has gotten ever fuzzier.
Even some senior members of the administration worry privately that
the White House regularly overplays its hand and should reserve the
national security argument for events tightly linked to the
prospect of the United States becoming involved in conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a significant risk of crying wolf,'' one of the
president's top security advisers concedes. ``This isn't Sputnik,''
he added, in another allusion to the Eisenhower years, when appeals
for education funds could be based on fears that the Russians were
well ahead in the race to build the first ICBMs.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly there is a strong moral argument for helping the
destitute ravaged by AIDS, in Africa or elsewhere. And no doubt the
disease could lead to political instability. But so can poverty,
and the 1.3 billion people who live on less than a dollar a day
trigger meetings at the World Bank these days, not in the Situation
Room.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Bush, eager to portray the current occupants of the
White House as long on butter and short on guns, carry the argument
one step further: by making the list of security threats too long,
they argue, the Clinton administration risks taking its eye off
more imminent threats.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Paul Wolfowitz, dean of the school of Advanced
International Studies at Johns Hopkins University and one of those
advisers, wrote recently, AIDS in Africa and the environment are
serious problems, but calling them national security threats
carries ``the implication that conventional security is no longer
something we need to worry much about.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0700 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-NATIONAL-SECURITY-REV     05-06 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-SECURITY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, NATIONAL SECURITY SAYS IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ten years after recapturing Europe, Dwight D.
Eisenhower calculated that the lessons of D-Day could be usefully
applied in persuading Congress to lace the land with highways. His
administration dreamed up the National System of Interstate and
Defense Highways and argued that these roads were not only about
economic development, they were about national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case of atomic attack on our key cities,'' he wrote in
1955, ``the road net must permit quick evacuation of target areas,
mobilization of defense forces and maintenance of every essential
economic function.''
</P>
<P>
   Half a century later, the highways he built can barely handle a
5 p.m. crush of commuters in their SUVs, much less a panicky
evacuation of the capital. But if he were alive today, the old
five-star might smile to hear the latest Clinton White House
strategy. The president and his national security adviser, Samuel
R. Berger, have taken up a mantra that granting permanent
``normal'' trading status to China isn't just about profit
opportunities, it's also about national security. At the same time,
the administration has labeled the AIDS crisis in Africa a threat
to national security, and Vice President Al Gore has raised similar
fears with his ``new security agenda,'' which includes global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   Without question there is a case to be made that economic chaos,
disease and climatic upheaval can all trigger political nastiness.
So all of this new labeling raises a question: Just when does a big
problem turn into a national security threat?
</P>
<P>
   On trade with China, the Clinton administration argument is that
granting normal trade status would reassure the Chinese that
America isn't trying to hem them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a national security point of view, it would in my view be
a very, very unwise and precarious move to say that the United
States doesn't care whether they're part of the world community or
not,'' President Clinton told an insurance group last week, a theme
he repeated nightly as he tried to win over 40 or so legislators
who were still undecided about the China bill.
</P>
<P>
   Only days before, the White House was arguing that the spread of
AIDS in Africa would lead to economic collapse, political
instability and civil wars that might eventually require American
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that we have a short list of national security
threats and East Timor is now off and AIDS is on it,'' Berger said
in an interview. But strife has many origins, he said: ``If it
creates instability, chaos, conflict and war, that has national
security implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, used a foreign policy speech last weekend to
argue for the need for ``forward engagement'' (presumably a
Gore-ism for trying to think ahead). He ticked off _ in no
particular order of priority _ pandemics, economic inequality,
global warming and the digital divide as potential security
problems that had to be nipped in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   In Gore's case, the political calculation is obvious: he is
trying to portray his opponent, George W. Bush, as a man caught in
what he termed a cold-war mindset that sees national security only
in the most conventional terms.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still unclear whether the new Democratic relabeling of
issues is just shrewd political marketing _ to Democrats who don't
like trade deals, and to Republicans who don't care for foreign
aid, particularly when it involves AIDS _ or a truly new agenda for
an age of new global threats.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell. As the Clinton presidency winds down, the
definition of national security threats has gotten ever fuzzier.
Even some senior members of the administration worry privately that
the White House regularly overplays its hand and should reserve the
national security argument for events tightly linked to the
prospect of the United States becoming involved in conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a significant risk of crying wolf,'' one of the
president's top security advisers concedes. ``This isn't Sputnik,''
he added, in another allusion to the Eisenhower years, when appeals
for education funds could be based on fears that the Russians were
well ahead in the race to build the first ICBMs.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly there is a strong moral argument for helping the
destitute ravaged by AIDS, in Africa or elsewhere. And no doubt the
disease could lead to political instability. But so can poverty,
and the 1.3 billion people who live on less than a dollar a day
trigger meetings at the World Bank these days, not in the Situation
Room.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Bush, eager to portray the current occupants of the
White House as long on butter and short on guns, carry the argument
one step further: by making the list of security threats too long,
they argue, the Clinton administration risks taking its eye off
more imminent threats.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Paul Wolfowitz, dean of the school of Advanced
International Studies at Johns Hopkins University and one of those
advisers, wrote recently, AIDS in Africa and the environment are
serious problems, but calling them national security threats
carries ``the implication that conventional security is no longer
something we need to worry much about.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But this is also an administration repeatedly stung by the
criticism that its foreign policy has been a series of belated
reactions, rather than the product of any global strategy. So
Americans may be ready to welcome anything resembling preparation
for new crises, as long as it differentiates between real security
threats, potential threats and social work. And it is possible _
though hardly certain _ that after a decade of unchallenged power
and prosperity, Americans are ready to think about their national
security in broader terms.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, any serious official who argued that admitting
Communist China into a Western trade regime might change China's
political culture would have been laughed out of the National
Security Council. Today, even some Republicans sound a lot like
Clinton when it comes to talking about the benefits of exposing
China to a Western-designed legal system or fueling the spread of
the Internet. ``China's emergence as a world power is a classic
security issue,'' said Richard Armitage, who has served several
Republican presidents, ``and if getting them into the world trading
system makes them more restrained, a better actor, then I'm for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's most potent argument may be the one he hasn't made in
public, chiefly to avoid offending two of America's closest allies
. In the first half of the 20th century, Germany and Japan lashed
out in large part because they felt the world was constraining not
only their military might, but their ability to manufacture and
export. Any global system that reduces trade barriers, the theory
goes, also deflates some of those pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But noneconomic forces also cause wars, and it is a mistake,
Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers acknowledges, to
``overemphasize the link between economic forces and future
conflict.'' Perhaps that is why Clinton and Berger last week opened
a new front in the China argument.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than argue the economic and political benefits of getting
China into the tent, they made the case that keeping it out would
court disaster _ that insulting China would strengthen the hand of
the People's Liberation Army in its battle over China's direction
with Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, the leader of China's move to a
market economy. But if the Chinese economy opens too quickly _
forcing tens or hundreds of millions of workers in inefficient
state-owned enterprises out of work _ Zhu could be blamed for that,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one thinks of the logic, Clinton's national security
case for letting China into the World Trade Organization seems to
be winning some converts. ``The AFL-CIO has an answer to the
economic arguments about this deal,'' one undecided congressman _
who asked not to be named _ said last week. ``But they don't have
any answers on the security side.'' On the other hand, the effort
to reclassify AIDS seems to have fallen flat. No one in either
party is talking about reallocating the trillions saved by the
Soviet Union's fall on international AIDS programs, or any other
foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   But China trade may be different. Eisenhower's highway system is
now crumbling, and members of Congress want it fixed. A few who are
on the fence about China have suggested that the place to fix the
Interstate System is in their districts before Election Day. That
might make them more amenable to the Clinton view of national
security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
