<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-PARENTS-JOB-BIAS-REVI     05-06 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-JOB-BIAS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORK RULES: GOING EASY ON PARENTS ISN'T SO EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here is the problem in theory: A good job on the
night shift opens up. A mother with several children is not offered
the job, which would be a promotion, because her supervisor assumes
_ wrongly _ that her family responsibilities prevent her from
working nights.
</P>
<P>
   Did the supervisor act properly?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone would say so. Certainly the mother is the only one
who knows whether she is able to work nights.
</P>
<P>
   Should the supervisor's action be against the law?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely, in President Clinton's view.
</P>
<P>
   Is the problem pervasive?
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of problem Clinton loves to address _ the way he
has promoted school uniforms to improve classroom discipline and
V-chips to block violent programs on television.
</P>
<P>
   His solutions cost little. They endear him to his admirers. And
his political foes often seem to have been outsmarted.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, with a stroke of his pen, Clinton ordered an end
to discrimination against federal workers because they are parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, there are still some employers who are
reluctant to hire or to promote employees who have children at
home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His order, he said, sent this message: ``No glass ceiling for
parents. The job they are doing at home is more important anyway,
and if they can do your job, you ought not to stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   The key phrase is ``if they can do your job.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would argue seriously, for example, that because an
employee cannot work nights, the government should be required by
law to create a day-side promotion.
</P>
<P>
   A more difficult question is what happens when two people are in
competition for employment or a promotion _ a single person who can
work long hours and a parent who cannot afford to. Is it
discrimination if the long hours are rewarded? Or is it
discrimination if they are not?
</P>
<P>
   The practical effect of the executive order on those kinds of
common situations is far from clear. The White House could not
offer a single case of discrimination in the past that the
president's executive order would now prohibit.
</P>
<P>
   Neither could the federal workers' union, the American
Federation of Government Employees.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Binion, the president of Local 12, to which Labor
Department employees belong, said, ``I know people don't get
assignments because they have kids, but I can't give you a specific
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff member who developed the policy, Bruce Reed, the
president's chief domestic policy adviser, conceded that he did not
know whether this kind of bias was a problem in the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that this is not a widespread practice,'' Reed said,
``but we'd like to be on the safe side.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive order was welcomed in some circles as a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good thing the president did, because it's a
marker,'' said Judith L. Lichtman, president of the National
Partnership for Women and Families, a liberal advocacy group.
``This is how you get the conversation to change about what is
acceptable and unacceptable behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But as so often happens here, the president's political
opponents were infuriated. It would be hard to overestimate the
rage Bill Clinton ignites in some quarters nowadays, even over an
executive order that may have no effect whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   The response from Rep. J.C. Watts Jr., R-Okla., chairman of the
House Republican Conference, was typical:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the latest meaningless proposal from an administration
desperately searching for a legacy that will endure after the
evening news ends. Having already claimed credit for solving every
problem under the sun, the Clinton-Gore team has apparently taken
to espousing solutions in search of new problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first broached the issue in his State of the Union
Message last year. As part of a long list of proposals involving
children and families, he declared:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ask Congress to prohibit companies from refusing to
hire or promote workers simply because they have children. That is
not right.''
</P>
<P>
   On the president's behalf, Sens. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and
Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., introduced legislation last year that
would have prohibited discrimination against parents by all
employers. The bill went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   So, unable to win support for a national policy, the president
issued the executive order, which applies only to federal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Its range is narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Parents would not be guaranteed any jobs. Someone who could not
work long hours because of family obligations would not have to be
offered a position that required overtime. A worker who was not
always free to travel could not expect a position that often
required last-minute trips. A supervisor would be free to
discipline an employee who was often late because child-care
arrangements fell through.
</P>
<P>
   It is harder to ascertain what the order would do than what it
would not do. White House officials made clear that the order sets
a goal and does not give anyone the right to sue the government.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would certainly not alleviate the stress many
parents face balancing the responsibilities of work and family.
</P>
<P>
   It would not seem to help, for instance, a clerk at the Labor
Department, a single mother who asked when she was interviewed last
week that her name not be used, who said she was sure she had been
denied a promotion recently because of her family obligations. When
pressed, she acknowledged that she had fallen behind in her work
because she had taken so much unpaid leave to deal with a
daughter's illness.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't interfere in any way,'' said Joe Lockhart, the
president's press secretary, ``with an employer's ability to reject
workers who aren't able to perform a job in question. It would
simply ensure that workers aren't discriminated against on the
basis of being a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem may be that this kind of discrimination is simply
too subtle to prove.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
