<HEADER>
A7573 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-N     05-06 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 7, moved Saturday, in the `a' category unless
otherwise noted.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   MOTHERHOOD-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Political strategies come
and go, but a few endure: Never underestimate the political potency
of motherhood. The leaders of the Million Mom March for ``sensible
gun control'' next Sunday, Mother's Day, have an appealing web
site, a shrewd media effort and an aggressive grass-roots
organizing campaign. But above all, they are invoking a very old
tradition in politics: Trying to break through ideology and
partisanship and make an appeal based on the moral authority of
women as mothers. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-STOCKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Nasdaq gave amateur investors
the impression that the thing to own is the new, new thing.
Meanwhile, the antiques world gave amateur appraisers the
impression that the thing to own is the old, old thing _ eBay
allowed Web surfers to go antiquing over high-speed access lines,
Sotheby's and Christie's arrived on the Internet, and ``Antiques
Roadshow'' became the most popular program on public TV. By Jenny
Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inside the section:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-SECURITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Defining national security:
Just when does a big problem turn into a national security threat?
If Eisenhower were alive today, he might be amused or puzzled by
the Clinton administration's linkage of national security to issues
like trade privileges for China, AIDS in Africa and global warming.
But it is possible that after a decade of unchallenged power and
prosperity, Americans are ready to think about their national
security in broader terms. BY David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   PARENTS-JOB-BIAS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A good job on the night
shift opens up. A mother with young children is not offered the
job, which would be a promotion, because her supervisor assumes _
wrongly _ that her family responsibilities prevent her from working
nights. Did the supervisor act properly? Hardly anyone would say
so. Should the supervisor's action be against the law? Absolutely,
in President Clinton's view. Is the problem pervasive? No one
knows. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONES-CRIME-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the use of
cellular phones as crime-fighting devices. Since the early 1990s,
cell phones have increasingly become the all-purpose, cure-all
solution for individual safety. The notion of being wired in the
electronic age is shared shared by both parent and child, salesman
and client, cop and felon. The issue, however, is whether people
are really safe, or merely think they are. By Jason Blair.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TECH-REVIEW (Undated) _ For believers in technology's
implied promise of an information utopia, in which people can see
or hear or read whatever they want (and show or tell or write
whatever they want), the Disney-Time Warner battle over ABC
transmission was an uncomfortable lesson that the more information
available, the more places in which it is available, the more the
logic of economics and egos will come into play to restrict it. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   GILLIGAN'S-REALITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ A screenplay featuring the
characters of ``Gilligan's Island'' and the new trend toward
``reality-based game programming.'' CBS maroons a group of real
people, contestants, on an island and keeps hundreds of cameras and
microphones pointed at them 24 hours a day to record everything
they say and do. People are voted out of the group one by one.
After a few weeks their small society, a microcosm of the world at
large if you will, devolves into something out of ``Lord of the
Flies.'' CBS awards the final contestant a million dollars or
something. The ``Gilligan' cast enacts the drama. By Jeff
MacGregor.
</P>
<P>
   E-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ For more than a year, I've been
experimenting with electronic books. The various e-book devices
felt like solid hardcovers in hand, but the first generation seemed
stiff to me, somehow nerdy and bulky. The cold gray screens of text
didn't offer the hypnotic calm of vanilla rag paper. Reading books
on a PC felt too much as if I was working, chained upright to a
desk. There was a reason why there was a paperback revolution. I
was drawn to the devices that offered one of the basic elements of
pocketbook design: portability. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-OBSTACLES-REVIEW (Washington) _ The debacle of the Sierra
Leone peacekeeping mission and the awkward U.S. response
demonstrate again that Africa takes more than good intentions. Now,
the likelihood of deployment of even the modest force for Congo
looks very distant. And even as the House approved a trade bill
granting new trading privileges to Africa, there are some doubts
whether many African countries have the economic capacity to take
advantage of it. The fact remains that sub-Saharan Africa is so
poor, that McDonald's cannot find enough of a customer base to open
one outlet in even one nation. By Jane Perlez. (Moving in the `i'
category)
</P>
<P>
   TOYS-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A tempest is brewing in
Washington, all because of an 11-inch blond bombshell. Mattel, in
association with two nonprofit women's groups, recently announced
plans for a Barbie for President 2000 doll. Almost immediately the
protests sounded. But why shouldn't American children learn about
civics and the virtues of public service via their favorite
playthings? By Bruce Kluger.
</P>
<P>
   SWORD&AMP;SANDAL-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ To mark the opening of
``Gladiator'' and the passing of Hercules actor Steve Reeves,
earlier sword-and-sandal epics are recalled for their memorable
utterances. It didn't matter whether the plots were derived from
the Bible, Greek mythology, tales of ancient Rome _ or, more
typically, some unholy mixture of the three. The dialogue
frequently managed to range from the ponderous to the purple, and
sometimes to the preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
