<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7574 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-ART-     05-06 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATES REAP THE BENEFITS OF CLINTON'S
EXPERTISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., N.M., Mich., Ind., La., Pa., Mich., Fla., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has become a crucial
behind-the-scenes player in the 2000 campaign, serving as a
tactical adviser for House, Senate and gubernatorial candidates
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although the spotlight has shifted to Vice President Al Gore and
Hillary Rodham Clinton, prominent Democrats portray the president's
role as that of an enormously valuable Strategist in Chief. They
describe him as a sponge for absorbing political statistics _ a
skill that is all the more enhanced because he has run twice in all
435 congressional districts. And he willingly brings his well-honed
political instincts to bear while exerting the power of the
presidency to elect Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been seeking election or re-election since 1974,
when he was defeated in a race for Congress. And the president's
closest advisers say that although he is no longer running himself,
his passion for electoral politics has never receded. They also
cite another, more personal, reason for Clinton's deep involvement:
He wants to burnish his own legacy with the election of Gore to
succeed him, the installation of Mrs. Clinton as senator from New
York and the return of the House to Democratic control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy can't live without a campaign in his life,'' said Sen.
John B. Breaux, D-La. ``Life is a campaign for him. He needs a
campaign to keep him going. This guy is not going to go into an
igloo and freeze away. He can't help but advise.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and historians say they have never known of a
president so deeply immersed in politics _ or a White House that,
even during a lame-duck period, was so focused on polls and
electoral considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The president is particularly engrossed in the first lady's
race, and to a lesser degree in Gore's. But his involvement in
campaigns from coast to coast is extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is much more than a fund-raiser in these campaigns, even
as he has collected millions of dollars for House and Senate
candidates. He offers candidates pointers on television and radio
advertising scripts. He played a significant role in urging some
prospects to run in the first place, and he often schedules trips
and policy announcements with an eye to helping specific
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   This portrait of Clinton has been gleaned from interviews with
more than two dozen candidates and strategists, as well as
lawmakers on Capitol Hill and officials at the White House and at
the Democratic National Committee. Joe Lockhart, Clinton's press
secretary, turned down a request to interview the president; some
of Clinton's advisers said they were worried that it would seem
unpresidential for him to discuss his activities openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the ultimate junkie,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli of New
Jersey, chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
``He has the best walking knowledge of anybody in American
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Rep. Ron Klink's drive to oust Sen. Rick Santorum,
R-Pa., Torricelli said: ``Last night he called me about the Klink
race. He said he was convinced Klink could beat Santorum. He said,
`I want to do something in Philadelphia to bring our base in for
Klink. I know he can carry western Pennsylvania, but he may have
trouble consolidating the base in the east.'''
</P>
<P>
   Klink said that he telephoned the White House after he won the
Democratic primary in April and Clinton ``took my call
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just lip service,'' Klink said. ``He's really focused
on this race. He can open doors with other individuals by telling
them that this race is very meaningful to him.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The president's network of contacts is vast because he has
stumped in more than half the congressional districts, his advisers
say.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Clinton calls candidates on the telephone. More often,
he grabs them to talk politics during his travels or at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Smith, a former Clinton political director, said he was at
the White House recently to watch an Arkansas Razorbacks basketball
game. At halftime, Smith said, the president cornered a group of
his guests and held forth about the Democrats' presidential
prospects in several states.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Gore not write off North Carolina in November,
even though Clinton lost the state twice. If the Gore campaign
takes that advice, it may cause the Bush campaign to rethink its
own electoral tactics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``He came over and said, `How do you think the math is
working?''' Smith said. ``He said, `I think North Carolina looks
good.''' But Smith said he cautioned Clinton that the Democrats
should think twice about pumping resources into the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that state broke my heart _ twice,'' Smith said.
``But he said, `I think we've got a shot.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Others who have talked politics with Clinton said he was
preoccupied with the need for Democrats to win the loyalty of
Hispanic voters. They said he had even spoken in detail about the
importance of married Protestants. And, they said, he was
particularly intrigued by contests in Michigan, New Jersey and
Florida, where Gore has been pressing his campaign amid the tumult
over the administration's handling of the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is obsessed with Florida,'' the case of the Cuban boy
``and how it impacts,'' Torricelli said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still convenes political meetings twice a month or so in
the ornate Yellow Oval Room in the White House family quarters. The
sessions are not as pressing as they were when they were held
weekly before the 1996 campaign, and the group of participants,
which often numbers close to two dozen, is usually larger than the
more exclusive club of the past. Gore does not attend anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clinton assembles his top aides, some Cabinet
secretaries and others to hash over how Democrats are performing
and to look for ways to use his presidency to help candidates.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the sessions, Mark Penn, a presidential
pollster, reviews the latest surveys on an overhead projector. The
discussion that follows is freewheeling, with Clinton _ who often
chews on an unlighted cigar _ sounding at times like a political
operative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a full-time campaign manager at these meetings,'' one
participant said. ``The entire meetings are discussions of how this
would be good for Al or for the first lady and how he can help the
legacy. Clinton is constantly saying, `This would help Al.'''
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the group's most recent meeting, in April,
recalled that Clinton said he wanted to accept invitations to speak
at college graduations in areas with high concentrations of
minorities, like Shiprock, N.M., where he thought his appearance
would help spur interest in Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite pastime of the group is mocking Republicans in
Congress, particularly when they do something that hurts them in
the polls. ``A common refrain is, `They must not read the polls,'''
a participant said.
</P>
<P>
   James Carville, an architect of Clinton's victory in 1992, said
of the president: ``If he calls me it would be to chat about Gore
and Hillary. But I've had him tell me ideas for brochures in Senate
races. He's a rare combination of somebody who's got the brains and
the gut.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, the national chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, said he was dazzled by the president's knowledge of one
congressional district in Indiana, Andrew's home state. ``He said
the 8th Congressional District is one that goes back and forth _
the bloody 8th,'' Andrew said. ``He knew that the southern part of
the district was more conservative than the northern part. But he
knew that in the southern part there had been tremendous growth
because of a Toyota plant that opened there. And he knew of the
Whirlpool plant in the northern part that had closed.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Lapolla, the manager of Union County, N.J., who is
seeking a House seat, said he ran into the president at a White
House Christmas party last year. ``As soon as he found what I was
running for, he said he liked our chances and he knew just about
everything about the district,'' Lapolla said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Honda, a state assemblyman from San Jose, Calif., said
Clinton helped persuade him to run for an open congressional seat
this year. ``He added the weight of his office to our race,'' Honda
said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has taken a particular interest in the campaign of Rep.
Rush D. Holt of New Jersey, a freshman in a tight race. ``His
knowledge of New Jersey politics, and about my race in particular,
is astounding,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Nelson, the state insurance commissioner in Florida, who is
running for the Senate, said Clinton went out of his way to praise
him at a dinner of Floridians in Washington last November _ a move
that he said helped considerably in persuading Democrats to take a
serious look at his prospects. ``The President stands up in front
of all these distinguished Floridians and proceeded to say very
kind things about me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is particularly involved in Mrs. Clinton's Senate
campaign. One participant at a meeting with Mrs. Clinton's advisers
said it was the president's idea that he not utter a word at his
wife's official announcement of her candidacy in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the issue came up of whether he would speak at Hillary's
announcement, he weighed in and said, `No,''' the participant said.
``He said, `I don't think that's right. This is her day.' There
were plenty of people arguing the other way because it seemed
unnatural for him not to speak. But it was a good judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's interest in his wife's race, Torricelli said
the president does not fully grasp the unusual assortment of
parties on the ballot in New York. ``He knows New York politically
less than a lot of the other states,'' Torricelli said. ``He
doesn't quite understand the mix of all those lines.'' Referring to
Sen. Charles E. Schumer of New York, he said, ``He calls Schumer
and gets his opinion and calls me and plays off where we might
differ.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While in past years some candidates have urged Clinton to stay
clear of their districts, most of those interviewed said they were
grateful for the president's wisdom and did not view him as an
unwelcome meddler. ``He's not a Mr. Buttinski,'' Carville said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some candidates were not so willing to bow before Clinton's
expertise, perhaps out of fear that they might appear too close to
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in elective office over 20 years in Michigan,'' said
Rep. Debbie Stabenow, who is running for Senate and campaigned with
the president last week. ``I know my state very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how often he takes advice from Clinton, Tony Coelho,
Gore's campaign chairman, said: ``I'm not going to go there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
