<HEADER>
A7578 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-USBUDGET-EARMARK-LADN     05-06 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USBUDGET-EARMARK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MEMBERS READY TO DUEL FOR PET PROJECTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's ``show me the money'' time in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard P. ``Buck'' McKeon, R-Santa Clarita, wants to show
his constituents $4.3 million for a Boys &AMP; Girls Club in Santa
Clarita, $5.5 million for a National Guard Armory in Lancaster and
$4 million to rid the Santa Clara River of ``demon weeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills, hopes to show an $8 million
contract to upgrade Navy sonar at L-3 Communications in Sylmar and
a $5 million outlay for a new Air National Guard communications
center in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, has requested $1.5 million
to help unsnarl the 101-405 freeway interchange and $500,000 to
fund an ongoing study of possible San Fernando Valley secession
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Those and thousands of other local spending requests from House
members, known as earmarks, have gone into the hopper as Congress
divvies up $600.3 billion in federal budget outlays for 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   The winners and losers will be revealed in early October when,
after months of wheeling and dealing, 435 House members and 100
senators approve a final budget and most head home to seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the earmark process say they are fulfilling their
duty to constituents by giving them a fair return on their tax
dollars and funding needed programs and improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the earmarks amount to pork barrel spending and are
a waste of taxpayers' money.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' $600.3 billion kitty, known as discretionary spending,
accounts for one-third of the basic $1.83 trillion spending plan
that was approved April 13 by House and Senate negotiators. Half of
the proposed budget is tied up in mandatory spending for programs
like Social Security, Medicare and welfare. Another 20 percent is
allocated to pay interest on the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Under the budget plan, $310.8 billion of the discretionary
spending is to be allocated for defense programs. Non-defense
outlays are to total $289.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The earmark process begins with a ``Dear Chairman'' letter from
a member of Congress to the head of the House subcommittee that
will first consider the spending request.
</P>
<P>
   Requests are also passed on to Southern California members of
the House Appropriations Committee, which shapes the size and scope
of all spending measures. Those key players include Rep. Jerry
Lewis, R-Redlands, who also chairs the Defense Appropriations
subcommittee; and Reps. Julian Dixon, D-Los Angeles, and Lucille
Roybal-Allard, D-Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Earmark requests are also coordinated with Democratic Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, California's representative on the Senate
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go into the process with very few expectations,'' said
Sherman, who has made seven local funding requests. ``My colleagues
know I'd be thrilled to get any of my requests approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman and other local House members stressed that earmarks are
not figments of their imaginations, but requests for help that
originate from cities, school districts and other concerned parties
in their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Strength in numbers can improve the prospects for a budget
request. For example, McKeon, Rep. Grace Napolitano, D-Montebello,
and Rep. Steven Kuykendall, R-Torrance, are jointly seeking $2
million to build three new county-run child care centers. A center
would be set up in each of their districts.
</P>
<P>
   A notable no-show in the scramble for earmarked money is Rep.
Edward Royce, R-Fullerton. A vocal opponent of what he calls pork
barrel spending, Royce makes no such requests and regularly votes
against outlays which he deems as wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   He has also teamed with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., to co-chair a
bipartisan group called the Porkbusters Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Royce is also an active supporter of Citizens Against Government
Waste, a watchdog group that annually publishes a ``Pig Book''
which spotlights allegedly wasteful spenders in the House and
Senate. The most recent edition, released April 5, targeted funding
requests that were approved last year for Lewis, Dixon and
Roybal-Allard.
</P>
<P>
   The three ``Pig Book'' targets have all defended their earmarks
as justifiable and beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman criticized the critics' premise that all earmarks are
pork and therefore inherently wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country is not so much a democracy as a democracy and
bureaucracy,'' said Sherman. ``There is a perception that we
elected officials in the democracy are either corrupt or not smart
enough to be corrupt. There's also a tendency to see the
bureaucrats as impartial, nonpolitical experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are not involved in the budget process, the bureaucrats
will make all of the spending decisions based on formulas and data
like the census,'' added Sherman. ``But the bureaucracy can also be
just as politically motivated as Congress and its decisions are
subject to the same flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman cited the example of transportation funding, mostly
amassed from the federal gasoline taxes paid by consumers.
Ninety-six percent of that money is returned by the bureaucrats to
state agencies like Caltrans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put up the 4 percent of transportation money we deal with
against that 96 percent any time,'' said Sherman. ``That 4 percent
is being spent just as well, if not more effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Native intelligence is a key issue for Napolitano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the bureaucrats just don't understand California and
its needs,'' she said. ``It's our duty to stand up for the people
we represent and return a fair share of their tax dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a fair share is a growing issue for Californians, who
have been sending more money to Washington than they have received
for 12 straight years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998-99, for example, Californians received a return of 89
cents for every tax dollar, a shortfall that averaged $595 for
every man, woman and child in the state. Californians, who make up
12.3 percent of the nation's populations, sent $212 billion in
federal taxes to Washington that year, amounting to 12.5 percent of
the government's total take.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that California will pencil out as a donor
state for the 13th year in a row when final tax and spending
receipts for 1999-2000 are released this fall.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
