<HEADER>
A7585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-(TRIM     05-06 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN OFFICIAL TRYING TO ENSURE RIGHTS IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Vladimir Kalamanov may have the toughest job in Russia.
As the Kremlin's special envoy for human rights, his task is to
convince a skeptical West that Russia is serious about ending human
rights abuses in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   It is a hard sell. Despite numerous accounts of pillaging,
beatings and killings by Russian troops in Chechnya, only a handful
of cases have been investigated by military prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   And while Kalamanov insists he is making progress, he is the
first to acknowledge that the Russian military routinely withholds
critical details about its investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that I am entirely satisfied,'' he said in an
interview. ``I have not received all of the information I have
asked for.''
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton and President-elect Vladimir Putin prepare
for their June meeting in Moscow, human rights is again emerging as
a politically charged issue _ and not just for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has made it clear that the brutal war
in Chechnya will not prevent it from doing business with Putin,
particularly on arms control. But the United States has also sought
to assure human rights activists that it is not neglecting the
issue and is pressing for an independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   That has put the spotlight squarely on Kalamanov.
</P>
<P>
   Most Russian officials reject Western human rights complaints as
a plot to blacken the nation's image. Kalamanov, by contrast, has
the disarming manner of agreeing with many of the critics and then
imploring them to accept that Russia is involved in a long and
complex struggle to build a democratic society and hold the
once-sacrosanct military to account.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should not see this as a game the president is playing to
influence international opinion,'' he said. ``The role of the army
and civil authority is being rethought, but we are only at the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, portray Kalamanov as an earnest official who
tells the West what it wants to hear, but who has been granted
neither the resources nor the authority by Putin to bring the
culprits to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kalamanov is a formidable figure,'' said Kenneth Roth, the
executive director of Human Rights Watch, the international rights
organization. ``He is aware of the atrocities, but he must work
through the chief military prosecutor, who is determined not to do
anything. The best way to inspire confidence is to deliver results,
and so far there have not been significant results.''
</P>
<P>
   A 47-year-old official of Syrian descent, it seems that
Kalamanov should be in a strong position. Eager to strengthen ties
with the West and avoid international sanctions, Putin has vowed to
end human rights abuses. And in February, Putin, who will be
inaugurated on Sunday, named Kalamanov as an ombudsman on human
rights and gave him the lofty mandate of protecting civil rights in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the official backing from the new Russian leader,
however, Kalamanov seems to be playing David to the Russian
military Goliath. His modest staff includes just 10 unpaid,
Chechnya-based investigators. (Russian authorities say the
investigators' salaries are on the way, and Kalamanov's goal is to
expand his Chechnya staff to 20.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kalamanov claims some successes. He has arranged for two
European officials to work with his team in Chechnya, a move
intended to assure the West that his efforts are not a whitewash.
And he has worked to assemble a list of prisoners in Russian
detention centers in Chechnya and helped them obtain legal
representation. Soon, he boasts, Chechnya will have a functioning
court system.
</P>
<P>
   And with an eye on the diplomatic calendar, he is pressing his
government to take several headline-making steps before Clinton
meets Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to open the northern part of Chechnya to Human
Rights Watch and to international and Russian organizations,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But what Kalamanov has not yet been able to do is to bring
Russian soldiers to justice. Human Rights Watch has documented a
series of assaults and killings in the Chechen town of Alkhan-Yurt
and in the Staropromyslovsky and Aldi areas of the Chechen capital
of Grozny. Kalamanov says he takes the reports seriously and that
his investigators have received corroborating testimony about some
of the abuses.
</P>
<P>
   But it is up to military and civilian prosecutors to bring
criminal charges, and they have been very reluctant. Military
prosecutors say they are investigating more than 300 crimes by
Russian soldiers in Chechnya, but only 10 involve allegations of
crimes against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two of these cases have been referred to the
military court for possible trial, and they concern the relatively
modest offenses of ``hooliganism'' and mishandling weapons.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of the military prosecutors to act has diminished
Kalamanov's authority. To monitor the effectiveness of the
prosecutor's investigations, for example, Kalamanov, has tried to
obtain crucial details of the cases. Instead, he has been given
only the most general statistics about the number of
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the military announced that Col. Yuri Budanov, the
commander of a tank regiment, had been arrested for the rape and
murder of a young Chechen woman. In general, however, the generals
have not been eager to publicize their investigations into human
rights abuses, a step that might deter the troops from committing
other crimes and win the confidence of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The result is evident at Kalamanov's office in the Chechen town
of Znamenskoye. Housed in a defunct winery, the office has received
more than 500 complaints, but they mostly concern delayed pensions,
appeals by refugees for tents and medicine, labor disputes,
problems in obtaining new documents and, to a lesser extent,
charges of illegal detentions and reports of missing persons. It
has not fielded any complaints about assaults or thefts by Russian
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they doubt our ability to help,'' Alvi Ayubov, the
deputy head of the office and an ethnic Chechen, said, referring to
Chechnya's residents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Ten, 20 or even 30 people cannot always solve these problems.
The cooperation of all the entire power structures in the republic,
including law enforcement bodies and human rights organizations,
are required.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
