<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-(TRIMS     05-06 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN FACES FREE-FOR-ALL IF TOP FACTION LOSES CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In the shadowy world of Japanese politics true turning
points can be difficult to spot.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few weeks, after the incapacitating stroke
suffered by a sitting prime minister, and the retirement from
politics of a former prime minister who was his mentor, Japanese
politicians and commentators have begun to speak of the end of a
style of factional politics that has been in force for 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden illness of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi last month,
and the retirement of Noboru Takeshita last week _ both men
belonged to the dominant faction of the long-ruling Liberal
Democratic Party _ has been likened to a corporation's abrupt loss
of both its chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's stroke forced the party's historically dominant faction
to surrender the prime minister's office to a rival group in the
party, led by the country's new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori. But
many analysts are treating Takeshita's retirement, officially
attributed to a severe back ailment, as the more significant event.
</P>
<P>
   In Japanese politics since World War II, Takeshita, 76, has had
few rivals in terms of sheer power or endurance. Although he was
prime minister for less than 18 months, he remained his party's
ultimate broker up to the nomination of his protege, Obuchi, in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His style was a sharp contrast to that of his predecessor,
Kakuei Tanaka, the sharp-tongued political don who preceded
Takeshita as the Liberal Democratic Party's undisputed kingmaker.
Tanaka was brought down by a bribery scandal in 1974 after serving
as prime minister for just two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tanaka was very gruff, very forceful and very opinionated,''
said Gerald L. Curtis, a professor of political science at Columbia
University. ``Then came Takeshita, the master consensus builder,
the master of the art of mediating between people who want
something from the government and the people who have the power to
give it.''
</P>
<P>
   By getting things done while allowing others to take the credit,
Takeshita perfected a model of money-centered, ideology-free
machine politics whose opacity and indirection perfectly suited a
modern Japan in full expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``To understand Takeshita is to understand what power means in
Japan,'' said Toru Hayano, a senior columnist at the Asahi Shimbun,
a major newspaper. ``He is not eloquent. He is not a big
philosopher. He has no special program of reforms. The essence of
his style was to adjust a little bit every day based on what you
have gathered up until then. If there is opposition, you consult
with others. When a decision is reached, you distribute the
rewards.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the rewards were distributed first to rural Japan,
whose wealth the government cultivated by protecting its
agricultural products from competition, and subsidizing
transportation and construction.
</P>
<P>
   Like his predecessor, Takeshita, in 1989, was forced to resign
as prime minister because of a scandal. However, he played the
pivotal role in determining the choice of seven of the next eight
prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that Takeshita and his faction became a virtual
politburo that used its control over the pork barrel to dominate
the country's overwhelmingly dominant party, suppressing debate in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   With Obuchi in a coma, the faction was caught with no obvious
candidate for the prime minister's office, and no one with the
power and prestige to serve as kingmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Takeshita's retirement should be seen as a symbolic event
indicating that this peculiar style of political control _ peculiar
even in the history of Japanese politics _ is beginning to
change,'' the Asahi Shimbun said in a recent editorial.
</P>
<P>
   What comes next, many feel, will be a period of unusual
competition, both within the Liberal Democratic Party and without.
The new prime minister, Mori, is widely expected to call
parliamentary elections on June 25. But hobbled by an unpopular
coalition with a Buddhist-affiliated party, and a weak economy, his
prospects are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   A poor result could cause the party to jettison Mori, sparking a
free-for-all in which no faction of the governing party can
dominate by sheer numbers. Under these circumstances,
long-submerged policy differences over questions like heavy deficit
spending, subsidies for the farming and construction lobbies and
economic liberalization would likely come to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently there is no order-giving power in the LDP and the
factions are disintegrating,'' said a wistful Shigezo Hayasaka,
Takeshita's longtime political secretary. ``Of course the LDP has
plenty of young people, but they are so conscious of their own
rights that they are no good at working within the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
