<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7617 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PUTIN-ST.PETERSBURG-A     05-06 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-ST.PETERSBURG-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORDS REKINDLE ST. PETERSBURG-MOSCOW RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The first time President-elect Vladimir
Putin deserted Moscow and staged a meeting with a visiting head of
state here, Russians hardly noticed.
</P>
<P>
   That was in March, when Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain
came to the city that Peter the Great built and that served as
Russia's capital for two centuries. The Russian and British leaders
strolled with their wives into the Mariinsky Theater, and from the
imperial vantage point of the czar's former box they watched the
gala opening of the opera ``War and Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But the second time it happened, when Putin abandoned the
capital last month and flew here to meet Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori of Japan in the splendor of the Winter Palace, tongues started
wagging that Putin was raising the status of his hometown in a
manner that touched the historical chord of rivalry between Moscow
and St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very big conflict, not only a conflict of cities but
a conflict of psychologies,'' said Anastasia Kuryokhina, one of the
city's cultural promoters and the widow of Sergei Kuryokhin, a
well-known poet and musician here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people in Moscow do not like St. Petersburgers,'' she
added. ``There are strong feelings. There are cultural differences.
Muscovites are practical and pragmatic. St. Petersburg tends to be
more romantic, more philosophical.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Muscovites have their own views. St. Petersburgers
have been disparaged for putting on airs, or regarded as dandies
who hold their inland countrymen in low esteem while living in
their own micro-culture of excessive intellectualism or, in
imperial times, just excess.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one took Putin's image-making very seriously. After
all, it was natural that this river city of canals and splendid
baroque architecture that is home to the Kirov Ballet, a lively
theater district and some of the world's great art collections
would receive some favor from Russia's new leader, the first to
come from here since the end of the Romanov dynasty. As long as
Putin was just engaged in gestures such as hanging a portrait of
Peter the Great in his Kremlin office no one seemed threatened.
Until now.
</P>
<P>
   While Putin was meeting here with the Japanese prime minister,
the speaker of Russia's parliament, Gennadi Seleznyov, a moderate
Communist who was also visiting the city, surprised an audience of
politicians and reporters by saying he favored moving Russia's
parliament out of Moscow and relocating it here on the banks of the
Neva River.
</P>
<P>
   That move would effectively reverse the shift made by Vladimir
Lenin, who put a symbolic stamp on the Communist triumph over
czarism by shifting the capital back to Moscow and renaming St.
Petersburg Petrograd. After he died in 1924, this city was called
Leningrad in his honor _ another move to extirpate memories of the
czarist past.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov said that Russia's members of parliament currently
suffer ``considerable inconvenience,'' working in ``ill-adapted
rooms'' across from the Kremlin in the nondescript former
headquarters of the Soviet state planning agency Gosplan since
troops loyal to former President Boris Yeltsin destroyed the former
parliament building while quashing an attempted coup in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov sketched a proposal for a new parliament building,
pledged to bring the issue to debate this month and concluded that
``the next Duma,'' the lower house of parliament, to be elected in
2003, ``could be meeting in St. Petersburg.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The man standing beside Seleznyov _ and beaming _ was St.
Petersburg's governor Vladimir Yakovlev, who has advocated moving
all or part of the Russian government here to enhance both the
restoration of the city and its long-term economic development.
Yakovlev told Seleznyov that a large tract of land was reserved for
a new parliament building near Smolny Cathedral in the center of
the city, and plans could be drawn up for modern offices and
elegant chambers for the upper and lower houses of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Putin said it was an ``interesting'' idea, but
from Moscow, there was only scoffing.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Yuri Luzhkov attacked the idea as ``mostly politicking''
and insisted that all major government institutions be located in
Moscow, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov predicted that while Seleznyov might succeed in
scheduling a parliamentary debate in the lower house, it would be
dead on arrival in the upper chamber whose members include Luzhkov
and Russia's governors and regional leaders, who are unlikely to
have any interest in spending huge sums of scarce national
resources to relocate the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The leader of Seleznyov's own Communist Party, Gennadi Zyuganov,
and other influential voices said Russia's economic woes would only
deepen if the three branches of government were split up.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov certainly succeeded in gaining extensive coverage and
reawakening a rivalry dating back to the founding of St. Petersburg
at the outset of the 18th century, when Peter sought a toehold on
the Baltic Sea and a window to Europe, sending thousands to their
death through his insistence on building a grand new capital on a
swamp and forcing the xenophobic nobles of Moscow to haul building
stones in their carriages and move their households here.
Resentment against the city has simmered ever since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
