<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PUTIN-CABINET _ MOSCOW _ On the eve of Vladimir Putin's
inauguration as Russia's president, the former KGB officer whose
hawkish, secretive demeanor has characterized his election has said
that economics, not military affairs, would characterize his term
in office. On Sunday, Putin will take the reins of the world's
largest country for a four-year term at a time of rising economic
fortunes and growth barely seen since the break-up of the Soviet
Union in 1991. Analysts credit the upturn to high world oil prices,
rather than structural changes made by government before or after
Putin became prime minister last August. However, the
president-elect told the nation this week that he has the political
might and will to keep the boom going. (Coker, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH box information attached to end of story.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 2 p.m. EDT Thurs., May 4, in both (i)
International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-CHINA _ BEIJING _ (New date.) What was it like returning
to China after five years? At first, the change and modernization
are really impressive. But, after a little while, you realize that
some things really haven't changed at all _ like the bureaucracy.
(Chao, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS (including mug of Chao).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., May 3, in (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: RUSSIA-UKRAINE-$ADV07 is reskedded to run Sun., May 14.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ Does Elian Gonzalez, as a six-year-old,
have a right to assert his desire for an asylum hearing over the
contrary wishes of his father? In what some legal scholars call a
complex dispute typically involving state court family law, the
appeals court in Atlanta will have to see how federal immigration
law applies in such a dispute. Story will explore motions by three
parties (Justice Department, Miami relatives and Elian's father) as
well as any similar cases from the past, including the 1980 dispute
involving a 12-year-old boy who wanted to stay in the United States
against the wishes of his parents, who wanted to return home to
Russia. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON _ As relatives of Thomas Jefferson and alleged slave
mistress Sally Hemings gathered Saturday at Monticello, a newly
formed group vowed to discredit evidence that the nation's third
president fathered children by Hemings. One of the Thomas Jefferson
Truth Foundation's first orders of business will occur today, when
its members try to exclude Hemings' kin from the Jefferson family's
annual business meeting. Will get reaction from Hemings'
descendents and officials of the Thomas Jefferson Memorial
Foundation, which in January endorsed the genetic and historical
evidence of Jefferson-Hemings children. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA _ Nowhere in Georgia is an industry's reliance on
illegal immigrants more obvious than in the 20 south Georgia
counties where the Vidalia onion harvest is in full swing. Two
years ago, after the INS raided a farm during harvest time,
complaints from congressmen gave illegals a temporary amnesty. That
underscores a historic trend: we tend not to enforce laws against
illegal immigrants in economic boom times when business needs
immigrant labor, but INS deports workers en masse in recessions and
depressions. In the last 2 years, with unemployment at its lowest
in 30 years, INS has all but stopped arresting illegals except at
the borders. (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA-SIDE _ The US is loathe to arrest illegal immigrants
working in hard-to-fill jobs in booming economies. But when a
recession or depression makes jobs scarce, the government rounds up
illegal immigrants by the thousands. Nowhere was this trend more
obvious than in May 1998, when the government let illegal workers
harvest the $90 million Vidalia onion crop in SE Georgia. This
13-inch sidebar accompanies a larger story about the importance of
illegal labor to the onion crop. The sidebar traces the link
between economic conditions and enforcement of immigration law this
century. In today's roaring economy - Surprise! - arrests of
illegals are way down and workplace raids hardly ever happen.
(Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   (Editors: This package is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week.
The layout is now available)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MUSTER _ WASHINGTON _ A group of veterans is pressing ahead with
plans to ``muster on the Mall'' in Washington on May 11 to press
Congress to fund the lifetime health care they say they were
promised when they made military service a career. They are relying
on the Internet to drum up support for the rally. In hopes of
drawing a larger crowd, the veterans want to hire country music
singer Jerry Reed to perform during the event and have started
taking pledges among themselves for the money. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TWILIGHT _ WASHINGTON _ He takes Air Force One around
the globe, jetting into foreign capitals to be feted as the senior
statesman of world politics and power. He draws rock-star welcomes
around his own country, where he can generate $1 million for a
fellow Democrat with a ten-minute speech at a political fundraising
event. He taunts his congressional foes _ those still left standing
_ with charges that their bid to impeach him threatened the
Constitution. Clinton is openly relishing the Indian Summer of his
political life, those final golden months before the August
political conventions usher him into the autumn of irrelevance.
(Deans).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The declaration of AIDS as a national security
issue is a start on understanding the 21st century. (Tom Teepen is
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Cox News Service columnist Howard Kleinberg
is on vacation. His column will resume May 22 for papers of May 24.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ At a minute past midnight on May 1, when Time
Warner yanked ABC stations from its cable systems in seven cities,
stories about the dispute opened the TV evening news in tens of
millions of U.S. homes. If not for a timely truce, the blanket
coverage all but ensured that President Clinton would have soon
stepped into that corporate cat fight. (Andy Glass is a columnist
for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I started following editor
Sam Malone's way of handling snake scenarios. He told readers he
was the ``Live Snake Editor,'' and if you wanted your picture made
with a snake, it had to be brought in alive. This drastically cut
the number of photo requests. There aren't many people besides
zookeepers and the occasional member of one of those
serpent-handling churches who are willing to hold a live snake long
enough for a photographer to get the camera focused and the picture
made. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   LOVEBUG _ Do repeated virus problems slow the march to the
Internet? What are the long-term marketing consequences for
Internet companies and others of what amounts to a cyberspace
Tylenol scare? The answers to those questions are no and not much.
The Internet has made itself as vital as the air we breathe; if the
air is dirty, we still breathe it, just as we'll still use the
Internet despite the threat of viruses. And Internet companies see
the cleanup from such viruses as just another cost of doing
business, much like shoplifting is to brick-and-mortar outfits. The
proof: the NASDAQ was up 60 points in morning trading Friday,
apparently paying no mind to the Love Bug. (Tamman and Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-STEW _ Take 200 pounds of meat, 100 pounds of onions,
100 pounds of potatoes, 12 gallons of tomatoes and a heaping
helping of history and within a few hours, you've got a good old
Southern stew. From Brunswick to Burgoo, a new exhibit of artifacts
and videos featuring Southern stewmaking is featured at the
University of South Carolina's McKissick Museum. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TOTES _ You'll never hear Jean Silverstein or the members of her
family complain about bad weather. ``We love rainy weather,
Mommy!'' her 2-year-old daughter Ella dutifully reports. That's
because lousy weather helps pays the bills at the Silversteins.
Ella's mom is responsible for creating the rainwear that keeps
thousands of Americans and Canadians cozy and dry. (Moss, Dayton
Daily News). 28. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-HITECH _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta's arts community is wooing the
area's hi-tech industry like never before. And John Bacon, CEO of
Iterated Systems, says local tech companies need the Arts in
Atlanta to have a greater presence and support, in order to help
attract and retain tech workers. A look at how the two communities
relate and how they are working on helping each other. (Sabulis,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 75. WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUTS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TV-SEASON _ There have been better TV seasons than the one about
to conclude, but rarely has there been a funner one, and most of
the credit goes to ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' It was as if
once a gameshow was unloosed in primetime to became the most
successful program on TV, everything was up for grabs. (Jubera,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH ILLUSTRATION and LAYOUTS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-POST _ A review of the TV show Cupid &AMP; Cate. Sometimes, TV
critics are wrong. It doesn't happen often. OK, you can stop
laughing now. But it does occur. Case in point: when I received the
tape of the CBS movie Cupid &AMP; Cate, I thought I had the film
pegged. Before watching it, I skimmed the press notes. I thought
they told me everything I needed to know. Cate De Angelo
(Mary-Louis Parker) is a woman in a tiresome relationship with her
boring fiance (David Lansbury). Cate's life, however, gets a
much-needed jump-start after her sister introduces her to Harry
(Peter Gallagher), a funny guy who makes Cate laugh and tingle.
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post). 25. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE-CLASH _ Somebody was pounding at the door. The teen-age
boy got up from the couch. Outside stood four large men in black
uniforms, helmeted and armed with big, scary-looking nightsticks.
``Can I help you?'' ``Police. Open up, kid.'' ``Um, nobody here
called the police.'' ``We're special police.'' ``Say what?''
``We're the Metallica Police. Don't make us get rough with you.''
(Rollins, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is Ron Rollins culture clash column.
</P>
<P>
   ROBBINS-PROFILE _ Profile of author Tom Robbins, in Dayton this
week to promote his newest zany novel. (Dempsey, Palm Beach Post).
35. MOVED
