<SLUG> BC-MILLION-MOM-MARCH-ART-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS AND ANGER INSPIRE MOTHER TO MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTMINSTER, Md. _ When her son was shot to death by another
child showing off his father's 9-mm pistol at playtime, Carole
Price decided to seek some rustic peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved here to get away from everything,'' said Price,
wearing a lapel-pin photo of her beaming 13-year-old son, John. He
was shot in the head two years ago in a Baltimore suburb by a
9-year-old neighbor who thought the gun was empty when he found it
resting alluringly in his father's night stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we did not realize what we were moving into out here,''
Price said. She now clearly knows, she said, as sure as her son was
one of 12 children killed daily by gunshot in the United States,
that there is no way to escape the harrowing aberrations of the gun
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Dotting the byways of the rolling green countryside here in
Carroll County, near the Pennsylvania border, Price, 37, soon began
to notice postings by gun clubs and enthusiasts for frequent
weekend shooting contests. ``Then I saw that the Republican county
committee was raffling off a 9-mm handgun for a political
fund-raiser,'' she said. ``I went through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, with two remaining children to protect, Price soon
became one of the state organizers of the Million Mom March,
scheduled for May 14 in Washington. A promised throng of hundreds
of thousands there and in 59 other cities will issue a unified
demand in the name of Mother's Day that politicians find the will
to regulate guns and their users as thoroughly as automobiles and
drivers are regulated.
</P>
<P>
   After dealing with exaggerated crowd estimates and warnings of
disruption at the recent World Bank protest in Washington,
officials there are saying that the Mother's Day march could prove
to be the real sleeper protest of the spring marching season. The
multicity crowds from all backgrounds are determined to force the
gun-control issue higher up the political agenda, led by mothers
wheeling offspring toward Capitol Hill in phalanxes of strollers.
</P>
<P>
   A counterdemonstration, the Armed Informed Mothers March, is
being promised in several cities by Second Amendment Sisters, a
pro-gun women's group newly formed in Dallas. Million Mom
organizers say they welcome the challenge as a chance to let
politicians measure where the sympathies of most women lie.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington organizers are emphasizing that Mother's Day
originated after the Civil War not as some nosegay commemorative
day but as a practical calling from the heart for mothers in the
sundered nation to take care of one another's wounded sons. Price
reflects some battlefield grit of her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 9-mm they raffled off was the same kind of gun my child
died from, and here were my representatives fund-raising with
one,'' she said, explaining how her organizational fury came to be
stoked by the sight of elected county officials making an American
political gala of a handgun raffle.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the organizers claimed a far larger booty than
expected, happily telling Price that it was because she organized a
protest of a half-dozen friends and relatives and attracted extra
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were coming out and calling us communists and saying,
`You made us a lot of money,''' Price said. ``One guy screamed in
my face to get out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   The flinty mother smiled tightly at this idea as the very last
thing she would ever do. ``I don't understand what they're scared
of about me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is I've got three buses going from Carroll
County,'' she said of 150 local people signed up for the Washington
march. ``Not many men; it's the women, and a lot of them are
saying, `I hope my husband doesn't find out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Price hopes they do, for the goal of the organizers is nothing
less than to drive gun control as the decisive issue in the
presidential and congressional elections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nine months ago, the idea of the march was broached by Donna
Dees-Thomases, a New Jersey mother, in Internet chats among women
appalled by the relentless pace of child shootings. The organizers
rallied round the searing image of terrified youngsters holding
hands and running for their lives in a day-camp shooting in the
Granada Hills section of Los Angeles on Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It steals your heart and your soul when you lose your child,''
said Price, who is hoping for something far more compelling from
women voters this year than the usual ``soccer mom'' bromides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure 10,000 alone from Maryland,'' said Price, noting that
Washington is the recommended destination for anyone within a
10-hour journey. More distant protesters are advised by the march
headquarters to join parallel protests in scores of regional
capitals across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling the politicians we're serious; we don't want to
bury any more of our kids,'' Price said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
