<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summerlike heat and humidity will cover a large area from the
southern Plains to most of the Eastern states on Sunday. Areas east
of the Appalachians from Virginia to southern New England will be
several degrees warmer than Saturday as increasing winds from the
west are warmed as they descend from the mountains. Clouds, showers
and cool air will linger near a front in extreme eastern New
England. It will be mainly dry elsewhere in the East, although a
few thunderstorms will erupt near the Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening disturbance will produce a cluster of thundershowers
from Illinois to southern Michigan. Farther west, a front will be
the focus for clouds and showers from the northern Plains to the
northern Rockies. Meanwhile, low pressure will move inland over
Oregon, promoting variable clouds and showers in the cool air from
northern California to Idaho.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: COLD-AIR FUNNELS
</P>
<P>
   Several weak tornadoes were noted in Arkansas on Thursday,
although witnesses said no thunder could be heard. The twisters
resulted from clouds called cold-air funnels. Unlike typical
tornadoes, which rely on steamy surface air to initiate
thunderstorms that spawn twisters, cold-air funnels form despite a
lack of warm, moist air near the ground. Instead, they rely on
pools of cold air a few thousand feet aloft to promote rising,
rotating columns of air. As pressure lowers in the column,
condensation occurs just below cloud base, revealing a funnel
cloud. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
