<HEADER>
A7665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TOTES0507-COX     05-06 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOTES0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hoping for a rainy day
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ You'll never hear Jean Silverstein or the members
of her family complain about bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love rainy weather, Mommy!'' her 2-year-old daughter Ella
dutifully reports.
</P>
<P>
   That's because lousy weather helps pays the bills at the
Silversteins. Ella's mom is responsible for creating the rainwear
that keeps thousands of Americans and Canadians cozy and dry.
</P>
<P>
   As product development director for the Totes-Isotoner Corp.,
based in Cincinnati, Silverstein:
</P>
<P>
   _ Designs and supervises all of the company's rainwear.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oversees the graphic designs of everything from umbrella hang
tags to catalogs, Web sites and gift packaging.
</P>
<P>
   _ Supervises the new children's division, designing all the
kids' raincoats and slippers herself, and coordinating umbrellas
and cold-weather products.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein _ clad on a casual Friday in jeans, black T-shirt
and a 10-year-old jacket of her own design _ sits in her office
surrounded by bins of colorful umbrellas and rain jackets on
hangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a neat new fabric called Watersilk,'' she says,
holding up a swatch. ``We're looking at a PVC fabric for kids that
changes color in water.''
</P>
<P>
   Her schedule frequently takes her to her favorite city, New
York, where she makes major-account sales calls, works with
industry-forecasting services, shops hot new areas for inspiration
and works with vendors to develop products.
</P>
<P>
   She goes to Hong Kong once a year to tweak production specifics
and look for new techniques and materials.
</P>
<P>
   John Catt, the company's marketing director for rain products,
credits Silverstein with being the first to spot and fill consumer
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean has a creative vision that is truly unprecedented,'' says
Catt. ``Our apparel business didn't exist four years ago and is
becoming an increasingly large part of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   That's thanks to Silverstein, who came up with the concept for a
``first-floor rainwear'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, if you wanted to buy a raincoat you'd go to
the apparel department and spend $150 on a nice piece of outerwear
and expect to get a couple of seasons wear out of it,'' Catt
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein proposed taking an accessories approach to rainwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research suggests the average female customer buys a new
umbrella every seven months,'' Catt says. ``Jean wanted to take
that spontaneous approach to other rainwear, so she came up with a
line of raincoats that looked terrific but could retail for $30 or
$35 or $40. She made sure the outer shell matched the hot umbrella
covers of the season and the linings matched our umbrella prints,
and we evolved from being an umbrella department into being a
full-fledged coordinated rain shop. It's a business that didn't
exist five years ago. Jean literally created this category and has
designed by hand every coat we've done since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's rain fashions were added in 1999; the kids' category will
debut this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the raincoats done well, Catt adds, but the
company is also selling more umbrellas because customers can now
assemble _ for about $60 _ coordinated ensembles of hats and coats,
umbrellas and ponchos.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein, who grew up in Cincinnati, began sewing at a young
age. When her parents insisted she go to college, she balked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the (high school) counselor the only things I loved
were fashion, travel and sewing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The savvy adviser came up with the perfect solution: the
University of Cincinnati's well-known fashion design program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only place I applied and it was perfect,'' says
Silverstein, 39, who today serves as a judge for the fashion
department's critique sessions and hires its graduates _ and some
of her former teachers _ as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to students is to make the most of their time in
school,'' she says. ``We're so lucky to have the design school
here. Cincinnati has a better reputation than any other fashion
design program in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As a student, she learned the business through co-op jobs at
Neiman Marcus in Bal Harbour, Maine, and at I. Magnin in Los
Angeles. Later she designed sweaters for The Eagle's Eye and
sportswear for MAG. She began traveling to Hong Kong, Taiwan, Korea
and the Philippines to perfect samples and ready lines for
production.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein's first job at Totes came in 1985 when she became an
assistant designer working on folding bags and luggage designs.
Later she designed umbrella patterns as a free lancer, and returned
to Cincinnati in 1990 when she was offered the job of director of
product development.
</P>
<P>
   One of her favorite projects dates to her student days at UC,
when she created a children's knitwear collection as a senior
thesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved children's wear,'' says Silverstein, who
still dreams of someday creating a kids' knitwear line.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she's getting her feet wet by designing kids'
rainwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great color outlet because you can do almost anything
and get away with it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new items are licensed products from Fisher Price for
this fall and a line of Harry Potter items that will be introduced
next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein's designs must specify every detail of each garment,
from outer shell material to zippers and buttons. She doesn't use a
drafting table, but sketches on a pad at her desk at work or
wherever she happens to be _ on airplanes, in restaurants. She's
always got a stack of European fashion magazines around to keep up
with trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the Burberry classic plaid thing is huge, so are
tech features such as elastic and mesh,'' she says, showing off a
sport utility jacket with built-in backpack straps.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Silverstein says she enjoys her job ``because it comes
naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
