<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-DEFENSE-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF JUDGE HIRES LAWYER IN INQUIRY INTO ASSIGNMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. District Court Judge Norma Holloway Johnson,
the chief federal trial judge in Washington, has hired a lawyer to
represent her before judicial and congressional inquiries into why
she assigned several criminal cases involving President Clinton's
associates to judges Clinton had appointed.
</P>
<P>
   The first act of the lawyer, Michael Madigan, in representing
Johnson was to tell a Republican-led congressional investigation
that his client would decline to testify at any congressional
committee hearing into her behavior. Madigan, an experienced
Washington lawyer, was last in the spotlight as chief counsel to
the investigation by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., of possible
fund-raising irregularities in the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., the chairman of the
House Committee on Government Reform, Madigan said Johnson would
decline the invitation to testify before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Madigan said it would be unprecedented for a
sitting judge to be questioned by Congress about such an issue.
``We have the greatest respect for Congress but the constitutional
issues of separation of powers are just too great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue stems from complaints by Republican members of
Congress that Johnson bypassed the usual computer-operated system
that randomly assigns cases to trial judges under her for a handful
of cases. Those cases involved Webster L. Hubbell, an Arkansas
friend of the Clintons and former senior Justice Department
official and Charlie Yah Lin Trie, a fund-raiser for the president.
Johnson assigned those and some other criminal cases involving
associates of Clinton to four judges Clinton named to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the governing body of the local federal judicial
circuit named a panel of five judges to look into the charges. The
panel, in turn, recently hired Joe D. Whitley, an Atlanta lawyer
and former official in the Justice Department under Republican
presidents, to conduct its investigation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his letter to Burton, Madigan gave some indication of what
his approach would be in defending Johnson before the special
judicial panel. He said that the practice of going off the random
assignment system and handpicking judges in ``certain kinds of
cases'' had been in effect for many years. He cited a policy
adopted in 1971 by then-Chief Justice Warren Burger allowing for
complex cases to be assigned outside the random system. That method
was used, he noted, in cases involving the Watergate and
Iran-contra scandals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEAMSTERS-OVERNITE-AR     05-06 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-OVERNITE-ART-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE AT OVERNITE POSES TEST FOR TEAMSTERS CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT7,8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne Smith, a loading-dock worker who has been on
strike since October, was unmistakably glum as he picked through
the union's food bank for tomato sauce, pasta and breakfast cereal
to feed his five young daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his family's hard times, Smith, a large, barrel-chested
man, vowed to hold out as long as it takes in the grueling strike
that has become James P. Hoffa's biggest labor battle in his first
year as Teamsters president.
</P>
<P>
   So far the six-month war looks like a draw, a very painful draw,
that has many Teamsters struggling to pay their bills, while the
union's adversary, Overnite Transportation Co., has had its bottom
line hammered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of tough getting by, but the company, they're still
not treating people right,'' Smith said as he and his wife, Tamyko,
stuffed 20 pounds of free groceries into a large box at Teamsters
Local 728. ``The food bank helps a lot, but it's hard when you have
five kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Overnite fight has become not only one of the most closely
watched labor showdowns in the country, but also a brawl between a
union renowned for its toughness and a scrappy company that is
showing just as much grit. Neither Hoffa nor Overnite's parent
company, Union Pacific, has offered the slightest hint of blinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually Union Pacific is going to get the message that they
have to come to terms with the workers at Overnite,'' Hoffa said.
</P>
<P>
   To raise the stakes, Hoffa said the union was planning a federal
racketeering lawsuit that would charge Overnite with breaking the
law hundreds of times, by, for example, firing many union
supporters, as part of a strategy to do anything to avoid a union
contract. The company denies using illegal tactics.
</P>
<P>
   That would follow a racketeering lawsuit that Overnite has
brought against the International Brotherhood of Teamsters,
accusing its members of firing shots at drivers who have crossed
the picket line. In the most serious incident, an Overnite trucker
was shot in the stomach while driving outside Memphis, Tenn.
Teamsters officials deny advocating violence and say Overnite is
exaggerating the incidents to win sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Goodwin, a senior vice president at Overnite, said: ``It's
true no one has proven yet that they are responsible for the
shootings, but we never had any shootings before. For them to deny
the violence is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa has much at stake. He wants to show that the Teamsters can
increase membership in its core freight division. That division was
his father's base, and his father, James R. Hoffa, boasted that his
crowning achievement while running the union was securing a
nationwide freight agreement that greatly improved drivers' wages
and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of the Teamsters say that the younger Hoffa, with
an eye to next year's re-election campaign, hopes to be able to
boast by then that he has signed a contract with Overnite and
unionized most of its 166 terminals. With 8,200 drivers and dock
workers, Overnite is the nation's largest nonunion company that
specializes in carrying less than full truckloads.
</P>
<P>
   The broader labor movement sees major stakes in the Overnite
dispute. Many labor leaders say it is the most flagrant example of
how unions, after surmounting numerous obstacles to get workers to
vote in a union, then have a hard time getting companies to sign a
first contract.
</P>
<P>
   At several Overnite terminals the drivers and dock workers voted
to unionize over five years ago, but they still do not have a
contract. The union says it represents 3,600 workers at 37
terminals, but the company says that because of legal challenges
the union represents only 1,800 at 22 sites. The company estimates
that 700 workers are on strike, while the union puts the number at
1,700.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For one of those strikers, Eddie Dunn, at Overnite for 24 years,
the stakes are highly personal and boil down to regaining dignity
at work.
</P>
<P>
   While walking the picket line in front of Overnite's large
terminal in Atlanta, Dunn talked about how managers there sought
five years ago to force the most senior workers to take early
retirement or to work part time without benefits. He also
complained that no matter how hard he worked unloading trucks, a
manager always questioned why he could not work faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treated you like you weren't a human being,'' he said.
``They want to intimidate you. They always want you to do more and
more and more. Sometimes after the way they treat you, you feel
like crying. They want to rile you, and if you say something,
you're fired, you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of the 200 workers at the terminal here are on
strike, walking the picket line since October. Some clergy have
walked with them and other unions have donated $50,000 to help with
their food bills and mortgage payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's out
here, and they thought once the first snowfall came, we would
fold,'' Dunn said. ``We're serious here. We're fighting for a
better future. If we don't win, our kids will face a future with
jobs paying $5 or $6 an hour, subcontracting, no benefits, no
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the picket line, some 30 strikers poured out tales about how
they felt mistreated by Overnite. One truck driver said he felt
insulted when a manager called his doctor to ask whether a note
saying he was sick was forged. Another driver said that after going
for 10 years without a critical write-up, he got a notice putting
him at the brink of dismissal, just days after he signed a petition
favoring a union.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Williams, a driver for 27 years, said: ``The main reason
we're striking now, it's not for benefits or money. It's about
Overnite not being fair to the workers.'' Overnite drivers earn
nearly $18 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a wiry man wearing an Atlanta Falcons shirt, said
something was profoundly amiss when a majority of the 200 workers
at the Atlanta terminal voted to unionize in 1995, and Overnite has
still not signed a contract with the union.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa said: ``The fact is they're not negotiating in good faith.
We have had 163 negotiating sessions with little or no progress.
That tells you the story of whether or not they really want a
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   But Overnite officials insisted that they were bargaining in
good faith and blamed the union for often postponing negotiating
sessions. Goodwin held out little hope for a settlement, saying the
company would never accept the union's demand to place Overnite
workers in the Teamsters pension fund. He said Overnite's pension
fund was in excellent shape, while the Teamsters pension fund was
underfinanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked diligently at trying to reach an agreement with
them,'' Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa sees a more fundamental reason behind the failure to reach
a settlement: a visceral anti-union animus. He said the dispute had
cost the company far more than a settlement would have. Overnite
has spent tens of millions of dollars fighting the walkout. Its
financial performance over the last half-year has been considerably
worse than that of its major competitors, and many analysts say the
dispute has hurt Union Pacific's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodwin asserted that Overnite's revenues were growing and
that it returned to the black in the first quarter. He said that
the cost of a union contract would make the company less
competitive and would far outweigh whatever costs the company had
suffered because of the walkout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
