<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-ROBBINS-PROFILE0507-C     05-06 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBBINS-PROFILE0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for roadside attractions on life's journey
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Tom Robbins is curious about us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only judge areas of interest by the mail that I get, and
I get a lot from Ohio,'' he said. ``So I thought I'd better check
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been here before, sort of, having been pulled from a
military transport plane on its way from Washington, D.C., to
Omaha, where Robbins _ then in the midst of a three-year Air Force
stint _ was stationed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the night in the stockade at Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base,'' he said. ``We stopped for refueling or whatever in
Dayton and they found out I was technically AWOL, so they escorted
me to the local brig hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in the late '50s, before Robbins, now 63, ``found his
voice'' while writing a review of a Doors concert, way before the
1971 publication of his first novel, ``Another Roadside
Attraction,'' but well into a life defined by its search for
nonexistent answers to all the very big questions.
</P>
<P>
   His newest book, ``Fierce Invalids Home From Hot Climates''
(Bantam, $27.50), takes on, in his words, ``the contradictory
nature of reality, the interplay of opposites that is the engine
that runs our universe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about having your cake and eating it too, which always
seemed to me to be an arrangement that is only fair. It's about the
possibility in today's world of combining a life of freewheeling
sensuality and high adventure with serenity and deep wisdom and
full consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, of course, it's personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born a romantic, and I've been a romantic all my life,''
he said. ``For the past 30-plus years I've been on a winding and
twisting spiritual path, and the two don't always interface very
smoothly. The whole essence of romanticism is the notion of an
elsewhere _ the romantic is always dreaming of other places and
other times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole essence of the mission of the spiritual disciple is
to be here now, to live in the the present and be fully present.
There's a real dichotomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins has said he considers ``Another Roadside Attraction''
the quintessential book of the 1960s. A plot summary _ Jesus' mummy
is stolen from the Vatican and displayed at a roadside zoo _ is
misleading and somewhat pointless; Robbins' books never lend
themselves to a nutshell treatment. Its reception by critics
confounded the author.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raised what I thought was a compelling issue _ what if it
were to be learned indisputably that Jesus Christ was not divine?
What would that say about the future of Western civilization? What
impact would that have on ethics and moral behavior?
</P>
<P>
   ``To my dismay, not one reviewer ever discussed that. I haven't
read a review voluntarily since, though I've had a few shoved in my
face.''
</P>
<P>
   A list of titles (''Even Cowgirls Get the Blues,'' ``Half Asleep
in Frog Pajamas,'' ``Jitterbug Perfume,'' ``Skinny Legs and All,''
``Still Life with Woodpecker'') would understandably give the
impression of weirdness within; a reading of first lines would
cement that notion. And Robbins, while offbeat, is a dead serious
writer, disciplined and meticulous in his work and work habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in pursuit of what I have sometimes called the perfect
sentence,'' he said. ``There's not a word in one of my books that
hasn't been gone over 40 times ... I almost read the ink right off
the page.''
</P>
<P>
   He still writes in longhand, with a goal of two pages a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say I only write on draft, it's a little misleading. I
write very slowly, and try never to leave each sentence until it's
as perfect as I can make it. There's no need for a lot of
revision.''
</P>
<P>
   His stories are often called wacky, zany, whimsical, and they
are, but that's one narrow way of looking at Tom Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plots are very tight,'' he said. ``They're full of cross
references _ as I'm writing I'm juggling many balls simultaneously
in order to keep them all in the air. I have to keep a lot of
things in mind. It's exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   He's reluctant to describe his writing process any further,
comparing it to ``those cooking shows on Japanese television where
they give the celebrity chef one or two mystery ingredients, then
ring the bell and he has 16 minutes to concoct a world-class meal.
If he fails, he commits culinary hari-kari, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start with two or three themes that are completely
unconnected at the time, introduce a character _ frequently a
female _ and very gently shove this character into a scene that may
or may not be overtly connected to one of the themes. Then I follow
their process. It's literally a trip, and the trick is in order to
achieve any kind of artistry with this method or working, it
requires an enormous concentration, a real intense focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a working method I would recommend to other
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been 5 1/2 years since his last release _ about right for
Robbins, who won't even begin a new book until his work promoting
``Fierce Invalids'' is behind him. He takes a year off between
novels and makes up for lost play time: On a two-day trip to New
York, he said he slept ``about two hours,'' and has a well-earned
reputation as a party boy, especially during the days of LSD and
Timothy Leary, both good acquaintances of his.
</P>
<P>
   Even his work, he says, is really like play: ``But it's hard
play.... Play is not necessarily frivolous. It's not a synonym for
the trivial.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins takes great care, and has fun with the language _
``Fierce Invalids Home From Hot Climates'' opens with this
sentence: ``The naked parrot looked like a human fetus spliced onto
a kosher chicken,'' and his descriptions can be breathtakingly
beautiful. But like he said, play can be very hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain amount of playfulness in my work, in my
world view, and when you read that on the page some people jump to
the conclusion that I just sit down and rattle these things off at
the top of my head for an hour or two, go out and carouse and come
back a few days later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. He writes every day: ``To sit around and wait for
inspiration is for amateurs,'' he said, ``and at the end of a
writing day I feel like I've been scraped off the track at the
Indianapolis oval.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
