u s BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-06 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `WEL-COME TO BOB SHEPP-ARD DAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the New York Yankees' pinstriped voice, Bob
Sheppard usually arrives at the Stadium at least two hours before
game time. In his public-address announcer's cubicle on the
mezzanine level, he goes over the lineups, the proper pronunciation
of the names of any new players and whatever special announcements
he has to make.
</P>
<P>
   But not Sunday. Because Sunday is Bob Sheppard Day at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   About half an hour before Sunday's game, the now retired
professor of speech at St. John's University, tall and erect at an
age he won't discuss, will be honored at a home-plate ceremony in
his 50th year of elegant elocution at the big ballpark in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted,'' he was saying now, ``but I don't know why.
All I have is longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   And all the Yankees have is history. Anybody who has ever been
to Yankee Stadium knows that it's more than longevity. It's how he
intoned, ``Joe Di-Magg-i-o'' and ``Mick-ey Man-tle.'' It's what
prompted Reggie Jackson, upon joining the Yankees in 1977, to go
out of his way to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got class,'' Mr. October said.
</P>
<P>
   That class is in the timbre of a voice that his, wife, Mary, has
described as ``caressing,'' especially in his precise
pronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take great pride,'' he said, ``in how the names are to be
pronounced.'' Of the thousands of players' names he has pronounced,
he remembered three of his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shig-e-tosh-i Ha-se-ga-wa,'' he said, slowly and surely.
``Jo-se Val-di-viel-so. Sal-o-me Bar-o-jas. They're so euphonic.''
</P>
<P>
   Some names concerned him, notably that of Wayne Terwilliger, an
infielder who came through the Stadium with the old Washington
Senators and the Kansas City Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worried that I would say, `Ter-wigg-ler,''' Sheppard said,
``but I never did.''
</P>
<P>
   His style has provoked mimics. Whenever Reggie Jackson is at the
Stadium, he visits the public-address booth and, in his best
imitation, greets the announcer with, ``Good eve-ning, Mis-ter
Shepp-ard, wel-come to Yank-ee Sta-dium.'' Joe Garagiola also
echoed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Derek Jeter is doing it now,'' Sheppard said.
</P>
<P>
   In other sports, especially pro basketball, some public-address
announcers sound as if they're emceeing a wrestling show, shouting
loudly and dragging out a name as if it were a drum roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to be clear, concise and correct,'' Sheppard said.
``I don't change my pattern. I speak at Yankee Stadium the same way
I do in a classroom, a saloon, or reading the Gospel at Mass at St.
Christopher's.''
</P>
<P>
   When he announces the lineups now, he sounds the same as he did
that April day in 1951 when he worked his first Yankee game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny Mize was the first baseman,'' he remembered, ``Jerry
Coleman was at second, Phil Rizzuto at shortstop, Billy Johnson at
third, Jackie Jensen in left field, Joe DiMaggio in center field,
Mickey Mantle in right field, Yogi Berra catching, Vic Raschi
pitching. We beat the Red Sox, and I got through it without any
gliches.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has had an occasional glitch.
</P>
<P>
   After working a Yankee game one afternoon, Sheppard hurried over
to Giants Stadium (he's done New York Giants games since 1956) and
said, ``Good evening, ladies and gentlemen, welcome to Yankee
Stadium.'' At halftime of an Army-Navy game in Philadelphia during
John F. Kennedy's administration, he informed the crowd that the
president was about to go from the Army side to the Navy side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cold,'' he recalled, ``but the president was only
wearing a business suit. I told one of my spotters, `He doesn't
even have a topcoat on.' I didn't realize my microphone was on.
Everybody in the stadium heard it.''
</P>
<P>
   His microphone should always be on. At St. John's coming
commencement, he will receive an honorary degree as a doctor of
pedagogy. In his translation, that means master teacher, as any
Yankee fan will attest.
</P>
<P>
   Once a St. John's quarterback, he was playing semipro football
on Long Island, N.Y., when he offered to be the PA announcer for a
pro football exhibition game at Freeport Stadium. That led to his
announcing the pro football Brooklyn Dodgers' games, then those of
the pro football Yankees in the old All-America Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later on, I did the New York Titans at the Polo Grounds,'' he
said of that early American Football League franchise known for its
lack of cash flow. ``I never got paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in his 50th season on the Yankees' payroll, he has never
missed a game because of illness. ``Weddings, births, family
parties,'' he said, ``I've missed a few games for those reasons.''
And he'll miss Sunday's game. After the ceremony, his longtime
backup, Jim Hall, will be the PA announcer.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Shepp-ard has the rest of the af-ter-noon off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
