<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-CLASH0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Open up, it's the MP3 MPs
 &HT;    By Ron Rollins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Somebody was pounding at the door. The teen-age
boy got up from the couch. Outside stood four large men in black
uniforms, helmeted and armed with big, scary-looking nightsticks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I help you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Police. Open up, kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, nobody here called the police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're special police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Say what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the Metallica Police. Don't make us get rough with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy stood aside as the four men stormed into the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's your computer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstairs. Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been named in court documents as having unlawfully
downloaded Metallica music off Napster,'' the first cop said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without paying for it,'' the second cop said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metallica's angry,'' the third cop said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're here to collect,'' said the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collect how?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You downloaded 10 songs. You owe Metallica $1.50 per song.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't have that much money on me, and my parents aren't
home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you should've thought about that when you were illegally
ripping off your favorite heavy-metal artists, then, shouldn't you?
You didn't think about poor Metallica when you were stealing them
blind at your keyboard, did you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You thought your nasty little MP3 player was above this fine
nation's copyright laws, didn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You thought you'd never have to suffer for taking food out of
Metallica's mouth, did you?''
</P>
<P>
   The Metallica Police all sneered. The kid dug into his wallet
and came up with $6. ``That's all I have right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, then. We'll take your computer.'' Three of the Metallica
Police fanned off through the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take my computer?!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, and back at the station we'll check your nasty little
hard drive to see which other poor musicians you've been filching
from. You thoughtless little swine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, but, but _ I'm a big Metallica fan! I have all their
albums!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, indeed you do, don't you?'' said one of the Metallica
Police, emerging from the boy's room. ``This copy of ``Load ``looks
like it came from a secondhand store.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah. So what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think the artist sees a penny from that sale, you
wretch? We'll have to confiscate this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, but, but....''
</P>
<P>
   ``But nothing _ he also has this tape from a live radio
broadcast in the early '90s. It's clearly unauthorized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good work. Bring it along.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of the Metallica Police emerged with an armful of books,
posters and CDs. ``Do you have receipts for any of this?'' he
demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can reclaim it at the station when you produce them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey! All I did was download a few songs! Metallica's got
plenty of money! That's not fair! It's just music!''
</P>
<P>
   The Metallica police all laughed. ``You pathetic little moron.
It isn't music. It's business. By the way, did you buy that concert
shirt in the arena at an officially authorized Metallicawear
outlet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I bought it in the parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hand it over.''
</P>
<P>
   As the cackling Metallica Police left the house, four more
uniformed men appeared on the front step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you guys?'' the boy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dr. Dre Police. Is your little brother home?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
