<SLUG> BC-IRAQI-EVIDENCE-REBUTTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT REHEARING, IRAQI DOCTOR WINS ROUND IN DEPORTATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb., Calif.)  By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Iraqi doctor who worked with the CIA against
Saddam Hussein, only to be jailed for nearly four years on the
basis of secret CIA evidence, may soon be free, his lawyer said
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ali Yasin Mohammed Karim was evacuated from Iraq to the
United States in 1996 after the collapse of a CIA plot against
Saddam, the Iraqi leader. He was summarily jailed in California on
the basis of reports compiled by the intelligence agency and
presented by the FBI to an immigration judge.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, D.D. Sitgraves, ruled last week that lawyers for
the jailed Iraqi now have presented ``more than sufficient
evidence'' to rebut the government's claim that he should be
deported as a threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who was rehearing the case, essentially reversed her
original 1998 decision, a 92-page ruling based almost entirely on
secret government evidence. That ruling was withheld from Karim's
lawyers on national-security grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The use of secret evidence, once exceedingly rare, has become
increasingly common in cases involving government claims of
national security. In November, a federal district judge in New
York freed an Egyptian man jailed for 3{ years on the basis of
secret evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But in October, in a case involving a Palestinian immigrant
jailed for nearly four years, a federal district judge in New
Jersey ruled, for the first time in the United States, that it was
unconstitutional to detain an immigrant on the basis of secret
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration judge in the Palestinian's case called some of
the government's secret evidence ``double or triple hearsay.''
Karim's lawyers say much the same in his case.
</P>
<P>
   Karim, a 37-year-old radiologist who worked with CIA-backed
Iraqi opposition groups, remains in jail, pending the judge's final
decision, said one of his lawyers, Neils Frenzen.
</P>
<P>
   His wife divorced him after he was imprisoned and he does not
know where his children are, or if he will see them again, Frenzen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has lost the things most dear to him _ his freedom, his
liberty, his family, his sons,'' Frenzen said.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge's ruling, handed down on Monday, means that Karim
may be granted political asylum this month, Frenzen said.
</P>
<P>
   The secret evidence against Karim was withheld from his lawyers,
until a former CIA director, R. James Woolsey, entered the case for
the defense in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey held security clearances sufficient to review the
evidence, most of which the government finally declassified. Much
of it was a series of suppositions by CIA officers, based in part
on hearsay, that Karim might have connections with Iranian
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Upon reviewing the evidence, Woolsey called it ``nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren J. Marik, a retired CIA case officer who was assigned to
Iraq and worked with Karim, testified last month that ``there was
nothing to bring any suspicion'' on him.
</P>
<P>
   Karim, an Iraqi Kurd, worked with the Iraqi National Congress,
which played a central role in a $20-million-a-year set of CIA
operations that sought to undermine Saddam. The clandestine plots
began shortly after the 1991 Persian Gulf War and went on for five
years, without success.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, the plots finally collapsed when the Iraqi
military seized towns in northern Iraq that had served as bases for
the plots. Karim and his family were among 600 men, women and
children who fled for their lives, along with a small group of CIA
officers who had worked with them. They were flown to Guam, and
then to California, where Karim was detained and jailed.
</P>
<P>
   The government's ``primary evidence was a CIA conclusion,''
Frenzen said. ``The FBI was told by one or more CIA employees in
Guam that Karim's cousin was an Iranian intelligence agent.''
</P>
<P>
   One FBI agent, John Peterson, testified that he could not say
whether the assertion, if true, had any significance for Karim.
``It may have nothing to do with him, it may have a great deal to
do with him,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   After the government agreed to declassify its evidence, it
offered to resettle Karim and five other Iraqis jailed as potential
national-security risks in a third country, not the United States
or Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting a resolution, the five have chosen to live with
their families in Lincoln, Neb., rather than spend years in prison
fighting the case. Karim chose to fight the government's case to
clear his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
