<SLUG> BC-TV-POST0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Cate &AMP; Cupid'' goes beyond fun and romance
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH Fla. _ Sometimes, TV critics are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't happen often. OK, you can stop laughing now. But it
does occur. Case in point: when I received the tape of the CBS
movie ``Cupid &AMP; Cate,'' I thought I had the film pegged. Before
watching it, I skimmed the press notes. I thought they told me
everything I needed to know. Cate De Angelo (Mary-Louis Parker) is
a woman in a tiresome relationship with her boring fiance (David
Lansbury). Cate's life, however, gets a much-needed jump-start
after her sister introduces her to Harry (Peter Gallagher), a funny
guy who makes Cate laugh and tingle.
</P>
<P>
   These storyline dots will be mighty easy to connect, I thought.
My assumption was ``Cate &AMP; Cupid'' would be a mostly fun,
lighthearted romantic romp. A sugary two hours with all the depth
of a kiddie pool.
</P>
<P>
   As I mentioned before, I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I get paid to actually watch the movies I write
about. Sure, ``Cate &AMP; Cupid'' is fun and romantic in spots. After
all, Cate and Harry do fall in love. They have coffee together. Go
to Alfred Hitchcock film festivals and eat Chinese food on Cate's
balcony.
</P>
<P>
   But the film is about much more than just Cate's and Harry's
love affair, which develops too quickly. It's about fractured
family relationships, old wounds that still hurt and finding one's
place in life. Issues all families can relate to on various levels.
Ironically, I found Cate and Harry's relationship the least
interesting component of the movie. Maybe that's because Gallagher,
and his bush-thick eyebrows, has always given me the creeps. He
should only play serial killer or stalker roles. His jarring looks
are better suited for those parts.
</P>
<P>
   Much more fascinating was Cate's rocky relationship with her
widowed dad (a scene-chewing Philip Bosco). Cate sells vintage
clothes for a living. But her dad playfully calls her a ``rag
seller.'' When he sees Cate for the first time in a long while, he
barks she looks pale and thin, and is in need of a good meal. The
comments, of course, sting. Verbal abuse is often more damaging
than physical abuse. Cate shows the hurt by simply lowering her
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   According to her father, Cate pales in comparison to her three
sisters. Francesca (Bebe Neuwirth) is a successful doctor. Cynthia
(Joanna Going) is a top fashion model. Annette (Rebecca Luker) is
the perfect mom with a banker hubby.
</P>
<P>
   But Cate does something her sisters don't _ she stands up to her
intimidating father. That's why there's a lot of stilted
conversation and awkward silence during the film's many dinner
scenes. Those scenes are also the movie's most powerful. Parker is
brilliant as the strong-on-the-outside, but fragile-on-the-inside
Cate. Bosco is also utterly convincing as the overbearing dad.
</P>
<P>
   And Gallagher?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he should get his eyebrows plucked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
