<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HOCKEY: GAUGING THE RISE AND FALL OF THE RED WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The decline of the Detroit Red Wings was verified Friday night
when they were eliminated again from the Stanley Cup playoffs by
the Colorado Avalanche, this time in five games, in a 4-2 finale.
After consecutive championships in 1997 and 1998, the Wings have
twice exited in the second round of the four-round tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche, which also bounced the Wings last spring, will
meet either Dallas or San Jose in the Western Conference finals.
With Ray Bourque healing on defense, Peter Forsberg robust at
forward and Patrick Roy both quick and cocky in goal, the Avalanche
might make the finals for the first time since it won the cup in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shame for the Wings, despite several tacky displays
of frustration on Friday. They are still a good regular-season club
but no longer of the top echelon in the postseason. Captain Steve
Yzerman, with no goals in the tournament, is near that career stage
where age _ he turns 35 on Tuesday _ and injuries begin to blend,
much as they did for Wayne Gretzky in his New York era.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, no matter how many Chris Chelioses and Steve
Duchesnes they collect, the Red Wings cannot fill the void left by
the tragic loss of Vladimir Konstantinov, paralyzed in a limo crash
while celebrating the first title. And what about behind the bench,
where Coach Scotty Bowman still seeks his record-breaking ninth
ring?
</P>
<P>
   In his experienced way, Bowman has let it be known through
others that it would be interesting for the Rangers to consider him
for the general manager's and coach's vacancies. Bowman held the
two jobs, in various combinations, in Buffalo, in the 1980s,
without great success. Even at age 66, he still has something to
prove. This is not to say the Rangers would offer Bowman all this
power or that he would accept it, or that the Wings would make it
easy to leave.
</P>
<P>
   It is just an intriguing thought, better than the possibilities
planted in the rumors involving Glen Sather and Colin Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   In the other Western bracket, Dallas took a 3-1 lead over San
Jose with a ragged 5-4 victory on Friday. The San Jose team is a
sports rarity: a scrappy underdog difficult to like. Maybe it's the
belligerence of Owen Nolan, the menace of Bryan Marchment or the
constant tripping, spearing, slashing and shoving of a dozen other
Sharks. Marchment left with an injury Friday and Nolan played in
evident discomfort. So the Sharks should fall out in Game 5 Sunday,
just as they should have fallen to the Blues in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche will probably hope that San Jose can extend the
Stars for another game or two, wearing down the Dallas veterans,
maybe injuring one or two of them, while Colorado rests. Rarely
elegant or charismatic _ despite stylists like Mike Modano, Brett
Hull and Sergei Zubov _ the Stars, like Detroit in 1998, know what
it takes to repeat. But, can they do it?
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the Devils had reason to fret before Game 5 with
the Maple Leafs in Toronto on Saturday night. New Jersey was the
best team for most of the previous four games and got only a 2-2
split to show for it. If Toronto's Mats Sundin, Steve Thomas and
Jonas Hoglund can find the form they showed in the first-round
elimination of Ottawa, the injury-depleted Leafs might be back in
the conference finals for the second successive season.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins must meet the winner of the wacky
Philadelphia-Pittsburgh series, which resumes Sunday, tied at two
victories each, on the ABC network at noon. The Flyers' 2-1 victory
in five overtimes Thursday night should give them momentum. But no
home team has won yet in this matchup. In this year's round of
eight, these two teams bring the best narrative and cast of
characters.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't Roger Neilson's cancer recovery and Eric Lindros'
concussion problems, it is the emergence of the undrafted rookie
Andy Delmore and the bullish determination of John LeClair and the
brilliance of Jaromir Jagr and the re-emergence of Herb Brooks.
This series in particular reminds even hockey knockers of why the
Stanley Cup playoffs usually make for the best tournament of the
sports year. These playoffs will be half complete this week, and
they are starting to get really good.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of good: Critics who constantly whine about poor hockey
telecasts (see name at top of column) should be fair enough to
notice when games are presented with flair and a knowing touch.
Such was the case in the Detroit-Colorado series on ESPN. The
camera work was an impressive blend of aggressiveness and
restraint, the whole product as good as anything Hockey Night in
Canada or MSG ever present.
</P>
<P>
   For those of the cult who make playoff viewing a nightly
obsession, telecasts like these are a joy to behold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
