<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS-HEAT BATTLE LINES DRAWN, BUT FIRST, A GROUP
HUG 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Welcome to another installment of the National
Basketball Association's premier rivalry, our main playoff event.
New York vs. Miami, brunchtime basketball served with your bagels,
rated PG (for Please, Guys, we need the ratings).
</P>
<P>
   Herewith, our historical primer on the Knicks-Heat series, now
into its fourth hit season, based on interviews over the previous
week with players and coaches from both teams, edited by NBA
Entertainment and narrated by Ahmad Rashad.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR I, 1996-97
</P>
<P>
   Seldom did any opposing coach in the history of professional
team sports ever receive the unadulterated love that Madison Square
Garden showered Pat Riley with before a second-round series between
his former team, the Knicks, and his new Eastern Conference power,
the Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   During the thunderous pregame ovation, Riley blew kisses to the
Garden faithful and thanked them again for attending the fan
appreciation gala he threw at his Connecticut estate upon his
amicable departure from the Knicks two years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``May the best man win,'' Riley said, smiling, while meeting the
handshake of his former boss, the Garden president, Dave Checketts,
who proceeded to pull Riley from the back of the neck and say,
``Come on over, Riles, and let's have a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5 of a stirring series that was already being hailed by
critics for its high level of aesthetic, sportsmanlike play, a
strange incident occurred late in Game 5 with the Knicks leading,
3-1. Lined up for a free throw, Knicks point guard Charlie Ward had
an untimely fainting spell and staggered into the knees of Miami
forward P.J. Brown. Brown wrapped his arms around Ward, flipped him
over as he would a baby and laid him gently behind the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody, help!'' Brown cried as Ward lay still.
</P>
<P>
   Closest to the scene, several Knicks responded to Brown's
frantic plea, forgetting that they were in violation of the
league's rule against leaving the bench during a game. Although
Riley pleaded with the league to consider the extenuating
circumstances, Commissioner David Stern insisted the rules must be
abided by. Several Knicks were suspended, and the Heat rallied to
win the series in seven.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR II, 1997-98
</P>
<P>
   In a shooting slump for much of the season, John Starks caught
fire in the second half of Game 2 in Miami, as the Knicks evened
the first-round series, heading back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Starks and his teammate Chris Childs were
both the unfortunate victims of media fiction. Childs, in fact, was
scratching a rash on his neck, not making the slash gesture, as it
appeared to several misguided newsmen. Meanwhile, Starks, a
longtime road arena favorite, was so excited by his clutch
shooting, he wanted to remain on the floor and sign autographs for
the South Florida fans. Holding up a pencil that would later be
mistaken for his middle finger, Starks began advancing toward the
admiring fans, but Larry Johnson grabbed him around the neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``John, we have a plane to catch and interview obligations to
meet,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, fellas,'' Starks said. ``Rain check.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in New York, Heat guard Eric Murdock caught Childs' rash,
and couldn't stop himself from scratching after making a big basket
in Miami's Game 3 victory. Game 4 was a Knicks-Heat classic, except
for another bizarre development in the final seconds of a
series-tying Knicks victory.
</P>
<P>
   While trying to cleanly establish inside position on Alonzo
Mourning along the baseline near the Knicks bench, Johnson lost his
balance and accidentally pushed Mourning into Jeff Van Gundy. The
diminutive Knicks coach was knocked horizontal and tried to keep
himself from falling by grabbing Mourning's leg. It took several
players and both team doctors to detach Van Gundy from Mourning,
who had such cramps in his legs from Van Gundy's grip that he
couldn't play in the Knicks' series clincher two days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lucky one for us, and one for you,'' Riley told his
protege, Van Gundy, after fighting through crowds of reporters and
fans to shake the winning coach's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disgraced with myself for injuring your player,'' Van
Gundy said. ``I owe you. Big Macs on me, after the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   YEAR III, 1998-99
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had made a key addition to their roster for another
first-round battle with Miami, Latrell Sprewell, the fearless guard
well known for heroically pulling several dangerous ticks from the
neck of his former coach, P.J. Carlesimo, at Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   After more critically acclaimed displays of offensive skill, the
Knicks won the decisive Game 5 in Miami again, on Allan Houston's
runner just before time expired. Charlie Ward called it a divine
act of preordainment, and Riley said he couldn't possibly argue
with him. Riley invited both teams to his home for a barbecue and
swim party, and they all sat around reminiscing about the happy
times they had shared _ Riley with Van Gundy, Mourning with Johnson
and Patrick Ewing, Hardaway with Sprewell, Brown with Childs, and
so on and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Then Riley stood up, raised his glass and said, ``A toast to the
winners!''
</P>
<P>
   ``To good sportsmen,'' Van Gundy said, ``and to getting together
again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year is now. Come on over, everyone, and let's have a hug. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
