<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-06 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENNSYLVANIA ABORTION POLITICS; WEST VIRGINIA'S GOP CHALLENGE; A
VIRGINIA PLEDGE; OHIO'S MOTTO; A FLORIDA PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., W.Va., Ohio., Fla., Va.)   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speculation has been especially intense since Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas raised the possibility that he may choose Gov. Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania as a running mate. Not only does Ridge hail
from an important battleground state with 23 electoral votes, but
he also happens to be a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whenever Ridge's name comes up, the point is almost
always made that unlike Bush, Ridge favors abortion rights, hardly
something that will endear him to the powerful Republican right. No
matter, Bush has said time and again, his friend merits
consideration as a top prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge's critics think otherwise, and they seem bent on driving
their point home.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Ridge surely would prefer to be viewed as a
governor who has cut taxes, improved schools, reformed welfare and
cleaned up the environment, the Pro-Life Caucus in the Pennsylvania
Legislature is pushing hard to strip $4.3 million for family
planning from the state budget, arguing that the money is
``contributing to the abortion process.'' Ridge wants to keep the
money in and, if the past is prologue, he will fight.
</P>
<P>
   When the issue came up in 1995, he managed to outmaneuver the
caucus, even though a majority of the Legislature is anti-abortion.
And in 1996, he worked a compromise, retaining state money for use
for family planning in general but agreeing that none would be used
for abortions or abortion counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Pro-Life Caucus, state Rep. Jerry Birmelin, a
Republican from Pike County in the northeast corner of the state,
says that while the governor may prefer that the funds issue not be
on the legislative agenda at this point in the presidential
campaign, the timing had nothing to do with him. ``Not my goal,''
Birmelin said the other day. ``It's not centered on him or anything
he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   WEST VIRGINIA: ASSESSING THE UNLIKELY
</P>
<P>
   There may be members of the U.S. Senate more entrenched than
Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va. But surely not many. Byrd, an exceptionally
adroit procurer of political bacon, has won seven six-year terms,
most by 2-to-1 or better, and the expectation is that he will win
an eighth term this fall by at least that much.
</P>
<P>
   So this is what David Tyson, the chairman of the West Virginia
Republican Party, had to say last week when asked whether the
party's primary on Tuesday might produce a viable Byrd challenger:
</P>
<P>
   ``Running against Byrd is like running against an icon. Sen.
Byrd is an institution, and there's no denying that he could be
impossible to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   That, to use an old George Wallace political aphorism, was
putting the hay down where the goat could get it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two primary contenders, Garry Adkins, an accountant,
took umbrage. He accused Tyson of ``assisting a Democrat'' and
demanded that the party remove him.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's reply:
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not endorse Democrats. I support the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   No action, thus far, by the party and no complaint, thus far,
from the other primary contender, David Gallaher, a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA: INCUMBENT'S MONEY-BACK OFFER
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Virginia's 5th Congressional District were not
especially surprised this year when Rep. Virgil H. Goode, a
lifelong member of their party, announced he would seek re-election
this fall as an independent and caucus with Republicans should he
win. His votes on Capitol Hill had been trending Republican for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   How hard will it be to win re-election as an independent?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not all that difficult. Both Democrats and Republicans
in the district, in the south-central part of the state, tend to be
strongly conservative, and in earlier elections Goode not only got
the Democratic vote but also a lot of the Republican vote. What is
more, the district, like Goode, has been trending Republican for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   So with no strong Democratic challenger in the offing _ and no
Republican even running _ he seems well positioned to win again.
But just to be safe, he tried last week to soften what Democratic
opposition there is.
</P>
<P>
   Any Democrat who gave him campaign money before he became an
independent, he said, could mail in a request for a refund _ he has
almost $400,000 in his war chest _ and it would be considered.
</P>
<P>
   As of the weekend, only one request had come in, for $50, and
the check was in the mail, with a note of thanks for past support.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO: TRUSTING IN GOD
</P>
<P>
   For 41 years, Ohio's official state motto was ``With God, all
things are possible.'' Then, two weeks ago, a three-judge federal
appeals panel ruled that the motto violated the religious freedom
clause of the Constitution because it was drawn from a statement by
Jesus in Matthew 19:26.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general plans an appeal, all the way to the
U.S. Supreme Court if necessary, a step endorsed last week by the
Ohio Senate. But two senators, Ben E. Espy of Columbus and Leigh E.
Herington of Revenna, both Democrats, are urging their colleagues
and the attorney general to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   They say they have a better, far less costly and time-consuming
idea: Adopt the phrase now found on U.S. money, ``In God We
Trust.''
</P>
<P>
   That one, they contend, is already the official U.S. motto and
therefore a sure legal winner.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: A PRAYER OF THANKS
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of religion and politics, here is the take of the Rev.
Donald L. Roberts of Sarasota, Fla., as expressed in his prayer
that opened the session of the Florida Senate on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be great to be God, to get what you want, when you
want it, how you want it. We mere mortals are not that lucky. We
are always having to compromise to get what we want. We call the
process politics. Thank you, Lord. The session is almost over, the
budget deal is cut, education got some more money, we cut a few
taxes and, in the end, most everyone in this chamber didn't get
everything they wanted. And that is good news. That's politics,
Lord, and unless you want to move over and give up the job of being
God, which some of think is our birthright, we will have to muddle
along being satisfied with being the politicians you can create.
It's the fun part of being human. In the name of the God of all
things, even politics and politicians and, in rare instances, a
lobbyist or two, amen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
