<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-MAIN0507-COX     05-06 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-MAIN0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Complex issues surrounding Elian's fate
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When an Atlanta appeals court granted an injunction
last month in the case of Elian Gonzalez, its ruling jolted many
scholars familiar with immigration and family law.
</P>
<P>
   In its April 19 decision, the court seemed to suggest that
Immigration and Naturalization Service officials should have asked
6-year-old Elian about his political asylum claim and whether he
wishes to live in Cuba, or in the United States against the wishes
of his father.
</P>
<P>
   The issue will be addressed again Thursday when the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals considers the contentious immigration
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of three judges also must decide who speaks for Elian:
his great-uncle Lazoro Gonzalez, the Miami relative who had
temporary custody and continues to fight for Elian's political
asylum claim; or the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has
been allowed to intervene in the case and now has custody of Elian
at the Wye Plantation on the Eastern Shore of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   If Elian's case was to be decided solely on state court family
law, it would be a no-brainer, family law experts said. This is
because most state courts give little, if any, weight to
life-altering requests made by minors, particularly if the child
has a surviving biological parent who has been found legally fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the issue of asylum seems to me an enormously
complicated question that I don't believe a 6-year-old has any
business deciding,'' said Paul Kurtz, a University of Georgia
professor on family law.
</P>
<P>
   The courts typically pay little attention to what a child has to
say, Kurtz added. ``That derives from common sense. Six-year-olds
don't know very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Gozansky, a family law professor at Emory University,
said that once Immigration and Naturalization Service officials
determined Juan Miguel Gonzalez was a fit parent, there should have
been little left to argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There shouldn't even be a dialogue now as to whether the child
would be better off growing up in the United States or Cuba,'' he
said. ``His father should have the right to return with his son to
his native land, the politics of that country notwithstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   But complicating the issue is that Elian's case is not
influenced solely by family law. It must also be decided in the
context of complex immigration statutes that require specific
procedures to be taken and findings to be made when federal
authorities consider political asylum claims.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has failed miserably in this regard, Kendall Coffey, the
lead lawyer for Elian's Miami relatives, said in briefs filed
before the court. Coffey is asking the court to appoint a guardian
with loyalties ``only to Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   And Coffey, the former U.S. Attorney in Miami, contended that
Elian's fear of persecution if he returns to Cuba is well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harm that would befall Elian if he is returned to Cuba is
clear: no freedom of expression, thought or speech,'' Coffey said.
``Elian will be forced into a program of desensitization and
reindoctrination, and to renounce his own mother and stepfather in
order to swear allegiance to the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, lawyers for Juan Miguel Gonzalez also minced few
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Miguel thinks that a 6-year-old boy found adrift in the
Atlantic Ocean and now caught up in the American legal system
craves the familiarity of his own bedroom in Cardenas,'' Gregory
Craig, the father's lawyer, told the court. ``Juan Miguel intends
to raise his child as he sees fit and where he sees fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig asserted that Elian's Miami relatives pressured the boy to
file his asylum claim and use the U.S. legal system in an attempt
to ``destroy'' Juan Miguel's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lazoro Gonzalez) now threatens to rob Elian of a childhood at
his home with his father, his family and his friends,'' added
Craig, who served as President Clinton's special counsel during the
impeachment trial. ``Nothing in law or humanity should compel such
a result.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of Walter Polovchak appears to be one of the few that
provides precedent to the three judges who will hear the case _
J.L. Edmondson of Atlanta, Joel Dubina of Montgomery and Charles
Wilson of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Polovchak's parents, Michael and Anna, left Russia with
their three children and immigrated to the United States. They
settled in Chicago but after several months, they decided to return
to the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   But 12-year-old Walter protested, preferring to stay in the
United States against his parents' wishes. He left home and went to
live with a cousin, who also lived in Chicago. Within days, the INS
granted Walter political asylum, separating him from his parents
and ruling he could stay in the United States if he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Michael Polovchak, a 42-year-old factory janitor,
strongly protested. ``Am I a drunkard?'' he asked members of the
news media. ``I am not. Do I starve my children? I do not. Have I
broken laws? I have not. So who is the government to take my
child?''
</P>
<P>
   A protracted litigation ensued, with Walter's parents trying to
regain custody and reunited the family in the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   They won one ruling when a federal court judge decided that
Walter should be returned to their custody. But in July 1985 the
7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overruled that decision. The
ruling came just a few months before Walter was about to turn 18
and become eligible to apply for U.S. citizenship, which he
eventually did.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the Chicago appeals court touched on the issue
of whether Walter, at age 12, was old enough to decide whether to
seek political asylum. ``Walter was presumably near the lower end
of an age range in which a minor may be mature enough to assert
certain individual rights that equal or override those of his
parents,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of a minor to decide which political system he wants
to live under increases with age, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter, who still lives in the United States, was pleased with
the court's ruling. He said at the time he missed his parents and
wanted to see them. But returning to the Soviet Union would
probably land him in jail. ``Freedom is something you can't buy for
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief on behalf of Elian's Miami relatives, Coffey
addressed the precedent set by the Polovchak case.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the 7th Circuit expressed skepticism that a
12-year-old boy was mature enough to seek asylum, Elian is an
``extremely bright child whose mental age is near the age of Walter
Polovchak when he filed his asylum application,'' Coffey wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He also contended that the INS did not follow proper procedure
when it failed to interview Elian, an omission the three 11th
Circuit judges criticized in their April 19 order.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing its stay keeping Elian in the country until the
appeals process is exhausted, the court seized on the language of
the 1980 immigration law that says ``any alien ... irrespective of
such alien's status, may apply for asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at age 6, Elian fits the description of ``any alien,'' the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   The judges did, however, note that the idea of a 6-year-old
filing for asylum, contrary to the wishes of his parents, ``may
seem a strange or even foolish policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Courts do not make immigration policy; Congress does, the judges
said. And if Congress intended school-age children to be able to
file personally for asylum, ``this court and the INS are bound to
honor the policy-decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Martin, a former INS general counsel and now a
University of Virginia law professor, said that was not Congress'
intent. And he predicted the 11th Circuit will not take the plain
language of the law that far.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
