u a BC-VIDALIA-SIDE0507-COX     05-06 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDALIA-SIDE0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Migrant workers transform rural communities
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIDALIA, Ohio _ The first migrant workers who arrive in
southeast Georgia each spring go shopping.
</P>
<P>
   They are Mexican crew chiefs getting ready for the 5,000 workers
who will harvest the $70 million crop of Vidalia onions. They buy
pots, pans, blankets, sheets and household cleaners like Clorox and
Pinesol.
</P>
<P>
   Then come the rest of the workers, mostly young Hispanic men who
leave behind families in their homelands to come pick onions in
flat, hot fields. They transform the rural communities of southeast
Georgia during the harvest months of April, May and June.
</P>
<P>
   Drive through Toombs County and you'll see Hispanic men shooting
baskets at a plywood goal at the Santa Claus Motor Inn. Turn the
radio dial past the sounds of salvation and steel guitars and
you'll hear mariachi music and the rhythms of spoken Spanish.
Stroll into the Piggly Wiggly in Lyons and notice the shelves full
of corn tortillas, sweet bread and guava nectar.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 counties, Hispanic migrants are as visible as they are
essential to the onion crop. The government said in 1998 that 70
percent were illegal immigrants, but few people in onion country
want the Immigration and Naturalization Service nosing around with
too many questions. Local law enforcement officers are also
deferential about the migrants. Chief James Reid of the Lyons
Police Department said his 14 officers _ one speaks Spanish _
sometimes arrest illegal immigrants for disorderly conduct, public
drunkenness and fighting. But he does not alert the INS because he
knows the role migrant workers play in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're an essential element to our farmers,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   For many migrants, Georgia is just one stop on a nationwide
circuit. After the onion harvest, they spend July and August in
tobacco and pepper fields in North Carolina. They move in the fall
to Ohio and Indiana to pick cucumbers and tomatoes. They return to
Georgia to plant the onions in November and December before going
to Florida for three months to pick oranges and grapefruit.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Coimenares, a slender 26-year-old illegal immigrant, is a
new arrival on the circuit. He has come to the United States with
his brother and a friend to earn wages that can be 10 times higher
than those in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, he sends $300 of his $400 paycheck to Mexico to
support his wife, 6-year-old son and infant daughter. His brother
and friend do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the old, white mobile home they share near Lyons, piles
of orange cord cover the living room floor. When they're not
picking onions, they use the cord to bale pine straw for farmers
who also rely on Hispanic migrant workers _ legal and illegal.
Elsewhere in the trailer, dirty clothes are strewn about. Taped to
walls of wood-grain paneling are two glossy magazine photographs of
scantily clad women.
</P>
<P>
   There are other pictures. Angel Coimenares keeps snapshots of
his wife and son in frames on the edge of his bed. Brother Pedro,
32, keeps his pictures in an album. Down the hall, friend Lorenzo
Rodriguez, 25, has four photos of his mother, wife and son in
gold-colored frames.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Georgia to help his family is Eliud Islas, 36, who left
his wife and three children in Veracruz, Mexico, after a storm
destroyed his house last autumn. He was one of dozens of migrants
working recently on a 60-acre field bounded by tall trees and a
country road near a crossroads called Johnson Corner.
</P>
<P>
   The snip-snip sound of a hundred clippers drifted through the
field. Men and women grabbed three or four onions at once and cut
brown roots from the bottom and green stems from the top. They
dropped the onions into into 6-gallon buckets. When the bucket
filled up, the workers poured them into bags.
</P>
<P>
   Two buckets fill a bag. The workers earn 70 cents a bag.
</P>
<P>
   Workers like Maribel Mendez, an 18-year-old illegal immigrant
from southern Mexico, can make $80 on a good day clipping and
bagging onions. Others lift and heave bag after bag _ 40 pounds
each _ onto slowly moving trucks. They can bring home more than
$100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Even though illegal immigrants sustain the onion business and
enrich merchants every time they buy a ham-and-cheese sandwich,
trash bags or bed sheets, their presence causes tension. In the
tiny town of Santa Claus, Hal Leverty has a front-row seat for the
culture clash that plays out each spring. He lives across from the
Santa Claus Motor Inn, where migrants live in hotel rooms and seven
mobile homes behind it.
</P>
<P>
   He complained about music from the trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't nothing an American would listen to,'' he said. ``On
weekends you can't hardly live here.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a mobile home with gray siding. ``Last fall I
counted 14 that came out of that trailer right there to go to work
one morning.'' While some locals gripe, migrants like Islas keep
working in the dirt and onions near Johnson Corner. The workers
have come to a field in a 1987 school bus with 22 green seats and
small sticker up front of the Virgin of Guadalupe, the patron saint
of Mexico. After the sun sets, they board the bus to go home to
aging mobile homes or hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The luckiest will go to a development onion grower R.T. Stanley
built for some of his workers. It has concrete picnic tables, a
soccer field with white goals and orange nets and a lake next to a
dozen duplexes of grey cinderblock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a model in this community,'' said Elmira R. Reynolds,
regional manager of the nonprofit Telamon Corp., which provides job
training and emergency food and transportation help to migrants.
</P>
<P>
   She sees that development as a sign of changing attitudes. Not
long ago, some farmers housed migrants in converted chicken coops.
Now more of them view migrants as an essential ingredient to a
healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the community has come to accept them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
