<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-VIDALIA0507-COX     05-06 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDALIA0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Illegal immigrants low priority in strong economy
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIDALIA , Ga. _ Rarely in Georgia has an industry's reliance on
illegal labor been so plainly revealed as it was here in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of that year's $70 million Vidalia onion harvest,
Immigration and Naturalization Service agents raided an onion field
and arrested 21 illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of more raids sent hundreds of migrant workers packing.
Farmers worried the crop would rot. Their hasty complaints to
Georgia congressmen led to a deal: The INS would let illegals pick
onions if growers promised to hire legal workers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   As this year's harvest of the sweet onions heads toward its
peak, labor is plentiful. Although the INS arrested 27 illegal
immigrants near Vidalia last year, the 1998 deal has been a clear
sign that attitudes toward illegal immigration _ and the
government's enthusiasm for enforcing immigration laws _ depend
very much on economics.
</P>
<P>
   When the economy is strong, the government usually makes it a
low priority to enforce illegal-immigration laws, but weaker
economies lead to crackdowns, said George Borjas, professor of
public policy at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The white-hot economy of the last decade has shaved unemployment
rates to their lowest levels in a generation. The number of illegal
immigrants the INS has arrested nationally in the last two years,
not counting criminals, fell from 22,000 to 8,600. That has been
good news to industries kept humming by their labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way we can get the job done is with Mexicans. They'll
start before the sun comes up and stay until after the sun goes
down,'' said R.T. Stanley, a prominent onion grower and chairman of
the Vidalia Onion Business Council, a group of 129 growers. Even
though the unemployment rate in the Vidalia onion region is 6
percent _ higher than the 3.4 percent state rate and the 4.1
percent national rate _ locals ``will not do this work'' because it
is low-paying and strenuous, Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   Most migrants make about $200-$300 a week in counties where
locals working other jobs average about $475.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 percent of year-round population in Montgomery, Tattnall
and Toombs counties, where the bulk of Vidalia onions are grown, is
Hispanic, but their numbers soar with the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   The industry leans so heavily on migrants, including illegal
immigrants, that farmers complained to Congress after the INS
arrested 21 illegal immigrants in 1998. Several Georgia
legislators, including Sen. Paul Coverdell and Rep. Jack Kingston,
both Republicans, signed a letter to Attorney General Janet Reno
saying the INS used ``bullying tactics'' and had shown ``a lack of
regard for farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   Their intervention led the INS to suspend raids after farmers
pledged to hire legal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell and Kingston are unlikely supporters of illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston said in 1993 that ``hard-working, tax-paying American
citizens are footing the bills for illegal aliens while their own
families are doing without.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Immigration Lawyers Association, which generally
advocates for immigrants, said Kingston did not side with the
association in seven major votes on immigration legislation from
1992-98. Coverdell has voted with the association on five of 12
chances, said Matt Tallmer, association spokesman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Ridgley, a spokeswoman for Kingsley, said Kingsley acted
in 1998 after ``jack-booted agents'' harassed migrant workers who
were in the country legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never condoned illegal aliens, but there is a big
difference between an illegal alien and a migrant worker who is a
legal guest in our country,'' she said. ``We are not going
wink-wink to any illegal aliens.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell also has defended his role in helping the onion
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I recognize that enforcement of immigration policy is
vital to maintaining our national security, INS...carried out its
campaign without ample regard for Georgia's farmers,'' he said last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell has introduced a bill to simplify a government program
that lets farmers import legal immigrants to work on farms _
Stanley and other farmers said the program costs too much and ties
them in red tape. Coverdell also pressured the Labor Department to
appoint an ombudsman to meet with farmers and relay their concerns
to top officials.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the INS has shifted its focus from rounding up
illegal immigrants to targeting the smugglers who bring them into
the country, said Bart Szafnicki, assistant INS director for
investigations in Georgia and three nearby states. Agents arrested
two smugglers in south Georgia last year and are examining records
in onion-company offices and discreetly asking questions as they
look for other smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Fischer, who until last year was the INS' top official in
four Southeastern states, including Georgia, said Congress has sent
mixed messages. On one hand, it passes laws against illegal
immigration and expects the INS to enforce them. But then
congressmen intervene on behalf of farmers and ask the INS to back
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have it both ways,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
