<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OCONNOR-MOURNERS-ART-     05-06 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-MOURNERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS MOURN CARDINAL AT ST. PATRICK'S 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11-13 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(With: OCONNOR-CHARISMA) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands of mourners from across the New York region
and the nation, including many children and disabled people,
converged Saturday on funereal-draped St. Patrick's Cathedral to
pay their last respects to Cardinal John O'Connor with prayers,
hymns and the ancient rites of Roman Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   On a sun-washed spring day with temperatures that climbed into
the high 80s, crowds stood for hours in long, slow-moving lines on
Fifth Avenue and 50th Street to enter the great cathedral double
doors draped with black-and-purple bunting for a last glimpse of
the cardinal, lying in state at the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Streaming under the arched gothic pillars almost all day, a
double line of somber-faced mourners filed past the cardinal's
bier, which was flanked by white-gloved police officers standing at
attention. Many people wept softly, and murmured prayers for the
cardinal, who died Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds also filled the 2,300-seat pews to overflowing for a
morning Mass in Spanish, for an afternoon Mass in English that was
organized for children and disabled people, and later for vesper
and rosary services. For many it was a day of reflection as well as
sorrow for the loss of the 80-year-old cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a wonderful man, a model for Catholicism,'' Frank
Rusch, an airline pilot from the West Coast, said after viewing the
body cloaked in scarlet and white vestments in a a red-velvet lined
mahogany coffin. ``He is very well thought of. I speak of him in
the present because he is still with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Kaatz, who drove 77 miles into town from upstate Wingdale,
N.Y., with her two children, said: ``It was important to see him.
It was very important for the children.'' Alluding to the
cardinal's eight-month struggle with brain cancer, she added: ``I
feel happy for him because he is at peace, and is where he always
wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Vasquez, who brought his wife and child from the Bronx,
said sadly: ``He meant a lot to us as Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   As preparations for the cardinal's funeral on Monday went
forward, there was no word from the Vatican on the selection of his
successor as the archbishop of New York, although speculation
continued to focus on Bishop Edward M. Egan, of the Archdiocese of
Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will lead a host of dignitaries at the funeral
_ 3,500 invitations are going out _ and the Vatican Secretary of
State, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, will represent Pope John Paul II and
officiate at the 2 p.m. funeral Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's events _ the second of three days of Masses and other
services leading to the funeral and burial in the crypt under the
altar at St. Patrick's _ gave striking testimony once more to the
admiration and respect that millions accorded the cardinal,
America's most influential Catholic leader.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., when the cathedral doors opened, the crowds waiting
to get in were already enormous. The lines snaked around into 50th
Street, then back to Madison Avenue, where they doubled back again
to Fifth Avenue. And they kept getting larger.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For some, the day's heat was a torment. About 11:30 a.m., a man
in his 70s fainted on the sidewalk. People nearby quickly went to
his aid, giving him sips of water and slices of orange. He revived
a bit and said he had been standing in line for about 90 minutes
and had walked about a mile to the cathedral from the Port
Authority Bus Terminal at 40th Street and Eighth Avenue. Firemen
took him away on a makeshift stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some people had flown in from Puerto Rico and other Caribbean
islands. Some had come by bus from other states. Many were
residents of the metropolitan area who had come by bus or subway to
pay tribute to a man they said had been a friend of the poor and
the sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the cardinal so much, I just had to come,'' said
Minnie Stinson of the Bronx.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his homily in Spanish, the Rev. Josu Iriondo, director of the
office of Hispanic affairs for the archdiocese, recalled the
cardinal's involvement with the Hispanic population, including his
two visits to Cuba and his efforts to sent food and money to
hurricane victims.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, dozens of buses drew up around the cathedral
carrying hundreds of elderly and disabled men and women, many of
them in wheelchairs or moving with the aid of walkers, canes or
crutches. Also on board were hundreds of children, many of them
mentally or physically disabled. They were helped into the
cathedral by counselors and aides from hospitals and nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1 p.m. Mass, pew after pew was filled with the children
and the disabled who were the special guests. Those in wheelchairs
sat in the aisles. It was relatively cool inside, out of the sun
and under the subdued light from chandeliers and high, arched
stained glass windows on either side of the nave. Organ music
swelled and a choir sang. Many in the crowd held rosaries, and some
cried softly as the Mass unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   The Mass began with a processional hymn, ``Sing With All the
Saints in Glory,'' followed by a psalm, ``We Shall Go Up With Joy
to the House of Our God.'' The Most Rev. Robert A. Brucato,
apostolic administrator of the archdiocese, read from the Gospel of
St. John, then gave the homily.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Mass was sponsored by the archdiocesan Offices
of Education and Persons with Disabilities, and he spoke of the
cardinal's contributions to disabled youths.
</P>
<P>
   And as the faint sweet aroma of incense drifted through the
cathedral, the lines to view the cardinal in his bier formed again
and moved slowly and solemnly forward.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
