<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OCONNOR-CHARISMA-NYT &LR;      05-06 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-CHARISMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR O'CONNOR'S SUCCESSOR, INFLUENCE ISN'T AUTOMATIC
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., Calif., Ind., Pa., Ill.)   (With: O'CONNOR-MOURNERS) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The leadership advice that Cardinal Terence Cooke often gave to
the voluble bishop who would succeed him in 1984 as archbishop of
New York was this:
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to swing at every pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   During most of the 16 years that Cardinal John O'Connor reigned
as the most combative and charismatic voice of Roman Catholicism in
the United States, he exuberantly ignored his predecessor's
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think I have swung at almost every pitch,'' the
prelate recalled in a 1994 appearance on the Charlie Rose show.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor rarely stepped back from the plate on matters of
abortion, contraception, gay rights and the ordination of women _
emotionally explosive issues that have divided American Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   He was almost always game for a doctrinally emphatic comment,
often with a pithy quote that appeared in the tabloids and the
evening news.
</P>
<P>
   His death last week is a reminder of the degree to which a
confrontational style helped make him the best-known and perhaps
the most influential voice in the American Catholic Church. But it
also underlines the difficulties facing whoever tries to put on his
leadership mantle.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's outsized personality and his in-your-face skills with
the New York media camouflaged what Catholic historians and church
observers agree is a significant diminution in the influence of
bishops in the daily lives of American Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is very distant from the lives of people on a daily
basis,'' said Frank Macchiarola, president of St. Francis College
in Brooklyn and a former schools chancellor in New York. ``The
challenge for the bishops is not that the people won't follow the
rules, but that they will not think the rules are significant.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of church historians said O'Connor was perhaps the last
cardinal archbishop in American history who could take for granted
the prominence of the Catholic Church in the public eye, as a
leading institution, a shaper of public opinion and an overwhelming
influence on the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key here is that O'Connor could take it for granted,''
said R. Scott Appleby, director of the Cushwa Center for the Study
of American Catholicism at the University of Notre Dame. ``His
great accomplishment was to extend the life of that influential
presence by his personal style.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's successor as the ad hoc leader of American Catholics,
whether he comes from the archdiocese of New York, Los Angeles,
Chicago or another major American city, will not be so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The priesthood in America is in decline, as is the community of
religious women working in Catholic schools and hospitals. The
Archdiocese of New York, in large measure because of O'Connor's
energy, is an exception to the dismal trend of institutional
downsizing in schools and parishes in major cities like Detroit,
Philadelphia, Chicago and San Francisco. Polls have shown for years
that many Catholics do not accept church teachings on
contraception, homosexuality and the ordination of women. Finally,
there is a deep demographic divide within the American church, with
new immigrants from Latin America and Asia on one side and
assimilated middle-class Catholic culture on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that you have authority because you occupy an office
is not very functional in the history of the American church,''
said David O'Brien, a professor of Roman Catholic studies at the
College of the Holy Cross in Worcester, Mass. ``You have to wonder
how long authority can be maintained without a real strong pastoral
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the views of several scholars who study the church,
O'Brien said the pastoral connection of bishops to believers was at
risk of being severed by demographic trends and by the insistence
of Pope John Paul II on strict doctrinal discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't quite know where this is going to go,'' O'Brien said.
``There has been such a strong emphasis on the teachings of the
pope. It is a very papal church now. There isn't much consultation
with the clergy or the laity. It looks like the pope feels he can
appoint anyone he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is widespread agreement among Catholic intellectuals
about the eroding influence of bishops in the lives of American
Catholics, there is considerable disagreement about how to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives argue that Catholics are thirsting for a strong,
doctrinally clear leader in the mold of O'Connor, a man with a
forceful personality who can cut a high profile as a preacher,
teacher and figure in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of his highly visible defense of Catholic teachings on
life, Cardinal O'Connor made it possible for a lot of Catholics who
wanted to believe in that teaching to get behind him,'' said Deal
Hudson, publisher and editor of Crisis magazine, a conservative
Catholic monthly published in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson argued that papal orthodoxy on issues like abortion and
gay rights did not alienate Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a bishop communicates in a pastorally sensitive way, it
will have an impact, and people's minds and hearts will come
around,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals in the church disagree, arguing that no archbishop in
the United States is likely to attain real national influence
unless he can somehow close the gap between papal doctrine and the
spiritual demands of the laity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholics can't help but see that institutionally the church
is still very clergy-oriented,'' said Paul Baumann, executive
editor of Commonweal, a liberal Catholic magazine published in New
York. ``It is impossible for bishops to get the kind of loyalty
they had unless there is some sign of change on contraception,
mandatory celibacy for priests and the role of women in the
church.''
</P>
<P>
   The kind of archbishop most likely to win a national following,
several Catholic historians said, is one who plays down divisive
issues like abortion and eloquently articulates a Catholic position
on larger social questions. What are the spiritual costs of
pursuing material wealth? What is the role of the state toward the
vulnerable and dispossessed? How do Americans square their rising
affluence with poverty elsewhere in the world?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental question that the leader of Catholics in
America has to address is why do Americans need a permanent
community of faith to fulfill their spiritual lives,'' said
Appleby, at Notre Dame. ``The answer cannot just be a sound bite
that says no to abortion or premarital sex. It has to be a whole
story that puts the noes in context and in which Americans
recognize their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the weaknesses of the Catholic Church in the United
States, O'Brien said, ``authority is a real tough thing to
maintain'' for any archbishop in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to come from personal charisma or from pastoral care,''
he said. ``Much of Cardinal O'Connor's authority came from
charisma. But there are not a lot of charismatic successors out
there. They are not in large supply in the American clergy.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternative, then, is pastoral care, which church
intellectuals define as listening to the deepest yearnings of
believers and challenging them with the teachings of the Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our time calls for dialogue, not confrontation,'' said the
Rev. Thomas Reese, a Jesuit who is editor in chief of America, the
Catholic magazine. ``That is what people are used to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
