<P>
   This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   CNS-CANDYBAR-LOYALTIES (New York) _ Some things never change,
and that includes Americans' taste in chocolate bars. Frequent
introductions and tinkering with time-honored formulas produce
flops more often than they produce new favorites for the shelf. In
fact, one spokeswoman says, most of the top 10 chocolate products
have been around for the better part of a century. By Rebecca
Webber. (850 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-DEATH-CLEANUP (New York) _ Death is not pretty, and often
someone has to clean up after it. Enter Bio-Recovery Corp., whose
medically trained employees will remove all traces of murder,
suicide or accidental death. By Trenton Daniel. (750 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-WOMEN'S-COLLEGES (New York) _ In the 1970's, with the
feminist movement at its peak, many women's colleges opened their
doors to men, and others folded rather than go coed. The remaining
women's colleges are enjoying a resurgence, perhaps surprisingly,
because they offer better academics and opportunities for women to
make their own marks. By Jocelyn Anderson. (930 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-TORTURED-SUITS (New York) _ A Ghanian diplomat who says he
was tortured by another diplomat in Ghana had his day in court
against the man he says was responsible, but the court was in the
United States. Under various rulings on federal law, foreigners who
claim torture at the hands of other foreigners can sometimes bring
lawsuits in the United States. By Sameer Yerawadekar. (1,050
words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-DANCE-THERAPISTS (New York) _ Behind the scenes of Broadway,
in addition to the props people, dressers and costume designers,
are a group of people who are literally responsible for the health
of a show. Dance therapists, working to heal or prevent injuries
that commonly occur with eight energetic performances a week, can
often save not just the individual dancers, but also the financial
health of a show. By Will Morton. (975 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-BOSNIAN-MUSICIAN (Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzogovina) _ Darko
Jelisic interrupted his career as a rising musician when the war in
Bosnia broke out. A cluster bomb seemed to end that dream, but
after Jelisic came to the United States to recuperate, he found not
only that he could still play, but that he and his music could
become popular symbols in his homeland. By Nathan Hegedus. (850
words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-NY-BUSES (New York) _ The city with the largest bus fleet
and some of the worst air pollution in the nation is caught in the
debate over whether the buses powered by alternative means are
really better for the environment than the diesel-powered buses
many want to replace. By Natalie Leston. (1,050 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-HYPNOTISTS (New York) _ Hypnotherapists, once put in the
same category as snake-oil salesmen and other medical quacks, are
gaining popularity. In fact, many doctors and more traditional
health-care professionals are taking hypnosis classes in attempts
to treat patients more completely. And they've even got a union. By
Stephen Parker. (1,075 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-KOREA-FAMILIES (Undated) _ The division of North and South
Korea also meant the division of many families, many of whom have
since been unable to contact, visit or otherwise find out anything
about their relatives. Now, a summit meeting between the leaders of
the north and south scheduled for June is giving hope that people
who have not seen each other for more than 50 years might be
reunified. By Michael Goldman. (850 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-E-RETURNS (New York) _ With the boom in online retailing,
what's a poor startup company to do when people start returning
merchandise before it's fully figured out how to sell it to them?
Why, turn to other startup companies, of course. There's no
shortage of dot-coms willing to help other dot-coms with their
e-returns. By Gus G. Sentementes. (1,050 words.)
</P>
<P>
   CNS-SNICKERS-CRIME (Undated) - A man in Texas has been sentenced
to 16 years in prison for stealing a Snickers bar. He was but the
latest person to be sentenced under one of the strictest repeat
offender laws in the country. By Kate Dawson. (850 words.)
</P>
</TEXT>
