<SLUG> BC-CNS-DEATH-CLEANUP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY CLEANERS SCRUB THE REMAINS OF DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(EDS: note contents) 
(Trenton Daniel is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By TRENTON DANIEL   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The apartment where the woman died was littered with
notes she had taped to the walls, letters and boxes of journals
scattered around her baby grand piano. The bathroom revealed a more
disturbing sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that?'' asked Ron Gospodarski, pointing to the edge of the
bathtub. ``That's skin. The blood, feces, and interstitial fluid
won't take much time to clean up. But the skin will probably take
about 45 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman died of heart disease at least eight days before
Gospodarski arrived on the scene. Perhaps she had collapsed onto
the tub, he speculated.
</P>
<P>
   It fell to Gospodarski, president of Bio-Recovery Corp., to
clean up the gory remains. ``Imagine if that was your relative,''
he said. ``You don't want to see that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   This kind of scrubbing isn't pleasant, but somebody has to do
it. For Gospodarski and his staff of 10, it's all part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, Bio-Recovery Corp. has restored homes and businesses
_ any place where homicides, suicides and accidents have occurred _
to cleanliness. The cleanup not only prevents the spread of
disease, but also helps to calm residents and neighbors, said
Gospodarski.
</P>
<P>
   The uniforms of Bio-Recovery's medically trained ``crime scene
cleaning, abatement and restoration specialists'' resemble
astronaut suits, white and baggy, with oxygen masks and rubber
gloves. Once encapsulated in this garb, the experts sweep the
surrounding area. Then they sanitize the infected area of all
pathological waste and associated debris and dispose it at a
medical waste-handling facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks ago a man killed himself with a shotgun,''
said the 37-year-old Gospodarski. ``Stuff was everywhere.'' . It
took several hours to clean the site.
</P>
<P>
   Although some 200 similar cleanup companies operate nationwide,
Bio-Recovery corners the market in the New York City region.
Gospodarski has had his work cut out this year. Along with local
law enforcement officers, his Queens-based company has watched the
city's murder rate rise after several years of decline. There were
190 homicides in the first three months of this year, up from 169
during the same period last year, according to police statistics.
Although Bio-Recovery isn't needed at every murder scene, a jump in
crime invariably means more business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working crazy hours, seven days a week,'' said
Gospodarski.
</P>
<P>
   Gospodarski's on-call staff consists of current and former cops
and public safety officers. They earn $25 an hour for as many as 20
calls a week, with a slow-down during the spring and summer months.
Outdoor deaths don't typically require the services of
Bio-Recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's warmer, more people will hang themselves in a
tree in the park, hurl themselves in front of a train, or throw
themselves in the East River,'' said Gospodarski matter-of-factly.
``They don't feel they have to stay indoors to kill themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, animals prompt the call. After rushing to a site,
it isn't uncommon to find dozens of living and dead cats in an
apartment, said Gospodarski, adding, ``It happens more than people
think.''
</P>
<P>
   The crime-scene cleanup industry is about 10 years old, said
Gospodarski, who is also president of the American Bio-Recovery
Association, a national group with about 200 members. He started
this nonprofit organization four years ago to set standards in the
profession. ``We want to make sure that when people go out there,
they know what they're doing,'' he said. Standards from the federal
Occupational, Safety and Health Administration and the Centers for
Disease Control govern the industry.
</P>
<P>
   One reason this niche of the clean-up business came about was to
make sure health standards are met, said John Heath, president of
Crime Scene Cleanup in Tampa Bay, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all these rules now because of diseases contracted
by blood, and there are regulations about where you can haul it,''
he said. ``Unless the mess is properly cleaned up, people open
themselves to a lot of fines.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gospodarski and his colleagues are sometimes glib
when discussing their work, they profess to have a serious
philosophy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are already traumatized by the event, and they can be
retraumatized if the mess isn't cleaned up properly,'' Gospodarski
said, viewing his company as a public service. ``We need to be
there for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
