u l BC-CNS-TORTURE-SUITS &LR;      05-06 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TORTURE-SUITS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS SUE FOREIGN TORTURERS IN AMERICAN COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients
desired)  
(Sameer Yerawadekar is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
  By SAMEER YERAWADEKAR  
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   NEW YORK _ Bawol Cabiri, 41,
collected his thoughts, breathed deeply, and quietly told a
Manhattan jury about 11 months of agony he said he underwent in
Ghana, his homeland.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cabiri said his life in New York as Ghana's Trade Counsel to the
United States came to a crashing halt on July 31, 1986. On that
day, said Cabiri, while he was in Ghana, officers of a new
government arrested him without charge. He said they forced him
into a cell three feet long and four feet wide, where he stayed for
almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, sometimes three times a night, Cabiri said, guards
tortured him. One held a shotgun to his head while another struck
him repeatedly. Other guards tied him up and kicked him in the neck
until blood erupted from his mouth. And Cabiri said the guards
administered electric shocks to his body, usually to his genitals.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who ordered the guards to do these things, Cabiri did
not hesitate. ``Ambassador Assasie-Gyimah,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baffour Assasie-Gyimah, dressed in a jet-black suit, cringed as
the jury turned to look at him. The jury had to decide whether
Assasie-Gyimah, the Ghanian ambassador to Niger, Mali and Burkina
Faso, formerly the Deputy Chief of National Security, ordered the
torture of Cabiri in a Ghanan prison locals knew as ``Hanoi.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabiri's allegations, dramatic though they were, could not have
found their way into American courts until 1980, when a federal
appeals court ruled that an obscure 1789 statute empowered federal
judges to hear cases brought by foreigners against other foreigners
who tortured them in foreign countries. Until then, the Alien Tort
Claims Act had been understood to allow foreigners to sue pirates.
But the Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit read the statute,
which allows suits alleging a violation of the ``law of nations,''
to allow foreigners to sue torturers.
</P>
<P>
   Cabiri's $5 million lawsuit, filed in 1994, was one of the few
that went to trial under the Alien Tort Claims Act. When the trial
began in February, it was only the second case to go to trial under
the Torture Victim Protection Act, passed by Congress in 1992 to
allow anyone, not just foreigners, to sue their persecuters in
federal court. The first was a suit brought in Hawaii against the
estate of former President Ferdinand Marcos of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Under this law, relatives of four nuns found raped, beaten and
murdered in El Salvador 20 years ago filed a multimillion-dollar
suit last year against two retired Salvadoran generals found living
in Florida. ``This was a crime that shocked America,'' said Rob
Varenik, a lawyer for the nuns' relatives. ``These are people with
blood on their hands. The U.S. should not be a haven for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Torture cases were first brought in American courts after the
appeals court decision in 1980. Human rights lawyers eagerly filed
suits against torturers who visited the United States, but quickly
ran into problems. ``In most cases, the defendant just goes home,
and the plaintiff wins a default judgment that isn't paid,'' said
Jennifer Green, an attorney at the Center for Constitutional Rights
and an expert on international torture law.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, in the 20 years since the appeals court decision,
only a few dozen cases went to trial under the Alien Tort Claims
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal academics wondered whether the United States should
be deciding cases involving people and events from abroad.
International lawyers said they worry that having American courts
hear these cases might prevent the growth of international legal
institutions. Nevertheless, for practicing human rights lawyers,
these cases provide the only chance of holding many torturers
responsible for their crimes. ``The problem isn't too few
lawyers,'' said Varenik. ``It's too few clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Clients are hard to find because victims often avoid talking
about their experiences. ``Torture leaves a stigma of guilt and
humiliation,'' said Doug Johnson, who heads the Center for the
Victims of Torture in Minneapolis. Though between 5 and 35 percent
of all refugees have been physically and mentally abused, according
to Amnesty International, few survivors come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that few refugees know that they can sue
their victimizers at all. ``People who have been tortured come from
poor, isolated communities, and they often don't know the
language,'' explained Tenzin Tethong, executive director of
Survivors International, a human rights group in San Francisco.
``They need to be found and told that they can get treatment, that
they can tell people about their torture, and that they can sue.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even among the minuscule number of cases that are filed, few
go to trial because defendants fail to appear. Ross Hanig, a
spokesman for the Center for Justice and Accountability, a
two-year-old victims' advocacy group, said that lawyers should look
for defendants who won't leave. ``It isn't that difficult,'' he
said. ``One of our clients walked into a park and saw the man who
tortured him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States does a terrible job keeping torturers out of
the country,'' said Reed Brody, advocacy director of Human Rights
Watch. Brody supports the passage of the Anti-Atrocity Alien
Deportation Act, which would empower the Justice Department's
Office of Special Investigations, currently charged with
identifying Nazi war criminals, to find and deport torturers. The
Act is currently before a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assasie-Gyimah did not have to stay,'' said S. Reid Kahn, his
lawyer. ``He could have gone home and never had to worry about it.
But he chose to stay and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   And he won. On February 9, 2000, the 12 New Yorkers on the jury
found Baffour Assasie-Gyimah not liable for torturing Bawol Cabiri,
now a United Nations administrator in Kosovo. ``We're appealing the
case,'' said Scott Kamber, Cabiri's attorney. ``The jury had a very
high standard for torture, especially because the case involved
high government officials. It's been a long time, and scars heal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
