<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7718 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-DANCE-THERAPISTS &LR;      05-06 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-DANCE-THERAPISTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHYSICAL THERAPISTS HEAL BROADWAY EIGHT TIMES A WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Will Morton is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By WILL MORTON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lana Gordon put on her 20-pound cheetah costume and
prepared to go onstage in ``The Lion King,'' but she had not
attached the puppet-like apparatus tightly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the midst of catching the puppet and realizing what
happened, my body jerked and was out of place,'' Gordon said. ``It
wasn't a natural movement.'' She had to get her hip ``pulled out,''
or unjammed, for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   As dancers strut their way across imaginary African plains,
stomp rhythmically in ``Riverdance'' and send partners skyward in
``Saturday Night Fever,'' a fleet of physical therapists helps keep
bodies ready for more. Part masseuse and part athletic trainer,
they teach performers to prevent injury and reduce the time needed
to heal. Unseen by the audience, physical therapists hope to keep
production costs down and healthier dancers on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what we teach is how to undo what the show has done
to them,'' said Sean P. Gallagher, who started as a Broadway
physical therapist in 1989. Today, his company, Performing Arts
Physical Therapy, works with shows including ``Cats,'' ``Swing,''
``Fosse'' and ``Footloose.'' With lots of partner work and lifting,
``Saturday Night Fever'' dancers suffer a lot of upper neck and
extremity problems, Gallagher said. Dancers in ``Cats'' suffer back
and hip problems from crawling around on the floor, he said,
``trying to be cats, when their bodies aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Broadway stages, which slant down toward the audience, also
pose risks to dancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like working on a hillside,'' said Brandi Doyle, one of
Performing Arts' eight therapists. ``Your body makes corrections.''
</P>
<P>
   Lana Gordon, now performing in ``Jesus Christ Superstar,'' said
physical therapists taught her how reduce back strain while dancing
on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're on heels and you're on a raked stage, your initial
response is to lean back,'' she said, slouching like someone would
while hiking down a steep hill. The proper way to keep pressure of
her back, she learned, is to tilt the pelvis forward and stick the
chest out. She walks as if the stage continues out into the
audience, not like someone who is trying not to fall into the
orchestra pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At eight shows a week, your body breaks down,'' said Gordon,
30. ``Muscles contract when they're not supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Riverdance,'' one of the most physically demanding shows on
Broadway, has a combination chiropractor and bone specialist on
staff, said Merle Frimark, the show's North American publicist. Two
full-time massage therapists also help lead warmups for the 36
Irish dancers, eight Russian dancers, three American tap dancers
and one flamenco dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers receive two massages per week, physiotherapist Ruth
Magee said. To add arch support, they line their shoes with
shock-absorbent insoles imported from London. Dancers practice a
range of exercises, including standing on one leg and on their
tiptoes, lying on their backs and pointing one leg at the sky or
putting one leg on a hip-high bar and leaning forward _ all ways to
stretch the hamstring muscle on the back of the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one show, a performer could stamp their foot about 3,000
times,'' Magee said in a buoyant Irish brogue. ``If you think of
the repetition and the trauma that you could give to your foot and
your shin, it's quite a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Physical therapists started getting involved with Broadway shows
more than a decade ago, around the time the Harkness Center for
Dance Injuries was founded as part of the Hospital for Joint
Diseases on East 17th Street. The center works to reduce the
frequency and severity of injuries, spokeswoman Marijeanne
Liderbach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, isn't this medical problem a pain for all of us,'' she
said. ``It's a pain for the dancer, and it hurts the company
financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Dancers normally earn $1,200 to $1,800 a week, according to
Actors' Equity Association, the labor union that represents
Broadway dancers. Injured dancers receive up to $650 a week in
worker's compensation pay and a supplement from Actors' Equity,
said Valerie LaVarco, who handles injury claims. Meanwhile,
production companies must pay replacement dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Plesa, a 22-year-old sprite of a dancer in ``Saturday
Night Fever,'' increased her regular physical therapy back in
October after a bad lift and landing in her first show on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``On day two of rehearsal, I broke my foot,'' she said ``I ended
up sitting in a chair for a month and a half.'' Her salary went
from $1,300 a week to $200 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Some Broadway shows resist hiring physical therapists because it
brings added expense to already pricey productions, said
Liederbach, of the Harkness Center. A 1993 study in The American
Journal of Sports Medicine found that in three seasons at a San
Francisco ballet company, 104 dancers suffered 309 injuries
resulting in medical insurance payments of nearly $400,000. Adding
physical therapy services, the company saved a half-million dollars
a year, Liederbach said.
</P>
<P>
   Like football and basketball players, dancers always face the
prospect of a career-ending injury at a young age. Spectators don't
think of the repercussions of injury when watching dancers,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see football players with their helmets on and crashing
into other and they think they're automatically going to get
hurt,'' LaVarco said. Because dancers appear more dressed up and
glamorous, ``I don't think that people get the impression that
injuries occur that can be career ending, such as a knee injury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a dancer to even hurt their knee, it's very scary,''
Frimark said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
