<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7720 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-BOSNIAN-MUSICIAN &LR;      05-06 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BOSNIAN-MUSICIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIAN IN NEW YORK ROCKS SARAJEVO WITH ONE HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Nathan Hegedus is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By NATHAN HEGEDUS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ The young radio executive and the
disk jockey stared wistfully at the folk dancers on the club's dark
stage. As the dancers rehearsed to a familiar accordion tune, the
two observers thought about another time in this same club, a time
that seems a world away _ the time when Darko Jelisic lit up this
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darko always had too much energy,'' said Zoran Catic, 29, the
general manager of eFM, a popular student radio station. ``The
girls were crazy for him. His band, Major, was the best `demo' band
in Sarajevo. Everyone knew them.'' A sadness crept into his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war stopped everything,'' shrugged his companion, Lejla
Omeragic.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,000 miles away, in a cramped Manhattan rehearsal
studio, Darko Jelisic grabs a roll of duct tape and a drumstick.
With one hand, he deftly wraps the tape around the drumstick, then
attaches it to the stub that is his other hand _ tattooed one at
that. He slowly builds the layers of silvery tape until the
drumstick is an extension of his limb. Then he swings his arms in a
controlled frenzy, pounding out the beat with his three band
members.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jelisic, 30, will be in his home recording studio,
wailing on his guitar, this time with his stump taped firmly to a
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do regular rock and roll, straight,'' the shaggy-haired
musician says emphatically. ``I'm born with that. That's my
style.''
</P>
<P>
   But although he lives and performs in New York, Jelisic's real
music scene is still in his homeland. He had been a rising star in
Bosnia in the early 1990's, but put his music career on hold to
help the Bosnian Army fight Serbian forces in 1992. On patrol on
Christmas Day 1992, he spied an object on the ground and
unthinkingly picked it up. It was a piece of a cluster bomb.
Jelisic's right hand was blown off. He was 22.
</P>
<P>
   In search of a prosthesis to replace his lost limb, Jelisic
arrived in the United States in 1993. Life in America, however, was
hardly easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``My English was like zero,'' he says. I couldn't even wash
dishes. Nobody gave me a chance. I worked sissy jobs like in a
flower shop.'' Only when Jelisic finally connected with local
Serbs, Croats and Bosnian Muslims in New Jersey did he snap out of
his doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't even want to speak his language at first,'' said Joe
Guerriero, a photographer friend of Jelisic. ``Only when he started
to feel more like who he was did he feel comfortable and make
connections. He stopped trying to be American so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Jelisic moved to New York City and earned a two-year college
degree in communications. Frustrated with his prosthesis, he taught
himself to play drums and guitar again. Soon he was playing in
three bands and recording solo, working in a corporate mailroom to
make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising twist has been his renewed popularity in
Sarajevo. This past winter, he sent his self-recorded album,
``Dare,'' to journalists, DJs and friends in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   He was amazed by the buzz. ``All the papers wanted to talk to
me,'' he says. ``I called my Mom, and she said, `Oh, I was just
listening to you on the radio.'''
</P>
<P>
   The album spent six weeks atop the charts of a top Sarajevo
radio station. During a February visit to Sarajevo, his first in
seven years, Jelisic did interviews with magazines and radio shows,
signed a record deal and taped three music videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darko was a big surprise for Sarajevo,'' said Jasna Hasovic, a
journalist with a top Bosnian newsmagazine called Dani. ``People
want to re-establish the rock scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see Darko,'' she said, ``we remember our life before
the war. It is as if he stayed frozen for these seven years. To see
Darko here in Sarajevo is to see something we have forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Jelisic reaps no financial security from his popularity in
Bosnia, where the pirate industry is the major circulation method
for music. Pirates copy his album and sell it for as little as
$2.50, said Lejla Omeragic. ``Here, everyone makes music only for
fun and art.''
</P>
<P>
   Jelisic said he was overwhelmed by the reaction. He found it
strangely surreal to be the object of adoration in a ravaged land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good time,'' he says. ``I had money, chicks, fame. But
it was plastic, not real. I felt depressed and squeezed into a
little space.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, even while accepting the United States as his home, he
still hungers for acclaim in Bosnia. His next album will be
released there soon, and he is working on a third. ``Before the
war, I tried to be number one,'' he says. ``But I never reached my
full potential. I guess I am trying to do what I couldn't do
before.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
