<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7721 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-NY-BUSES &LR;      05-06 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-NY-BUSES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTA PLAN TO BUY FEWER DIESEL BUSES HAS SOME GROUPS STILL FUMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Natalie Leston is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By NATALIE LESTON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every weekday morning, Samantha Chang rushes to her
bus stop in Staten Island so that she will be near the front of the
line. But she isn't just concerned with getting a seat for her
half-hour ride to the World Trade Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate standing at the end of the line or sitting on the back
of the bus because I can smell the fumes right away and I breathe
in all that black smoke,'' said Chang, 30. ``I would never let my
2-year-old son ride with me on a New York City bus because of all
the fumes.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City's fleet of 4,300 buses is the largest in the
country, transporting 2.2 million people _ more than a third of the
city's population _ each day. In a city that has one of the worst
air quality records in the nation and an asthma rate three times
the national average, all but 100 of its buses are powered by
diesel fuel. After years of debating with environmentalists and
months of negotiating with state lawmakers, the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, which oversees the city's public
transportation, decided in April that 44 percent of all buses
bought under its next capital budget plan will not be powered by
diesel. But the MTA seems to have some reservations about changing
from diesel technology, and some environmentalists say the plan
does not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan is indeed a step in the right direction,'' said Chyi
Sun, a researcher at Inform, a New York-based environmental
research group. ``But it's not like the MTA is saying `I realize
the error of my ways' and that diesel is very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 cities, including Los Angeles, Houston, Cleveland
and Phoenix, are converting their bus fleets to natural gas, which
environmentalists say is the best commercially available
alternative to diesel. New York City Transit, one of five MTA
agencies and the operator of the subway and bus systems, now plans
to have 650 natural gas-powered buses by 2005. It also plans to
have 390 hybrid-electric buses using electric motors that draw
current from a small diesel engine. The agency also agreed to
install special pollution traps by 2003 on the exhaust pipes of
every diesel bus in its fleet and to use low-sulfur fuel in the
tanks of all diesel buses.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the MTA proposed keeping 70 percent of its new fleet
diesel-powered. But the state Assembly vetoed that plan. After
negotiations in Albany involving transit officials,
environmentalists, lawmakers and the governor's office, the MTA
agreed to increase the number of natural-gas buses in its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a negotiated plan,'' conceded Albert O'Leary, vice
president of public affairs for New York City Transit.
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials say they have been attempting to find
alternatives to diesel for several years. New York City Transit
says it has put 90 natural-gas buses on the city's streets so far,
with another 134 expected by year's end. But O'Leary said
natural-gas buses are not necessarily the best alternative to
diesel.
</P>
<P>
   Officials point to a study by the Northeast Alternative Vehicle
Consortium, a Boston-based nonprofit agency that conducted a
yearlong test of New York City buses. The study found that buses
powered by natural gas may not be better for the environment than
buses powered by a combination of diesel and electricity. They also
cite a study by the Harvard School of Public Health, which found
that natural-gas buses may spew as much or more pollution as the
most advanced diesel buses. The report concluded that natural-gas
buses produce less soot, but that diesel emits less greenhouse
gases, which contribute to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   But environmental groups say the studies are faulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MTA uses emissions data not from street level monitors,
where the dirty buses are, but from rooftops, where the air is
cleaner,'' said Tom Congdon, program director at the New York
League of Conservation Voters, a nonprofit, political arm of New
York's environmental community.
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials also have argued that natural-gas buses break
down 50 percent more frequently than the diesel models. And the
only natural-gas fueling facility, at the Jackie Gleason Depot in
Brooklyn, has had a host of problems, including a gas leak and two
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd only be able to carry one-half of the number of people
with compressed natural gas buses,'' O'Leary said. ``That would
mean that we would need 8,600 buses in our fleet to accommodate the
same number of riders we do now, and that would create traffic,
which is the biggest source of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to point fingers at the MTA, but it is
primarily environmentally friendly. For every person that takes a
bus, you get one less car on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups say it makes no sense for New York City to
pursue the still-developing diesel-hybrid technology when the
cleanliness of natural-gas buses has already been proven.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to using tax money, it seems to us that they
should make the wise solution in investment,'' Congdon said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet O'Leary also pointed out that the city's bus garages would
need to be retrofitted to handle natural gas. It can cost anywhere
from $25 million to $40 million to convert a city bus depot so that
it can refuel and service natural gas safely, he said.
Hybrid-powered buses would not require retrofitting garages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at all the available technology for the one that
gives the greatest benefit at the lowest cost,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Transit said its goal within 10 years is to
develop electric buses that use fuel cells, a technology that would
power buses entirely with devices that make electricity through
chemical reactions rather than combustion. Those buses would
produce no emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental advocates applaud that plan, but many say that
until that technology is developed, they remain committed to
fighting diesel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is stand behind a diesel bus in New York
City to see what's going on,'' Congdon said. ``And to see that a
lot more needs to be done right away.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
