<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7722 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-HYPNOTISTS &LR;      05-06 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-HYPNOTISTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPNOTISTS' SUGGESTIONS TAKEN MORE SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Stephen Parker is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By STEPHEN PARKER   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He's no Svengali and he won't dangle a pocket watch
before your eyes, but Nolan Baer does know how to lull people into
a trance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like the ocean?'' asks Baer, seated Indian-style in
stocking feet at his Midtown Manhattan office. Then the 44-year-old
hypnotist trips a switch and fills his patient's headphones with
the ebb-and-flow crashing of waves. ``Close your eyes and relax.
Breathe deeply _ inhaaaaale, now exhaaaaale.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five minutes later, the new patient in the reclining chair
emerges from a semiconscious state and wonders what time it is.
Leaving Baer's office, with its triangular Zen clock, framed Hindu
paintings and Native American hand drum on display the visitor
steps into the elevator feeling like he just had a power nap.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have long dismissed hypnotherapy as quackery, but these
alternative specialists have gained new respect in treating bad
habits, phobias and anxiety. They have made inroads as teachers and
doctors at major medical schools and hospitals. In recent years,
they have organized several associations, a guild and a labor
union. They've even established an International Hypnosis Hall of
Fame in Blue Bell, Penn., which features memorabilia and busts of
famous practitioners, says spokeswoman Barbara Muested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypnosis is misunderstood because of what people see on stage,
television and in old Svengali movies,'' says Stephanie Benoric, a
Manhattan hypnotherapist at The Hypnosis Institute, which offers
training workshops throughout the country. ``Everybody wants to
know, `Will I be controlled? Will I quack like a duck?' People
don't realize its value as a therapeutic tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Ryder, a Manhattan psychologist who uses hypnosis with
patients on a daily basis, says the practice cannot place anyone in
danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one loses control of their conscious being,'' Ryder says.
``You are never unconscious, like a zombie. To the contrary, you
are more conscious and aware of who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a practice with a long history. Some date hypnotism back
several millennia to trance rituals practiced by tribal shamans and
medicine men. Others say it evolved from Austrian physician Franz
Anton Mesmer's use of magnets and relaxation to cure patients in
the late 1700's _ hence the term ``mesmerize'' _ and later from
Sigmund Freud's use of relaxation techniques. But its modern-day
popularity has steadily increased since the 1970's, when society
warmed to alternative therapies, Baer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a trend of people seeking more holistic,
non-drug, safe treatments,'' Baer says. ``These treatments work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hypnosis sessions usually last between 20 minutes and an hour,
depending on the individual's needs and hypnotic receptiveness. A
single session with a New York City therapist may cost anywhere
from $150 to $1,500, says Benoric of The Hypnosis Institute. Baer
charges $180 for a one-and-a-half to two-hour evaluation and $90
for each one-hour session.
</P>
<P>
   A hypnotherapist will use imagery and deep-breathing techniques
to deeply relax patients to the verge of sleep, then offer helpful
suggestions. In their hypnotic state, patients may consciously
daydream while their unconscious mind receives and employs the
suggestions, Baer says.
</P>
<P>
   Some hypnotherapy patients can break bad habits through the
power of hypnotic suggestion alone, he says, while others work with
the therapists to consciously change negative behavior, such as
avoiding coffee while treating anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Hypnotherapists who aren't doctors or psychologists _ called
``lay therapists'' _ generally avoid treating patients for serious
physical conditions unless the therapy complements a licensed
doctor's care. They stick to smoking-cessation, weight-loss and
anxiety treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to want to be hypnotized in order for it to work,''
Baer says. ``That's the only requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he admits, ``I'm not sure anybody knows how it really
works.''
</P>
<P>
   A National Institutes of Health panel of 12 neutral medical
specialists presented research in 1995 that found ``strong evidence
for the use of hypnosis in alleviating pain associated with
cancer.'' The panel also suggested that hypnosis can effectively
treat other conditions, such as tension headaches and irritable
bowel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Now the American Medical Association is calling for new research
to evaluate the effectiveness of hypnosis and other alternative
therapies. It advises doctors routinely to ask patients about their
use of these alternatives and encourages education about
nontraditional medical practices. A January article in the Medical
Students Journal of the American Medical Association suggests
hypnosis is more effective than placebo, but it works best for
those with the greatest ability to relax.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the new recognition, hypnotherapists have
organized their own labor union to preserve hypnotherapy as a
distinct, separate practice from other alternative therapies. About
7,000 practitioners belong to the National Hypnotists Guild, which
started a labor union in 1994 that now has 400 members. The
National Federation of Hypnotists, or NFH 104, is part of the
AFL-CIO's Office and Professional Employees International Union. It
supports licensing or regulation _ but on the union's terms, says
union secretary Ed Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Hypnotherapists' training varies from a few hours and
certification to years of medical school, licenses and academic
degrees. Licensed doctors and psychologists use hypnosis to treat a
variety of medical conditions, from easing pain and nausea
associated with cancer patients' chemotherapy to slowing the
debilitating effects of multiple sclerosis, says Ed Hightower, the
NFH 104 chapter chairman in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Forms of hypnosis are even being taught in major medical
schools. Dr. Herbert Benson, for example, teaches ``relaxation
response procedures'' at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Benson says he does not teach hypnotherapy per se, but he likens
it to other practices, including yoga, Tai Chi and meditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a marked overlap with hypnotherapy,'' Benson says,
``but hypnotherapy is just one of scores of procedures that take
you to the same place - a physiological state of quietude.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
