</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-KOREA-FAMILIES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT MEETING SPURS HOPE FOR KOREAN-AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Michael Goldman is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By MICHAEL GOLDMAN   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Harry Bang saw his sister Yong-hi, she was 20 and
living with her husband and two young boys near Bang's birthplace
in what is now North Korea. That was 55 years ago. Today, Bang, 71,
acknowledges from his home in Oakland, Calif., that he doesn't know
much else about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether she's sick, or even alive,'' he said.
``I'm very eager to find out, and very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Bang's lack of knowledge about his sister can be traced to a
decision more than a half century ago to attend a middle school in
the southern part of the country. At the time, the Korean War was
raging. By the time it was over, the Korean peninsula was divided
along ideological lines and the 38th parallel. Travel and
communication between the communist north and democratic south were
severed, as were ties not only between Bang and his sister, but
also between relatives in 10 million other families.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a recently announced summit meeting between the leaders of
the North and South Korean governments is giving Bang and other
Korean-Americans around the country new cause for hope. The
meeting, the first between heads of state of the two countries, is
to include discussions on issues that divide the two Koreas,
including reunification of separated families, economic cooperation
and political reconciliation. It is scheduled to take place in the
Pyongyang, the North Korean capital, from June 12 to 14.
</P>
<P>
   That pleases Marn J. Cha, a Korean-American professor of
political science at California State University, Fresno, who is
the founder of International Separated Families Coalition, a group
that helps Americans of Korean descent locate relatives in North
Korea. Cha estimates there to be at least 100,000 Korean-Americans
with relatives in North Korea. While he says that some may have
been able to visit them during brief, highly orchestrated meetings
granted by the North Korean government, none have been able to
visit the country freely, and many, like Bang, haven't had any
contact at all in more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting, Cha said, is a ``breakthrough'' that ``will
likely allow unfettered visits to North Korean relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Family reunification is not the only positive outcome of the
summit meeting for Korean-Americans that Cha predicts. He said it
is likely that Korean-Americans will no longer be stigmatized by
South Korea for making trips to visit relatives in the north. The
Korean-Americans who have been fortunate enough to travel to North
Korea, Cha said, have long been viewed in South Korea as
``ideologically suspect.'' On occasion, visas to enter South Korea
are denied because of prior visits to North Korea, he said. With
the summit, Cha said he hopes ``that kind of suspicion will be
lifted away.''
</P>
<P>
   Yongmok Kim, a retired Korean-American professor of modern
far-east history at California State University, Los Angeles and
the University of Southern California, said the meeting will also
allow Korean-Americans to draw more freely on a historical
strength: the ability to act as mediator between the two countries.
``North and South Korea have many things they don't want to lose
face on because they've been in confrontation for five decades,''
Kim said. ``Korean Americans can play the role of a good-faith
mediator. The summit meeting might give them more leverage to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Eung Pyo Choi, the 68-year-old Korean-American owner of a
bookstore on West 32nd Street, the heart of New York's Koreatown,
the meeting has a more sentimental resonance. ``We need this summit
meeting to unify Korea,'' Choi said. ``Everyone wants reunification
because North and South Koreans, we all have the same language and
the same culture. We are the same people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim, however, plays down the likelihood of the summit bringing
about change as significant as reunification, citing what he views
as the narrow political motivations behind it. Kim said that the
North Korean leader, Kim Jung II, is agreeing to the meeting
primarily to secure aid for his country's ailing economy. According
to a South Korean government estimate, North Korea's per capita
income in 1998 amounted to only $573 against $6,823 in South Korea;
and South Korea does about as much trade in two or three days as
the North does in the whole year.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Kim said, the South Korean leader, Kim Dae Jung,
could have his eye on the Korean legislative elections as much as
any lasting peace. ``I think this meeting could be more or less a
getting acquainted session more than anything else,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bang, the thought that the summit won't reunite him with his
sister is hard to fathom. ``I very much try to eliminate that sad
idea from my mind,'' he said. ``I hope, I pray to see her before I
die. For the first time since the Korean War, I think I will.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7724 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-E-RETURNS &LR;      05-06 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-E-RETURNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMPANIES HELP ONLINE RETAILERS DEAL WITH MANY UNHAPPY RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Gus G. Sentementes is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By GUS G. SENTEMENTES   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's no secret that e-tailers have problems
delivering goods. But they don't do much better with returns,
either.
</P>
<P>
   With skimpy staffs and few brick-and-mortar outlets, many online
shops don't have the internal resources to receive and inspect
customer returns _ or the savvy to figure out how to make some
money by reselling the returned products, as real-world retailers
do.
</P>
<P>
   So who are the retailers turning to for solutions? Other
dot-coms, of course.
</P>
<P>
   A new wave of online startups has sprung up to provide ``reverse
logistics'' services to e-commerce sites. Some companies offer
``outsourcing,'' taking control of the whole return process for
online retailers. They offer warehouse space to receive returns and
systems to track them. Other firms are designing high-powered
logistical software for bigger e-tailers that want control over
their own returns process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of pain associated with e-commerce for
e-tailers,'' said Brian Farley, Corporate Comptroller at
ReturnView.com, an Irvine, Calif., startup. ``We're hoping to help
e-tailers better manage the void of returns, or their consumers
lose interest in purchasing online.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for online retail. Global e-commerce
spending is estimated to grow to $1.3 trillion by 2003, from $111
billion last year, according to International Data Corp. of San
Jose, Calif. Meanwhile, e-tailers processed nearly $2 billion in
returns in 1999 _ and that figure is expected to jump more than 500
percent by 2004, according to Forrester Research, a market-research
firm based in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Managing returns well is a key part of keeping customers happy.
Numerous studies show that customers strongly consider the
complications of returning the product before purchasing it online.
And so far, catalog companies that also do business online _ not
e-tailers _ have the highest rates of online customer satisfaction
when it comes to order deliveries and returns, according to a
recent survey by Shop.org and Boston Consulting Group. This is
because catalog companies were well-equipped to handle merchandise
returns before they started selling on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ReturnView, and other firms, are trying to level the playing
field for e-tailers. ReturnView's clients set up their Web sites
with special software so that all return requests go straight to
the outsourcing firm's system, which directs the returns to storage
firms ReturnView has contracts with. When the products arrive at
the warehouses, workers inspect the products and decide what to do
with them: return them into inventory, return them to the original
vendor, or refurbish them for resale in other markets.
</P>
<P>
   All of this automation provides insight into customers' return
habits for ReturnView's clients, said Farley, which e-tailers can
use to streamline their own sales and operations. The site launched
in March and is still in talks with potential clients, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Return Exchange offers the same services as ReturnView, but
takes them a step further. The Santa Ana, Calif., company can sell
returned and refurbished products through its own online auction
directly to consumers. And, like ReturnView, the Return Exchange
can offer its clients a mine of data on customer return habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be a one-stop shop for the e-tailers,'' said
Claudine Mabini, a spokesperson for Return Exchange, which was
launched in February.
</P>
<P>
   One company, Ireturnit.com of Austin, Texas, plans to offer a
different model for outsourcing. Instead of handling returns for
e-clients at the clients' own sites, Ireturnit wants to offer one
catchall site where users can go to return products for a variety
of companies. Users will be guaranteed a full refund for using
Ireturnit's site, says Roland Galang, Ireturnit's business
development manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very attractive for the consumer,'' Galang said. ``As a
venture capital-backed deal, we're willing to take the underwriting
risk for the company. We justify it as a marketing expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Other firms are trying to let e-tailers handle returns on their
own. Several months ago, Yantra, of Acton, Mass., introduced
PureEcommerce 2.0 _ software that tracks goods from companies to
customers and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1995, Yantra started out designing software for
warehouses and inventory management. But nine months ago, Yantra
re-tooled its software to support Internet-based inventory
management, targeting burgeoning online retailers, said a Yantra
spokesperson. It currently has about 20 clients and over 200
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The market for reverse logistics for dot-coms is so appealing
that some bricks-and-mortar companies are jumping into the game.
Take Marketing Out-of-the-Box. Founded in 1991, the Niles, Ill.,
company focused on traditional clients until 1997, when it broke
into e-commerce. Now e-clients outnumber real-world businesses 3 to
1, says David Newberger, the company's founder.
</P>
<P>
   Being a bricks-and-mortar business means MOTB doesn't have to
outsource its warehouse operations, unlike most online
reverse-logistics firms. MOTB employees receive and inspect the
returned product, and determine why it was returned. If it's
saleable, MOTB puts it back into the client's inventory of
products. If it can't be sold again or is damaged but can be
refurbished, MOTB will either return the product to the vendor, or
dispose of it through secondary market channels, like auctions or
liquidators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handling returns well is important because the name of the
game is customer acquisition,'' Newberger said. ``You want to
satisfy and keep a customer a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   While e-commerce experts lately have sounded the death knell for
most dot-com e-tailers, business is booming for Newberger's
company. The firm is quadrupling its warehouse and operations space
to 400,000 square feet from 100,000 square feet by mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for real,'' said Newberger. ``We have a new client each
week, some business-to-business, some business-to-consumer.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
