<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7725 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-SNICKERS-CRIME &LR;      05-06 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SNICKERS-CRIME </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNICKERS BAR LANDS MAN BEHIND BARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(ATTN: Texas) 
(Kate Dawson is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By KATE DAWSON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A jury in East Texas has sentenced a man to 16 years in prison
for stealing a candy bar worth less than a dollar, an example of
how the state with the highest incarceration rate in the country is
cracking down on habitual criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Payne III, 29, was on parole for felony theft when he
was caught shoplifting a ``Super Size'' Snickers bar from a
convenience store in the town of Tyler in December.
</P>
<P>
   A misdemeanor shoplifting conviction normally carries a maximum
$500 fine and no jail time. But since Payne had a criminal record,
including seven convictions for theft, and was on parole, the
district attorney was able under Texas law to charge him with a
felony. Assistant District Attorney Jodi Brown, who tried the case,
could have asked for a sentence of 20 years in prison. Instead she
asked the jury for 16, more than most violent offenders receive in
the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message from this case is that regardless of the value of
the item stolen, a habitual criminal reaches the point where a jury
and a prosecutor say enough is enough,'' said Jack Skeen, district
attorney for Smith County.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts said that is just the law of the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if East Texas has tougher laws, just tougher
lawyers,'' said George Dix, a law professor at the University of
Texas in Austin, referring to state prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is second only to California in the number of state
prisoners it houses. But for every 100,000 people in Texas, some
700 are incarcerated, compared with nearly 500 for every 100,000 in
California.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 90's Gov. Ann Richards began building new state
prisons, tripling the number of beds by 1994. Prosecutors began
pushing for plea bargains, which decreased the average amount of
time prisoners spent behind bars but increased the number of
prisoners. State legislators passed tougher juvenile crime laws,
sending younger offenders to prison and nonviolent offenders to
state jails for shorter sentences. On average, it costs the state
$21,000 a year to house someone in a prison, but a year in a state
jail is around $6,000 less.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, according to Dix, was to send nonviolent offenders
like Payne to state jails and reserve the prisons for inmates
convicted of violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But in the case of Payne, the district attorney said the issue
was his record. Since age 16, Payne had been convicted 10 times,
for theft, assault and possession of a controlled substance. He was
in and out of prison for half of his life. In 1993, according to
the district attorney's office, he was sentenced to 10 years for
felony theft and served about four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough was enough,'' Skeen said. ``The jury refused to put him
back out on the street after some short period of time to continue
committing criminal offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Dix said Payne's chances before a jury were not very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the West,'' Dix said. ``We feel very strongly about
citizen justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas is one of only a handful of states that have jury
sentencing, where a panel of peers sentences the defendant, rather
than a judge. Dix said that prosecutors generally expect jurors to
hand down harsher sentences in straightforward cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Texas has a reputation of being more stringent, more
strict with criminals,'' Dix said. ``The idea is that jurors will
be more sensitive to these issues than a judge so they'll give them
a stricter sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees that long prison terms will cut down on
crime. State Rep. Toby Goodman, who is both a former prosecutor and
defense lawyer, said Payne's sentence was way over the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would it benefit the state of Texas by throwing this guy
in prison?'' asked Goodman, who is a Republican. ``Yeah, the guy's
a dummy, but what's next _ execution?'' But one of Goodman's peers
in the House thinks Payne deserved the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people just focus on the Snickers Bar then it does seem
silly,'' said State Rep. Will Hartlett, also a Republican. ``But he
was clearly a chronic career criminal. What if they let him out on
parole and he killed someone? He has to be put away before his
crimes get worse and worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Dix said Payne will be required to serve at least four years of
his sentence before being eligible for parole. But Hartlett said he
feels no sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, he got 10 years several years ago for felony theft and
he served about four years,'' Harlett said. ``Now he'll serve out
the rest of that sentence. That's what should have happened in the
first place. Maybe now he'll straighten up in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goodman said Payne received a tough sentence at least in
part because he was in a tough part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Texas is one place in the U.S. that you don't want to
commit a crime, even stealing candy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
