<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-MENS-MARATHON-NYT     05-06 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MENS-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUT UP THE THERMOSTAT: HERE COMES WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Temperatures in the 70s and creeping humidity were
forecast for early Sunday morning for the men's Olympic marathon
trials. This was not unexpected by Todd Williams, one of the
favorites, who spent much of the last 18 weeks training on a
treadmill in his basement in Knoxville, Tenn., the thermostat
cranked up to 75 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``No window, no fan,'' Williams said. ``Psychotic.''
</P>
<P>
   One of America's top distance runners, a two-time Olympian at
10,000 meters, or 6.2 miles, Williams has been trying to make his
body calloused to the marathon distance of 26.2 miles. For his two
previous marathons, he concentrated on speed work but ran out of
gas in the final two miles, crossing the finish line on fumes in 2
hours 11 minutes 17 seconds at the 1997 Chicago Marathon and in
2:14:56 at the 1999 Chicago Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   He has since realized that he needed more endurance training.
So, preparing for the trials, he did six two-hour runs on his
treadmill, using the soft running surface to cushion against injury
and the basement thermometer to acclimate himself to the expected
heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think it made me a little bit crazy,'' Williams said.
``When I hit the 20-mile mark, I'll think back to all the sacrifice
I made running for two hours on the treadmill, and I think I'll be
able to push through the pain a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   His basement was the toasty equivalent of the reptile house at
the zoo. The Dungeon, his friends call it. It comes complete with
bathroom, shower, bedroom, weight room and treadmill. Williams
trained and slept downstairs while his wife, Stephanie, and their
two daughters, Brooke, who is 3, and Bailee, who is 10 weeks, lived
upstairs. Some runners go to the mountains for isolation, some go
overseas. Williams went to his carpeted dungeon, where the
entertainment ranged from ESPN to the cartoon adventures of Scooby
Doo. He watched entire college and professional basketball games
while running in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I live as hard as I can possibly live and sacrifice
and do things I think are going to help,'' said Williams, who is 31
and has a psychology degree from the University of Tennessee. ``I
put everything in this basket. I told my wife I needed to get a PO
box at the back door, so I can get my mail delivered down there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was particular urgency for speed this weekend. The Olympic
A qualifying standard was 2:14. Among Americans, only David Morris
and Joe LeMay met the standard during the qualifying period for the
2000 Games in Sydney, Australia. For Williams to make the Olympic
team, he had to win Sunday's trials, or finish in the top 3 under
2:14. Here, things got complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he would renounce an Olympic bid if he won
Sunday's trials but did not meet the A standard. Essentially, he
was protesting against the American selection process, which said
that only the winner of the trials would go to Sydney if the
first-place runner finished slower than 2:14 and was someone other
than Morris and LeMay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think someone needs to make a stand,'' said Williams, who
stood to relinquish $75,000 in prize and bonus money if he
renounced a victory on Sunday. ``I don't think it's fair for guys
who killed themselves in November and December to run the
qualifying time and not to get to go.''
</P>
<P>
   He could make all this moot, of course, by running faster than
2:14, which he planned to do regardless of smothering heat and
humidity. Needing more stamina in his legs after finishing the
final two miles of the 1999 Chicago Marathon at a depleted
six-minute pace, Williams began an endurance program this year that
called for runs up to 2 hours 26 minutes indoors and 2:45 outdoors.
One outdoor workout consisted of a four-mile warm-up, the running
of stadium steps, three track repeats of 2,000 meters at 5:55 pace,
more stadium steps, a 10-mile run at six-minute pace, three more
repeats of 2,000 meters, stadium steps and a warmdown run of four
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Williams has suffered from a stitch in his right
side during races. The problem, he said, occurred in membranes
supporting his liver. He has attempted to resolve the situation by
exhaling when his left foot strikes the ground, which, he said, was
less jarring on his liver. On Sunday, he also planned to have an
injection of Xylocaine to numb his right side.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he walked into a discount store and bought 17 baby
bottles with pop-up straws to use as containers for his sports
drink on the race course. ``They looked at me like I was crazy,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   If his grueling, eccentric methods did not result in a berth in
the Olympics, Williams said, it would be a long time before he
tried another marathon. But he would not allow himself any negative
thoughts. Regardless of the temperature, he planned to run a
succession of 5:05 miles, hoping to run the last mile as fast as he
ran the first. That way, Williams would run under 2:14 and most
likely qualify for an all-expenses-paid trip to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either trained for it or you didn't,'' he said. ``They
won't be handing out any tissues to wipe your tears at 10K (10,000
kilometers). We've got to go for it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
