<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COREY JOHNSON HAS PROVIDED SUPPORT TO ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn., N.Y., Pa.)   By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time Corey Johnson came out to the world last week, he
had already come out to most everyone who mattered to him _ his
parents, sister, best friend, teachers, football coach and
teammates _ in a gradual, sometimes orchestrated process that
lasted more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   So, the hundreds of thousands who cheered the linebacker at the
Millennium March for Equality in Washington last Sunday were just
another big-game crowd. Of course, they all seemed to want to shake
his hand and tell him their life stories, if not option his life
story, date him or sign him up as spokesman for their gay
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was chasing me,'' Johnson said in the middle of last
week, sounding tired but still floating on a celebrity high. It was
late at night in his Middleton, Mass., home and he was just back
from one of his part-time jobs, as a secretary in a real-estate
agency. ``I'm weighing offers. After I graduate next month, I'd
like to travel, check out some colleges for the year after and
think about the book and movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, Johnson turned 18, and he is the activist
equivalent of the teen-age National Basketball Association draftee,
a Kobe with a mission. As the first high school football captain to
declare his homosexuality so publicly, he immediately proved, as he
put it, that ``you don't have to do drama or be a drum major to be
gay.''
</P>
<P>
   The early response to his formal coming-out announcement, on the
front page of The New York Times last Sunday, was an avalanche of
e-mail messages to the Times Web site or to me at, as you must
remember, Thelipsite(at)aol.com (all of them were forwarded to
Coreyjohnson2000(at)aol.com). Most expressed appreciation to
Johnson for giving them hope; some had been closeted high school
athletes and remembered the pain and shame of secrecy. Johnson's
high school, Masconomet, was singled out for the quality of its
teachers, coaches and students, not to mention its long-term
commitment to diversity training.
</P>
<P>
   There is a feel-good aspect to this story for straights, who can
feel big-hearted and progressive, and for gay men and lesbians, who
can feel that their world is becoming safer. Without diminishing
those feelings, it's also useful to remember that Corey's Coming
Out didn't just happen. A high school community (not quite
unanimously) rallied around a handsome, popular star jock, not a
scrawny, vulnerable band member. The school had a Gay Straight
Alliance in place with two advisers, one of them a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   The Masconomet administration brought in the Gay Lesbian and
Straight Education Network, which has a contract with the Safe
Schools program of the state of Massachusetts (which has two openly
gay members of Congress). The stars were in their courses on this
one; think about a star football player even trying to come out
under Friday night lights in Texas. Or in a New York City public
high school.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Dan Woog, a 47-year-old openly gay assistant
soccer coach at Staples High School in Westport, Conn., where he
once played, thinks that Corey Johnson will ``give courage to the
kid out there'' who may someday really shatter the stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the one who will make the difference is going to be a
superstar who comes out in high school, and the country follows him
to Division I, then to the pros, and the all-star game and the
league championship,'' Woog said.
</P>
<P>
   Woog, author of ``Jocks: True Stories of America's Gay Male
Athletes,'' published two years ago by Alyson Books, was on the Gay
Lesbian Straight Education Network panel led by Jeff Perrotti where
Johnson first asked for help in coming out. He thinks Johnson's
story brings up an important coaching issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got an athlete in the closet, you've got an athlete
who can't fully concentrate,'' Woog said. ``Coaches have to make a
safe, accepting environment for all kids, gay kids, poor kids, kids
with the wrong sneakers, fat kids. In my workshop, I try to
convince coaches it's not just the right thing to do, it'll show up
in their wins and losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gallagher, 43, who was a star at Valhalla (N.Y.) High and a
varsity tackle at the University of Pittsburgh, thinks he would
have been a far better football player if he had been able to come
to terms with his sexuality. He might even have done better in his
Jets tryout, although he was up against Mark Gastineau. He
certainly would not have, at the age of 28, after his first
homosexual experience, climbed to the top of the Kensico Dam,
overlooking his high school field, and thrown himself off.
Gallagher's neck was broken. He is a quadriplegic.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher, founder of Alive To Thrive (aliv2thriv(at)aol.com)
and author of the semiautobiographical ``Johnny In The Spot''
(1stBooks, 1998), often speaks at high schools. He says he sees too
many kids struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``That coach you idolize tries to motivate you with anti-gay
slurs,'' Gallagher said, ``and you wonder what he's telling you, if
he's seeing through you. This Corey is a pioneer, a leader, but
he's up against the hypocritical right-wing hatemongers who want to
punish people for being human. I say there are no straights or
gays, just `strays.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
