<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HANOVER-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      05-06 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANOVER-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S ESTRANGED WIFE CALLS THEIR MARRIAGE `VERY PRECIOUS' 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Donna Hanover said Saturday that her marriage to
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was ``very precious'' to her, as she spoke
publicly for the first time since the mayor disclosed he had
prostate cancer and acknowledged a friendship with another woman.
</P>
<P>
   In an unlikely setting, at the back entrance of St. Patrick's
Cathedral, Hanover held a news conference before she joined
thousands of mourners to pay her respects to Cardinal John O'Connor
early Saturday afternoon. She arrived with a phalanx of staff
members, who had notified news organizations in advance that she
would make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate all the love and kind thoughts that so many
people have sent me and my children during these difficult days,''
said Hanover, wearing a black suit and appearing pale.
</P>
<P>
   Trembling perceptibly, Hanover said, ``I will be supportive of
Rudy in his fight against his illness, as this marriage and this
man have been very precious to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover and the mayor have led separate lives for the last few
years, and she has not appeared at his side publicly during his
second mayoral term. Their lengthy estrangement, though, drew
considerable attention on Wednesday after The New York Post
published photographs of Judith Nathan, the Upper East Side
resident who has accompanied the mayor to town hall meetings and
other public events in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day the photographs were published, Giuliani devoted
the first portion of his news briefing to them. He called her a
``very good friend'' and told reporters in the Blue Room at City
Hall that he hoped they would respect her privacy. Later in the
week, asked specifically whether the friendship was romantic, the
mayor would only say that this was a private matter.
</P>
<P>
   Since the news broke of the mayor's cancer and of his friendship
with Nathan, Hanover's spokeswoman had issued statements but
Hanover had not appeared in public in response to queries.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, she would not take any questions from reporters,
and spoke obliquely about the future. ``The well-being and safety
of Andrew and Caroline,'' the couple's 14-year-old son and
10-year-old daughter, ``will be my primary concern in any decisions
that have to be made, as has always been the case,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover withdrew days ago from ``The Vagina Monologues,'' an
Off-Broadway play about subjects like orgasm and birth that she and
two other actresses were to begin appearing in on May 30. In a
statement, she cited ``personal family circumstances'' as the
reason for her postponement of the acting role, and the statement
did not mention her husband's name.
</P>
<P>
   As she prepared to enter St. Patrick's on Saturday, she
explained her special bond with the cardinal, who died Wednesday.
Appearing to have difficulty maintaining her composure, her eyes
watering, she said: ``Cardinal O'Connor often told me that my
family was in his prayers. He was a Navy chaplain, and I was raised
in the Navy, and we have that as a special bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to pay my respects, and I will have no further
remarks today,'' she said, then walked up the back stairs, followed
by her staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
