<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES: EXPOS; INDIANS; DYE; TRADES AND AVERAGES; APRIL
BATTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expos' Express Stalls
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos seemed to be off to a promising season. Then
they arrived in Colorado. The Expos, with a 14-9 record, should
have been suspicious; the Rockies had just scored 29 runs in a
three-game series with the Mets, even though they lost two of the
games. But Colorado did not lose any of the three games with the
Expos, amassing 43 runs and 55 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like you can't explain it,'' said Jim Beattie, the
Expos' general manager, who was an eyewitness to the series in
Colorado. ``You can explain it. We just didn't pitch well. I don't
know if we go in there and say we can't pitch here. We pitched up.
We hung a lot of sliders, breaking balls, changeups. We didn't
pitch inside well. Jeffrey Hammonds hit a grand slam on an 0-2
fastball. We just didn't locate fastballs. That has nothing to do
with pitching in Denver or anywhere else. We made a lot of bad
pitches. So it's explainable.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians Look to Rebound
</P>
<P>
   The joke could be on the Indians. Frustrated by their failure to
win a World Series, any World Series, the Indians fired Manager
Mike Hargrove and named Charlie Manuel, their hitting coach, to
replace him. General manager John Hart said the team needed a new
voice in the dugout. The problem is that new voice may be lulling
the Indians to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's five-time division champions are struggling through
the kind of start they thought they left behind when they became a
force in the American League six years ago. This season, however,
matches the start they had in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In April of that season, they were not in first place for 17
successive days. Sunday marks the 17th successive day they have not
been in first this season. Their record before Saturday was 13-13,
the same as it was three years ago. The Indians went on that season
to fall two outs short of winning the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   `That's Business'
</P>
<P>
   At 22, Jermaine Dye played in the World Series for the Atlanta
Braves. At 26, Dye is a star for the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what team I'm on, as long as I'm in the big
leagues fulfilling a dream,'' Dye said. ``It would have been nice
to play my whole career in Atlanta, but it didn't work out. Maybe
someday I'll get a chance to go back there, but right now I'm happy
where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   After hitting .281 for the Braves as a rookie in 1996, Dye
figured to be with them for a while. The next year, he recalled, he
had a good spring training and prepared to settle in, especially
after David Justice and Marquis Grissom were traded to Cleveland
late in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to be slotted in to play every day,''
Dye said. ``All of a sudden I got traded.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only two days after the Justice-Grissom trade. ``That's
part of baseball,'' the outfielder said. ``That's business.''
</P>
<P>
   Dye said he did not know how to react to being traded for the
first time, especially at such a young age. But, he added: ``I knew
Kansas City wanted me and liked me a lot. I just needed to go over
there, put on a new uniform and realize I'm on a new team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dye struggled his first two seasons with the Royals; in fact, he
spent part of each season in the minor leagues. But last season he
blossomed into a legitimate major league hitter with a .294 batting
average, 27 home runs and 119 runs batted in. That performance set
him up for what he has done early this season.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, he led the American League in home runs
(12), doubles (12), slugging percentage (.795), total bases (89)
and extra-base hits (24). He was tied for second in hits (41), tied
for third in runs scored (24), third in runs batted in (29) and
fifth in hitting (.366).
</P>
<P>
   But he was not among the leaders in outfield assists, as he was
last season when his 17 assists were tied for first.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I don't have any,'' he said. ``This year guys aren't
running on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Deals, Small Numbers
</P>
<P>
   The biggest moves the Cincinnati Reds made during the winter
were the acquisition of Ken Griffey Jr. and Dante Bichette. A year
earlier, they traded for Michael Tucker. Those three players formed
the Reds' starting outfield on opening day. Entering Saturday's
schedule, Griffey was hitting .210, Bichette .219 and Tucker .167.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit did not figure on a .225 average for Juan Gonzalez when
it traded for him and offered him a $140 million contract. But then
Gabe Kapler, who went to Texas in the Gonzalez trade, is hitting
.200. Reggie Sanders was traded to Atlanta and is hitting .139.
Mark McLemore signed with Seattle as a free agent and has a .204
average. Pittsburgh signed Wil Cordero, who is hitting .208.
</P>
<P>
   While Derek Bell floats in the high .300's for the Mets, Roger
Cedeno is hitting .202 for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Some other bad early averages of players who aren't new to their
teams: Tony Clark, .155; Rey Ordonez, .179; Homer Bush, .182; Ray
Lankford, .193; Rickey Henderson, .203; Cliff Floyd, .203; Eric
Karros, .204; and Jose Offerman, .207.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Power Company
</P>
<P>
   Before batters hit 931 home runs this April, the most prolific
April for home runs had come in the 1996 season. If this season
proceeds like that one, the home run frequency is very likely to
slow. That April produced 2.30 home runs a game, but the average
for the entire season wound up at 2.18 a game. This April's average
was 2.56.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
