<HEADER>
A7734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOLOCAUST-RESCUER-ART     05-06 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-RESCUER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A WARTIME ESCAPE TO A STATESIDE REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By COREY KILGANNON c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1943, Walter Marx, a Jewish teen-ager, was fleeing the Nazis
in a small town in northwest Italy. A young Italian woman saved his
life by hiding him from German soldiers and helping him escape.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 years passed, and though Marx made several trips
back to the town, Borgo San Dalmazzo, the two did not meet again
until a surprising and touching reunion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Marx, now 74 and retired in Roslyn, N.Y., was invited to a
ceremony in the town for a monument he had helped pay for,
dedicated to the many townspeople who aided Jews driven there
during the war.
</P>
<P>
   In his dedication speech, Marx spoke of the young woman in the
town who once risked her life to save his, adding that he had not
seen her again despite many searches.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a 78-year-old woman came from the crowd crying. She
hardly resembled the brave 22-year-old woman with a pretty smile
and thick chestnut locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remembered a beautiful girl, not a woman with white hair in
her 70s,'' Marx said, ``but somehow I knew it was her.'' Weeping,
the woman introduced herself as Magdalena Gibaudo. The two hugged
as the crowd responded with applause and tears. He offered to treat
Gibaudo to a visit to New York to stay with him. She arrived on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a leather couch in his large house on Long Island on
Thursday evening, Marx and Gibaudo, over tea and strawberries,
discussed how to avoid traffic during their weekend of sightseeing
in Manhattan. It was a far cry from sitting, 57 years ago, in her
father's hotel, planning how to avoid Nazis and the train to
Auschwitz while sneaking Marx to the underground.
</P>
<P>
   With a group of some 1,300 Jews fleeing France, Marx and his
mother walked over the Alps and stopped at the small Italian town.
The two stayed several nights at a small hotel called the Caballo
Rosso, owned by Gibaudo's father.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nazis soon rounded them up with other Jews and put them
into a temporary camp in town. Gibaudo would see Marx toiling in
work crews in town. He injured his back pushing a truck and spent
three months in a local hospital. She visited him there and visited
his mother in the camp, bringing them food. But then the Jewish
prisoners, including his mother, Johanna Marx, were put on the
train to Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Marx, whose father, Ludwig Marx, was arrested earlier in France
and sent to a death camp in Poland, sneaked from the hospital on
crutches and asked Gibaudo to hide him in the hotel. Though she
risked being shot by the Nazis, she took the teen-ager in and later
guided him to the foothills of the Alps, where she introduced him
to members of the Italian Underground.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to work for the underground, and posed as an
interpreter for the Nazi secret service. He discovered and helped
foil a Nazi attack, he said, and was later wounded in a battle
against German soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he learned that his parents had died in the
camps, and at age 19 he came to New York. He started an air freight
business and married. He and his wife, Ellen, a German Jew who
survived the Holocaust by living in a convent in Belgium, had three
sons. Through the years he often took them back to Borgo San
Dalmazzo, but the inn had been demolished, and he had no luck
finding Gibaudo.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the war, Gibaudo said risking her life for Marx and
other Jews in danger was something that came ``del cuore,'' or from
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do it,'' Gibaudo said, adding that she never forgot
the terror in the face of that handsome 17-year-old who showed up
on crutches one night at her father's hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helping him has remained one of the most important events in
my life,'' she said. ``I always hoped he would come back, but I
never really believed he would.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibaudo said she also helped Jewish prisoners, including Marx's
mother, hobble onto trains with no idea that they were headed to
death camps, a cruel twist that has long tormented her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is such a painful thing to remember walking those people to
the train and watching them get on,'' she said. ``I cannot forget
that. I cannot even read about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marx said he would always feel indebted to Gibaudo and would
always feel a special tie to Borgo San Dalmazzo.
</P>
<P>
   The horrible memories of persecution are indelible, he said,
``but the experience has helped me face life with a lot of courage,
and surviving has given me a sense of pride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
