<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-MARATHON-AMERICAN     05-06 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-AMERICANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LONG-DISTANCE RUNNERS ARE PSYCHING THEMSELVES OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 (With OLY-MENS-MARATHON) 
 By MARC BLOOM   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the new U.S. citizen Khalid Khannouchi is sitting
out Sunday's men's Olympic marathon trial in Pittsburgh, his status
as a ``ready-made'' star who is far superior to other Americans
emphasizes an irony that contradicts most explanations on the
demise of American distance runners.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the Kenyans and other Africans is often cited as the
main reason why an American man has not won the New York City
Marathon since 1982 and the Boston Marathon since 1983 or been
close to an Olympic medal since Frank Shorter's gold in 1972 and
silver in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it is said, Africans typically run many miles to
school and have the advantage of a running-rich, high-altitude
environment. In Kenya, there are no other big-time sports to
attract athletic talent; if you're a good athlete, you run.
</P>
<P>
   But the root of the American problem is not based on training
environment or physical strength. The problem stems from the mind.
We're psyched out.
</P>
<P>
   When Khannouchi, 28, came to the United States from Morocco in
1993, he was not a running sensation. In high school, he had run
3,000 meters in 8 minutes 35 seconds, which would not have won the
high school event at last week's Penn Relays. The record for U.S.
high school boys is 8:05.8. But Khannouchi believed he could be a
great runner and focused solely on that mission. He got a job as a
dishwasher and trained at night.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a coach or formal training doctrine behind him,
Khannouchi knew that distance-running success took years to
achieve. Winning a marathon would not be a slam dunk. You had to be
patient. You had to sacrifice. Eventually, your time would come.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi waited. As recently as March 1996, he was still the
kind of also-ran who would place ninth in the 3,000 meters at the
U.S. national indoor meet. He had no sponsor and made a few bucks
here and there off the racing circuit. He thought about quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after four years of running while dodging Brooklyn
traffic, Khannouchi made a breakthrough in 1997. After Khannouchi
won the Chicago Marathon that fall in 2 hours 7 minutes 10 seconds
(his world record, set last year at Chicago, is 2:05:42), I visited
him at his home in Wyckoff Heights on the Brooklyn-Queens border.
Then, he lived in a third-floor walkup and did speed work at
Victory Field, on a scrubby track barely adequate for the joggers
who circled it wearing headphones.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Khannouchi never conceded anything to the Kenyans or
anyone else. He ran nose-to-nose with the Kenyans and eventually
defeated them. If anything, some of the Kenyans feared Khannouchi.
They would whisper about him in awe when he turned up at races.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Kenyans respected American runners like Steve Prefontaine,
Alberto Salazar and Craig Virgin. Recently, I spoke with Virgin,
the only American man to win the world cross-country title, an
event now dominated by Kenyans. Virgin, who grew up on a farm in
Illinois, said he never doubted he could beat anybody in the world.
</P>
<P>
   For years, however, American runners have sulked with a sense of
inferiority, thinking the Kenyans have the edge and there's nothing
to be done about it. Americans have despaired so deeply that they
race almost exclusively among themselves and avoid Kenyans and
other foreign opposition at all cost.
</P>
<P>
   The telling statistic is not only that in the last 10 years only
three American men have made the top-10 at the New York City
Marathon. It's also that leading Americans no longer run races like
New York or Boston at all.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the Americans' poor self-image has had a disturbing
trickle-down effect that could have drastic repercussions. Last
week, at a high school track meet in New Jersey, I saw an example
of that. I overheard a white youngster entered in the mile telling
a teammate his prospects for victory were not good. He said to his
friend: ``See that black guy over there? He's in the mile. I'm
going to get blown away.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the African-American youngster, an
inexperienced freshman, rushed out too fast in the lead and faded.
The white kid won. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
