<HEADER>
A7740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CZECH-OPEN-PRISON-(TR     05-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-OPEN-PRISON-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CZECH JAIL WITHOUT BARS, WOMEN TEND TO THE ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By LADKA BAUEROVA c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Martina Holmanova, a cheerful blonde in
her early 20s, is a convicted criminal serving two years for
assisting armed robbery. She is also, as part of an experiment that
contrasts starkly with the overcrowded, underfinanced prisons
common in the Czech Republic, a nurse who has learned to delight 90
elderly patients with her animated puppet shows.
</P>
<P>
   Holmanova is one of 57 inmates of Repy female prison on the
outskirts of Prague. In Repy, the windows do not have bars, the
single guard does not carry a gun and the convicts mingle with
nuns, doctors and nurses to tend the elderly patients with whom
they share the building.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners, neatly made up and dressed in civilian clothes,
can walk alone in the surrounding gardens or join the sisters in
prayer. Some travel unescorted across the city to work.
</P>
<P>
   With 238 prisoners for every 100,000 citizens, the Czech
Republic has one of the highest prison populations per capita in
Central and Eastern Europe. The Czech Prison Authority has become
so desperate that it is sending less serious offenders home.
</P>
<P>
   But the Repy prison's 65 beds, housed in a 19th-century mansion
with a large garden and a beautifully renovated chapel, are almost
never full. The prison's manager and chief psychologist, Alena
Krizova, says she has trouble finding enough offenders who meet the
criteria of her unique institution, established in 1997 and now
boasting an impressive record: 90 percent of its past inmates have
stayed clear of crime since their release.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women here are first-time offenders convicted of
nonviolent crimes like theft and embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidate must not be aggressive or highly neurotic,''
Krizova said. ``Intellect does not matter _ we have slightly
mentally disabled individuals as well as college graduates.''
</P>
<P>
   Those chosen to serve time in Repy live seven to a room at most,
and can choose whether roommates are smokers or not. Once a week,
they may buy extra food and sweets in a canteen and cook meals in
the kitchen. Inmates with skills are encouraged to share them; one
prisoner with her own computer is showing others how to use it, and
a former inmate who knew English gave language lessons. The
prisoners can sew and knit, study or raise tomatoes and cucumbers
in the greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But Repy's inmates cannot leave without permission. They get up
at 6 a.m. and go to bed at 10 p.m. Lovers, husbands, children and
relatives may visit only once every two weeks for 90 minutes.
Depending on the gravity of their crime and on their behavior, the
prison occasionally allows them a weekend at home.
</P>
<P>
   Jitka Matulova, 31, never gets a free weekend. Given the
seriousness of her crime, she should not even be in Repy. Six years
ago, she tried to kill her husband by detonating a Semtex bomb in
his car.
</P>
<P>
   She was sentenced to 12 years and spent five of them in two
high-security prisons. But her good behavior, repentance and
growing religious belief so impressed the prison chaplain that he
persuaded the authorities to allow her to transfer to Repy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hesitated a long time before we accepted Jitka,'' Krizova
said. ``But she's proven herself. She is the kind of a person who
needs to experience success, who needs to hear praise when she does
something well.''
</P>
<P>
   Matulova, who now works as the hospital's cleaning lady, still
remembers her astonishment when she arrived at Repy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought me here on the Children's Day,'' she recalled.
``The garden was full of kids, they were having a party, and the
guard told me, `Go on, join them.' I couldn't do it. For weeks, I
couldn't get over seeing a window without bars.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Jana Sustrova, 43, one of the few recidivists here
(``an incorrigible thief, but otherwise a super girl,'' Krizova
says), served time even under the communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when they brought me here, I thought they were kidding
me,'' Sustrova said. ``I just didn't believe this was a prison.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It took months, Matulova recalled, to get used to the freedom of
movement, civilian clothes, openness and the civil behavior of the
guards. Now, she takes great solace in her faith, Repy's frescoed
chapel and the compassionate nuns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more time and space to think about my sins here,'' she
said. ``Faith helps.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sister Simeona Kovalska, a St. Boromeus nun who works as the
hospital's head nurse, said she tells new inmates that she does not
care about their background, that here the important thing is
tending the patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see,'' she said, ``how honored they feel when the old
ladies call them `nurses.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
