<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-06 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$4 MILLION CAN'T BUY VICTORY IF LUCK IS NOT ON YOUR SIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (With RAC-KENTUCKY-DERBY) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Favorites don't always win; that much is given
and even longed for in sports. The upsets are the lifeblood of
competition, a vital part of the foundation that all things _ even
the hopeless _ are possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky Derby has taken the upset to an unrivaled extreme.
The last favorite to win this coveted race was Spectacular Bid, who
won by 2} lengths in 1979. The Derby is a graveyard of failures for
horses who rumble into Louisville cast as favorites.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this race so hard on favorites? Like everything else
in horse racing everyone has an opinion, no one really knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that you have so many horses, that's why favorites
don't win,'' said the trainer Billy Ashenbrenner. ``A 20-horse
field is a joke. You can't pick a winner out of a 20-horse field
any way, shape nor form. The horse that wins it is lucky. And with
a 20-horse field, it's mostly bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck. You hear that word a lot in horse racing. Spend $4 million
on a horse, and you rely on lots of luck?
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you put the large number of horses in a gate and they
have to go as far as they're going, so many things can transpire
that it's hard to predict who the winner is going to be,'' said the
trainer Robbie O'Connor. ``You need a lot of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   But anything can happen. Last week, Fusaichi Pegasus threw his
exercise rider and fell down. The horse was not injured. Luckily.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these horses get fantastic care _ how you can give this
much money for an animal,'' O'Connor said. ``All of them are taken
care of very well. Yet you can come in here one morning all they
have to do is take one bad step and that $2 million, $4 million
investment is not worth an egg sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   The Derby Jinx doesn't always hit at the Derby with a loss in
what should have been a victory. For many favorites the jinx hits
before they even get to Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   _ In March, Greenwood Lake was the early favorite but got a
hairline fracture of his left front ankle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last year, Wondertross had an intestinal blockage the day
after he finished sixth in the Blue Grass.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1998, Lil's Lad was eliminated with a chipped left front
ankle detected three weeks before the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also in 1998, Coronado's Quest was withdrawn from the Derby
because of behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1992, A.P. Indy was withdrawn on the morning of the
Kentucky Derby because of a fractured bone.
</P>
<P>
   There is no jinx, in reality, just a pumped up atmosphere and a
competitive track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around here a long time and everyone I've ever
talked to says this is the hardest race in the world to win,'' said
Doc Danner, an agent who represents Pat Day and other jockeys. He
pointed to last year's race, when Charismatic held off Menifee, one
of the favorites, who had to come out of the 19th hole and weave
his way through a mass of horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, our sport is like going to the casino, too,'' Danner
said. ``If you don't have a little Lady Luck on your side, believe
me, it makes it harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Churchill Downs itself. The scene alone can
intimidate the inexperienced rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about the Derby _ it's the way the race
develops _ it takes a lot of luck,'' jockey Tracy Hebert said.
``Having a good trip, breaking good, staying out of trouble,
cutting corners, not having to go around the whole field. Some
horses just don't run here as good as they run at Belmont. It's got
nothing to do with the favorite not winning, just the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be the crowd, it could be the noise. Who knows?
Nobody knows. This track is a hard track, a horse weights 1,500
pounds, that's pretty big to be hitting on the hard ground. If they
get to stinging, not comfortable, they won't put out. At Belmont,
along the stretch, the track is deeper and the speed will back up a
little bit. Here the speed won't back. You got to be in contention
unless you got a real, real good horse that will come from way out
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like this is a big track, but you get 20 horses in a
race and you got to maneuver and come around, before you know it,
the wire's there. At Belmont, the track is huge. You've got plenty,
plenty room, a long stretch; the race track's a little deeper, the
horse will come back a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Derby Day will come and go, the crucial answers unanswered: Can
you buy a Derby victory? Can you breed a champion?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you spend that kind of money for a horse, your
percentages go way up,'' O'Connor said, ``because you are buying
the pedigree and a horse that's already proven he can run some. But
there's a lot to be said for luck in this game, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have the big money to spend; you better have the luck
also following it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, $4 million worth of luck would seem to be enough for a
Derby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
