<HEADER>
A7742 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SYDNEY-UPDATE0507     05-06 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-UPDATE0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sydney learns Atlanta lesson
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Staging the Olympics isn't a competitive
sport, but it sometimes seems that way to the cities that host the
world's biggest event.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Atlanta, the site of the Centennial Games, was
in a wind sprint for the finish line, struggling to complete venues
little more than a month before the Opening Ceremonies. In
contrast, Sydney seems to be jogging toward the tape, having
finished all but one of its 28 venues.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium Australia, the vast arena where the 2000 games will
begin Sept. 15, has been open for more than a year and already has
handled huge crowds for rugby and a concert by the Bee-Gees.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, in a full dress rehearsal for prime time, 5,500
runners competed in the Host City Marathon, testing a brutally
hilly Olympic course that took them across the Sydney Harbour
bridge, past the famous Opera House and, many sweaty miles later,
into the big oval of the Stadium. It was almost like the real
thing, complete with a cheering crowd and medal ceremonies set to
stirring music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a chance to work out details we never had in
Atlanta,'' said stadium manager Jim Brown, who oversaw the baseball
venue in 1996. ``Four years ago at this time, people were still
worried about electricity and plumbing.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee has praised Sydney for being
further along than any other host city. Atlanta inadvertently
inspired much of the early preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney wanted to present the best Olympics, and the only way to
do it was to avoid the much-publicized problems _ the commercialism
and the technology and transportation glitches _ that, in the eyes
of the world media, tarnished the Atlanta games. Despite its
successful bidding program, SOCOG already has taken plenty of
criticism. Rowers have complained that weeds in the regatta lake
impede their oars, runners have whined about winds sweeping through
Stadium Australia and, in a first for the Olympics, triathletes
have worried about man-eating sharks invading Sydney Harbour during
the swimming leg of their competition.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious problem by far has been ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Australians might love sports even more than Americans do, and
they flooded SOCOG with order forms when tickets went on sale last
year. But few got tickets to the events they wanted, in part
because so many had been set aside for sponsors, national Olympic
committees and other VIPs.
</P>
<P>
   When news leaked out that less than 10 percent of the seats in
some events were available to the average Aussie, it provoked a
lasting backlash in this egalitarian society where ``mateship'' is
a fundamental principle. The Sydney organizers are still recovering
from the public-relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mucked it up,'' admitted the Billy Payne of this operation,
Michael Knight, a career politician who is the third person to
serve as Olympics minister and SOCOG president. ``Australians feel
a proprietary ownership of the Games. They therefore feel an
entitlement to tickets in a way Americans didn't.... We followed
the Atlanta model of ticketing, and we shouldn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   In most other ways, Sydney has managed the Olympic buildup in a
different way from Atlanta. After the Australians edged Beijing for
the 2000 bid in September 1993, plans proceeded slowly. Then more
than 200 SOCOG staffers attended the Centennial Games to observe.
</P>
<P>
   The chief lesson Sydney took from Atlanta was to get the
government much more involved, not only financially, but with the
ultimate authority to decide anything related to the Olympics.
Unlike Atlanta's privately funded and privately coordinated effort,
Sydney's is underwritten by the state of New South Wales. Atlanta
spent $1.7 billion on the games, but Sydney is spending at least
twice that much, a third of it coming from taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money has gone to develop the Sydney Olympic Park, a
sprawling Disney World of athletics located nine miles west of the
central city on Marabush Bay, a far tendril of the harbor. Fifteen
of the venues with almost a quarter-million seats are concentrated
at the site, which is 40 times larger than Atlanta's Centennial
Park.
</P>
<P>
   The area once was a notorious wasteland that had been used as an
arms depot, slaughterhouse and garbage dump. In places were
asbestos and small amounts of such toxic chemicals as dioxin. It
was so bleak that part of the site _ an old brick pit _ was used as
a set for the post-apocalypse world in the movie ``Mad Max: Beyond
the Thunderdome.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the waste has been destroyed or contained and has been
covered with parkland. In the middle of the green space sit arenas
for baseball, tennis, swimming, field hockey, track and field. The
most conspicuous of them, Stadium Australia, looms over the site
with twin grandstands whose white roof superstructures seem to open
to the sky like a giant bivalve. With a capacity of 110,000, it is
billed as the largest stadium in Olympic history. As with almost
all the facilities, it will remain after the games, when it will be
reduced by 25,000 seats and used for rugby and soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators will not be allowed to drive into the Marabush Bay
area during the Olympics. They either will take a new train line
built for the occasion or hop buses at park-ride lots scattered
throughout the city. Hundreds of bus drivers will be brought in
from out of town. Getting lost is easy in Sydney. The metro area,
at 4 million people, is slightly more populous than Atlanta, but it
has half the highway system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transportation continues to scare me,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   As for that other bugaboo that haunted the Atlanta Games,
``commercialism,'' don't expect to hear about hordes of tacky
souvenir tents in Sydney. ``It won't happen,'' said Ed Hula,
veteran Olympic reporter who moved from Atlanta to Sydney to cover
the 2000 Games. ``Things are much more regulated here. Street
vendors get shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney has other things to worry about, though. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Strikes. Trade unions have clout in Australia, and
transportation workers have threatened to walk unless the
government guarantees them bonuses during the games.
</P>
<P>
   _ The last venue. Olympic planners always wanted beach
volleyball to be held at nearby Bondi Beach, the spiritual home of
Australia's surfing. Construction of a temporary 10,000-seat
facility that will close much of the beach for months is set to
begin any day. Neighbors vow to throw themselves in front of the
bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to surf on that beach,'' said Lee Rhiannon, a member
of the state Parliament and leader of the local opposition. ``My
grandmother and grandfather's ashes are scattered off that beach. I
resent giving it up so the Olympics can televise some scantily clad
women jumping around in the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Protests. Aborigine runner Cathy Freeman is one of Australia's
best shots for a rare medal in track and field, and her people are
pulling for her. But it won't stop them from using the Olympics as
a platform for drawing international attention to their plight. The
federal government can't decide whether to make a formal apology to
indigenous peoples for a history of shabby treatment, but
Aboriginal leaders plan to force the issue with marches and
demonstrations during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the preparations are coming to an end, and the drum roll is
beginning. On Wednesday, the Olympic flame will be rekindled in
Greece and begin its long journey toward Stadium Australia _
through the islands of the South Pacific, underwater by a scuba
diver at the great Barrier Reef, by train and plane across the
Outback, held high by golfer Greg Norman as he crosses the Sydney
Harbour Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Four months from the Games, restaurants are booking celebrities;
St. Mary's Cathedral is finishing the twin spires it had wanted to
erect for a century but didn't until the Olympics; and the city's
400 legal brothels are advertising their come-ons. One is the Tokyo
House offer of an ``Olympic's Special'' _ sushi served on naked
female bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Glitches will happen. Traffic probably will be horrendous. But
with its scallop-edged harbor and its sail-roofed opera house,
Sydney really would have to mess it up not to be remembered as one
of the most telegenic Olympic sites. Whatever happens, the city
does not seem quite as eager for vindication as Atlanta sometimes
appeared to be in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sydney is very confident of itself,'' author and journalist
David Marr said. ``If the world applauds us, we'll lap it up. If it
doesn't, we'll be indifferent to the world's opinion. The Olympics
has only exaggerated our arrogant delight in our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
