<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7749 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRA-ARMS-BOS &LR;      05-06 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRA-ARMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA TO ALLOW ARMS MONITORING, PAVING WAY ULSTER ASSEMBLY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a stunning departure from its previous hard-line
stance, the Irish Republican Army said Saturday it would allow
international inspectors to check its arms dumps as part of ``a
process that will completely and verifiably put IRA arms beyond
use,'' a gesture that could revive the suspended power-sharing
government and the flagging peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble greeted the IRA
statement with cautious optimism. His party's refusal to sit in a
government with the IRA's political representatives in Sinn Fein
led to the suspension of the Northern Ireland Assembly just 72 days
after it was created. The IRA's reluctance to begin disarming led
to the assembly's suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does appear to break new ground,'' said Trimble, offering
hope that the IRA's gesture is enough to convince doubters in
Trimble's party that the IRA is sincere about wanting to let Sinn
Fein pursue a united Ireland through democratic methods.
</P>
<P>
   But Trimble stressed that he needed clarification on the IRA's
intentions before he would consider asking his party council to
rescind its refusal to rejoin the local government.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, welcomed the IRA statement, saying they want to
restore the power-sharing government on May 22: ironically, or
appropriately, the date by which the IRA and other paramilitary
groups were supposed to disarm completely under the terms of the
Good Friday Agreement of 1998. It was an offer by Blair and Ahern
to revive the power-sharing government, which includes two members
of Sinn Fein in the 12-member Cabinet, that led the IRA to make its
dramatic counteroffer Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The two governments said they had already settled on the two
international inspectors: Martti Ahtisaari, the former Finnish
president who brokered the end to NATO's war with Yugoslavia last
year, and Cyril Ramaphosa, former chief negotiator for the African
National Congress and now a leading businessman in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not been previously involved in Northern
Ireland, Ahtisaari's stock as an international statesman rose
dramatically when he persuaded Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to withdraw his troops and end the 78-day war over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ramaphosa, a confidant of Nelson Mandela, is an old hand in the
Byzantine world of Anglo-Irish politics. He hosted Northern
Ireland's political parties at workshops in South Africa aimed at
getting them to make peace as the ANC did with the white National
Party to end apartheid. Ramaphosa has also visited Belfast
regularly, a relationship that began in Boston in 1992 when
Ramaphosa and his white counterpart, Rolf Meyer, were brought to a
conference with Northern Ireland leaders at the University of
Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Republican sources said that Ramaphosa has helped convince the
IRA's seven-member ruling Army Council that it had to find a
compromise that would allow the IRA to retain its pride but also
allow the stalled peace process to move forward. Ramaphosa is
friendly with Brian Keenan, whom many observers consider the most
dominant member of the IRA's Army Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cyril has street `cred' with the Army Council, especially
Keenan,'' said one IRA member, who stressed he was speaking as an
``ordinary volunteer,'' not as a spokesman for the IRA leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Padraig O'Malley, the senior fellow at the John W. McCormack
Institute of Public Affairs at UMass-Boston who organized the
conference that first brought Ramaphosa into contact with the
Northern Ireland parties, confirmed that Ramaphosa and Keenan are
``on good terms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know each other, and they trust each other,'' said
O'Malley. ``Cyril and David Trimble also get along. Trimble knows
Cyril's qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   According to spokesmen for Blair and Ahern, the British and
Irish governments approached Ahtisaari and Ramaphosa on Thursday
and Friday, asking if they would take on the roles of arms
inspectors. An IRA source suggested Ramaphosa's acceptance of the
job on Friday helped persuade the IRA to make its statement
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While the IRA stopped short of agreeing to turn in weapons, an
act demanded by the Protestant unionists before they will sit again
in government with Sinn Fein, it was widely seen as a huge
concession by the IRA, which equates its weapons with its
existence. Many in the IRA consider handing in guns tantamount to a
surrender _ which it had carefully avoided when it called a
cease-fire to allow the political process to take over.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, the IRA said it would re-enter discussions
with the international commission charged with disarming
paramilitary groups as part of the Good Friday Agreement that was
supposed to transform the conflict in Northern Ireland from a
violent one to one based strictly on democratic politics. The IRA
had cut off contact with the commission after the British
government suspended the local government in February.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's IRA statement was more specific than a statement it
issued just hours before the British government suspended the
power-sharing government. In a last-ditch effort to halt the
suspension, the IRA pledged it eventually would put its weapons
``beyond use,'' a phrase that the British government deemed too
vague to prevent Trimble and his party walking out of the assembly
and collapsing the power-sharing government.
</P>
<P>
   But after nearly three months of patient coaxing by Blair and
Ahern, the IRA's statement Saturday went much further.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRA leadership has agreed to put in place within weeks a
confidence-building measure to confirm that our weapons remain
secure,'' Saturday's statement said. ``The contents of a number of
arms dumps will be inspected by agreed third parties who will
report that they have done so to the Independent International
Commission on Decommissioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying it would ``initiate a process that will completely and
verifiably put IRA arms beyond use,'' the IRA said, ``The dumps
will be re-inspected regularly to ensure that the weapons have
remained secure.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRA said the arms inspections will be carried out ``in such
a way as to avoid risk to the public and misappropriation by others
and ensure maximum public confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone in Belfast, an IRA member said he believed
the statement by the IRA leadership ``will be a tough sell to the
grass roots,'' and will be seized upon by republican dissidents as
evidence of ``going soft and selling out.'' But the IRA's Army
Council historically has never done anything it believes would
cause a serious split in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough was a diplomatic triumph for Blair and Ahern,
who had held meetings with the Northern Ireland parties in London,
Belfast, and Dublin over the last two weeks, seeking a compromise
from the IRA, which had refused to even discuss turning in weapons,
and unionists, who had demanded guns up front before returning to
the suspended assembly.
</P>
<P>
   So jaded were most observers here about the prospects of a
breakthrough that the talks organized by the two prime ministers
received only a fraction of the attention similar meetings had
generated last year when the peace process had stalled over the
fate of paramilitary weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But spokesmen for both Blair and Ahern insisted that was a
deliberate strategy. They said the high-pressure, high-profile
negotiations of last spring, last summer and last February
collapsed, in part, because there was too much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better to do it quietly,'' said a spokesman for Blair,
who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``When you have
high-profile discussions, you have parallel negotiations going on
in the newspapers and it creates difficulties for everyone
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Boston, where he has returned after a lengthy stay
in South Africa, O'Malley described Saturday's IRA statement as ``a
major breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who knew the history of the IRA, their traditions and
culture, knew they would never turn in weapons. This is about as
far as you can expect them to go,'' said O'Malley, who has written
extensively about Northern Ireland and has spent the last decade
facilitating meetings between politicians there and in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley said Ahtisaari's integrity is unquestioned, and that
Ramaphosa is ``one of the best negotiators in the world.'' He said
that if the IRA was threatened with a split because of its
leadership's willingness to have its weapons checked, Ramaphosa
could help mollify dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes to a split, they have one of the most skilled
negotiators in the world at their disposal,'' said O'Malley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
