<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      05-06 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIER'S CAREER ENDS AS A REIGN STARTS  
 LINKS WITH PAST DOLPHINS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There will be debates about his drafts _ did they produce stars
or busts? There will be debates about his eye for talent _ did he
go after the right free agents or not? When someone like Bobby
Grier leaves the game, a longtime football man who has survived
four owners and eight head coaches, his career goes under the
microscope, and everyone takes a turn with the scalpel, picking and
dissecting.
</P>
<P>
   Grier is someone many people outside of the Boston area may not
know. And when he was fired in his capacity as director of player
personnel by New England Patriots coach Bill Belichick last week,
it made little news around the country, in direct contrast to the
retirement of San Diego general manager Bobby Beathard, another
person who has dedicated his life to football.
</P>
<P>
   Grier's quiet disposition will not allow him to state what
should be said: that he was one of the league's most dedicated
workers and in a rarity in the sport, a man who was a scout, coach
and executive in a career that spanned almost three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Grier declined to comment on his dismissal. Others in the
Patriots organization were saddened by his firing and said Grier
was somewhat surprised because two years remained on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Grier's fate, however, was very likely sealed when Belichick
hired a close friend of his, Scott Pioli, a former director of pro
personnel for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   A further indication that Belichick has anointed himself the
Patriots' football guru came on the same day Grier was fired, when
Dave Uyrus, the team's director of pro scouting since 1997, was
also dismissed. Grier's son, Chris, a scout with the team, will
most likely be asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unpleasant thing for me to do,'' Belichick said in
a statement. ``I recognized that Bobby Grier has made significant
contributions to the New England Patriots over many years, in
various capacities, as has Dave Uyrus. I enjoyed a good working
relationship with Bobby in preparation for the recent draft, as I
did in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is unrelated to any specific event, performance
or personal relationship,'' Belichick continued. ``It is more a
reflection of my general feeling to proceed in a new direction with
regard to the structure and operation of our personnel
department.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some black coaches who were outraged that Grier, one
of the few black general managers in the National Football League,
was not allowed to exit with grace, the way Beathard did in San
Diego. That anger may be legitimate, or it may not, but overall
this has nothing to do with race. It is about control. Does a team
give final say on all personnel matters to the head coach or the
general manager?
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Grier reflects a continuing bitter argument on
the issue. Bob Kraft, the owner, decided to give Belichick final
say on all personnel matters. He is among the owners who believe a
head coach can simultaneously handle the duties of coaching and
evaluating college and pro personnel. Other owners and general
managers say it is impossible for a head coach to do both.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's decision to give Belichick total control may stem from
an incident that involved Bill Parcells, his longtime nemesis and
former coach. In the 1996 draft, Parcells wanted to pick defensive
end Tony Brackens while Grier wanted wide receiver Terry Glenn.
Kraft sided with Grier, and Parcells, frustrated with his lack of
total control, bolted for the Jets. The rift led to Parcells'
infamous statement: if he wanted to cook the meal, he should be
allowed to shop for the groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft may have wanted to avoid any potential future divisions by
consolidating the power behind Belichick, who joins the likes of
Atlanta's Dan Reeves, Seattle's Mike Holmgren, Denver's Mike
Shanahan and Minnesota's Dennis Green as coaches who have the last
word.
</P>
<P>
   Grier is deciding if he wants to stay in football or simply
retire. There have been rumors that the league office may be
interested in him. No matter what Grier does next, his reputation
as a hard and loyal worker is forever secure.
</P>
<P>
   LINKS WITH PAST DOLPHINS
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, coach Dave Wannstedt is doing something quite smart _
surrounding himself with familiar and friendly faces from the
Dolphins' past.
</P>
<P>
   At the April draft, Jimmy Johnson, the former head coach, gave
Wannstedt advice about choosing players. Last weekend Don Shula
made an appearance at a practice for the first time since he
retired in 1996. And Wannstedt turned the locker of retired
quarterback Dan Marino into a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all a part of the Dolphins organization,'' Wannstedt
said. ``When you say `Miami Dolphins' you think of Don Shula, Dan
Marino, Jimmy Johnson. I'm not intimidated by what this
organization has done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins have been a somewhat fractured franchise recently.
Shula and Johnson did not truly get along. Marino and Johnson were
also not great pals. And the team has endured its share of bad
off-field news, including the accusations against the former
running back Cecil Collins, who was accused of breaking into a
woman's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt is simply trying to create a more unified, even homey,
atmosphere, and having keen football minds around like Shula and
Johnson certainly cannot hurt.
</P>
<P>
   COWBOYS' $1 MILLION LINEBACKER
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cowboys linebacker Dexter Coakley signed a one-year
deal worth $1.27 million, becoming the first Dallas linebacker in
the 11 years Jerry Jones has owned the team to earn more than $1
million a year. ... Tampa Bay Coach Tony Dungy spoke to prisoners
in a Florida correctional facility, telling them to never give up
on life. They applauded Dungy, then questioned him. ``Why do you
keep running Warrick Dunn up the middle?'' one asked. ... In
minicamp last week, the Washington Redskins worked cornerback Champ
Bailey at wide receiver but do not plan on using him for punt and
kick returns next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
