<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VA-DULLES-REAL-NYT &LR;      05-06 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-DULLES-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NORTHERN VIRGINIA, THE DULLES TOLL ROAD IS THE PLACE TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Md.)   By JAMES R. HARDCASTLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESTON, Va. _ Rents for office space along the highway leading
from the nation's capital to Washington-Dulles International
Airport are soaring as companies involved in telecommunications and
the Internet compete for the limited space available.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies that have already emblazoned their logos on
new buildings along the road _ or soon will be doing so _ are
Andersen Consulting, British Telecom, Cable and Wireless, Nextlink,
Nextel, Oracle, Sprint, Teleglobe Communications, Time Warner's
Roadrunner unit and Winstar.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in demand are buildings along a 6-mile stretch of the
Dulles Toll Road from Reston to the airport, where signs can be
attached to buildings that are visible from the highway. About
129,000 vehicles, mostly driven by commuters, travel down the toll
road each day, and last year nearly 20 million passengers used the
airport. That figure represents a 25.8 percent increase from the
previous year, making Dulles the fastest-growing airport in the
world, the Airports Council International said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government owns the airport and the 16-mile-long
toll-free access highway leading to it. In 1984, the Commonwealth
of Virginia opened a 12-mile four-lane toll road sandwiching the
airport access highway, mostly for commuter use. It has twice been
widened, so there are now four lanes in each direction on the outer
edges of the access highway.
</P>
<P>
   The tolls range from 25 to 85 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many firms in the technology area are absolutely set on
getting toll road visibility,'' said Raymond Ritchey, an executive
vice president of Boston Properties, the developer that is erecting
a number of office buildings in the Reston and Herndon, Va., area.
Typically, the companies are three to 10 years old and are seeking
name recognition so that they can attract new employees and
investors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But visibility along the toll road doesn't come cheap: That
location demands a 10 to 15 percent rent premium, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Annual rents in new buildings along the toll-road corridor range
from $28 to $35 a square foot, including utilities, and are rising
rapidly, said David Ross, the president of Atlantic Realty of
Tysons Corner, Va., who together with Intertech of New York, is
developing a 27-acre mixed-use site adjacent to Reston Town Center.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Properties is asking for annual rents as high as $44 a
square foot for the top floor at 2 Freedom Square, a 16-story tower
proposed for Reston Town Center and expected to be completed in
early 2002. This compares with the $13 to $14 per square foot
charged for prime space in Reston in 1993, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Reston is a 7,400-acre planned development, founded in 1961, 18
miles northwest of Washington in Fairfax County. With a population
of about 55,000, it straddles the highways leading to Dulles
airport five miles away. The town of Herndon is on the north side
of the road between Reston and the airport. Reston has about 11.5
million square feet of office space, and Herndon about 6.1 million
square feet, according to market data from Grubb &AMP; Ellis, the real
estate services company.
</P>
<P>
   With the opening of the toll road in 1984, office development
exploded in the 1,000-acre strip zoned for commercial use on both
sides of the highway in Reston. Demand for new space collapsed in
the early 1990s and was not rekindled until 1996. Contributing to
Reston's growth as an Internet center is the fact that it is
crisscrossed by fiber-optic cable installed to serve national
intelligence agencies and America Online, whose headquarters is
just north of the airport. The CIA leases two 130,000-square-foot
buildings adjacent to Reston Town Center, and the National Imagery
and Mapping Agency leases a 400,000-square-foot building nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the telecommunications companies in the Reston area are
growing so fast that their management is hard-put to estimate what
their space needs will be. To guard against running out of space,
several have leased entire buildings and then have subleased the
surplus space.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle Service Industries, the Oracle Corp. unit that
specializes in data-management software for governments and
health-care and other companies, took another tack in dealing with
future expansion. It moved into its headquarters in a
210,000-square-foot, eight-story building on the toll road in
October, but it bought the 24-acre site for $14 million back in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Oracle Service Industries, which was then headquartered
just northwest of Washington in Bethesda, Md., had started to look
at possible sites in the Washington area that could accommodate
projected growth. It decided that Reston offered the best
combination of access, quality of life and proximity to its present
and future work force. Oracle is now building the second parking
garage on the site, which will serve a second office building that
is expected to open in November 2001. The site is zoned for a
maximum of 725,000 square feet of office space.
</P>
<P>
   As technology companies cluster along the toll road, legal and
investment services companies are following. Instead of leasing
whole buildings, they are taking floors of premium space in Reston
Town Center, the 80-acre mixed-use development that serves as the
toll-road corridor's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which opened in 1990 and has a Hyatt hotel and
upscale restaurants, is being developed by the Terrabrook unit of
Westbrook Partners of New York. Boston Properties is Terrabrook's
partner in building and leasing offices in the center, which will
be completed in 2004 if the current pace of construction continues.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest transaction last year in the corridor, Winstar
Communications of New York signed a lease for three buildings with
a total of 700,000 square feet being developed by Tishman Speyer in
its 170-acre Woodland Office Park along the toll road south of
Herndon.
</P>
<P>
   America Online opened its offices in leased space along the toll
road at Tysons Corner, about four miles east of Reston, in the
early 1990s. In 1995, AOL purchased a 235,000-square-foot
industrial building along the toll road and converted it to a
computer center. After outgrowing the space, AOL moved to new
headquarters it built along the extension of the toll road north of
the airport in Loudoun County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
