<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7758 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-DISARM-1STLD     05-06 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-DISARM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BREAKTHROUGH, IRA WILL ALLOW ARMS INSPECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to add comments from Clinton and to restructure: moves down
statement by McClartey; moves up Donaldson statement, to follow end
of 1st optional trim; restructures graf that follows to smooth for
pick up; moves up Ahern statements; adds 4 grafs to end with
comments from Clinton administration) 
By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Irish Republican Army offered Saturday to open its
secret arsenal of weapons to international inspection as a way of
meeting peace negotiators' demands that it ``completely and
verifiably'' put its arms beyond use.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from the underground organization was issued just
12 hours after Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and his Irish
counterpart, Bertie Ahern, made a public call to the group for such
reassurance, and it lifted hopes of ending the deadlock over
disarmament that has frozen progress on the Northern Ireland peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   It represented the first time the IRA had ever explicitly
addressed the crucial and emotive subject of disarmament, and the
proposals went further than even its main political representative,
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams, had said anyone could expect.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA also said it would reappoint representatives to the
independent disarmament commission that it broke contact with in
February, after Britain put the power-sharing government in Belfast
on hold after only eight weeks. Britain said it had based that
action on the failure of the IRA to make expected moves on weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Ahern said early Saturday that they hoped to restore
the home rule government by May 22, and they set out a new
timetable pushing back until June 2001 the deadline for a number of
measures intended to secure peace for Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   Those steps include the disposal of paramilitary weapons, a
greater reduction in British troops in the province, a new police
force with more balanced membership among Roman Catholic and
Protestant officers and new human rights provisions.
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, leader of the province's largest Protestant
party, the Ulster Unionists, greeted Saturday's statement with
customary wariness, but he said that it was welcome and promised
that his party would devote serious attention to it. If he decides
to go forward, Trimble will have to overcome the deep reluctance of
a significant minority in his party to re-entering government with
their Sinn Fein rivals without an actual handover of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said: ``It does appear to break new ground. There are
some quite positive elements in it.'' He added, however, that
``there are points that we want to tease out the meaning of.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, the head of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic
and Labor Party, was asked by the BBC Saturday what he would say to
Trimble, with whom he shared the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize. He
replied, ``I would say to David that I think this is what they have
been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Hume added, ``I think it is making very clear that the gun has
been taken out of Irish politics forever.'' He said the most
significant part of the statement was ``that they are going to put
their guns beyond use, and they are going to have that verified.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The quick sequence of events followed a familiar pattern in the
last years of the Northern Ireland peace talks where months of
stalemates, exchanges of accusations and gloomy predictions are
broken by spurts of activity that raise hopes of an end to three
decades of sectarian conflict that has cost more than 3,600 lives.
</P>
<P>
   David McClartey, an Ulster Unionist legislator from the
suspended assembly, said he and colleagues had emerged from a quick
meeting feeling encouraged by the IRA statement. ``I think there
was a degree of positivity about this statement which hasn't been
there before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Donaldson, the most prominent hardline dissident, made
it clear Saturday night that he would challenge any attempt by
Trimble to take the party back into government based on Saturday's
statement. ``It would appear that the proposals on arms fall well
short of what unionists have been looking for throughout this
process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, the Sinn Fein president, presented Saturday's statement
as a triumph. ``I know there have been some who have been skeptical
about whether republicans, the Irish Republican Army in particular,
were really interested in this process,'' he said. ``I think
today's statement shows that they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, Adams had been warning against expectations that
the IRA could respond to the demands for a statement on arms.
Saturday he said: ``This is not an abstract, historical kind of
thing, a dry turning over of the page. This is a life and death,
blood and sinew, emotional and painful step for the IRA to make
because it wants this to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern called on unionists to view Saturday's development
positively, saying that the statement ``had all the clarity that
people have looked for in the last 12 months or so. We've put a lot
of effort in to try to get this issue addressed,'' he said.
``People were skeptical that there would be an IRA statement; now
they can see it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that unionists who might be uncertain about whether to
accept the deal should remember how far Northern Ireland has come
since the peace talks began. ``There is now very little violence,
tourism is beginning to flourish and economic activity is moving
up,'' he argued. ``People want to move away from the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish, who are sponsors of the talks that
resulted in the April 1998 peace accord, announced that the
promised inspections of the arms dumps would be led by two
outsiders. They are Martti Ahtisaari, the former Finnish president
who served as a special U.N. peacemaker during NATO's war with
Yugoslavia over Kosovo last year, and Cyril Ramaphosa, former
secretary-general of the African National Congress in South Africa,
who played a major role in ending apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   The two men will report their findings to the independent
international commission that has been charged with supervising the
disarming of the paramilitary groups. ``The dumps will be
re-inspected regularly to insure that the weapons have remained
secure,'' the IRA statement said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The naming of the two foreigners as third parties continued a
tradition in the ongoing effort to end the conflict in Northern
Ireland where outsiders are called in to mediate the major disputes
between the province's two deeply distrustful communities. The head
of the disarmament panel is a Canadian, Gen. John de Chastelain,
and the broker of the original agreement was former Sen. George J.
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for de Chastelain said after Saturday's statement,
``The commission welcomes the recent development and looks forward
to re-engaging actively with the paramilitary groups to further the
peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland peace settlement is an attempt to balance
the desires of republicans, most of whom are Catholics, to draw
closer to and one day merge with the Irish Republic, with those of
the largely Protestant unionists, who want Ulster to remain part of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The original agreement and the various referendums and votes
that have followed have brought a large measure of political
stability to Northern Ireland and have drastically reduced levels
of violence. The IRA and the Protestant paramilitary groups have
maintained cease-fires for nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, the IRA said it would make sure that there was
no ``misappropriation by others'' of its weapons, a reference to
public concern over renegade guerrilla groups that object to the
cease-fires and seek to bring the whole peace settlement down with
acts of violence. One of them, the Real IRA, set off a car bomb
four months after the signing of the accord, in the town of Omagh,
killing 29 people and wounding more than 200.
</P>
<P>
   Progress has continually come to a halt over the issue of
disarmament, with unionists arguing that they cannot serve in
government with Sinn Fein as long as it has its ``private army,''
and republicans countering with the claim that the cease-fire
itself, which they call the ``silence of the guns,'' is sufficient
proof of their commitment to peace.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Sinn Fein leadership has tried to persuade the IRA to begin
disarming, and, according to British security sources, almost
succeeded in January but failed to get unanimous backing from
members of the ruling army council. Adams is known to fear
provoking any divisions in the ranks because of the republican
movement's history of violent fallouts.
</P>
<P>
   The republican reluctance to disarm stems from a feeling that
the IRA is an undefeated army and from a resistance to taking part
in any action that could be construed as surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure in recent months to get the settlement process up
and running again has been on Sinn Fein, but Saturday's statement
shifts the focus to the Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   At the last meeting of the party's ruling council, Trimble kept
his leadership with only 57 percent of the delegates' votes after
being challenged by an uninspiring former grand master of the
militant Orange Order, who played on widespread resentment in the
party over what critics view as Trimble's excessive willingness to
make concessions to republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA statement made a rare positive reference to unionists,
saying, ``The full implementation, on a progressive and
irreversible basis by the two governments, especially the British
government, of what they have agreed will provide a political
context, in an enduring political process, with the potential to
remove the causes of conflict, and in which Irish republicans, and
unionists can, as equals, pursue our respective political
objectives peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement Saturday, President Clinton called the
IRA's disarmament announcement a ``significant step'' and a cause
for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``These developments offer renewed hope to the people of Norther
Ireland that politics will once and for all be pursued through
exclusively political means,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official said Saturday's
announcement is the first time the IRA has put out a ``clear and
unequivocal'' statement about moving forward with the peace effort
and renewing ``confidence'' in the accord by permitting inspections
of its secret weapons stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a sense that it's going to begin, and they are
committed to go all the way through,'' said the official, who is
familiar with the peace effort. ``Both of these things have been
the keys to getting a real clarity about what the IRA's intentions
are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
