<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-CATAMARANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 1,000-MILE TEST FOR OFFSHORE BEACH CATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.C.)   Herb McCormick is editor of Cruising World magazine.  
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Awash in the nautical lexicon are a sea of oxymorons _ small
gale, light anchor, jumbo shrimp _ that at first take seem like
contradictions, but which upon further review are marvels of
concise description. But Monday, off Fort Lauderdale, Fla., a race
begins that is centered around a waterborne concept _ offshore
beach catamarans _ that many find impossible to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right, you hear people talking about offshore beach
cats and you wonder what doesn't belong in there,'' said the
45-year-old multihull whiz Randy Smyth, laughing. ``Probably the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by phone from Florida, Smyth, the five-time winner and
defending champion of the Worrell 1000, should know. For when the
20-odd two-person crews launch through the morning surf in Fort
Lauderdale to start the first of 11 legs en route to Virginia
Beach, Smyth will be the odds-on favorite. When asked how many
times he has competed in the Worrell, his answer is short: ``Enough
to know better.''
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, the 1,000-mile race is the frenzied dream
child of the Virginia restaurateur Michael Worrell, who has seen
the event evolve from a four-team, nonstop torture test among
like-minded maniacs, in 1974, to a highly organized affair that
includes dedicated shoreside crews that follow the sailors up the
coast; an international fleet of top-flight competitors; and
copious safety rules and precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are still a lot of great sailors who look at this
event and say it's not their cup of tea,'' Worrell said. ``But for
a certain cadre of hard-core sailors, this is their thing.''
</P>
<P>
   One must be hard-core to even contemplate a Worrell, because as
the fleet hopscotches its way up the Atlantic seaboard _ each leg
averages about 100 miles, and two of them are overnight runs _ the
air and water temperatures plummet while the odds of being ambushed
by a weather front thundering off the coast shorten.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, that confluence occurred at the worst possible time
and place: Cape Hatteras, N.C. Even though there were no injuries,
one boat was dismasted and three more sustained significant damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thousand-fathom line is very, very close to Hatteras,''
Worrell said, referring to the undersea shelf delineating deep and
shallow water in the Western Atlantic. ``These huge ocean swells
come roaring in from the sea and literally trip over Hatteras.
That's why the surf is so huge there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cape Hatteras aside, landing and taking off in rolling surf is a
threat to hulls, rigs and rudders at every checkpoint. But for
Smyth _ a two-time Olympic silver medalist in Tornado catamarans _
the nighttime legs bring the most fearful conditions. ``You're
zipping along, it's pitch black, and there are all sorts of shoals
out there, many of which move around and are uncharted,'' Smyth
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're flying at 20 knots and, bingo, you hit a six-inch
spot of thin water. The boat stops but you just keep on flying.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the Worrell is being contested in identical Inter 20
catamarans, which should boost the hopes of another Florida
skipper, Brian Lambert, a class veteran. But Smyth's deck seems
stacked; his crewman, Matt Struble, a former Michigan State
pole-vaulter, is also the reigning Inter 20 North American
champion. Ultimately, Smyth believes his greatest threat will come
from the Australian duo of Brett Dryland and Rod Waterhouse, who
finished second last year and have raced in a combined 17 Worrells
between them.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum are the half-dozen or so teams
entering their first Worrell 1000. Among the rookies are the
event's first woman skipper, Susan Korzeniewski of Liverpool, N.Y.,
and her crew, Davis Murray of St. Thomas, Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Korzeniewski, a champion Hobie 16 sailor, has realistic
expectations. ``We haven't practiced a lot in this type of boat,''
she admitted. ``It's going to take a little time to get up to speed
with some of the other teams. But we hope to sail respectively and
stay with the fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   In Murray, a boatbuilder and seasoned offshore sailor, she has a
game partner with similar aspirations. ``Our goal is to race hard
every day and sail smart without breaking anything,'' he said. ``If
we come in last and that's the best we can do against these guys,
we'll be very happy with that. What we really want to do is finish
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who avoid breakdowns and misfortune are due to arrive in
Virginia Beach on May 20. ``Electrical storms, whales, sharks,
military exercises, fishing piers _ there're all kinds of things
waiting out there,'' Smyth said. ``It's kind of a fun race because
it's a new story every day. And none of us know what it's going to
be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
