u s BC-BBN-PHILLIES-FAILURES     05-06 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-FAILURES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILS ARE BURROWING BUT NOT SURRENDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theirs was a belated arrival, but the Philadelphia Phillies
finally made an appearance in the 2000 season last week.
</P>
<P>
   Until they peeked out from their realm of repose, sort of like
the groundhog on Feb. 2 in another Pennsylvania town, the Phillies
seemed as if they might just take a pass on this season. Until they
erupted for 14 runs and a second successive victory against
Cincinnati, the Phillies had shown no evidence of life. Their vital
signs were as comatose as their third-base coach's signs were
unproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't hit,'' general manager Ed Wade was saying as
the Phillies began their game against the Reds last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wade was explaining his team's putrid first month. ``It's
nothing more complicated than that,'' he said. ``Collectively,
we've gotten off to a horrible start offensively. It's tough to win
games when you're not scoring. Looking back at our club coming out
of spring training, you wouldn't figure it was a team that couldn't
score runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The night before, the Phillies had defeated the Reds for only
their third victory in the last 15 games, and they had raised the
National League's lowest batting average by .003 to .230. But even
after they erupted with a 21-hit barrage before Wade's eyes and
sent the team average soaring to .242, they remained the league's
lowest-scoring team.
</P>
<P>
   They also had ended their series with the struggling Reds and
began a three-game weekend series with the Atlanta Braves, whose
lead over them (12 games, entering Saturday night's game) is the
largest margin in the major leagues. A groundhog couldn't have dug
a deeper hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go back and change a 7-and-17 April,'' Wade said.
``We realize what that means. We can't do anything about it. I
think some people would like us to throw up our hands and
surrender. But we don't do that. Our guys aren't made that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Players, however, have a tendency to try to do too much when
confronted with rampant adversity. A player in an 0-for-18 slump
tries to get three hits in one at-bat. Players on a team with a
seven-game losing streak try to hit a six-run home run. Teams
distant from first place try to make up six games in one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been impressed upon them that we can't approach
it that we're going to make up for 7-17 in four days,'' Wade said.
``We have to continue to play the game the right way and hopefully
mount up more wins than losses. We need a couple teams in our
division to slow down a little bit. I know they ran off a 15-game
streak, but the Braves hopefully can't do that another time or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Phillies had harbored thoughts of upending the Braves
this season, they can put their efforts to better use, like trying
to catch the Mets, who have had their own nightmarish experience
since winning nine in a row, a streak that now seems a little less
remote than ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies played their first 23 games without Curt Schilling,
their No. 1 pitcher and the soul of the team. Last season the
Phillies resembled a wild-card contender until Schilling went on
the disabled list with an ailing right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   They were four games back in the wild-card race when Schilling
pitched for the last time before going on the disabled list in
August. When he returned in September after a nearly four-week
absence, they were 13{ games behind the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Returning last week following off-season shoulder surgery,
Schilling is viewed as a catalyst who can stir the team. Wade sees
that possibility, but he expressed a cautionary note.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are trying to link our problems in the latter stages of
last season with the problems at the beginning of this season,''
the general manager said. ``I think they're unrelated.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even Schilling could repeatedly have won games in which the
Phillies scored no more than three or four runs, an offensive
development that occurred in 19 of the first 25 games. With
basically the same hitters, the Phillies last season finished in
the top half-dozen teams offensively.
</P>
<P>
   But they went to Atlanta last in total bases and only one home
run ahead of the lowest home run total. They had been last in home
runs before Mike Lieberthal and Rob Ducey connected against the
Reds on Thursday for the team's first home runs in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Lieberthal, Doug Glanville, Bobby Abreu and Alex
Arias were the team's .300 hitters. Right now only Abreu is on that
level. A five-hit game Thursday raised Glanville's average by 34
points to .284. Liberthal's three hits pushed him to .258. Arias
was hitting .088. Others not contributing offensively included Ron
Gant (.222), Desi Relaford (.211) and Kevin Jordan (.159).
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good and continue to feel good about our lineup,''
Wade said. ``The best alternative we have right now is to be
patient. The wolves at this point have a lot of suggestions about
knee jerk reactions we should be having. But you can't make
decisions based on knee jerk reactions. The dumbest thing we could
do is be impatient and make moves based on what has happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
