<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-FOLLOWUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN KILLING OF DOCTOR ELUDES SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The search continues for James C. Kopp, the 45-year-old fugitive
indicted last June in the killing of Dr. Barnett A. Slepian, an
obstetrician who performed abortions in the Buffalo, N.Y., area.
</P>
<P>
   Slepian was killed inside his home in Amherst, N.Y., by someone
shooting from woods behind his house.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp appears on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list, with 29 aliases,
including Clyde Swenson, Enoch A. Guettler, P. Anastation and
Atomic Dog. He has also been sought for questioning in four
nonfatal sniper attacks on doctors who perform abortions in western
New York, and is wanted by Canadian officials in the 1995 attack on
Dr. Hugh Short, of Ancaster, Ontario, who was shot in the right
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news for the public is that the FBI, if it has a
strength, it's in locating fugitives and apprehending them,
especially if they're on the top 10 list,'' said Paul Moskal, a
special agent with the bureau in Buffalo. ``Ultimately, all of
those people are caught, with rare exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is offering a reward of up to $50,000 for information
leading directly to Kopp's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as likely on the corner on 42nd Street as he is in
Tokyo,'' said Moskal, who added that Kopp had been arrested abroad
in the past. ``This is the type of investigation where tens of
thousands of man-hours are invested, and in that sense we're a day
closer, every day that goes by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
