<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOWNHOUSE-REAL-950(3T     05-06 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWNHOUSE-REAL-950(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BUYERS BRING TOWN HOUSES BACK FULL CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By NADINE BROZAN c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeffery and Faith Larsen of Greenwich, Conn., have
been anticipating life in an empty nest, now that their children
are 14 and 15 years old. So they have decided to move to a new
nest. That nest, it turns out, will be an old one, a four-story
town house on East 62nd Street built in 1870 and expanded to five
stories in 1919.
</P>
<P>
   When the Larsens move in _ the target date is January _ they
will join a small but impassioned band of city dwellers who are
bringing town houses full circle back to their origins as
single-family homes after decades of being subdivided into
apartments. Projects like the Larsens' require stamina,
determination and more than likely a great deal of money.
</P>
<P>
   Larsen, the chief executive of ICor Brokerage Inc., a
four-month-old company that offers business-to-business online
brokerage services, said that he paid more than $2 million for the
house and estimated that the renovation costs would probably hit
$1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 10 studio apartments in the building and a duplex
that once housed an art gallery were demolished. In addition, the
facade will be rebuilt to its original state, a step that has the
required approval of the Landmarks Preservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really ugly, and now it will be really beautiful,''
Larsen said. ``I want to bring it back to the look and feel of a
block in a historical district.''
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the house to exactly what it was in 1870 is an almost
impossible task, though. ``Because a fifth floor was added, we
can't make it look exactly is it did, so we must be innovative,''
Larsen said. ``We are putting on a mansard roof with two dormers.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Larsens have seized a rare opportunity is clear, but
just how rare is impossible to measure.
</P>
<P>
   No definitive figures exist for the number of town houses in the
city. A computer analysis of city property records by The New York
Times, using descriptions that would suggest town houses, found
4,400 buildings in Manhattan and 15,200 in Brooklyn that fell
within the parameters. Those figures were arrived at by counting
the number of residential buildings of three to five stories on
lots less than 25 feet wide. The buildings had no more than 12
units and were built before 1905, after which few town houses were
constructed in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Other estimates vary widely. For example, figures taken from the
city's Department of Finance by the Real Estate Board of New York
put the total number in Manhattan at 1,386, a mere sliver of the
borough's residential market, which includes 200,000 co-ops and
65,000 condominiums, according to the board's estimate. For
Brooklyn, Steven Knobel, the executive vice president of Mitchell,
Maxwell &AMP; Jackson, an appraisal firm, said, ``Our guess is that
there are somewhere around 45,000 town houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, according to the Real Estate Board of New York, 145
town houses changed hands in Manhattan. The single-family town
house is experiencing something of a renaissance, a trend that has
been accelerating in recent years, brokers say, bringing back a
style of gracious living in buildings that don't soar to the sky
and dwarf their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a time the single-family house in Manhattan became almost
extinct,'' said Tim Desmond, a town house broker at Stribling &AMP;
Associates. ``In the 1920s, with the advent of big apartment
buildings, apartment living came into vogue, and houses went out of
favor. That left housing stock that was chopped up into four to 12
units.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the apartments in buildings with three or more units
were subject to rent control or rent stabilization, limiting the
profits the landlord could reap. After 1986, they lost even more
luster as investments, when federal tax laws were changed to
significantly restrict their use as tax shelters. But other factors
were emerging to make the single-family house a diamond on the
market, although sometimes a diamond in the rough. Those factors
include a soaring economy, a dwindling supply of large prewar
co-ops and a growing resistance to what some prospective buyers
describe as the tyranny of co-op boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are again in a gilded age in New York, but unlike the
turn of the century, there is no vacant land, so people are
reconverting these buildings,'' said Frederick W. Peters, president
of Ashforth Warburg Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers say their clients have numerous motives. ``With a
different perception of safety in the city, people who might not
have thought of doing it 10 years ago are today, and people who 10
years ago might not have been in a position to utilize the entire
house are now,'' said George W. van der Ploeg, a vice president at
Alice F. Mason Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a trend toward larger, more opulent houses,'' he
said. ``A town house is probably 5,000 square feet, bigger than
most apartments, and that makes a statement. In addition, some
people chafe at the concept of the co-op board having so much
power, from approving the buyer to approving the renovation.''
</P>
<P>
   And, many brokers say, compared with the square footage of a
co-op or condominium, a town house offers a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a lot more bang _ or space _ for the buck,'' said
Barbara Fox, the president of Fox Residential Group. ``Say you live
in a 20-foot-wide house that is 60 feet deep. For five floors, that
gives you 6,000 square feet. You would have to have an immense
apartment to equal that. Plus you probably get a garden in the
back, you may get a terrace and you can improve the roof and have a
sun deck. It is not cheap, but it is a lot cheaper than getting the
same interior and exterior space in a co-op.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The trend seems to have no geographical limits. In Manhattan,
houses are being snapped up on the East and West Sides, uptown and
downtown, from Harlem to Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no undesirable neighborhoods for this in
Manhattan,'' Peters said, but he did agree that there are some
blocks that command special attention. ``Notoriously, the most
desirable street is 70th Street between Park and Lex. It is famous
for some incredibly beautiful buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, where town houses have long been dominant in some
neighborhoods, the market is surging as well. Brooklyn Heights, the
oldest landmarked district in the country, commands the highest
prices, $2 million to $3.5 million, said Christopher Thomas, a
senior vice president and the sales director for William B. May in
Brooklyn. ``And we are doing a lot of business in neighborhoods we
didn't go into three years ago, like Fort Greene and Clinton
Hill,'' he said. In Fort Greene houses are going for $700,000 to $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Magnett, the president of the Corcoran Group in
Brooklyn, said: ``Prices are soaring here, though they are nowhere
near those in Manhattan. A vice president of Juno.com and his wife
who are now renting on the Upper East Side are buying the
first-ever million-dollar brownstone in Clinton Hill and converting
it to a single-family.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand has led, not surprisingly, to bidding wars. Richard
Steinberg, managing director of Ashforth Warburg, put a
single-family house at 161 E. 62nd St. on the market last month for
$3,150,000. ``Within four hours I had three full-price offers,'' he
said. ``We went to sealed bids and sold it over the asking price by
$150,000.'' Should the deal fall through, he said he had two backup
offers in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg is also the representative for Premiere Properties of
Manhattan, a company owned by a British investor, Michael Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew there was a shortage in the New York market of
high-end single-family homes, so two years ago he decided to buy
multiunit buildings as long as they could be delivered vacant,
renovate them and resell them,'' Steinberg said. ``So far, he has
done two, including a building on East 66th Street that he bought
for $3,750,000 and sold for $7,250,000.''
</P>
<P>
   From the buyer's perspective, the single most critical
consideration in the decision to convert a town house that contains
four or more units is whether those apartments are occupied and
whether they are rent-controlled or rent-stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants who are not protected by rent control or stabilization
can be legally evicted at the end of their leases. To evict a
rent-controlled tenant, the owner must obtain an order from the New
York State Division of Housing and Community Renewal verifying the
owner's compelling need for the apartment and then must start court
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Stabilized tenants are protected, too, but Housing Court can
authorize evictions at the end of the lease if the apartment is to
be occupied by the owner or an immediate member of the family.
People 62 and over or people with disabilities may not be evicted
from a stabilized apartment on the grounds of the owner's need for
it unless the landlord provides a comparable apartment nearby at
the same or lower rent.
</P>
<P>
   With all these conditions standing as potential barriers to the
full conversion of a town house, many prospective buyers make it a
condition of sale that the building be empty, and many sellers make
payments to tenants to move.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mark, a general contractor who bought a 10,000-square-foot
mansion at 8 E. 77th St. for himself and his family of six, did
that when his bid on the building was accepted. ``When we bought
it, it had three or four tenants, and our contract was subject to
its being vacant,'' he said. ``We gave the seller six months and
then could have broken the contract. There was one holdout, so we
gave another three months, but they had to pay him $250,000.''
Houses converted to single-family status by previous owners or ones
that can be emptied by the sellers are worth significantly more
than those with tenants in residence. Sara Gelbard, a senior vice
president of the Corcoran Group who specializes in Greenwich
Village, Chelsea and Gramercy Park, recently closed on a house in
Chelsea with a duplex apartment and two floor-throughs for
$1,750,000, a sum she described as unusually low. ``Two doors down
there is a house on the market that has been renovated for
single-family with an asking price of $2.6 million,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My recommendation is never to buy anything with the intention
of kicking people out,'' she added. ``Offer either to buy them
another place or settle with them. You have to be creative.''
</P>
<P>
   She gave this example: ``Several years ago, I had an owner who
bought co-ops for two tenants, relocated them and is allowing them
to stay for life, and then he will own the apartments.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the wispiest of hints that a building may be for sale is
likely to strike fear in the hearts of tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting more calls all the time over the issue of owner
occupancy,'' said Michael McKee, associate director of the New York
State Tenants &AMP; Neighbors Coalition. ``We are seeing more and more
eviction cases being brought against tenants in rent-regulated
apartments in smaller buildings. Some of those times it's because
landlords want to occupy the entire building and other times
because they simply want to charge market rents.''
</P>
<P>
   McKee would like to see the laws amended so that rent-stabilized
tenants would have the stronger protections rent-controlled tenants
have, and he favors limiting the number of apartments a landlord
can take over. ``That would make people safe in their own homes,''
he said. ``There are cases when the owners act in good faith and
other times when they use occupancy as a ruse. They simply have a
relative live there for a few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Although empty buildings fetch higher prices, there are still
some owners who want _ or need _ the income generated from tenants
to help carry the mortgage or provide a sense of security. And some
brokers, Paul Massey, the president of Massey Knakal Realty
Services, among them, contend that ``buying such a building is
absolutely worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you value a building with a stabilized tenant in it and you
put a value on the same building were it to be empty, there is a
huge leap in value that allows you to pay the tenant,'' he said.
``If there are three or four tenants, you get more of a break.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate: ``The average multiple-unit dwelling in the city
sells for about $200 a square foot,'' he said, ``and the average
single-family residence for $500 to $1,300 a square foot.''
</P>
<P>
   When San Orr, an investment banker, and his wife, Sarah, an
owner of Babybox.com, a Web site that sells baby gifts, began
looking for a town house last year in the Park Slope and Fort
Greene sections of Brooklyn, they considered renting out part of
whatever they bought for the income it would generate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we decided not to, because we found a house where we
didn't need the rental income,'' said Orr. He would not divulge the
price he paid for the house, which is in Fort Greene. ``We have two
dogs, and we are expecting a baby in August,'' he added, ``and we
wanted not to have to worry about people coming and going. We also
felt that we would best be able to restore the initial character of
the building in its entirety rather than just using one
apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once a building is empty, the process of transforming it into a
single-family residence can take a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though in some ways it is more difficult to do a house than an
apartment,'' said Mark, who has been the contractor on several town
houses and is now doing his own, ``logistically it is easier. You
don't have to have the plans approved by the co-op board or the
building's architect, only by the city. You can work 10 hours a
day, not 5.''
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the project helps, too. ``In any renovation, the
more you do, the easier it is,'' he said. ``Trying to make new work
blend into existing conditions is the most difficult. If you
totally gut a place, it may cost more and take more time, but it is
less difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But one buyer's difficulty may be another buyer's nightmare.
Whenever he hears a building described as having ``good bones,''
Warren Pearl, a contractor who has been renovating town houses in
Manhattan for 30 years, becomes suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients and architects say that all the time,'' he said, ``and
what they don't realize is that they are all wrecks, simply because
they were converted a long time ago, probably with improperly done
structural modifications to accommodate all those kitchens and
bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl estimates a renovation will cost 50 percent of the
purchase price. ``If you pay $6 million, it will cost approximately
$3 million,'' he said. ``In terms of square footage, high-end
residential jobs are about $300 to $400 per square foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Renovating town houses in New York City presents unique
challenges. ``You have problems here you don't see anywhere else in
the country,'' Pearl said. ``You have attached houses and sometimes
one wall is not attached. Manhattan is filled with underground
streams, which is why buildings often lean, and there are flooding
problems people aren't even aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the more serious flaws he encounters are joists damaged by
walls, plumbing and electric lines added when the house was
converted to apartments, and water damage from inadequately caulked
bathtubs and leaky radiators and roofs. ``People don't understand
the scope and extent of work that is necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly proved true for a woman who moved into a house on
the East Side with her husband and three children in February. It
was not until the building had been gutted during a year of
construction work that they were told that the joists _ the beams
that hold up floors and ceilings _ were collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing I learned from the experience was to
remain calm when the surprises come,'' said the woman, who spoke
about her experiences only on condition that her name not be used.
``The biggest thing for me was to tackle the problem of the day,
and every day there were new problems, electrical, plumbing,
joists. If you don't like dealing with problems, this is not for
you.'' Michael Hourihan, a former tax lawyer who is now commercial
real estate developer, has converted two brownstones in Manhattan.
He is still recovering from a structural surprise. ``I usually live
in the houses myself for a while before selling them, but my most
recent one I ended up selling quicker than I had anticipated,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Hourihan bought a house on East 69th Street that
had been built in the 1870s and converted to a rooming house in the
1930s. Gutted by fire about 30 years ago, it was rebuilt into a
four-family residence. When he bought it, Hourihan intended to
carve out a duplex for himself, retain two rental apartments to
carry the mortgage and then take over the whole building for his
own use in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the process of doing cosmetic renovations in the rental
space, we discovered structural flaws that were a result of the
renovation after the fire, stuff even an architect and engineer who
came through couldn't see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The necessary repairs would have been so extensive, he said,
that ``once I had to do that level of rip-out, I decided it would
be too costly to put in kitchens and bathrooms for the apartments
only to rip them out in a few years when I wanted to change it to a
single-family,'' he said. Instead, he skipped right to the final
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved in for a short while, but it didn't make sense to be
paying the heavy mortgage, so I put it on the market around
Thanksgiving, and it will close on April 25.'' He bought the
building for $1.4 million, he said, and spent $350,000 in
renovations that would have cost far more had he not been in the
business. He is selling it for $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the house the Orrs bought in Brooklyn needed
relatively little repair. Since it only contained one rental
apartment, whose kitchen and bathroom they have already removed,
they did not have to gut it. ``It was renovated with new electrical
and plumbing systems in the late 1970s, so the renovation is mainly
to change it from a two-family to a one-family house rather than
major structural changes,'' Sarah Orr said.
</P>
<P>
   They took down a 25-foot wall that had been put up to keep the
stairway private and are installing 10-inch steel beams to prevent
floors from sagging.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the woman who is renovating the East Side town house
is moving into the home stretch, picking out knobs, putting up
house numbers at the front door, installing lighting fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected crises are now a memory. ``I thought my house
would be nice, but I never thought it would be this beautiful,''
she said. ``It's great having a basement for storage, having a
place to put bills, having a basketball net in the backyard, being
able to open the door and just walking outside without going into
an elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is one break she has yet to make. ``You definitely
miss the handyman,'' she said. ``So I have hired the handyman from
my old building to come in one Sunday a month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
