   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ Does Elian Gonzalez, as a six-year-old,
have a right to assert his desire for an asylum hearing over the
contrary wishes of his father? In what some legal scholars call a
complex dispute typically involving state court family law, the
appeals court in Atlanta will have to see how federal immigration
law applies in such a dispute. Story will explore motions by three
parties (Justice Department, Miami relatives and Elian's father) as
well as any similar cases from the past, including the 1980 dispute
involving a 12-year-old boy who wanted to stay in the United States
against the wishes of his parents, who wanted to return home to
Russia. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON _ As relatives of Thomas Jefferson and alleged slave
mistress Sally Hemings gathered Saturday at Monticello, a newly
formed group vowed to discredit evidence that the nation's third
president fathered children by Hemings. One of the Thomas Jefferson
Truth Foundation's first orders of business will occur today, when
its members try to exclude Hemings' kin from the Jefferson family's
annual business meeting. Will get reaction from Hemings'
descendents and officials of the Thomas Jefferson Memorial
Foundation, which in January endorsed the genetic and historical
evidence of Jefferson-Hemings children. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA _ Nowhere in Georgia is an industry's reliance on
illegal immigrants more obvious than in the 20 south Georgia
counties where the Vidalia onion harvest is in full swing. Two
years ago, after the INS raided a farm during harvest time,
complaints from congressmen gave illegals a temporary amnesty. That
underscores a historic trend: we tend not to enforce laws against
illegal immigrants in economic boom times when business needs
immigrant labor, but INS deports workers en masse in recessions and
depressions. In the last 2 years, with unemployment at its lowest
in 30 years, INS has all but stopped arresting illegals except at
the borders. (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA-SIDE _ The US is loathe to arrest illegal immigrants
working in hard-to-fill jobs in booming economies. But when a
recession or depression makes jobs scarce, the government rounds up
illegal immigrants by the thousands. Nowhere was this trend more
obvious than in May 1998, when the government let illegal workers
harvest the $90 million Vidalia onion crop in SE Georgia. This
13-inch sidebar accompanies a larger story about the importance of
illegal labor to the onion crop. The sidebar traces the link
between economic conditions and enforcement of immigration law this
century. In today's roaring economy - Surprise! - arrests of
illegals are way down and workplace raids hardly ever happen.
(Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   (Editors: This package is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week.
The layout is now available)
