<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ At a minute past midnight on May 1, when Time
Warner yanked ABC stations from its cable systems in seven cities,
stories about the dispute opened the TV evening news in tens of
millions of U.S. homes. If not for a timely truce, the blanket
coverage all but ensured that President Clinton would have soon
stepped into that corporate cat fight. (Andy Glass is a columnist
for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I started following editor
Sam Malone's way of handling snake scenarios. He told readers he
was the ``Live Snake Editor,'' and if you wanted your picture made
with a snake, it had to be brought in alive. This drastically cut
the number of photo requests. There aren't many people besides
zookeepers and the occasional member of one of those
serpent-handling churches who are willing to hold a live snake long
enough for a photographer to get the camera focused and the picture
made. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
