<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-NY-SENATE-LIBERALS-     05-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-SENATE-LIBERALS-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND CLINTON COURT LIBERAL PARTY IN SENATE BID
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to delete art advisory: No photo will be sent with this
story.)  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani returned Saturday to what has
been a solid source of support throughout his political career _
the Liberal Party, and its leader, Raymond B. Harding _ and asked
for the party's backing as he sets his sights on the U.S. Senate.
But Hillary Rodham Clinton also appeared before the same group,
arguing that her views were more in touch with the Liberal ideology
than were those of the Republican mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Clinton each spent an hour in private at a
Manhattan hotel with the policy committee of the Liberal Party, the
first step in the party's move toward choosing its nominee by June
6. This usually barely noticed rite for candidates in New York drew
a bustle of attention Saturday, evidenced by a lineup of cameras
and security officers, reflecting the state and national political
implications that have become attached to the decision by Harding's
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not my first time being interviewed by the Liberal
Party,'' Giuliani said as soon as he left the meeting, grinning as
he noted his longstanding ties with one of the smaller parties that
his advisers believe could provide the winning margin in this
election. When a reporter asked if he considered Harding a close
adviser, Giuliani responded: ``I consider Ray Harding to be more
than a close adviser. I consider him a close personal friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pointed to the same friendship in remarks that seemed to
lower expectations on her chances of winning the support of a party
that almost invariably backs the Democratic candidate in statewide
elections. ``I'm well aware of the mayor's relationship with Mr.
Harding and the party,'' she said. ``But I came today to ask for
their consideration, based on the issues that I'm talking about in
this campaign and what I would do in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton is aware, the only time a Democrat running for
statewide office won without the cross-endorsement of the Liberal
Party occurred in a Court of Appeals race in the 1970s, when judges
to the state's highest court were still elected. Giuliani's aides
noted this fact in a handout they distributed to reporters just
before Clinton left the committee meeting to talk with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party has been pivotal to Giuliani's electoral
success as mayor, not so much because of the relatively few votes
he drew on the Liberal line, but because the party's support has
allowed him to blur his ideological designation, making it more
comfortable for some Democrats to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   Harding was able to steer the endorsement to Giuliani with
relatively little difficulty during his three races for mayor. But
this high-visibility Senate race has presented the party with a
particularly complicated choice, and it has put Harding in the
position of choosing between the potential future of the
55-year-old party, on the one hand, and his loyalty to a man who is
a close friend and a source of jobs for his family and party, on
the other.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual display of public dissension, some Liberal Party
members said in recent days that they would oppose backing
Giuliani, arguing that it would be a betrayal of the party's
philosophy to send another Republican to the Senate. And if he
backs Giuliani, Harding risks losing a presidential candidate:
Clinton's aides have been pushing Vice President Al Gore to decline
the Liberal Party line if the party backs Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides said Saturday that he might well accede to
Clinton's request. They said he would put off the decision as late
as possible, giving him time to assess whether he needs the Liberal
Party to win in New York (right now, his aides believe that he does
not), as well as to see whether Giuliani stays in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ragone, a spokesman for Gore's campaign, said that the
vice president was now beginning a closer look at the thicket of
independent parties in New York, and that he would ``consider the
endorsement'' of any party that shared his views. However, Ragone
added, ``the vice president is a strong supporter of Hillary
Clinton, and our campaign will do everything we can to elect her
the next senator from New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Harding's friends have tried to convince him that the
Liberal Party's standing might be permanently damaged if it
supports Giuliani and he defeats Clinton this fall. And the
advantage that Harding now enjoys by having Giuliani in City Hall
ends in a year even if the mayor loses, because he will not be
allowed to run for a third consecutive term.
</P>
<P>
   Harding has told friends that he will delay a decision as long
as possible, in no small part to see whether Giuliani indeed stays
in the race. The mayor learned recently that he had prostate
cancer, and he has said he will decide whether he can stay in the
race based on his medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party endorsement has proven important to Giuliani's
political success to date, but Giuliani may be taking some risks in
aggressively seeking its support in this race. For one thing,
taking the Liberal Party line means giving up the Conservative
Party line, said the Conservative Party chairman, Michael Long, who
argued that it was ideologically dishonest for one candidate to run
on both lines. The Conservative Party historically has been as
critical to statewide Republican candidates as the Liberal has been
to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did today _ with Hillary no less _ they both went and
knelt at the altar of Ray Harding, who in fact gave us Bella Abzug,
John Lindsay and Mario Cuomo,'' Long said. ``Doing that, that sends
a clear signal to the world that he wants to run with Al Gore, he
wants to keep the Liberal tradition, and I don't know who the real
Giuliani is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition, running as the Liberal candidate is likely to
complicate Giuliani's efforts to portray Clinton as a liberal. That
has been the central thrust of his fund-raising appeals, and
statewide Republican candidates have, for a decade, routinely
attacked their Democratic opponents as liberal, a tactic that has
proven particularly effective upstate.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani was asked Saturday whether he considered Clinton a
liberal, he demurred. ``I think it would be overly simplistic to
put labels on people,'' he said. ``I think you can say somebody is
a liberal on something and moderate on something else and
conservative on something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning the question to himself, Giuliani said: ``I think about
me, they would say, he's conservative on economic matters, he's
conservative on law and order. But he's moderate, and possibly even
liberal, on social issues. It would depend on the part of the
country you're in. In New York City, I'm often seen as very
conservative. I travel south and west, I'm seen as very liberal. I
like that, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding greeted Clinton politely when she arrived at the meeting
at the Intercontinental Hotel, but, one participant said, asked no
questions, sitting quietly in the back of a room that was thick
with cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Clinton share positions in their support of
abortion rights, gay rights and gun control, as Harding noted after
the meeting. But Clinton pointed out some differences between them
on issues of concern to Liberals, including her opposition to
Giuliani's school voucher program, and her criticism of the large
tax cuts being advocated by Republicans in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Asked her view of what the Liberal Party stood for, she
responded: ``Based on what I know of it and what I've read about
it, it stands for a sort of positive, progressive tradition in New
York politics, and the kind of issues we've talked about. Very
strong support for public education. Strong support for child care
and working families. Strong support for a minimum wage increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Giuliani and Clinton news conferences were somewhat
raucous. At Giuliani's, a state Democratic Committee employee had a
hand-held video camera to record the mayor's remarks, a routine
tactic used by Republicans and Democrats to gather material for
future advertisements. But Giuliani's City Hall press secretary,
Sunny Mindel, stepped in front of the Democratic aide, held up a
sheet of paper in front of the camera, and stood on tiptoes as the
aide raised the camera. Mindel, who does not work for the campaign,
stopped when she noticed that a reporter was taking notes on what
she was doing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
