<HEADER>
A7773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-KENTUCKY-DERBY-48     05-06 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KENTUCKY-DERBY-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUSAICHI PEGASUS ENDS THE FAVORITES' DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Fusaichi Pegasus, the $4 million colt named
for the flying horse of mythology, came flying through the
homestretch at Churchill Downs on Saturday to win the 126th
Kentucky Derby by a length and a half over Aptitude. He became the
first favorite to win the race since 1979, when Spectacular Bid
captured the race.
</P>
<P>
   The bay son of Mr. Prospector confirmed the powerful signs that
he supplied while winning four of his first five races, and he did
it with style, finesse and power while Kent Desormeaux left his
whip at his side and let the horse render one more virtuoso
performance.
</P>
<P>
   And he glowed through this one, moving relentlessly from last
place in the pack of 19 on the first turn until he bolted into the
lead as they turned for home while 153,204 spectators at Churchill
Downs, the second-largest crowd in Derby history, roared in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus ran the mile and a quarter in 2:01 for the
fifth-fastest time in Derby history, and he had to turn on the heat
against a full cast of exceptional rivals. Aptitude, who ran third
behind Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood Memorial in New York three
weeks ago, finished strongly, with Impeachment third and More Than
Ready fourth.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 126th Derby and one of the most richly endowed with
quality horses and story lines. It was run on a summery afternoon
at Churchill Downs before the huge crowd that approached the race
record of 163,628, reached for the 100th Derby in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders, movie stars and celebrities of all stripes
stood out in the throng for America's ``most exciting two minutes
in sports,'' and for a personal look at the ``flying horse'' that
dominated the clamor leading up to the race.
</P>
<P>
   But besides Fusaichi Pegasus and his Japanese owner, Fusao
Sekiguchi, who paid $4 million for the colt when he was a yearling,
drama unfolded on all sides. Sekiguchi, the 65-year-old
entrepreneur, appeared at his Barn 41 on the day before the Derby
after flying from Tokyo, and said through an interpreter: ``I
believe that to win is what he is destined to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Derby, though, was packed with other theatrical scripts:
Captain Steve, named for Capt. Steve Thompson of the Louisville
police department; The Deputy, winner of the Santa Anita Derby,
conditioned by Jenine Sahadi, who was the 10th female trainer with
a horse in the Derby and was aiming to become the first to win it;
Marlon St. Julien, the first African-American jockey in the Derby
since 1921; China Visit and Curule, the two horses from the Middle
East sent halfway round the world by Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid
al-Maktoum of Dubai in his continuing effort to extend his racing
empire and his unusual training methods; and 88-year-old Harold
Rose, the breeder, owner and trainer of Hal's Hope, hoping to
fulfill his dream of turning a stable of mostly claiming horses
into the home of a Kentucky Derby winner.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The tone was set on the day before the Derby when the Kentucky
Oaks drew a record crowd of 106,156 for a race that dates back to
1875 for the inaugural season of racing at Churchill Downs. And
many in the crowd suspected they had seen an omen of leniency by
the stewards, who kept everybody waiting in the starting gate for
an unusually long time while crew members tried to coax Vivid
Sunset to stay in her stall.
</P>
<P>
   The race was finally won by Secret Status, who overcame a
stumbling trip down the backside and rallied bravely under Pat
Day's handling to score by six and three-quarters lengths. But the
question hung over the track for the Derby: Would the stewards take
a similarly soft attitude in case Fusaichi Pegasus balked or
cavorted when entering the gate?
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus originally was supposed to break from stall No.
16 in the gate, but Globalize was scratched after his stable pony
bit him on the leg and everybody moved one slot toward the rail.
Still, the first 14 filled the main gate, and the next five took
their positions in the auxiliary gate.
</P>
<P>
   They still were four horses short of the record number of 23 who
started the centennial Derby in 1974, but they matched the total of
19 reached last year, when the one-time claiming horse Charismatic
won for D. Wayne Lukas. It was the fourth victory for Lukas in his
career as America's most successful trainer, a man who started 35
horses before the 126th Derby and who won the race four times.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lukas and Bob Baffert between them won the Derby five
times in the last five years as the dominant trainers in the Triple
Crown. But this time, Baffert arrived in Louisville with just one
horse, Captain Steve, although Lukas entered three: High Yield,
Commendable and Exchange Rate.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked about the likelihood that he could win the
Derby for the fourth time in six years and the fifth time overall,
Lukas replied: ``We're not exactly 30-1. We're going over there
with a pretty good arsenal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
