<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 05/06/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 6, 2000 -- O'CONNOR-REMEMBRANCES --
Sandi Merle, 59, who describes herself as ``just a Jewish kid from
Paterson, N.J.,'' counted Cardinal John O'Connor as her best
friend. Merle met the cardinal at a reception given by the New York
Board of Rabbis, when he first came to New York. She was moved to
tears by an anti-abortion comment, and he comforted her. ``Five
years ago he absolutely changed my life around,'' says Merle who
had experienced clinical death after heart surgery and needed to
understand why she had been spared. ``Instead of going to my rabbi,
I went to my cardinal. ``He helped me find what it was I was spared
for and to have a more active role in Jewish-Catholic dialogue.''
(Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 6, 2000 -- HOLOCAUST-RESCUER --
Magdalena Gibaudo, 79, and Walter Marx, now 74, a Jewish teen-ager,
who fled the Nazis in 1943 in Borgo San Dalmazzo, a small town in
northwest Italy, meet once again after being reunited for the first
time last year at a ceremony in the town for a monument he had
helped pay for, dedicated to the many Italian townspeople who aided
Jews driven there during the war. Gibaudo, was the young Italian
woman who saved his life by hiding him from German soldiers and
helping him escape. Gibaudo and Marx at Kennedy International
Airport getting ready to spend some time together in New York. Marx
now lives in Roslyn, N.Y. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 6, 2000 -- O'CONNOR-MOURNERS-3 -- A nun
prays for the late Cardinal John O'Connor at St. Patrick's
Cathedral, Saturday. As the second ofthree days of Masses and other
services for O'Connor took place, thousands of mourners from across
the New York region and the nation filed solemnly into the great
cathedral to pay their respects to the Archbishop of New York.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 6, 2000 -- O'CONNOR-MOURNERS-2 -- A set
of hands in prayer and a photo remembering the late Cardinal John
O'connor at St. Patrick's Cathedral, Saturday. Thousands of
mourners from across the New York region and the nation filed
solemnly into St. Patrick's to pay their respects to the Archbishop
of New York. As preparations for the cardinal's funeral on Monday
went forward, there was no word from the Vatican on the selection
of his successor, although speculation continued to focus on Bishop
Edward M. Egan, the head of the Archdiocese of Bridgeport, Conn.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 6, 2000 -- O'CONNOR-MOURNERS-1 --
Thousands of mourners from across the New York region and the
nation, including many children and disabled people, converged on
funereal-draped St. Patrick's Cathedral on Saturday to pay their
last respects to Cardinal John O'Connor with prayers, hymns and the
ancient rites of Roman Catholicism. Saturday's events, the second
of three days of Masses and other services leading to the funeral
and burial in the crypt under the altar at St. Patrick's, gave
striking testimony once more to the admiration and respect that
millions accorded the cardinal, America's most influential Catholic
leader. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PITTSBURGH -- May 6, 2000 -- OLY-MENS-MARATHON -- One of
America's top distance runners, a two-time Olympian at 10,000
meters, or 6.2 miles, Todd Williams has been trying to make his
body calloused to the marathon distance of 26.2 miles. Williams has
used what he calls a ``psychotic'' training regimen for a
marathoner by running on a treadmill in a 75-degree basement at
home. Williams, 432, in the lead, in the finals of the 5,000 meter
run at the USA Outdoor Track &AMP; Field Championships in Indianapolis
in late April. (Mary Ann Carter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WESTMINSTER, Md. -- May 6, 2000 -- MILLION-MOM-MARCH --
Carole Price, 37, has sought gun control since her son John, on
button and amongst other pictures, was shot to death. John, then
13, was shot in the head two years ago in a Baltimore suburb by a
9-year-old neighbor showing off his father's 9-mm pistol at
playtime. With two remaining children to protect, Price soon became
one of the organizers of the Million Mom March, scheduled for May
14 in Washington. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ATLANTA -- May 6, 2000 -- TEAMSTERS-OVERNITE-2 -- Almost
half of the 200 workers at the Overnite Transportation Co.'s
Atlanta terminal are on strike. So far the six-month war looks like
a draw, a very painful draw, that has many Teamsters struggling to
pay their bills, while the union's adversary, Overnite, has had its
bottom line hammered. Workers walking a picket line outside of an
Overnite terminal in Atlanta. (Michael A. Schwarz/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ATLANTA -- May 6, 2000 -- TEAMSTERS-OVERNITE-1 -- Despite
their families hard times, many workers have vowed to hold out as
long as it takes in the grueling Overnite Transportation Co. strike
that has become James P. Hoffa's biggest labor battle in his first
year as Teamsters president. So far the six-month war looks like a
draw, a very painful draw, that has many Teamsters struggling to
pay their bills, while the union's adversary, Overnite
Transportation Co., has had its bottom line hammered. Workers
walking a picket line outside an Overnite terminal in Atlanta.
(Michael A. Schwarz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ST. LOUIS -- May 6, 2000 -- DRUGS-SAVINGS-2 -- Sharon
Lewis, an Express Scripts employee, a large pharmacy benefit
management company in St. Louis, labels drugs for the company's
mail-order prescription service. Express Scripts also arranges
discounts from pharmacies for members of managed care plans.
Pharmacy benefit management companies, or PBM's, which handle drug
benefits for 200 million Americans, are being assigned an important
role in widely discussed proposals to add a drug benefit to
Medicare. (Bill Stover/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ST. LOUIS -- May 6, 2000 -- DRUGS-SAVINGS-1 -- Pharmacy
benefit management companies, or PBM's, which handle drug benefits
for 200 million Americans, are being assigned an important role in
widely discussed proposals to add a drug benefit to Medicare.
Barrett Toan, chief executive of Express Scripts, a large pharmacy
benefit management company in St. Louis, says ``the company must
collect transaction fees from employer health plans to cover the
costs of processing claims.'' (Bill Stover/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BETHESDA, Md. -- May 6, 2000 -- SCI-GENOME-FRACAS -- The
10-year project to decode the human genome is entering its end
game, but the high goal of unlocking the secrets of human heredity
is ending in a fractious exchange of claims and countercharges.
Within a few weeks, both contestants in the genome race plan to
declare victory, but in different terms, each already judged
imperfect by the rival team. Dr. Francis Collins, head of the
National Institutes of Health unit of the Human Genome Project, the
rival team. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 6, 2000 -- HAMPTONS-HAVENOTS-3
-- After several moves in the East Hampton area, Lee and Tina
DeGraaf, with their daughter Shannon, found a place 45 minutes
away, in Flanders, N.Y., which they snagged a year ago for $900 a
month. ``We couldn't find a house there,'' says DeGraaf, a marina
worker. Like many other year-round residents in East Hampton, he
and his wife have spent their married life moving from one rental
to another. (Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 6, 2000 -- HAMPTONS-HAVENOTS-2
-- The Hamptons has always been a place of contrasts: of workers
and wealth, of masons and millionaires, of carpenters and kings of
dot-com. But within the last year the gap has grown. In East
Hampton, where the average house price is $573,725, more than
triple the national average, even salaries as high as $110,000 no
longer guarantee a two-bedroom, two-bath bungalow with Montauk
daisies and a picket fence. A large home under construction in East
Hampton. (Chris Maynard/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 6, 2000 -- HAMPTONS-HAVENOTS-1
-- In the Hamptons, as well as in the United States' wealthiest
enclaves and resort towns, many of those who were born here, along
with others who arrived more recently, are being forced out.
Housing in East Hampton is increasingly available only to the
highest incomes and trailer park homes will give way to a park as
large homes are built in the area. (Chris Maynard/The New York
Times)
</P>
