<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT0507-C     05-06 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Boxing out' redefined by Heat-Knicks
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This much is clear: The New York Knicks and Miami Heat
share a love/hate relationship. That is, the teams hate each other
and love to beat each other.
</P>
<P>
   And so, we have the one true, lasting and ferocious rivalry in
the NBA. Opening bell in the Eastern Conference second-round series
is Sunday afternoon in Miami. Watch out for the blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what happens in a New York-Miami series?'' Toronto
Raptors coach Butch Carter added. ``First of all, there will be a
fight. And who's going to stay on the bench in a fight?''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting has been a part of the teams' intense recent playoff
history. There was one three years ago when the Knicks' Charlie
Ward was picked up and thrown to the floor by P.J. Brown at Miami
Arena, leading to the Knicks having six key players suspended for
leaving the bench. The Heat won that series.
</P>
<P>
   The next year was the Larry Johnson-Alonzo Mourning ``fight'' at
Madison Square Garden. The combatants, former teammates in
Charlotte, squared off and threw punches, but none landed. They
were suspended; the Knicks won the series.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, while there was not a fight, there were all kinds
of physical confrontations not seen in other series. Finally, in
Game 5 of the first round, the eighth-seeded Knicks upset the No.
1-ranked Heat on Allan Houston's last-second shot in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   All of this animus began when Pat Riley abruptly bolted from the
Knicks in 1995 to become president and coach of the Heat. The
dislike and desperation to defeat the other has not declined since.
In fact, it's only heightened with all the drama, words and
seemingly endless hype. It's some sort of karma that this is the
fourth year in a row they meet in the playoffs (New York's won the
last two).
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have to beat them to get over a mental hump?'' Riley
asked rhetorically. ``Or is it to make my life better? Or is it to
make my peace of mind, you know, so I can wake up in the morning
the next day? Or when I'm 65 years old I won't have any nightmares?
No. I'm past that now.''
</P>
<P>
   That may or may not be true. The Knicks have ended the Heat's
season the past two years, and since Riley has not gotten his team
to the Eastern Conference finals in four years with the Heat, the
pressure is at a crescendo. That's just one storyline in a series
that has them all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, for one, wishes it was just about
playing the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be a war,'' Van Gundy said, mockingly. ``Geez,
Louise. Everybody out there should use their mute buttons. You
could play the same things from last year and the year before.
They're the same stories. We don't even need new newspapers. We
just take the newspapers from last year. No one's going to write,
`Mourning's been unbelievable, Mashburn's had a great year. What is
everybody doing not talking about Mashburn for an All-Star? They're
going to repeat Mourning-Ewing, Houston's shot, Van Gundy-Riley,
Van Gundy brothers, Hardaway shot. ... God. Overdone, overhyped,
and I can't wait till the game starts so we can focus on this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Heat beat the Knicks three of four. One of the
wins was with all-star enter Alonzo Mourning out with an injury and
the other was with Olympian Tim Hardaway sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway missed the first-round series against Detroit with a
foot injury, but Anthony Carter filled in nicely in the three-game
sweep. Hardaway practiced with the team late last week and said
he's about 75 percent healthy and will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tim's experience is so irreplaceable,'' Mourning said.
``He's been there. He knows how to run this team a little better
than A.C. right now and A.C. knows that.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks know Miami is desperate to get to the conference
finals, and to get there through New York would be most gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're the monkey they're trying to get off their
backs,'' New York guard Latrell Sprewell said. ``We're the team
they're looking for. After what happened to them last year, I know
the revenge factor and all those things are going to play into it
and we have to be aware of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
