<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PUBLIC-TOILETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE IN NEW YORK MAY SEE PLACES TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the wintry city smells of roasting chestnuts and
pretzels melt away into summery scents of cut grass and open
sewers, New Yorkers are still lacking that luxury that many smaller
cities take for granted: the public toilet. But that may be
changing shortly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the city rolled out its plan for a 20-year franchise
for 3,300 bus shelters, 430 newsstands and 30 toilets. A handful of
design firms spent millions of dollars in pursuit of the franchise,
part of it trying to create the prototypical New York toilet. But
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani suddenly canceled the project in June 1998,
saying the city would prefer to ``encourage competition and greater
design variation.''
</P>
<P>
   And citizens stood by, crossing their legs and clenching their
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great study in how a city can fail to solve a
serious problem when given an excellent cost-free solution,'' said
Doug Lasdon, executive director of the Urban Justice Center, which,
under the name of Legal Action Center for the Homeless, issued a
report 10 years ago about the need for public toilets. ``How come
we can't do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Peter Vallone, the City Council speaker, is hoping to help
deliver the bathroom pass to end all bathroom passes _ 100 toilets
for the city, at $50,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rising from the failures of the administration's plan to put
in pay toilets, the speaker has put in $5 million in our budget,''
said Jordan Barowitz, Vallone's spokesman, who added that the
speaker had just come back from Europe with snapshots of himself in
front of various public potties from world capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the mayor will agree with this plan, and we will be
negotiating this with him in the upcoming budget talks,'' Barowitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to use city money to build the toilets, instead of
creating a public restroom franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can build them ourselves,'' Barowitz said, ``and worry
about selling advertising and franchises later, so the public can
have some relief.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
