<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT &LR;      05-06 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL AND LAKERS LEAVE KINGS IN THEIR REARVIEW MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ These last-minute script changes can be murder.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it was supposed to happen: The Los Angeles Lakers,
the team that dominated the regular season, ending it with a 67-15
record and generating talk of a National Basketball Association
dynasty in the making, were supposed to wave sweetly and then run
down the Sacramento Kings like a tractor-trailer passing a speed
bump.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Lakers handily won the first two games of the
three-of-five-game series in the first round of the NBA playoffs,
then fumbled the third in the final quarter and never even held the
lead at any point during the fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Los Angeles was forced to face the possibility that
its team might be eliminated from the playoffs in the fifth and
decisive game by a speed bump that turned into a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Lakers were able to call in some script doctors
_ Los Angeles is full of them _ and do a little tinkering with the
final act. The result was a fairly thorough roto-rootering of the
Kings before a raucous crowd at the Staples Center, 113-86.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers controlled the game from the opening tip and led by
10 points or so throughout most of the first half, extending their
advantage to 15 points just before the half.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, it only got worse for Sacramento, with the lead
inching up to 20, then 25, then 30, finally peaking at 37 before
Lakers coach Phil Jackson sent in the bench, and the lead finally
dwindled to a mere bone-crushing 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers led about any way you looked at it, with a field-goal
average of 52 percent to the Kings' 34 percent and 54 rebounds to
the Kings' 35. Even the Lakers' bench performed well against the
Kings' more touted bench, scoring 42 points, just one less than the
Sacramento reserves. Chris Webber led the Kings with 20 points, but
he was the only team member in double digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty confident about it, but you don't know until
they throw up the tip and there you go,'' Jackson said after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The man who took much of the heat for the Lakers' losses in
Games 3 and 4 was center Shaquille O'Neal, a leading contender for
the league's most valuable player award. The Kings double- and
triple-teamed him and effectively blunted his shooting game,
leaving him with point totals of 21 and 25, around half of the 46
points he scored in the opening game.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday night's victory, however, O'Neal was back in full
form, scoring 32 points and grabbing 18 rebounds. He said afterward
that it was a call from his father that got him back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of down after the two bad games I'd had,'' O'Neal
said. ``My dad said to me, `You idiot, you always play bad in
Sacramento. Just play good at home.'''
</P>
<P>
   After that, O'Neal said, he replayed the season in his mind and
realized that he had in fact always played below par in Sacramento.
It gave him confidence going into the final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was being kind of hard on myself,'' he said. ``Thank
God for home-court advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that all of the talk of an MVP award had also
played a part in O'Neal's fifth-game renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds are pretty good he's going to be named MVP in the
next two weeks, and he wanted to prove to people that he was worthy
of that,'' Jackson said. ``And he did that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory certainly provided a boost for Los Angeles, which
had been on full smug alert following the team's initial two
victories followed by panic after its two subsequent losses.
</P>
<P>
   This was not at all how it was supposed to happen. The Kings had
gone into the playoffs as the eighth-seed _ the Lakers were seeded
No. 1 _ and had ended the regular season 23 games behind Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers knew they had history on their side in the final
game. Only twice since the five-game playoff matchups began in 1984
had a No. 1 seed fallen to a No. 8 seed in the first round. But the
Lakers had also had a history of bingeing on defeat in the
postseason in recent years, losing four games in a row to San
Antonio last year and four in a row to Utah the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if we didn't bring our A-game, we were going to be
making history,'' O'Neal said after Friday night's victory. ``And
we didn't want to make history that way. So we brought our
A-game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will next face the Phoenix Suns in the second round
of the playoffs, beginning Sunday with a two-game homestand at
Staples Center. The Suns have lost to the Lakers each time they met
this season, but Jackson was cautious Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the whole story,'' he said. The Suns had improved
as a team throughout the season, he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal agreed. ``They're scrappy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Lakers' critics have pointed out that the team had
dominated the recent season so handily that it had yet to undergo a
close brush with disaster, the kind of character-building exercise
that a team often needs to reach the championships. Perhaps,
Jackson said, this series with Sacramento was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care when it had to happen, but I've been talking all
year about how we needed a trial by fire,'' Jackson said.
``Certainly, a team has to have that at some point to develop the
mettle and grit and to be able to sustain the poise, direction and
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us a lot of push, and we needed that as a basketball
team if we're going to advance.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal added, ``This was a good test for us. We just have to
remain dominant at home and then win some on the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
