<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PENNSYLVANIA TO LOUISVILLE, FANS LOVE IT  
 NBC POISED TO TAKE OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL AMDUR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Beth Branthoover always wanted to see the
Kentucky Derby in person. So Tom and Bettyjean Branthoover of Black
Lick, Pa., gave their daughter a special present for her 41st
birthday Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove eight hours to get here for the Derby,'' Beth said
outside the Churchill Downs clubhouse as she held a ticket for an
early race. ``I can't believe I'm here. I've always watched it on
TV. I just never thought I'd see it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what she wanted,'' said her father, who had bought VCRs
and other electronic equipment as presents in the past and then
decided on a special occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Beth also brought her own distinctive style to a social setting
that is always No. 1 in fashion. The owner of a designer shop,
Beth's Custom Leather, in the small town near Pittsburgh, she wore
her own creation topped with a straw hat covered with peacock and
rooster feathers and a mink band. A lucky horseshoe from childhood
adorned the hat.
</P>
<P>
   According to surveys by Churchill Downs several years ago, 60
percent to 70 percent of the Derby fans are from out of town. Their
impact on the local economy is substantial: In the most recent
estimate, done in 1990 by a University of Louisville economist, the
figure was around $90 million. Today it is probably closer to $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a big day for the locals as well. Calvin Watson, 35,
is district manager of a Family Dollar store two blocks from the
track. He has been a Derby regular for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has horses and I've been around horses all my
life,'' said Watson, who was sipping a mint julep, the official
drink, with a colleague, Robin Brickey, who had hitched a ride to
the track because she did not want to fight the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Brickey grew up on a farm in Sandy Hook (population 1,500),
where, she said, ``we always had horses,'' and still do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great-great-grandparents won the Derby a long time ago,''
Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   The horse? ``I can't remember,'' he said. ``That's before me.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC Poised to Take Over
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's telecast of the Derby marked the end of a long run
for ABC, which had been the Triple Crown network for many years.
Next year, the Derby will move to NBC as part of a five-year Triple
Crown package.
</P>
<P>
   Race officials hope the switch will provide more promotion and
exposure for the Derby, which has had declining ratings in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Derby, however, falls in the middle of the National
Basketball Association playoffs, which are also televised by NBC.
Churchill Downs officials realize their telecast may be sandwiched
around NBA games _ for better or worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
