<HEADER>
A7786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HEAT-RILEY-2TAKES     05-06 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-RILEY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WINNER WITHIN, A LEGACY IN QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When people ask if he needs to beat the Knicks to feel
whole again _ if he needs another title so he can escape the awful
purgatory of this unforgiving game _ Pat Riley answers with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I felt that way,'' he said. ``But as you get older,
you get out of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are laments. Some run almost as deep as his resolve to
win a championship for the Miami Heat. As he prepares for the
fourth consecutive Heat-Knicks playoff crucible, he has let go of
countless tough losses, moved on.
</P>
<P>
   But one still haunts him. Game 7 of the 1994 finals, in which he
came so close to bringing the Knicks their first title in more than
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really made a coaching mistake,'' Riley said after practice
on Friday afternoon. ``I stayed with John for too long. I did. I
say that now because he was so cold. At the time, he was also
pressing.''
</P>
<P>
   John Starks shot for two for 18 against the Houston Rockets that
June night, chucking up long jumpers, trying in vain to shoot
himself out of a slump, shot after missed shot after missed shot.
Believing in Starks to a fault, Riley failed to pull the shooting
guard he had plucked from obscurity and molded into a starter. The
Knicks went down, 90-84.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do it over again, the guy that I would have given
some quality minutes to and I didn't was Rolando,'' he said of the
more experienced Rolando Blackman. ``I always to this day regret
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always look back and think about it because we were so
close. It was right there, for the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head. A rueful smile passes across his tanned,
lined face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up three to two. Just got to win one game. Couldn't
get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years later, I wouldn't let a man miss six in a row
without giving him a rest. I'll probably live to regret saying
that, but I think you just learn as you go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Resting his right arm against a pushed-in wood-stained bleacher
_ the tiny diamonds from his 1987 Lakers world championship ring
gleaming _ the 55-year-old coach had just finished practice. He
began to reflect on his career, retirement, a championship lost and
paradise almost found.
</P>
<P>
   The Starks story has a parallel. The Heat is flawed _ two
consecutive first-round playoff eliminations before this year _ yet
Riley believes in his team's ability to win a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the franchise is in good shape,'' he said. ``We have a
great arena and more season tickets. But it really comes down to
winning. Can we win a championship? And that's where, to this
point, I've failed in New York and I've failed here.''
</P>
<P>
   Failed? He will become only the second coach in history to
record 1,000 victories. In 18 years, his teams have won their
division 16 times. No coach has won more playoff games (149). He
won four championships in Los Angeles. He resuscitated franchises
in New York and Miami. He said that was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both those franchises benefited, but they didn't get
what they thought they were going to get from me,'' Riley said.
``And that bothers me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me, it just really bothers me. I'd like to leave my
career with one more title and leave some other players with one,
so when they look at me, they say: `You know what? You're the real
deal. You know what? They were right about you.' They can't say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been chastised for not upgrading the Heat's roster with
younger players. Riley the coach does not buy the argument that his
loyalty to players has undermined Riley the team president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the coach should say: `Look it, it's time. Now,''' he
said. ``I know this team and when it's time to move in another
direction with some guys, and I also know when it's not. And I
don't think last year's bounce by Allan Houston was the time to
say, `This is a bad deal here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great, great group of guys. Hard-working, good
men. Are they good enough to win? That's going to be the ultimate
tragedy if they're not. Because they'll know they're not good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat players say Riley has mellowed; he is not as critical
and listens more often to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still Riles, the coach who gets more out of you than
anyone,'' Dan Majerle said. ``But there is a personal side you get
to see now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley has been characterized as a tortured soul, someone who
can't leave his home or fathom life without another championship
ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to fear the consequences a lot more, but I don't
anymore,'' he said. ``I have had nothing but good things happen to
me in my career. I've had some downs. Leaving New York was a very
difficult time. A lot of people thought it was very easy for me to
leave. The departure was one that was very ugly and consistent for
a couple of years. I never wanted that to happen anywhere in my
career. But it did.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The conversation shifted toward retirement. Last summer, he
signed a contract extension through 2004-5, but admitted on Friday
that he thinks about leaving the game sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might not even make it through that,'' he said. ``I'm at the
beginning of the end. I don't feel the same pressure I felt when I
went to New York. I don't feel the same pressure I felt when I
first came here. I know the ship is good.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has managed to spend more time with his wife, Chris,
and their two children, James, 15, and Elisabeth, 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``James is a don't-do-sports kid,'' he related about his
children, who were adopted as infants. ``He's a computer kid and a
musician. And Elizabeth is very well-rounded. They're good kids.
Like any other kids, we have our problems. It's hard to parent
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``James had a difficult time with being James Riley, because he
would get kidded. But he's over it. Elizabeth sort of likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they don't want to share me with anybody. They get annoyed
when people come up and ask for autographs.''
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted to being somewhat superstitious. One of the
rumors around New York was that he and Chris had their Greenwich,
Conn., home exorcised when he coached the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exorcised?'' he said. ``My wife is a devout Christian. She
used to go in with holy water to Boston Garden. When she went to
Madison Square Garden, she did the same thing, made sure this place
was blessed for `my husband.'
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we didn't have an exorcist come in. My wife is strong
enough to do that herself. Her and her mother would walk around
with the Bible and go in the closet. They'll take care of the
exorcism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley plans to write a definitive book on coaching and something
on pro basketball. Beyond his best-selling motivational books, he
has sold six screenplays with the help of professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't been made yet, but I produced the work,'' he
said. ``I've sold them to all of the studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a half-decent thinker. I'm going to get a ghost
writer, help me organize it. And I'm going to continue to speak. I
like that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his scripts is titled ``The Seventh Game.''
</P>
<P>
   A renowned storyteller in the locker room, he still uses drama
and metaphor to spur the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked a little bit today about `U-571,''' he said,
referring to the World War II submarine film that he took his
players to see last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my players the other day didn't know the meaning of
it. You cannot make an analogy with `U-571' and the Heat and what
that whole movie is about?''
</P>
<P>
   He answered his own question, talking about what he believed was
the first message of the film: leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first officer was expecting a command,'' he said. ``He
didn't get it and he asked his captain why. And the captain said,
`You're a good leader but you can't command this fleet.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Why? I'd give my life for these men.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `I know you would, but you don't know what it takes in
warfare to be able to go up to another man and make him give his
life, order him to give his life for the sub.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't do that. He was faced with that dilemma at the end
of the movie. He was faced with the dilemma of ordering one of the
sailors down to release the dormant torpedo in the tube.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the Miami Heat has been depth-charged two years in a
row,'' he said, his voice rising. ``We have a dormant torpedo tube.
And we have to have a sense of urgency of opening this damn thing,
OK? Do you guys understand that? In other words, do your job. Be a
sailor. Do your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley collects himself. He takes his arm off the bleachers and
steps back. ``That was my symbolic message,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
