<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-SONS-TEAMS-KAN &LR;      05-06 2264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONS-TEAMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY'S SPORTS FUTURE IS IN THE HANDS OF YOUNGER GLASS AND
HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY COVITZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Perhaps no issue concerns Kansas City sports
fans more than the future of their highest-profile professional
teams. The truth is, the future may look a lot like the present.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Hunt and Dan Glass, understudies within the Chiefs and
Royals empires, embody the probable next generation of ownership in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt and new Royals owner David Glass,
their second-oldest sons are passionate about sports. Like their
fathers, they are humble and introverted, buttoned-down and
businesslike. And they share their belief in Kansas City as a
sports town.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Glass, 40, was appointed president of the Royals last week
and finds himself taking a crash course in the business of
baseball. David Glass, 64, also named other family members to the
board of directors, including his wife, Ruth, sons Dan and Don and
daughter Dayna Martz.
</P>
<P>
   ``When David had an interest in purchasing the club,'' Royals
general manager Herk Robinson said, ``one of the things he made
very clear was if he would purchase the club, it would be as a
family project, so the commitment could be extended well beyond his
lifetime. That commitment has never wavered.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Hunt, 35, joined the board of the Chiefs last year, and is
showing a greater interest in the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the elder Hunt began transferring his ownership
of the Chiefs to his four children, Lamar Jr., Clark, Sharron
Munson and Daniel. The children now have 98 percent ownership,
divided equally among them, and Hunt and his wife retain 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is most actively involved in Hunt Sports Group, whose
interests include the Chiefs, the Wizards and the Columbus Crew of
Major League Soccer, and a small share in the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clark has an excellent business mind and excellent affinity
toward business,'' said Lamar Hunt, 67. ``I wouldn't say he's
working for me _ he's working with me and trying to keep me out of
trouble, which isn't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are perils when sons take over for successful
fathers, no matter how well and how long they are groomed for the
roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched second generations of lots and lots of families,
and it's difficult,'' said David Glass, who helped build Wal-Mart
into the world's leading retail chain. ``Some master it, though,
and do it very well, and they get respect and recognition in their
own right after a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inevitable that anyone who is following someone else is
judged a little more harshly.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball and business defined Dan Glass' formative years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a sports junkie, and Dan and his brother were
both raised that way,'' David Glass said. ``I got them interested
in baseball at a very young age, and they developed a love for the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Springfield, where his father was general manager
of Consumer Markets, a grocery chain, Dan and his brother
accompanied their father on pilgrimages to St. Louis in the late
1960s and '70s and watched their beloved Cardinals play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou Brock and Bob Gibson were my favorites,'' Dan Glass
recalled. ``I'd listen to the Cardinals broadcasts, and when my dad
got home I'd give him a play-by-play of what happened. `Brock got
on, stole second; Ted Sizemore bunted him over to third....' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Glasses moved to Bentonville, Ark., in 1976 when David Glass
joined Wal-Mart as executive vice president of finance. Instead of
attending college, Dan Glass entered Wal-Mart's management training
program. He spent five years with the chain, first in Fayetteville,
Ark., and then as an assistant manager in Tahlequah, Okla., Tulsa,
Okla., and Carbondale, Ill., before deciding he could do more with
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Glass enrolled at Southwest Missouri State and after two years
transferred to Drury College in Springfield, where he earned a
degree in business administration.
</P>
<P>
   He also received an education from two of America's most
successful businessmen, Wal-Mart founder Sam Walton and his father,
who in a 24-year career with the company rose to president and
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Sam Walton, I saw how people-oriented he was,'' Dan Glass
said, ``how motivational he could be around people, just by being
himself, but at the same time, getting his work done. Nobody could
quiz a store manager more without them knowing it than Sam could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up with my dad, I was never intimidated by the boss
guys coming in or the guy in the three-piece suit. I always felt I
had the knack for being able to relate to the guy in the
three-piece suit as well as the blue-collar guy. Sam taught me a
lot about discipline and how to relate to people, and how you treat
them fairly and make them a part of everything and a part of the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Those lessons learned make David Glass confident in Dan's
ability to run the Royals one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of potential,'' Glass said. ``You really benefit
if you like what you're doing and care a lot about it. He really
likes the baseball side of it. The business side of it...he won't
enjoy it as much as the baseball side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan has a lot to learn, he knows he's got a lot to learn and
that's the best part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Chiefs game Clark Hunt can remember was on Christmas
Day 1971. He was 6 years old when the Chiefs lost a playoff game
27-24 in double overtime to Miami in the longest NFL game ever
played and the last game at old Municipal Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas had a lot to do with it,'' Hunt said of the memory.
``The length of the game had a lot to do with it, and I
specifically remember the missed field goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs went 15 long years without appearing in another
playoff game, while Clark's schoolmates in Dallas reveled in the
success of the Cowboys in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting from the time I was old enough to be picked on at
school, the Chiefs certainly struggled,'' Hunt recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The razzing turned Hunt into a fierce competitor, and he won the
respect of his classmates as a star athlete at St. Mark's School of
Texas, a private high school. As quarterback-punter-kicker, Hunt
led St. Mark's to a 10-0 record as a senior. He was also a standout
soccer player and pole vaulter.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt went on to play soccer at Southern Methodist University, a
Division I powerhouse. Hunt, a defender, was captain of the
Mustangs as a senior and was a two-time Academic All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hunt grew up in one of America's wealthiest and one of
Texas' most prominent families, he remained well-grounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always amazed me when I was around Clark, how he wanted to
be just another one of the guys,'' said Schellas Hyndman, the
longtime soccer coach at SMU. ``Think about this: Why do you need
to go to college when you have a future in place, an inheritance,
and why do you need to go to be a 4.0 student? Clark sometimes was
his own worst enemy, because everything to him had to be done 100
percent right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clark always wanted to be known for what he has accomplished
and not because of his name.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some SMU opponents, notably arch-rival St. Louis
University, tried exploiting Hunt's side of the field, figuring he
was on the team only because of his name and whatever donations his
family would make to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Hyndman recalled a conversation a few years later with St. Louis
coach Joey Clarke, who told Hyndman: ``We always thought you might
have had Clark Hunt out there because he was Clark Hunt. All the
time we were trying to go at him, because of his name, and then we
found out later, he was your best defender.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Glass worked for the Royals before his dad became the owner.
He spent 1994-95 as a baseball operations assistant and 1996-98 as
assistant director of player personnel, a position that gave him
the responsibility for developing the club's Latin American
program.
</P>
<P>
   Under Glass' direction, the Royals built a dormitory and
upgraded practice facilities and initiated classes for
Spanish-speaking players, teaching them English and how to adapt to
American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved to see him come to the Dominican, because he took
everyone out to dinner,'' Royals second baseman Carlos Febles said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing fancy, mind you. Just trips to Burger King with about 40
or so players in tow.
</P>
<P>
   When Dan Glass joined the organization, it could have been easy
for some Royals front-office officials to question his
qualifications and wonder whether he had a job only because David
Glass was the chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, Dan wanted to be here because Dan wanted to
learn this business,'' said Jay Hinrichs, senior director of
operations and administration. ``We didn't think he used his
influence to talk to his father as chairman of the board or to
influence any players' careers, our careers or any of our
decisions. I think he left business at business and family at
family. That's a trait his family instilled in him, and he can
separate the two.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass, who has a son, Dayne, 18, and daughter, Danielle, 16, and
lives in Olathe, Kan., left the organization in 1999 when his
father was negotiating to buy the Royals. He did some real estate
development and dabbled in the stock market, but most of all he
discovered how much he missed baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's defining his role in replacing Mike Herman, longtime
club president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be very hands-on,'' Dan Glass said. ``I want to know
each one of our players and know about their families. I care about
all these guys. A lot of these kids, like (Mike) Sweeney, Febles,
(Carlos) Beltran, I grew up with in the minor leagues. They're
almost like part of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Glass learned from Sam Walton, he views management as a
team effort, one that includes his father, Herk Robinson and the
rest of the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me who's running the organization, my dad and Herk
are running it, and we all have input,'' Dan Glass said. ``It's not
really by consensus, but being smart and using all your people.
Some of your best ideas come from the bottom up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's a lot of my role right now, to think about what
we need to improve and be able to implement some of those good
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Hunt works alongside Lamar Hunt at Unity Hunt in a
skyscraper in downtown Dallas. Clark runs the business side of the
family's companies, including Hunt Financial Group and Hunt Capital
Group, and for the past 10 years has been responsible for creating
several investment funds that manage more than $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Hunt spent two years as a financial analyst for Goldman,
Sachs and Co., before joining his father's office in 1989 _ the
first season that Carl Peterson was the club's president and
general manager and Marty Schottenheimer was head coach.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Clark Hunt saw the Chiefs reach the playoffs again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very fortunate in Kansas City to have Carl Peterson
over the past 11 years,'' he said, ``and Carl and Marty get the
credit for turning the franchise around from the difficulties we
had in the '80s, and that has been a very good lesson for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Hunt's ownership style is to let the football people make
the football decisions and the front-office executives make the
administrative decisions, an approach Clark advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Hunt has some contact with Peterson but deals mostly with
Dennis Watley, a senior vice president who oversees sales,
marketing and stadium operations for both the Chiefs and the
Wizards. Watley compares the son's attention to detail to his
father's.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is also a second home for Hunt because his wife,
Tavia, a former Miss Kansas, is a graduate of Lee's Summit High
School. Tavia was working for the Chiefs' public relations
department in 1991 when a club employee suggested that she meet
Clark Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the stadium carrying all my bags, pushed the
elevator button, the doors opened, and when I saw this young lady,
I thought, `This must be her,' &UR; '' Hunt recalled. ``We didn't meet
at that time, because people don't talk on elevators. We met at the
kickoff luncheon, August 26, 1991.''
</P>
<P>
   They were married in 1993 and now have a 1-year-old daughter,
Gracelyn, whom they call Gracie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Clark was a little boy, he played all kinds of ball,''
Tavia Hunt said, ``and I think it's genetic, because `ball' was our
1-year-old's first word.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals' and the Chiefs' leases at the Truman Sports Complex
expire in 2015, and there's an undercurrent of concern and
insecurity in Kansas City about whether the Arkansas-based Glass
family would move the Royals or whether the Hunts would ever return
their franchise to its Texas roots.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be little ground for concern.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs have led the NFL in attendance for six straight
years, and Hunt said plans were in the works to continue upgrading
Arrowhead with wider concourses and more suites so it would keep
pace with the newer stadiums in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chiefs have the greatest fan support in the NFL,'' Clark
Hunt said, ``and I couldn't imagine any kind of scenario where they
wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass also envisions continued improvements at Kauffman Stadium,
which would mean more revenue for the club as well as amenities for
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is going to be here forever,'' Dan Glass said.
``This is a great baseball town. They're great fans. They deserve a
team here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
