<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7795 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-FISHER-BETTELHEIM-KAN     05-06 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-BETTELHEIM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRAILBLAZER OF WESTERN CIVILIZATION' CRAFTED AN IMPRESSION IN
BROOKFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKFIELD, Mo. _ Odd what can animate a Missouri town. Here,
it's a tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, it's the obelisk-shaped marker of the Rev. Bernard
J. Bettelheim, dead 130 years and now being resurrected, at least
metaphysically, thanks to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to the worn marble gravestone in Rose Hill
cemetery, John A. Swearingen, a lawyer, noted that while nearby
Laclede could claim General of the Armies John J. Pershing, and
that Marceline, just to the east, produced a fellow named Walt
Disney who drew cartoons, Brookfield now has Bernard J. Bettelheim.
</P>
<P>
   Bettelheim?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. In fact, the man's resume makes Pershing's and
Disney's accomplishments, at least in terms of variety, look
downright spare.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard J. Bettelheim was a Hungarian Jew; a rabbinical student;
a physician; a scientist whose specialty was the eradication of the
cholera scourge; a linguist conversant in 20-plus languages; a
convert to the Anglican faith; a friend of famed African explorer
David Livingston; a world traveler; a Christian missionary to
Okinawa; a translator of the Bible's King James version into
Japanese, its Okinawan dialect and Chinese; Commodore Matthew
Perry's interpreter in the 1853 opening of Japan; an emigrant to
the United States in the late 1850s; a Civil War Union Army
surgeon; and a Brookfield businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's an eclectic resume.
</P>
<P>
   When Bettelheim died in 1870, age 59, hundreds here turned out
for his funeral. He owned property all over the surrounding area
and in Brookfield, then a boom town with hopes of greatness. People
spoke of the man as the ``Trailblazer of Western Civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bettelheim became a forgotten man. His marble monument here
weathered and was rarely noticed, because it was in the older part
of the burying ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look in that section and you see what look to be big empty
spaces,'' Swearingen said. ``But it's full. In those first years
here there were lots of epidemics and lots of mass graves. And many
of the graves weren't marked then, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway around the world, in a cemetery at Naha, Okinawa, is
another, far more imposing, monument, erected in 1926 to
commemorate the 80th anniversary of Bettelheim's arrival on the
island as a Christian missionary. One of the stones in the
monument, 2 feet by 2 feet by 6 inches, was donated by the
Bettelheim family and cut by the Bain Monument Co. here in
Brookfield.
</P>
<P>
   On the huge shaft of the memorial are Japanese characters
telling of Bettelheim's life and work. Atop the monument, in the
English alphabet, is ``B.J. Bettelheim, 1811-1870.''
</P>
<P>
   In Okinawa and Japan, groups hold symposiums on Bettelheim. Four
years ago there was a sesquicentennial celebration of his arrival
there in 1846. He is mentioned in church services among the
Christian communities in the islands. What papers and records he
left behind are jealously guarded, open only to scholars.
</P>
<P>
   In Brookfield, for all those years, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Swearingen blames the Depression: ``His children went on after
he died. They were part of the community. Business people. There's
even a Bettelheim Building here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from what I can learn, the hard times of the 1930s pretty
well ruined them. They moved on. And without them, without their
influence, there was nobody to remind people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettelheim's revival, said Swearingen, occurred because of a man
in St. Louis in the late 1980s and the emergence of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Leslie Konnyu, after years of research, privately
published The Bettelheim Memorial Album, written in English,
Hungarian and Japanese. Konnyu, who died in the early 1990s, was a
poet, a geographer, a historian and an academic. He was also the
founding editor of The American Hungarian Review, a journal devoted
to the accomplishments of that nation's emigres.
</P>
<P>
   Finding Bettelheim, for Konnyu, must have been like winning the
lottery, Swearingen said.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, shortly after the monograph was published, Wanda
Harwood, a historian here, learned of it and adapted part of it for
an article. Swearingen said nothing really happened when Harwood's
piece appeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sort of said, `Well, that's interesting,' and went on
about their business.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be Swearingen, exploring the Internet a couple of years
ago, who would come upon a small and vague reference to Konnyu's
book. There were plenty of references to ``Bettelheim'' on the Web.
But all but a few dealt with Bruno Bettelheim, a famous American
psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got Konnyu's book on interlibrary loan out of St.
Louis,'' Swearingen said. ``I couldn't believe it. So I started
taking it around to people here. You'd show it to them, and their
eyes sort of would glaze, but when they'd read it their jaws fell
open.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Swearingen was sending e-mail to Japan and
Okinawa filling out the picture of the man who has to be
Brookfield's most famous resident. He has a stack of replies from
people in those two places who are delighted Brookfield has
rediscovered Bettelheim.
</P>
<P>
   Swearingen thinks in time there could ultimately be another
monument to Bettelheim in one of the city parks.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dorsey, Brookfield's mayor, said that the Bettelheim story
was fascinating, but that any memorial would be a couple of years
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is John's baby,'' he said. ``He's doing the research. But
people are getting interested. I have to tell you that for years
I've gone by that Bettelheim building and never given it a second
thought. Not one. And then we find all this out.''
</P>
<P>
   Swearingen acknowledged having an occasional ``what if''
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a man who was obviously talented,'' he said. ``So you
wonder that if he had lived, if he had become a real force, what
might have happened to this town? Back then, in the late 1860s,
this was a small city when Kansas City was just a collection of
shacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if Bernard Bettelheim had used his powers of persuasion _
and you know he had some _ to go to the movers and shakers, the
railroad barons, and they had decided Brookfield was the place to
build and develop?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, those are just daydreams. But they're fun to think
about, especially when you go out to Rose Hill and see his old
monument.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
