<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG UNIT HAS IT `SEVERELY LOCKED IN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Arizona lefty Randy Johnson is a few more wins
from his second straight Cy Young award with the Diamondbacks,
thanks to an unreal April in which Johnson went 6-0 with a 0.91
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   But just how dominant he's been is better illustrated by his
complete- game win Friday in which he allowed one earned run and
had his ERA go up. It ballooned all the way to 0.93 to go with his
7-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he keeps doing this, we'll be looking for the cape in his
locker,'' Arizona pitching coach Mark Connor said. ``What is there
to say? I've seen it so much it doesn't amaze me. He's just
severely locked in right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's six victories in April tied Dave Stewart and Vida Blue
for the most wins in the month, but Johnson was even more dominant.
Stewart was 6-0 with a 2.98 ERA for Oakland in 1988. Blue was 6-1
with a 1.19 ERA for the A's in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely focused, and good things have been happening,''
Johnson said. ``I feel very blessed with my ability I've been going
out there with. It's a great reward with the work I put into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's superb start should get a test Wednesday when the
Dodgers face him at Bank One Ballpark. Randy Johnson is 1-4 with a
4.27 ERA in his regular-season career against Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson. Randy Johnson also had trouble in two playoff starts
against Davey Johnson's Baltimore Orioles in 1997. The Big Unit
went 0-2 with a 5.54 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Wait 'til next year: Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood allowed one run in
six innings in his return to the majors Tuesday, but don't expect
to see the best of the young right-hander for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors tell you, `Next year he's going to be
Secretariat,' '' Cubs manager Don Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing pitches with complete ease mentally is the issue with
pitchers coming back from major arm injuries. Typically, that
comfort doesn't come until the second year of pitching after the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get better for almost two years,'' said Dodgers team
physician Dr. Frank Jobe, who didn't perform the surgery on Wood
but is a pioneer of arm surgeries. ``In the second year they have
confidence built up, and then they go all out. I bet you (Wood's
statistics) will be better in the second year than they are this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Throw inside, will fight: Even with long suspensions handed out
by Frank Robinson stemming from the fight between the Detroit
Tigers and Chicago White Sox, Giants manager Dusty Baker doesn't
think it will prevent such events in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably just make some guys want to meet guys by the
bus (to fight),'' Baker said. ``In the old school, guys would just
meet by the bus. The three-strike rule hasn't stopped crime. The
jails are fuller than ever. The death penalty hasn't stopped people
from killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Harried Hampton: Maybe Mets lefty Mike Hampton should have
thought a little more about signing a contract extension before the
season because he's certainly losing a bundle of money with the way
he's started.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was acquired from Houston for Octavio Dotel and Roger
Cedeno to be the Mets' staff ace. He's anchoring them, all right,
holding them down. Hampton won 22 games and had a 2.90 ERA last
season, but this season, he can't find the plate. He's walked 36 in
38 innings and is 2-4 with a 6.52 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason (Tom) Glavine gets those pitches outside, But
if you're all over, you're not going to get calls like the call
today. You're not going to get the flip of the coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Barry Bonds became the first player to hit a ball
on a fly into McCovey Cove, the channel of water beyond the
right-field fence at Pac Bell Park. ... The Colorado Rockies
finished a six-game homestand Wednesday in which their pitchers
allowed 8.83 runs a game, but the Rockies went 4-2. Colorado
averaged 10.83 runs a game. ... Philadelphia lost a team-record 17
games in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
