<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT &LR;      05-06 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGNERS LEAVING SIERRA LEONE; HUNDREDS MORE MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story, previously eliminated, has been restored.)  
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Foreigners and officials with
international relief groups left Sierra Leone Saturday, as the
United Nations reported no progress in obtaining the release of
more than 300 of its peacekeepers and civilians kidnapped during
clashes last week with the rebel Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred more Zambian peacekeepers are missing, U.N.
officials in New York said, though it was not clear whether they
had been taken hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the capital, as most people waited to see whether the
crisis would prove a bump toward a difficult peace or a descent
back into the chaos that engulfed the West African country in
recent years, rebel officials gave no indication of yielding to
diplomatic pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Foday Sankoh, the leader of the Revolutionary United Front, has
steadfastly denied his organization's involvement in the
kidnappings and the deaths of at least four Kenyan peacekeepers,
accusing the United Nations of causing clashes after trying to
force some of his men to lay down their weapons. The rebel
organization, which is nominally part of a power-sharing national
government, repeated its denials Saturday after Sankoh met with
officials from Nigeria and Mali.
</P>
<P>
   ``You now have a lot of fabrications, tall tales about the
RUF,'' Eldred Collins, the spokesman for the rebel group, said in
an interview at Sankoh's compound Saturday. Denying that the group
was holding any peacekeepers hostage, he added, ``They are
scattered in the bush because they do not know the terrain.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Freetown, the Kamajors, a militia that supported the
government, was reportedly rearming in its stronghold in the south.
Many Kamajors, like many rebels, had refused to lay down their
weapons as required by a nine-month-old peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 45,000 combatants in the country's nine-year
war, half are said to have given up their weapons. The actual
figure is probably a lot lower, and widespread fighting could
resume quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Given that history, and the fierce fighting in Freetown in which
thousands were killed or had their hands chopped off during a rebel
attack in January 1999, the capital's airport and helipads were
busy Saturday. Scores of officials of international relief groups,
including the World Food Program, and Lebanese and Nigerian
families were seen leaving.
</P>
<P>
   At a helipad just next to the United Nations' main building
here, 11 flights had carried passengers away. Most foreigners were
reportedly headed to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for business today,'' said Solomon Johnson, an
official at the heliport. ``But it's not good for the country. It's
just one way. No coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord signed in July, all combatants should have
voluntarily given up their weapons months ago. But the warring
parties, and the Revolutionary United Front in particular, refused
to do so at several camps across the country.
</P>
<P>
   While the United Nations provided a $300 incentive, there was
little reason for the combatants to stay inside the camps for the
expected three months. Activities that were supposed to teach them
skills and help them reintegrate into society were never put into
place.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, U.N. peacekeepers had finally been deployed
into most areas of the country _ though never in the diamond mining
district of Kono to which the Revolutionary United Front still
clings. The peacekeepers encountered frequent obstacles erected by
the rebels; it was clear that the rebels remained in control of at
least half the country.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's incidents occurred just as the United Nations was
building up a presence _ with 8,300 soldiers already here _ on a
continent that the international community had avoided in recent
years, after failed missions in Rwanda and Somalia. The trouble in
Sierra Leone was expected to have a negative effect on the West's
willingness to send peacekeepers to Congo, a country involved in a
far more complex war.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.N. officials on Saturday continued to seek support
in speeding up troop deployments to Sierra Leone. The force had
been scheduled to reach its full strength of 11,000 by July.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, France and Britain, the former colonial
power, have said they will not send ground troops, though they are
considering technical and logistical help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
