<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0507-COX     05-06 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush reaches $10 million goal
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service Gov. George W. Bush reached his goal of
<TEXT>
raising a fresh $10 million by the end of April, and he plans to
keep going in an effort that could give him a big summer spending
advantage over likely Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore.
The vice president can spend only around $9 million more before the
Democrats' national convention in August under the limits he agreed
to in exchange for millions of dollars in taxpayer money. Bush, who
has not been accepting federal funds, can spend as much as he can
raise. That could give Bush, who already has spent a record $73
million on his presidential campaign, a huge financial edge. The
Republicans' convention begins July 31 in Philadelphia, the
Democrats' Aug. 14 in Los Angeles. After the conventions, Gore and
Bush each will receive $67.6 million in federal funds and cannot
raise any private money for their campaigns.
<P>
   BRADLEY, FEINSTEIN FAVORED DEMS FOR V.P.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey senator and presidential candidate Bill
Bradley and California Sen. Dianne Feinstein were mentioned most
frequently when Democrats were asked who they want as vice
president, according to an NBC-Wall Street Journal poll released
Friday. Bradley was named by one-third of the Democrats and
Feinstein was named by one-fifth. The following other possible
candidates all received 6 percent in the poll: Florida Sen. Bob
Graham, Indiana Sen. Evan Bayh and former Maine Sen. George
Mitchell. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson received 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH COURTING CALIFORNIA LATINOS WITH NEW STYLE
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Friday predicted that he would win California, which has
the largest electorate vote, by courting the Latino vote and
marketing a new montage of images. He declared himself a
``different kind of Republican'' who could capture the state's 54
electoral votes. As if to prove his point, Bush's swing through
Southern California this week was heavy on style, if not always
substance. In two days, Bush ate tacos in heavily Hispanic Santa
Ana, chatted with residents in Spanish, met with youths in Mission
Viejo and celebrated Cinco de Mayo on Friday by meeting with
Hispanic leaders in San Diego County. Bush, who is methodist, also
attended a Roman Catholic Mass in Orange County, where most
Hispanics are Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   However, a Field Poll released earlier in the week shows that
although Hispanic voters have increased by 1 million in the past
decade, the overwhelming majority are Democrats. Sixty percent of
Hispanics polled said they are Democrats, 22 percent said they are
Republicans and 18 percent were not affiliated with any parties.
Many Hispanics said they remained alienated from the GOP, which led
fights during the 1990s against illegal immigration, affirmative
action and bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN, BUSH SUMMIT PLANNED FOR TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited ``summit'' between Bush and Sen. John McCain on
Tuesday in Pittsburgh, is likely to produce smiles and handshakes,
but it is far less certain that the GOP rivals will manage the sort
of meaningful reconciliation that party regulars are hoping for.
McCain's advisers have said the Arizona senator will not formally
endorse Bush. That apparent coyness on McCain's part is disturbing
to some Republicans. McCain, Bush's former GOP opponent, has said
he is not interested in being Bush's running mate. Late Friday,
Bush told ABC-TV ``I would want to talk to him about it.''
</P>
<P>
   POT SHOT MISSES THE MARK
</P>
<P>
   Bush raised questions Friday about Gore's trustworthiness, but
also faced questions about his own credibility after asserting that
the vice president had once been a member of the National Rifle
Association. Gore aides said that, to their knowledge, he had never
belonged to the NRA. Bush said he was waiting for Gore himself to
definitively answer the question, and said that whether or not he
had been a member, Gore's voting record in Congress suggested he'd
once been a fervent backer of gun rights. ``My position is that
when it was convenient politically he voted one way, and when it's
convenient politically, he's changed his tune,'' Bush said. The
issue came up after Bush on Thursday told reporters: ``I've never
been a member of the NRA. Al Gore's been a member of the NRA, if
I'm not mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON FLUB COULD HELP BUSH
</P>
<P>
   In trying to help Gore, President Clinton inadvertently promoted
the wrong man Friday. Clinton was asked about a videotape that
portrayed the National Rifle Association as hankering to operate
out of a potential Bush White House. ``I don't know that they think
that (NRA Executive Vice President Wayne) LaPierre will literally
have an office here if President Bush _ I mean, if Governor Bush _
gets elected,'' Twice later, Clinton referred to Bush as the Texas
governor, to try to clear things up.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
