<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA WILL SELL YOU ON TEAM USA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thirty minutes after being introduced Friday as
the manager of the 2000 United States Olympic Baseball Team, Tom
Lasorda was autographing a few baseballs. He made sure to put Team
USA under it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should put 2000 on it,'' someone said.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda snatched the ball back, looked at the person and ...
smiled wide.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. Everything about it was so right.
</P>
<P>
   What's amazing is it took Major League Baseball and USA Baseball
a couple of months to make a decision that should have taken a
couple of minutes. Lasorda is a natural for this.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better man to be Olympic coach. There is no better
personality to sell baseball as an Olympic sport. He tried to sell
the Los Angeles Dodgers to everyone, but let's face it, Giants fans
and Padres fans and Yankees fans were raised to detest Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even they have to adore him.
</P>
<P>
   About the only bad thing that can come from it is people who
grew up and grew fond of hating Lasorda might actually root for him
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the manager of the Dodgers for 20 years, I think a lot of
the Dodger fans really love me,'' Lasorda said. ``But now, the
whole country is supposed to love me because I'm representing the
whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the quintessential Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Very few cared about Olympic baseball before. Very few might
care about it in the future. But for two weeks in September, folks
will pay attention to what's taking place in Sydney, Australia. And
they'll do so for the sole reason of Lasorda being the manager.
</P>
<P>
   It's doesn't matter who the players are - though 40-man roster
guys from major-league teams will get the chance to participate for
the first time. It doesn't matter who the coaches are. What matters
is that Lasorda, one of the most recognizable men in baseball, will
be there.
</P>
<P>
   They know Lasorda in Asia, in Europe, in South America and
Central America. They love him everywhere, and everyone knows him.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Darren Dreifort is the only member of the Dodgers
to play in the Olympics, competing in Barcelona, Spain, in 1992. He
said the selection of Lasorda is perfect. The Americans are yet to
win the gold medal since baseball was sanctioned for the 1992
Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have probably the greatest ambassador to the game of
baseball there is, representing America's team, and that's not the
Atlanta Braves,'' Dreifort said. ``They picked the best guy to send
over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams called Lasorda last week to find out why he hadn't
been named manager of the Olympic team yet. Lasorda knew he was the
leading candidate, but he wasn't sure what was holding it up.
</P>
<P>
   So Williams called the commissioner's office of Major League
Baseball to pitch Lasorda as the perfect guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me back and said, `Hey, I talked to them,' and they
said, `Hey, Ted, relax, don't worry, everything's OK,' '' Lasorda
said. ``I called him, and he was so thrilled to know that it was
official.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lasorda wants Williams to come to Australia to talk to the
players before the Olympics begin.
</P>
<P>
   There will be some minor-leaguers on Team USA, maybe some
college kids. They grew up learning about Lasorda, about his
ability to motivate. They'd probably never have a chance to meet
Williams. Now, Williams could be giving the pregame speech.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't happening before.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda embodies Dodgers pride. Bleeding Dodger Blue is his
credo, and his enthusiasm never wanes, and his desire to motivate
never ceases.
</P>
<P>
   He cares deeply about winning the gold medal and representing
the United States. He'll probably make you care the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
