<SLUG> BC-DERBY-RACE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESORMEAUX FINDS WAY OUT OF TROUBLE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHON RAND  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Jockey Kent Desormeaux thrust his helmet
joyfully in the air with both hands Saturday after Fusaichi Pegasus
gave him his second Kentucky Derby victory in three years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Desormeaux didn't reach the winner's circle at Churchill
Downs until he got back in the good graces of a trainer with a top
3-year-old. He's now made the transition from the doghouse to being
top dog twice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux in 1995, at age 25, became the youngest rider ever to
win 3,000 races. But top trainers in southern California became fed
up when they considered too many of his rides uninspired, and they
stopped using him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux mended his fences, though, and in 1998 Bob Baffert
put him on Real Quiet, which won the Derby and Preakness, then
finished second in the Belmont. Desormeaux publicly admitted he had
started to believe that he, not the horses, was responsible for
winning races and needed to be reminded that wasn't the case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, however, Desormeaux was back in the doghouse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and Neil Drysdale, who trains Fusaichi Pegasus, were
unhappy with several of his rides and stopped using him during the
Del Mar meeting near San Diego. Drysdale resumed using Desormeaux
over the winter, but Baffert has not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux has won all five races he's been aboard Fusaichi
Pegasus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a huge year the previous year.... We were just not in
tune with each other,'' Drysdale explained diplomatically. ``We
both felt it would be good to have a breather from each other.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When asked what it took for Desormeaux to get back on his
horses, Drysdale replied, ``Just a bit of time and his attitude.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux's attitude couldn't have been more upbeat when
Fusaichi Pegasus won the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct on April 19. The
colt's dominance that day established him as the inevitable
Kentucky Derby favorite. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, however, he and his wife, Sonia, learned their
year-old son, Jake, was deaf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were devastated,'' Desormeaux told the Daily Racing Form. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out, I had to take a deep breath and sit alone
for a while.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux was particularly distraught because he lost the
hearing in his right ear after a spill at Hollywood Park in 1992. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux's skillful maneuvering of Fusaichi Pegasus after the
horse's poor start Saturday demonstrated the brilliance that
convinces trainers to give him second chances. He didn't panic and
instead patiently moved Fusaichi Pegasus up the rail, then swung
the colt outside on the final turn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Fusaichi Pegasus, an alert start seemed crucial to his
chances to win, because he was breaking from the No. 15 post in a
19-horse field and usually runs just a few lengths off the
leaders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The racing gods smiled on us, the rail opened up and he moved
up,'' Drysdale said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Desormeaux, Drysdale is smiling on him again,
too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
