<HEADER>
A7815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DERBY-CRITTENDEN0507-     05-06 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERBY-CRITTENDEN0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fusaichi Pegasus outruns his reputation
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Behind most of the field at the start, favored
Fusaichi Pegasus spent most of the race maneuvering around horses
like a motorcycle dodging through a pack of tanks. But when he
burst into the lead at the top of the stretch, the Kentucky Derby
was over.
</P>
<P>
   In winning by 1/12 lengths over long shot Aptitude, Fusaichi
Pegasus elevated himself from prospect to wonder horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pretty boy can run,'' said jockey Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   While the other jockeys on the Derby challengers were pounding
at their horses at the finish, Desormeaux had put his whip away.
</P>
<P>
   Now racing has to wonder if any challengers will show up to take
on the Derby winner in two weeks at the Preakness Stakes in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Purchased at auction two years ago for $4 million by Tokyo
software manufacturer Fusao Sekiguchi, the Kentucky-bred colt
destroyed almost all modern guidelines for picking Kentucky Derby
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus became the first favorite to win the race since
Spectacular Bid in 1979. He is the first Wood Memorial winner to
take the Derby since 1981. No son of Mr. Prospector, long the most
successful of Kentucky sires, has ever won the Derby before.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers without Derby experience rarely finish first in the
race. Fusaichi Pegasus made Neil Drysdale a winner in his first
Derby. ``Humbling and rewarding,'' said Drysdale, named to the Hall
of Fame this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know this horse is lightly raced,'' said Drysdale, a
suggestion that the Derby winner, with just six races, is still
improving.
</P>
<P>
   The entries that were supposed to be prime challengers finished
far from the front.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy, trained by Jenine Sahadi, trying to be the first won
ever to win the Derby, came in 14th as the No. 2 betting choice.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, from the barn of Bob Baffert, the Derby's winning
trainer in 1997 and 1998, led by a head after a mile, but came in
eighth, fading fast.
</P>
<P>
   High Yield, thought to be the best of the three Wayne Lukas
entries, was a baffling 15th at the finish, a neck ahead of Florida
Derby winner Hal's Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Todd Pletcher, with four horses in the race, was third
with Impeachment and fourth with More Than Ready, certainly a
successful introduction for a first-time Derby trainer. His other
two horses misfired, with Trippi 10th and Graeme Hall last.
</P>
<P>
   Hal's Hope held the lead for the first 3/4 mile, then was passed
by Captain Steve and Trippi. At the top of the stretch, Fusaichi
Pegasus was in the lead, with More Than Ready a head back and
Wheelaway in third by another head.
</P>
<P>
   Famous because of his price tag and his promise, Fusaichi
Pegasus, on this one day at least, was better than his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love challenges,'' his owner said through an interpreters.
``I love breaking records and setting new records.''
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi, 64, said he would have been willing to spend another
million to buy Fusaichi Pegasus. ``When I laid eyes on him two
years ago I knew he was a Derby winner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 153,204, the second biggest in Derby history, was at
Churchill Downs on an 82-degree afternoon. They got the smallest
win payoff ($6.60) on a Derby champion since Spectacular Bid. With
19 starters, the purse for the race was $1,188,400, biggest in the
126 years of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi gets a $150,000 bonus for his ownership of the horse
that won both the Wood and the Derby. Drysdale's share of the
Wood-Derby bonus is $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Derby winner came into the week before the race with the
reputation of being a wild horse, one who bucked and raged on the
practice track. Fusaichi was calm on Derby Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things he does on the track come from his inquisitive
temperament,'' said the owner. ``That was nothing to be concerned
about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Be sure he is comfortable early in the race,'' Drysdale told
Desormeaux in the saddling process. ``He will do the rest.'' That
worked out well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
