<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MADCOW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE GOES ON THE OFFENSIVE AGAINST MAD COW DISEASE
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for general rewrite. Deletes `ART' from slug.)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUELLAS, France _ At first the veterinarian said that it might
just be milk fever. Then the possibility of a brain tumor was
discussed. But as the laboratory took longer and longer to report
test results, Guy Jambon accepted the inevitable. One of his herd
had been infected with mad cow disease, although none had ever been
detected in this southeast region of France.
</P>
<P>
   The health department trucks came a few days later, on Feb. 18.
In one morning, all 670 of Jambon's cows were taken for slaughter
and incineration _ leaving the barns, the pens, the milking room
and the fields empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part that got to you was how quiet it was,'' Jambon said.
``I was saying to myself, `We don't really understand anything. How
did the cow get this disease? How did this happen here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jambon is not alone in raising such questions. The number of
cases of mad cow disease discovered in France, as in many other
countries in Europe, has been climbing steadily. The totals are
still minuscule compared with those in the United Kingdom, which
has reported 178,000 cases of the deadly degenerative brain disease
since 1986, and endured a four-year ban on its beef by other
European nations.
</P>
<P>
   But what many experts find alarming is that the numbers are
going up at all, given that strict preventive measures were ordered
in 1996, when scientists first linked mad cow disease, also known
as bovine spongiform encephalopathy, to a similar brain disease in
humans.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are totals rising, but more and more countries have
reported cases of the disease. It has now been discovered in
native-born cows in 10 European countries, including Portugal,
Switzerland, Belgium, the Netherlands, Liechtenstein, Luxembourg
and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the issue has been all over the front pages lately as
the pace of cases appears to be rising steeply this year. In 1997,
six cases were detected in France. In 1998, 18. Last year, it was
30. This year, 16 new cases have been reported already, roughly one
a week.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are so worried that they intend to begin random
testing of cows that have died after exhibiting suspicious behavior
before the start of summer. As many as 50,000 of France's 21
million cattle are expected to be examined each year under the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Hirsch, the head of France's new food safety agency, is,
like many other officials here, bracing himself for the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could certainly show that there is much more mad cow out
there than we have detected so far,'' Hirsch said. ``We just don't
know. There is so much we don't know about this disease, we can
hardly say with confidence that it is under control. We'll have to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   But French officials are not the only ones concerned. Earlier
this year, a group of scientists advising the European Union on the
issue warned that millions of Europeans may be at risk of catching
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the fatal human version of mad cow
disease, despite their governments' claims that their countries are
free of the disease. The European Union has been urging broader
preventive measures throughout its 15 member countries. But some
countries have refused, saying they do not have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see these measures taken,'' said Beate
Gminder, a spokeswoman for David Byrne, the food safety
commissioner for the European Commission, the executive body of the
European Union. ``The number of cases of mad cow may be much larger
than we know. It could be that cases exist much more extensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are still highly puzzled by the disease, which was
first recognized in cows in 1986. It appears that it is not caused
by a bacteria, a virus or a fungus, but stems from infectious
particles called prions, perhaps acting in concert with a virus or
other agent. The disease kills brain cells, leaving the organ full
of holes and resembling a sponge.
</P>
<P>
   Since the human form of the disease was first recognized in
1995, more than 35 people have died of it in Britain. Estimates of
how many people are likely to be infected range widely. Some
British scientists have speculated that another 75 people will die
of the disease in the next 20 years. Others say 80,000, depending
on the incubation period and how the infection is passed from
animal to human.
</P>
<P>
   No one yet knows how much infected meat someone must eat before
the lethal brain-wasting disease takes hold, or if some other
factor must be present, too. To date, efforts to prevent the
disease in cows have centered on eliminating animal feed that
contains infected animal parts.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts believe that, apart from foodstuffs and
cow-to-calf transmission, there may be a third, and yet unknown,
mode of transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disease is one of the great mysteries of the century,''
Hirsch said. ``We don't know exactly what is the nature of this
disease, so we don't know what steps to take to prevent it. We do
have many questions about modes of transmission. We are looking at
different things.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, France has taken perhaps the most conservative position
in Europe, refusing to even accept British beef despite assurances
by European Union officials that it is as safe as any other beef on
the market. (The European Union is currently moving forward with a
lawsuit against France over the matter. )
</P>
<P>
   But while the European Union may feel France has gone too far in
trying to protect itself from British meat, it is urging many
European countries to take more precautions against mad cow disease
than they have been willing to take so far.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven European Union countries, including Britain and
France, have taken the strictest preventive measures. Not only do
they control the animal feed, but they also prevent the parts of
the cattle most likely to carry prions, including the brain, spinal
material and intestines, from even entering the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission would like Austria, Denmark, Finland,
Germany, Greece, Sweden, Italy and Spain to do the same. (Italy and
Spain currently only ban the most infective parts of the beef from
countries with known cases of the disease.)
</P>
<P>
   The European Union is also planning a monitoring program
starting in 2001 that would test up to 65,000 cows a year
throughout its member nations to build a realistic picture of a
disease that many fear is underreported.
</P>
<P>
   While Britain has been hit hardest by the disease, Ireland is
next with 466 cases. Portugal has had 371 and Switzerland 351. The
next highest country is France, with 92 cases detected since 1991.
Most of France's cases have been in the north, where there is a
greater likelihood of exchanges of feed and cattle with Britain.
But lately, cases have begun to be detected in other regions of
France.
</P>
<P>
   French officials had predicted that because of their precautions
cases of the disease would be declining by now. Experts note that
it no doubt took a while for the 1996 regulations banning animal
parts from animal feed to take hold. And there may also be
instances in which regulations were ignored and the effects are now
being seen. A recent European Union report still found traces of
meat and bone meal in some samples of French feed despite the ban.
But some experts say they are not sure such incidents account for
the rise in numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Britain's Conservative Party has called for a
European ban on French beef. But the appeal has largely been
dismissed as a political tit-for-tat, as the numbers of infected
cattle are still very small. In addition to France, the United
States continues to ban British beef. But it does not have similar
restrictions on beef from elsewhere in Europe, Gminder said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, French farmers unions and the government have stepped in
quickly to help farmers whose herds have been hit by the disease.
Within a week of losing his cows, Jambon had 30 young calves back
on his farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was at least something to keep him busy,'' said Gilbert
Limandas, the president of the local farmers union. ``There is no
question that this is a real trauma for the farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he goes about his work, Jambon says, he is still scared
it will happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no precautions to take because I had already taken
all the precautions I knew about,'' he said. `So, I'm back doing
the same thing and hoping it doesn't happen again. We are all
wondering around here: `Who will it hit next?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
