<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS MINICAMP BEGINS WITHOUT DERRICK THOMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JASON WHITLOCK  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life without Derrick Thomas began in earnest Saturday afternoon
for our Kansas City Chiefs and for us, their followers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Wizards-type crowd showed up at Arrowhead Stadium for a
non-contact minicamp practice. It was as if the regular season _
Christmas around here _ came early for Chiefs fans. They dusted off
their grills and practiced the fine art of tailgating,
beer-guzzling and setting unrealistic expectations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise me,'' said Chiefs tight end Tony Gonzalez,
referring to the crowd. ``We have the best fans in the NFL.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and his teammates also got to practice a little, too _
the fine art of honoring Thomas' memory. That's what this 2000
season is all about. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't intend for this to be construed as a knock, just a
statement of fact: So far the Chiefs have done very little this
off-season in terms of improving their personnel from a year ago.
Signing a trio of solid interior offensive linemen _ Brendan Stai,
Jeff Blackshear and Aaron Graham _ made good sense considering the
Chiefs appear likely to lose either Will Shields or Dave Szott, or
both. But it doesn't move the Chiefs anywhere near the playoffs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Landing a big-ticket free agent won't be what helps the Chiefs
make a Super Bowl run this season. Rather, their best chance to
surprise us is if they've truly learned a lesson from Thomas' death
and use his memory to inspire a focused, disciplined,
enjoy-the-moment-because-it-could-be-taken-away effort. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think there's a small chance it could happen. The Chiefs got
off to a good start Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They genuinely appreciated the enthusiasm from the 12,577 fans
who attended Saturday's practice. Cunningham was so excited that
during his post-practice chat with the media, he sounded like a
high school coach preaching the importance of school spirit. The
players fed off the fans' energy, too, and turned their practice
intensity up a notch. Following the practice they acknowledged the
fans by throwing T-shirts and footballs into the stands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I realize the actions were mandated by management _ owner
Lamar Hunt, King Carl Peterson and Cunningham know the Chiefs have
had a dreadful off-season in terms of public relations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this may be the closest thing to an apology we ever see or
hear from the Chiefs as long as Peterson is in control of the
franchise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think the fans should _ and did _ graciously accept the
apology and view it as a sign that the Chiefs are taking a few cues
from Thomas, their future Hall of Fame linebacker. He never had a
problem acknowledging when he was wrong _ just remember the way he
handled the Monday Night Football situation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' spirit hung over Arrowhead Stadium on Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything we can do to raise (Derrick's) name up we're going to
do,'' running back Donnell Bennett said. ``He's a big part of what
we're going to do this year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everyone I spoke with said the best way to honor Thomas is to
win. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out there and win the Super Bowl,'' said
Gonzalez, who like the rest of his teammates has a No. 58 decal on
the back of his helmet. ``I talked to Derrick's mom just a couple
of nights ago, and she said Derrick's up there watching over us
now. She said she feels that we're going to go to the Super Bowl
this year, and I believe her.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Center Tim Grunhard, a native of Chicago, added: ``I compare it
to when Harry Caray died and the Cubs made the playoffs. He was up
there turning the wheels or something because (the Cubs) kept
getting all the breaks. I think D.T. will be up there making sure
we get the breaks.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
