<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIEFS-ELVIS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS QUARTERBACK TAKES OFFENSIVE LINE ON HUNTING EXPEDITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY COVITZ  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing like spending a few early-morning hours sitting
in a duck blind or wading through snake-infested wilderness in
pursuit of pheasant or wild boars to bring teammates closer
together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's why Chiefs quarterback Elvis Grbac invited nine teammates
to an off-season hunting expedition to south Texas. All expenses,
including first-class travel, were paid by Grbac. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was Grbac's way of showing appreciation to his offensive line
for keeping him injury-free for the first time in his three seasons
with the Chiefs. It also was a means of developing esprit de corps
among teammates and demonstrating that Grbac wants to be a leader
of this team in 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys got to finally know who I am,'' Grbac said. ``That's
where the relationship will grow between individuals. Anytime you
can get away from the game, or whatever your profession, and spend
time with people, you're going to get to know them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to get them away from football, and not to talk about
football, just relax, just a bunch of guys having a good time _ it
was awesome.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grbac stole the idea for the hunting trip from Joe Montana. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe used to do things like this,'' Grbac said. ``He would
always say, `You don't realize all the pain an offensive lineman
goes through until you watch it on the film on Mondays, and they do
it week in and week out. I get touched maybe two or three times.'
So it's an opportunity to pay your respects to those guys.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was no stroll through the woods, either. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The wake-up calls sounded at 4 a.m., and hunting guides took
Grbac's group by bus into the wild about 35 miles outside Houston.
They hunted for duck, snow geese, pheasant and boar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And they rolled back into the hotel well after dark. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that Elvis is as driven off the field as he is on,''
center Tim Grunhard said. ``We started hunting at 5 in the morning,
and by noon, I was ready to quit. But we kept going until 5 at
night. Twelve hours of hunting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When Elvis has a goal, whether it's to hit a tight end across
the field or to bag a wild boar, he's driven to do it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides Grunhard, those who joined Grbac on the trip included
guard Will Shields and tackle Glenn Parker, now with the New York
Giants; defensive end Ty Parten and three players no longer with
the team: linebacker Greg Manusky, deep snapper Ralph Tamm and
tight end Ted Popson. Guard Dave Szott, who was ill, and tackle
Victor Riley, whose wife had a baby, were late scratches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This was also a chance for guys who may never play again, an
opportunity to go out in style,'' Grbac said. ``We talked about our
families, we talked about our futures, what we're going to do, we
talked about hunting, we talked about a lot of things we don't talk
about during the football season. It was kind of nice. '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grbac missed 10 starts in his first two seasons because of
injuries and another six starts when he was benched at the end of
the 1998 season, so he never felt comfortable taking a leadership
position with the Chiefs, much less taking teammates on a hunting
expedition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, in the NFL, when you get injured, you are
shuffled to the back,'' Grunhard said. ``People don't talk to you
as much, people tend to stay away from you. When he was hurt, he
didn't get a chance to become a big-time member of this team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Grbac missed only three snaps and threw for 3,389
yards and 22 touchdowns, the most by a Chiefs quarterback since
Steve DeBerg's 23 in 1990. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, Grbac, 29, wants to put his imprint on this team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys in the offense have finally gotten comfortable with
my style of play and what I do for the team,'' Grbac said. ``Last
year was a turning point for me, just being healthy for the entire
year. They knew the same quarterback was going to be there every
day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last training camp, there was some question of
whether Grbac would be able to hold off veteran Warren Moon for the
starting position. But Grbac was one of just eight NFL quarterbacks
to start all 16 games in 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The doubt about him has vanished. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When Elvis walks out on the field now, there's no question who
the quarterback is,'' coach Gunther Cunningham said. ``There's no
question he's like a different guy. Last year, I was concerned
about him, getting his confidence level to where it should be, and
now he's just changed completely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good attitude, the players look to him, they
listen, and they saw it all a year ago when he was performing on
the practice field, how consistent he was, how effective he was,
and then he went into the games. All the games weren't perfect, but
a lot of them were very good.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grbac planned the hunting trip before Derrick Thomas' untimely
death, but the trip gave the players an opportunity to share their
thoughts on the tragedy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good for the guys because it was the off-season,'' said
Parten. ``If it was in season, then everyone as a team would be
able to talk to one another about it. It was good for us guys down
there, driving out in the van to go hunting, and the subject would
come up and we'd talk about it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grbac plans to make the hunting trip an annual event, and he
hopes next time his teammates will have something to celebrate.
While Grbac led the Chiefs to a 9-7 record, reversing the 7-9
debacle of 1998, they missed the playoffs for the second straight
season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks are measured by winning, and Grbac, who has a Super
Bowl ring from his four seasons in San Francisco, understands
what's at stake this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say all you want about the franchise winning 100
games,'' Grbac said of the Chiefs' success in the 1990s, ``but you
look at the stretch the last couple years, and we have not made the
playoffs, and that's a problem. We pride ourselves on being in the
playoffs, and when I got here I talked about winning the Super
Bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it's all about. Guys have matured from last year,
and understand their roles. Hopefully what happened last year, we
can build on that and get better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
