<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7915 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2Takes-L     05-06 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPT LAPD OFFICERS RUINED CASES WITH THEIR LIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH  
 and BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Illegal searches and false testimony by corrupt
officers _ not planted evidence _ tainted most of the vacated
felony convictions related to the LAPD Rampart scandal, a Daily
News investigation has found.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the 73 felony convictions overturned thus far
actually included significant evidence of crimes that became
tainted because corrupt officers initiated arrests without probable
cause, according to a review of court documents and confidential
investigative reports.
</P>
<P>
   As the worst police corruption scandal in city history continues
to unfold, attention has focused on the most violent acts of police
thuggery, the planting of evidence and the framing of suspects as
described by dirty-cop-turned-snitch Rafael Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Guns and drugs, however, were not planted on suspects in the
majority of the overturned cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand what goes on in Rampart and places
like Watts. They're virtual police states where civil rights
protections don't apply,'' said Connie Rice, a nationally
recognized civil rights lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Since the scandal broke last September, the public's response to
the corruption has been muted by the perception that many of the
victims were hardly sympathetic figures or law-abiding citizens. A
review of the cases confirms that perception, and the circumstances
around the arrests could help to reduce the city's liability.
</P>
<P>
   When the corrupt cops illegally kicked down a door, rifled
through a room or frisked a suspect without cause or consent, they
often found what they suspected: a pound of cocaine stashed in a
bottom dresser drawer; 50 small balloons filled with crack sitting
in a car; marijuana plants growing on the balcony; cocaine
concealed in a butter container; loaded guns.
</P>
<P>
   Rice argued it is a dangerous but common path for gung-ho
officers in Los Angeles and many other big cities to fabricate
probable cause in order to arrest people they believe are guilty of
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you go down that road, it's just a couple of (steps) away
from, 'I might as well fabricate the evidence, because they're all
bad. They're all guilty of something and sooner or later they'll be
arrested anyway,' '' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what created Rafael Perez.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Daily News' analysis of the vacated cases, at
least 56 percent of the convictions that have been tossed out by
the state Superior Court involved defendants who were actually
carrying drugs or guns or who were in the immediate proximity of
drugs or guns. In those cases, officers routinely fabricated
stories to justify how they obtained the evidence and then lied in
court to ensure the arrest appeared legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, about 25 percent of the vacated convictions were
tainted because Perez and other cops planted guns or drugs on the
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the remaining cases were overturned either because Perez
had unconfirmed doubts about the actions of his former colleagues
or because a conviction was based largely upon his trial testimony.
In fact, in at least two of the vacated cases Perez maintains the
arrests were legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even criminals have rights,'' said LAPD Cmdr. David Kalish, a
spokesman for the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers must have reverence for the law. Violating an
individual's rights, whoever they are, is counter to our principles
and core values and to the oath of office every police officer
makes to support the constitutions of the United States and of the
state of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several cases where evidence was planted on a
person. But in many of the cases, had the officers followed the
rules and done their job right, they could have made legal
arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Perez has told investigators that he and his
partner stopped a man ``who just looked out of place'' on Temple
Street in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk to him,'' Perez recalled in an interview with the
corruption task force. ``All of a sudden, he drops ... a black
canister. I mean, real obvious. I mean it was his. He dropped it.
And we arrested him.''
</P>
<P>
   That, however, wasn't enough to guarantee a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   So Perez and his partner then falsified their police report and
lied in court to solidify the arrest, saying they observed the man
buying cocaine from a dealer. With two prior convictions, the man
was sentenced to two years in state prison and then deported. His
conviction was overturned last month after county prosecutors
learned about the falsified police report.
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, Perez said he and two other officers got
word from a confidential informant named ``Oscar'' that drugs were
being sold out of an apartment. Rather than set up an observation
post, the officers fabricated a story about witnessing the drug
dealing and then kicked down the door.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the apartment, Perez said, the cops found a variety of
narcotics, including more than a pound of cocaine. They even caught
a person dropping ``a big cookie of rock cocaine inside the
toilet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two people were arrested and eventually pleaded guilty to drug
charges in 1997. They were sentenced to three years in state
prison, and were deported after their release. Last month, the
convictions were overturned after Perez told prosecutors the search
and seizure took place without probable cause.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Gil Garcetti said the Daily News' findings
didn't surprise him, but in no way alter what transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no excuse for an intentional crime committed by a
police officer. These are intentional crimes committed by police
officers,'' Garcetti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victim's race, nationality, record, whatever, shouldn't
matter. A police officer cannot get away with committing a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   While Perez is an admitted liar and a convicted felon, his sworn
statements relating to the overturned cases have been confirmed by
LAPD detectives and the District Attorney's Office. The Daily News
has obtained a transcript of the confidential testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Perez offered his confessions of corruption to prosecutors last
September in exchange for a more lenient sentence for stealing
about $1 million worth of cocaine from an LAPD evidence locker in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the corruption probe, more than 20 officers
either have been fired, have been suspended, or have quit. And
three officers were charged last month with crimes. More charges
are expected to be filed within the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   Joel R. Isaacson, who represents two Rampart officers _
including Paul Harper, who was charged with criminal misconduct two
weeks ago _ disputed the credibility and significance of Perez's
statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're relying on his testimony. We disagree,'' Isaacson
said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the officers facing prosecution have denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the City Attorney's Office, which has settled three
cases for about $120,000 each, has attempted to assess the city's
liability for the scandal on a case-by-case basis. No one in the
office has analyzed how many of those wrongfully convicted had
drugs or guns in their possession or had been at gang parties where
guns and drugs were present.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Assistant City Attorney Thomas C. Hokinson, head of the
office's civil litigation branch, said the analysis would be ``very
helpful'' to the city and could reduce its liability. The financial
fallout has been estimated to be at least $125 million and possibly
as much as $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is helpful in going to the issue of determining what
damages actually were sustained,'' Hokinson said. ``It's one thing
if the allegation is that someone planted the drugs and another if
he had the drugs to begin with. That's a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, it changes how a jury looks at the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of weapons or illegal drugs will affect (the
jurors') judgment of what is reasonable compensation for the
plaintiffs,'' Hokinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Public Defender Kimberly Wong, who represented one of the
defendants whose convictions have been overturned, said her client,
Walter Rivas, always maintained drugs were planted on him.
</P>
<P>
   Wong said Rivas' conviction illustrates how unwilling the
criminal justice system is to challenge police claims of probable
cause, especially when the defendants come from poor, inner-city
neighborhoods awash in drugs and guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people in our community accept that the ends
justify the means,'' Wong said. ``It's a slippery slope, because if
the community accepts the first step that the probable cause was
fabricated, then the next logical step is planting the drugs on
people like Mr. Rivas who never had any drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who was involved in the March 1998 arrest of Rivas, later
told investigators he believed the arrest was dirty. Rivas is
currently in federal custody at an INS detention center. He has
filed a civil lawsuit against the city, naming seven officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always one guy who doesn't run, maybe because he's
innocent. He can pay for that,'' Wong said. ``They can break you
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
