<SLUG> BC-BBN-MARLINS-SMITH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLINS' SMITH ENJOYED PLAYING IN JAPAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Passing up a season in the major leagues could be
the best move of Mark Smith's baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   After spending years bouncing around in the minors and sitting
on the bench in the majors, the former USC All-American opted to
spend last season in Japan. While it's a move often considered the
last resort for extending a pro career, it appears to have provided
a significant boost for Smith, who is back in the United States and
off to the best start of his big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   The outfielder earned a spot with the Florida Marlins as a
non-roster invitee and entered this weekend's series against the
New York Mets batting .333. He has never batted better than .285 in
the majors. He has just four starts, but he's appeared in 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had opportunities before I left for Japan to stay in the
United States,'' Smith said. ``But I just wanted to go over there
for the experience and financially it made more sense to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japan experience helped me. People think that the baseball
in Japan is second rate to over here. The pitchers over there are
every bit as good as the pitchers over here, there's no doubt in my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The 293 at-bats he had playing for Yakult were 100 more than in
any of his previous major league seasons. He batted just .243 but
hit a career- high 20 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   It took about a month to get used to the customs of a new
country and league, but after that Smith said he fit in and found
it less of a challenge than being a reserve player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Smith said of the role he has filled since he was
initially called up to the majors in 1994 for a short stint with
Baltimore. ``It's probably one of the hardest things to do in
baseball, when you're asked to go in and perform and you haven't
been in there everyday, maintaining your skills. Any bench player
you talk to is probably going to say the same thing. It's very
difficult, but you just got to go in there and be ready to battle
every time you're in there. Nothing comes easy being a bench
player. It's definitely a lot easier when you're playing
everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 29, established school career records for RBI (168),
stolen bases (57) and triples (13) at USC. He was a first-round
draft pick by the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the second season he's been on the opening-day
roster of a major-league team. Before he went to Japan, the
highlight of Smith's professional career had been hitting a home
run to clinch a 10-inning combined no hitter for teammates
Francisco Cordova and Ricardo Rincon with the Pirates in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Playing time is the only thing Smith feels kept him from doing
better in the past, but just being in the major leagues keeps him
happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some young outfielders we'd like to give some time
and (Smith)'s accepted his role,'' Marlins manager John Boles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're here in the big leagues,'` Smith said. ``You can't
complain about being in the big leagues. ... I just wish I had
gotten more of an opportunity. I got a chance in Japan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
