<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-L     05-06 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS EDGE ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ To bunt or not to bunt.
</P>
<P>
   That was the question when Garret Anderson was at bat with
runners on first and second and nobody out in the ninth inning in a
scoreless game between the Anaheim Angels and Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   But Angels manager Mike Scioscia said it never entered his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit into a double play and the Mariners ended the game
on Mark McLemore's RBI single in the bottom of the ninth for a 1-0
victory Saturday before 43,427 at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Garret is a guy you want up there swinging the bat
with a chance to win the game,'' Scioscia said. ``You have Garret,
(Troy) Glaus and (Scott) Spiezio coming up. All you need is a base
hit by one of those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``G.A. is hitting fifth and I look for him to drive in runs for
us all year. He's hitting there because he has the potential to
drive in over 100 runs a year. You have to stick with him.''
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson grounded into the short-to-second-to-first double
play, Glaus struck out looking to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners closer Kazuhiro Sasaki (1-0), who got Anderson to hit
into the double play and then retired Glaus, created his own mess
by walking Mo Vaughn and Tim Salmon to start the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki escaped and got the win only because the Mariners did
what the Angels could not do - get a bunt down.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell opened the ninth with a single off Mike Holtz (0-1)
and pinch runner Charles Gipson took second on Dan Wilson's
sacrifice bunt. Holtz tried to throw a 2-2 fastball low and away to
McLemore, but he got the ball up and McLemore lined it to
right-center field for the game-winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of game execution is important,'' Scioscia
said. ``They got 'em on, got 'em over and got 'em in.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has only 11 sacrifice bunts in his career, so he
wouldn't say he was expecting a bunt sign when he stepped to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about it,'' Anderson said. ``I asked Ron
(Roenicke, the Angels third base coach), does he have me bunting.
He said no, so I went to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Scioscia) knows the type of hitter I am. I think he made his
judgment based on that. There are going to be times he might ask me
to bunt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to take the bat out of G.A.'s hands,'' Scioscia
reiterated. ``We already had a runner in scoring position. The
table's already set.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason runs were at a premium was because both starters
pitched well.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners starter Gil Meche didn't get the victory, but he shut
out the Angels on two hits through seven innings. Arthur Rhodes
threw a scoreless eighth, setting up Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   For the Angels, Kent Mercker was starting in place of the
injured Jason Dickson and threw five scoreless innings. He was on a
limited pitch count because he had been pitching out of the bullpen
all season. He made 76 pitches and allowed only three hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoreless,'' Mercker said when asked to evaluate his
performance. Mercker has admitted his disappointment at not being
in the starting rotation despite a solid spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doesn't matter how you feel or what you do as long as you
don't give up runs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker's changeup was particularly effective, as he struck out
five.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to throw that pitch when you know how to use
it,'' he said. ``When you're throwing out of the 'pen you don't
have time to get everything going. I'm pleased with how I threw, I
just wish today I wasn't on a pitch count. Mentally I felt I was
where I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Meche still doesn't have a win this season, but he lowered his
ERA to 3.51 on Saturday. The Angels finished with only two hits -
singles by Salmon and Anderson. They had only three baserunners in
scoring position all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Meche) made tremendous pitches when he had to,'' Scioscia
said. ``We just had to go a little deeper into our bullpen than
those guys did and they eventually got to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were without relievers Troy Percival, Mark Petkovsek
and Shigetoshi Hasegawa because their arms needed rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
