<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTENFIELD, WALBECK WORKING WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia doesn't like the
idea of matching catchers with certain pitchers. He says his
catchers should be interchangeable when it comes to working with
the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But Scioscia is going with catcher Matt Walbeck when Kent
Bottenfield is pitching. Walbeck has started only nine games this
season, and six have come with Bottenfield on the mound. The
battery has worked well together lately, as Bottenfield has given
up only four earned runs in his past three starts, covering 21
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been leaving everything up to Matt,'' Bottenfield said.
``I haven't shaken him off in three starts. He's allowing me to
learn the hitters. He's teaching me, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield is making his first tour through the American
League, having spent his entire career in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Wally has an understanding of the league Kent is
looking for,'' Scioscia said. ``Right now, they're working well
together. Will it always be that way? I can't say that. Somewhere
along the line we'll get Bengie (Molina) to catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the mark: Darin Erstad went 0 for 4 Saturday, his average
dipping below .400 for the first time this season (.398). Erstad is
hitting .143 (3 for 21) on the current road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys have made some good pitches against him,'' Scioscia
said. ``He's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   On the grill: While Erstad has cooled off, Tim Salmon has heated
up. Salmon reached base four times Saturday with a single and three
walks. He's hitting .563 (9 for 16) on the trip, raising his
average to .269.
</P>
<P>
   Getting close: Shortstop Gary DiSarcina worked out Saturday and
took another step toward returning from a sore right shoulder.
DiSarcina is likely to be back in the starting lineup today or
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dads get no rest: Reliever Al Levine rejoined the team Saturday
after going home to be with his wife, Linda, who gave birth to the
couple's first child late Thursday, a boy, Anthony Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Levine didn't have much time to rest before getting back out
there. He pitched 2 innings Saturday, allowing no runs and two
hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
