<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OCONNOR-MOURNERS-1STL     05-06 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-MOURNERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS MOURN CARDINAL AT ST. PATRICK'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to expand by 600 words. Includes more information on Bishop
Egan. Breaks into two takes.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT11-13 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(With: OCONNOR-CHARISMA) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands of mourners from across the New York region
and the nation, including many children and disabled people,
converged on a funereal at St. Patrick's Cathedral Saturday to pay
their last respects to Cardinal John O'Connor with prayers, hymns
and the ancient rites of Roman Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   On a sun-washed spring day with temperatures that climbed into
the high 80s, crowds stood for hours in long, slow lines on Fifth
Avenue and 50th Street to enter the great cathedral's double doors,
draped in black and purple bunting, for a last glimpse of the
cardinal, lying in state at the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Streaming under the arched Gothic pillars almost all day and
into the evening, a double line of mourners filed past the bier,
which was flanked by white-gloved police officers at attention.
Many people wept softly and murmured prayers for the cardinal, who
died Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds also filled the 2,300-seat pews to overflowing for a
morning Mass in Spanish, for an afternoon Mass in English that was
organized for children and disabled people, and later for vespers
and rosary services. For many it was a day of reflection as well as
sorrow for the death of the cardinal, who was 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a wonderful man, a model for Catholicism,'' Frank
Rusch, an airline pilot from the West Coast, said after viewing the
body cloaked in scarlet and white vestments and lying in a
red-velvet-lined mahogany coffin. ``He is very well thought of. I
speak of him in the present because he is still with us.''
</P>
<P>
   As preparations for the cardinal's funeral on Monday went
forward, there was no word from the Vatican on the selection of his
successor as the archbishop of New York, although speculation
continued to focus on Bishop Edward M. Egan, of the Diocese of
Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   While the selection process is secret, with harsh penalties for
anyone who breaks the silence, some church officials have virtually
confirmed Egan's appointment, saying that an announcement as early
as Tuesday or Wednesday is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is Egan,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty evident,'' another senior church official
involved in the early stages of the selection process said. He
indicated that the church's highest officials in New York and the
Northeast had already been notified, but said they would keep
silent out of respect until after the cardinal's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was to lead a host of dignitaries at the
funeral _ 3,500 invitations have gone out _ and the Vatican
secretary of state, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, was to represent Pope
John Paul II and officiate at the 2 p.m. Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's events _ the second of three days of Masses and other
services leading to the funeral and burial in the crypt under the
altar at St. Patrick's _ gave striking testimony once more to the
admiration and respect that millions accorded the cardinal,
America's most influential Catholic leader.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., when the cathedral opened, the crowds waiting to get
in were already enormous. The lines snaked around into 50th Street,
then back to Madison Avenue, where they doubled back again to Fifth
Avenue and redoubled back toward Madison. And they kept getting
larger.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the day's heat was a torment. About 11:30 a.m., a man
in his 70s fainted on the sidewalk. People went to his aid, giving
him sips of water and orange slices. He revived a bit and said he
had been in line for 90 minutes after walking about a mile to the
cathedral from the Port Authority Bus Terminal at 40th Street and
Eighth Avenue. Firefighters took him away on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   Some people had flown in from Puerto Rico and other Caribbean
islands. Some had come by airplane and bus from other states. Many
residents of the metropolitan area took buses or subways to pay
tribute to a man they said had been a friend of the poor, the sick
and immigrants struggling to make a new life in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the cardinal so much, I just had to come,'' said
Minnie Stinson, a Bronx homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Rosado, 21, a cashier at the Candado Plaza Casino in Old
San Juan, Puerto Rico, said he had flown to New York with his
family for the Mass in Spanish. ``I am really, really Catholic, was
raised in a Catholic house,'' he said. ``The cardinal gave so much
to the poor and the rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Maximo Mendoza had come with 18 others from his Bronx church
because of the cardinal's support for Hispanic immigrants. ``He
opened the door for Mexicans,'' Mendoza said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Doyle, 76, came by bus from Scranton, Pa., where he said he
had known John O'Connor as a bishop. More than personable, he
recalled, O'Connor had known many of his parishioners by their
first names.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Kaatz, who drove 77 miles into town from upstate Wingdale,
N.Y., with her two children, said: ``It was important to see him.
It was very important for the children.'' Alluding to the
cardinal's eight-month struggle with brain cancer, she added, ``I
feel happy for him because he is at peace, and is where he always
wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Vasquez, who brought his wife and child from the Bronx,
said sadly, ``He meant a lot to us as Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   People from Mexico, the Dominican Republic, Cuba and other
Caribbean and Latin American nations, as well as many non-Hispanic
people, attended the Mass in Spanish, which was celebrated by the
Most Rev. Francisco Garmendia, auxiliary bishop of the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the politicians, to the police, to all the nationalities
represented here today, we are all brothers today in respect for
the cardinal,'' Garmendia said. ``We want to thank you, cardinal,
for all you did for us in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his homily in Spanish, the Rev. Josu Iriondo, director of the
office of Hispanic affairs for the archdiocese, spoke of the
cardinal's warm relationship with Hispanic people, of his two
visits to Cuba and of his sending food and other aid to hurricane
victims. ``He was a lover of life, a defender of life, of the sick,
of the poor,'' Iriondo said.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the 2.4 million Catholics in the archdiocese
are of Hispanic descent, church officials say, and about 100 of its
413 parishes are predominantly Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, Esperanza Morales, an official of the Tepeyac
Association of New York, which represents Mexican immigrants, said:
``He always talked to us in Spanish, and always wanted to help us.
We loved him. We want to tell him `thank you' for all he did for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, dozens of buses drew up around the cathedral
carrying hundreds of elderly and disabled men and women, many of
them in wheelchairs or moving with the aid of walkers, canes or
crutches. Also on board were hundreds of children, many mentally or
physically disabled. They were helped into the cathedral by
counselors and aides from hospitals and nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1 p.m. Mass, pew after pew was filled. Those in
wheelchairs sat in the aisles and made new rows. Many in the
audience were neither young nor disabled.
</P>
<P>
   It was relatively cool inside, out of the sun and in the subdued
light from the lofty chandeliers and the high, arched stained-glass
windows on either side of the nave. Organ music swelled and a choir
sang. Many in the crowd fingered rosaries, and some cried softly as
the Mass unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a processional hymn, ``Sing With All the Saints in
Glory,'' followed by a psalm, ``We Shall Go Up With Joy to the
House of Our God.'' The Most Rev. Robert A. Brucato, apostolic
administrator of the archdiocese, read from the Gospel of John.
</P>
<P>
   The Mass was sponsored by the archdiocesan Office of Education
and its Office of Persons with Disabilities, and Brucato spoke of
the cardinal's devotion to the disabled and to young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very concerned man, with a hands-on approach,''
Brucato said. He also spoke of the cardinal's friendship with a
police officer, Steven McDonald, who was shot and paralyzed in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   While those in the pews could not see the cardinal, television
monitors positioned here and there provided close-up views of the
body.
</P>
<P>
   After the homily, the Mass continued with the Liturgy of the
Eucharist and the preparation of the altar for communion. A hymn,
``On Eagle's Wings,'' was sung by Michael Joncas. The Eucharist
prayer, including the acclamation ``Holy, Holy, Holy,'' was
followed by the communion rites.
</P>
<P>
   Another hymn, ``I am the Bread of Life,'' was sung by Suzanne
Toolan. The concluding rites were the Prayer after Communion and
the recessional hymn ``For All the Saints.''
</P>
<P>
   As the last bars of the recessional faded and the aroma of
incense drifted through the cathedral, lines to view the cardinal
formed again and moved solemnly forward. One could hear the
shuffling of many feet, the creak of wheelchairs, the clink of
coins in a poor box. People crossed themselves at the sight of the
cardinal and again on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the sun's glare on Fifth Avenue, Tanya Melendez, an East
Village resident, asked her sons Devon, 10, and David, 9, both
students at Our Lady of Pompei School, to reflect on the cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least he's in a better place,'' Devon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's in a better place too,'' David said. ``What he's
been through has been a great life for him. He lived the way he
wanted to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
