<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRIFYING THE FANDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An hour after the park cleared, when the clubhouse was
practically empty, Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan sat in front
of his locker, staring at the day's pitching chart.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Pedro chart _ something to behold and save. An original
Pedro chart is like sheet music penned by Mozart himself, or a page
torn from Hemingway's typewriter that would someday turn up in ``A
Farewell to Arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Kerrigan rank Pedro games the way some of us might list the
top five Jack Nicholson roles or Larry Bird's best playoff moments?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I just sit back and enjoy it,'' said the coach. ``I take
it all in because I know I'm not going to see something like this
for a long time. I marvel. I really do. I'm jealous, too. I would
like to have that stuff for just one inning. Just give me one
inning or one batter.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach was only one of thousands hurling bouquets at the feet
of Pedro. And this was on a day when Martinez suffered his first
loss since last Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro fanned 17 in a 1-0 defeat at the hands of Steve Trachsel
(best known as the man who surrendered the first No. 62 to Mark
McGwire) and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays at sold-out Fenway Saturday.
One can only guess what we'd be saying and writing today if Pedro
had actually won the game. His 130-pitch (91 for strikes)
masterpiece came on the heels of a tumultuous, suspension-packed
week and thrilled the K Kult of Red Sox Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, that was some game,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams.
``You just have to write what you feel rather than me say anything.
He had phenomenal stuff . . . up, down, in, out. We just couldn't
score. Did you guys enjoy watching that kid pitch today?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Jimy, we did. It was impossible not to enjoy a tidy,
old-timey, double complete game (when's the last time we saw one of
those?), which was played in 2 hours 36 minutes (the most exciting
156 minutes in sports) and featured mound artistry normally
associated with bygone days when Walter Johnson faced Smoky Joe
Wood at state-of-the-art Fenway in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox announced that Pedro dropped his appeal of a five-game
suspension that was doled out by MVP-turned-hardball policeman
Frank Robinson. In a prudent move, Martinez will begin serving his
sentence Sunday, which means he can take the mound in Baltimore
Friday pitching with one extra day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck to the O's. They'll be facing a man who is 13-1
(including playoffs) since Aug. 19, a man with a 2000 record of 5-1
with a 1.22 ERA, 67 strikeouts, and 9 walks in 44 1/3 innings. At
this hour it feels like Pedro and Randy Johnson could start the
All-Star Game and post zeros deep into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays can hit. Tampa's lineup includes Greg Vaughn,
Jose Canseco, Fred McGriff, and Vinny Castilla. Castilla whiffed
four times. After striking out three times, Vaughn drove home the
run when he slapped a curveball to left-center with Dave Martinez
on second and two out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tip my hat to him,'' said Pedro. ``Greg Vaughn put up a good
battle. I have nothing to regret. I would take that outing again
against anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt he had better stuff on that starry night last
September in New York when he punched out 17 of the world champion
Yankees. But it was difficult to remember another game in which so
many righthanded batters buckled their knees and froze as
curveballs whirred across the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Steve ``Psycho'' Lyons, in from the press box for Fox TV, said,
``I was playing center field the night Roger (Clemens) struck out
20 and I've never seen so many hitters fooled like this today.''
</P>
<P>
   We have come to expect nothing less. There's a buzz in the
streets outside Fenway on days when Pedro pitches. Fans walk to the
park expecting something wonderful to happen. It's a festival of K
cards with a sprinkling of Dominican flags. Rarely are the legions
disappointed. Saturday they stood and cheered Pedro when he walked
in from right field after completing his warmups. It was a
referendum of sorts _ Sox fans voting yes on the question of
whether he should have retaliated in Cleveland. The Nation stood
again after Martinez retired John Flaherty on a comebacker for his
final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are supposed to have fun with it and I'm glad I'm able to
supply some of the stuff they expect,'' said Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed no regret about the end of his winning streak, or
the waste of a 17-strikeout performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally tip my hat to Vaughn,'' he said. ``There's no
whining. No crying in baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
