<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PEDRO-SUSPENSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEAL OF SUSPENSION DROPPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a Red Sox spokesman came into the press box in the ninth
inning Saturday afternoon and said general manager Dan Duquette had
an announcement to make, everyone knew what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said that pitcher Pedro Martinez was dropping the
appeal of his five-game suspension and would serve it, beginning
Sunday. By doing so, Martinez will retain his spot in the rotation,
delaying his next start by only one day, to Friday in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was suspended by Frank Robinson, Major League
Baseball's vice president for on-field operations, after he hit
Roberto Alomar of the Indians with a pitch in the eighth inning
last Sunday in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In the same inning, Cleveland pitcher Charles Nagy had hit Jose
Offerman, in apparent retaliation for a knockdown pitch Martinez
threw at Cleveland catcher Einar Diaz in the seventh. Both teams
were warned after Nagy hit Offerman, and Martinez was automatically
ejected, along with manager Jimy Williams, when he hit Alomar in
the backside.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Robinson announced Martinez was fined and
suspended and Nagy fined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro Martinez did withdraw the appeal of his suspension,
which will allow him to take his regular turn in the rotation,''
Duquette said. ``This was the most common-sense way to resolve the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette spoke with Martinez Saturday morning in a back room of
the Red Sox clubhouse. The GM said that while Martinez would have
had a ``strong case,'' neither the pitcher nor the team wanted to
risk him losing time while it was being heard. A hearing on the
appeal had been tentatively scheduled for Wednesday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no guarantee that they would make a decision the
same day,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had no comment on the matter. Catcher Jason Varitek
said he was not surprised the matter did not distract Martinez from
pitching brilliantly in a 1-0 loss to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't think that would change his focus,'' Varitek said.
``I wouldn't expect that from him. That was something that was out
of his control. The only thing he could do was give it his best
shot and he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8017 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-BBNOTES-BRUSHBACK     05-06 2006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-BRUSHBACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUSHBACKS AREN'T THROWBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Kibler, who was a highly respected umpire in the National
League for a quarter of a century before reluctantly retiring in
1989, said he was having lunch Friday near his home in Southern
California when he ran into Irv Noren, the former first baseman and
outfielder who played for six teams, including the Senators and
Yankees, in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him, `Can you believe these guys nowadays?' ''
Kibler said. ```A pitcher throws a pitch 2 inches inside, and
hitters want to charge the mound.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Irv told me a story about when he was with the Senators, they
were playing with Detroit, and Virgil Trucks was on the mound. `I
was in the box, and I just scraped the dirt with my spikes,' Irv
said. `Trucks said to me, you better dig a little deeper, because
in a couple of minutes, you're going to be lying in it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of pitches later, and Trucks knocked him on his back.
Irv wasn't sure who the umpire was, he thinks it was Bill McGowan,
but the umpire said to him, `What are you going to do, young man?'
Irv said to him, `I think I'll stay right here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The story, of course, underscores the place the knockdown pitch,
the brushback pitch, the beanball pitch have had forever in the
culture of baseball, a culture Frank Robinson has been commissioned
to change by the lords of the realm.
</P>
<P>
   It may be an impossible task, as the uneven hand of Robinson's
justice demonstrated last week. Does Pedro Martinez have the right
to move a hitter off the plate? Of course. Did his pitch come
dangerously close to Einar Diaz's head, when he could have
accomplished the same purpose by throwing at a lower latitude?
Absolutely. Were the Indians justified in their anger? Imagine the
Sox' reaction if Bartolo Colon ever comes that close to Nomar
Garciaparra's head, and you have your answer.
</P>
<P>
   Was Charles Nagy justified in throwing at the next Red Sox
batter to come to the plate after the Diaz knockdown? By the
unwritten code by which the game is played, yes. Was Dan Duquette
correct in his assertion that plate umpire Tim Tschida could have
ejected Nagy then and there? Indeed, there is plenty of precedent.
Was Martinez reckless when he hit Robbie Alomar, knowing he would
be tossed for doing so? Yes. Did everyone in a Sox uniform think
Pedro was merely standing up for one of his own? You know the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez gets suspended, pending his appeal; Nagy gets a token
fine. And no one is satisfied that such an incident will be avoided
in the future. Indeed, both Sox manager Jimy Williams and Tigers
manager Phil Garner suggested that teams may adopt the strategy of
baiting Martinez as a way to get him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly been an area of trouble for a lot of years,''
Kibler said. ``When I first came to the big leagues _ I stayed for
good in '65 _ players handled it themselves. If a batter wanted to
go (charge the mound), he could. (Willie) Mays was knocked down by
everyone in the world, and he never charged the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem today is you only have one pitcher on a
staff with good control, who if he wants to move a guy off the
plate will throw at his arm or his leg, not at his chin. The other
guys may aim low, and the pitch is high.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildness, of course, was not the issue for Martinez, who has the
best control in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bob) Gibson, he wouldn't throw at you unless something had
happened in the game,'' Kibler said. ``I remember one game in
Dodger Stadium, Dick Stello was umpiring behind the plate, and
Gibson threw one 6 feet over the batter's head. Stello went to the
mound and told Gibson that was a fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gibson later met with Chub Feeney (the National League
president) and said, `Let me ask you a question. If you think I was
throwing at that guy, do you think I would have thrown it 6 feet
over his head?' Chub said, `No.' `Then why am I getting fined? If
I'm going to get fined, I'm going to drill the guy the next time.'
Chub told him, `Forget it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kibler is skeptical that the knockdown pitch can be legislated
out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Chub 20 years ago, `Now we're warning the pitchers,
warning the dugouts,' but then the next guy who comes inside a
little bit, we're in the jackpot, because we've got to throw the
pitcher out of the game. That puts all the pressure on us. Let the
players handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Players seldom charged the mound, Kibler said, because the
offending pitcher knew the next time he came to the plate, he would
invite retaliation. That, of course, can't happen in the American
League, where the designated hitter precludes pitchers coming to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, Kibler said, may have economic reasons for asking
the commissioner to legislate the brushback pitches and brawls that
inevitably accompany them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners may have said, `We've got to protect the players
because they're making too much money,' '' Kibler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, I remember when Gibson was pitching, guys on the
opposing team would say to each other, `Don't mess with Gibson
today, because he's not going to take it out on you, but on the
next guy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these things should be taken out of the umpires' hands
and put in the players' hands,'' Kibler said. ``They're all making
millions of dollars. If they want to kill each other, go ahead. The
umpires can't control it, because it's not fair. You're going to
give the first guy (who throws at a hitter) a free shot, and then
throw the next guy out of the game? That's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the umpires can do is what Duquette was advocating
last week. The umpires are empowered by the rules to issue a
warning, or eject a pitcher, if they suspect he was deliberately
throwing at a hitter. If Tschida thought Martinez was aiming at
Diaz's head, he could have warned him immediately. And he certainly
could have tossed Nagy for his obvious nailing of Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because umpires don't like the rule (about warnings),
sometimes they let it go a couple of batters too long, and then you
have a donnybrook,'' said Kibler. ``If the umpire says, `I'm
stopping it right now,' maybe you'd have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget Offerman, who could have defused the
situation by picking himself up and taking his base, accepting that
Nagy plunking him on the hip was payback for Diaz eating dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it would have been done, back in the good old
days,'' Kibler said with a chuckle. ``Back in the good old days,
when pitchers were pitchers, hitters were hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   And everyone knew his place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pen writes the story
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch has a sprained left wrist and was looking at
going on the disabled list for the first time in his career. Ricky
Ledee, the left fielder, is barely above the Mendoza Line. David
Cone has been whacked around, Roger Clemens has been inconsistent,
and even El Duque, Orlando Hernandez, was lit up by the Orioles
Friday night. And still, the Yankees roll on with the best record
in the American League. ``It's their bullpen,'' a major league
scout said. ``They've got the best group of relievers in baseball,
and that's even before they get to the closer. (Mike) Stanton is
throwing better than I've ever seen him.'' Stanton, the Bombers'
lefthanded specialist, qualifies as the Ex-Sox Player of the Week,
as the Yankee bullpen breezed through April with a 7-0 record.
According to the Elias Sports Bureau, it is the first time
anybody's bullpen has made it through April undefeated. Stanton
already has made 15 appearances and began the weekend with a 2.31
ERA. In 11 2/3 innings, he'd allowed just 11 hits and two walks
with a dozen strikeouts. Until the Orioles cuffed them around
Friday night, the pinstriped pen had a 1.20 ERA in its previous
dozen games. (Of course, New York still won Friday, on a Jorge
Posada home run in the ninth.) Stanton, Jeff Nelson, Jason
Grimsley, and Ramiro Mendoza, the swingman, give the Bombers depth
and quality no other team can match. The scout, incidentally, said
do not be fooled by Clemens's record. ``He's throwing the ball real
well, in terms of his velocity and command,'' the scout said. ``He
doesn't have the late action on his ball that he had earlier in his
career, but he's still effective. Cone has shown nothing, but I
wrote him off early last year, too, and look how he bounced back.
He's one of those special guys.'' . . . Padres pitcher Woody
Williams, who was a teammate of Cone in Toronto, was found to have
an aneurysm in his shoulder in virtually the identical spot where
Cone had his, under the left armpit. Williams is expected to be out
almost three months after having surgery last week. Cone called
with support. Williams said he noticed something was wrong the day
after his first start, in New York, when his wrist was red, sore,
and swollen. ``I didn't think anything of it,'' he said. ``The
second start, my fingers were numb and cold. And those last three
starts were hard to get through. If I'd kept pitching, chances are
I might've lost my hand.'' Cone was the same age (33) as Williams
when he had surgery in 1995; in his first start back, he threw
no-hit ball for seven innings. ``It's a scary-sounding word,'' Cone
said, ``but it is fixable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's at-bats dry up
</P>
<P>
   Another Padre still hurting is Tony Gwynn, who has had fluid
drained from his knee five times. The eight-time batting champion,
who is on the DL, is hitting just .186, and it's almost certain
that the soon-to-be 40-year-old won't get the 502 at-bats he needs
to kick in next season's $4 million contract extension . . . The
early returns suggest that these Atlanta Braves may be stronger
than ever. The 15-game winning streak, a club record, was the
longest in the National League since Mays was a rookie, in 1951.
The pitching staff had a 1.98 ERA during the streak while the
offense not only outscored the opposition, 77-32, but showed a
knack for scoring late, pushing across 13 runs in the eighth inning
during the six-game trip that ended their streak. And a look at the
schedule suggests the Braves won't be slowing down soon. Starting
this weekend with the Phillies, the Braves do not face a team with
a winning record until they meet the Yankees June 1. And of their
next 19 games, the Braves play a dozen against teams currently in
last place, including six with the Phillies and three each with San
Diego and Milwaukee. Andres Galarraga is the great comeback story
of this or any year, catcher Javy Lopez has returned from a
difficult knee surgery as good as ever, and while John Rocker
continues to alienate anyone with a double-digit IQ, he had been
untouchable on the hill until Friday. Still, the difference between
this club and its predecessors may be the depth of its bench. Bobby
Bonilla, Wally Joyner, Trenidad Hubbard, and sensational kid
shortstop Rafael Furcal have joined Eddie Perez and Keith Lockhart
to give Bobby Cox more weapons than he's ever had . . . The Twins,
picking four spots ahead of the Red Sox in the 1994 draft, made
second baseman Todd Walker their first selection. The Sox took
Garciaparra. Last week, Walker, who hit .316 two seasons ago, was
sent down to the minors. He has asked to be traded, claiming
manager Tom Kelly has no confidence in his defense or his ability
to hit lefties. He's right on both counts. At the time he was sent
to Salt Lake City, Walker was batting .234, just .150 with runners
in scoring position . . . Who said it? ``Someday we'll wake up in
baseball. The brushback pitch is where it's got to stop. This isn't
the grand old game. We can't have guys throwing 95 mile-per-hour
weapons at someone's head. Baseball better get it stopped.''
Answer: Yes, it was a Clevelander, but he doesn't work for the
Tribe. Those were George Steinbrenner's words two years ago, after
Armando Benitez, then of the Orioles, hit Tino Martinez in the back
with a fastball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
