<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-YASHIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO GET MOVING ON YASHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Senators last week hinted that they finally might trade
franchise center Alexei Yashin. Ottawa general manager Marshall
Johnston didn't make a Yashin deal sound like a fait accompli, but
the fact that he put the suggestion out there is a sure sign of
what's to come in the next few weeks _ the hottest sweepstakes
since the Quebec-Philadelphia deal that landed Eric Lindros on
Broad Street in '92.
</P>
<P>
   Yashin, in St. Petersburg, Russia, for the World Championships,
promptly and predictably responded to Johnston's hints with an ``I
love Ottawa'' campaign with the media. Great place, a great hockey
town, full of great people, he said. What he could have added, but
didn't: ``And I can't wait to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the sincerity. While he spoke, Yashin's girlfriend, Carol
Alt, punctuated his comments with what were chronicled as soft
kisses on his neck. If I weren't still sitting here with my
shinguards in place, another long season drawing to a conclusion as
I type this, it would be enough to make my knees buckle.
</P>
<P>
   The time has come, no matter what an arbitrator rules later this
month about his contract, for Yashin to be kissed goodbye by the
Senators.
</P>
<P>
   True, he is one great talent, and it's that talent that offered
him the comfort level to thumb his nose at a contract worth $3.6
million and demand one of two things from the Senators _ either a
lot more money or a trade to another club that would pay him a lot
more money. But people should live up to their signatures. If your
name means nothing, what does? Yashin showed the world, especially
those Ottawa fans he now praises, that honor is as old-world as the
one-time Russian empire.
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto later this month, arbitrator William Holden will
decide whether Yashin, suspended by the Senators early last
November for failing to report, still owes the team a year's work
at the agreed-upon price of $3.6 million. Holden's decision, said
Johnston, could influence whether the team seeks to move him.
</P>
<P>
   But Holden's ruling truly will be nothing more than part of the
negotiating price when the Senators open the bidding. In fact, even
if Holden doesn't declare Yashin a Group 2 free agent, and says he
has to work a year for the $3.6 million, Yashin no doubt will
insist that any club acquiring him just tear up the arbitrator's
decision. He already has lost a year's pay. He isn't going anywhere
for a deal of less than, say, three years at $8 million or better.
</P>
<P>
   The questions now are: (1) Who will pay him that? (2) What will
that team have to surrender?
</P>
<P>
   The first question isn't so tough. There are always clubs
willing to pay big dough for elite players, no matter how much they
complain about the salary drain. He's a malcontent when it comes to
money, but Yashin is an elite player, unique in that he has the
slick moves of a savvy pivot and the booming slapper of a power
forward. Think: Mike Modano-Cam Neely hybrid.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Senators have to think of landing an elite
player. That's always the trickiest part. When it came time for the
Oilers to deal Wayne Gretzky in '88, when he was right around
Yashin's current age, Oilers owner Peter Pocklington was only too
happy to take more in cash ($15 million) than in player stock
(Jimmy Carson, Martin Gelinas) and draft picks. But Ottawa needs a
big name in return, someone who can bring some real grit to the
lineup and make the Senators a bona fide contender.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of prospective swaps, as viewed here: Zigmund Palffy,
Los Angeles; Sergei Fedorov, Detroit; Keith Tkachuk, Phoenix; Teemu
Selanne, Anaheim; Vincent Lecavalier, Tampa Bay; and Lindros,
Philadelphia. Of the bunch, Tkachuk and Lindros by far would bring
the most grit. The real prize to acquire from Anaheim would be Paul
Kariya, and he's only a year younger than Yashin, but the Ducks
wouldn't be that daring, and the Senators don't want his price tag
($10 million a year).
</P>
<P>
   Nearly eight years later, wouldn't the Flyers love to have a
do-over for the Lindros deal? Remember what they gave up for
L'Enfant Terrible: Peter Forsberg, Steve Duchesne, Kerry Huffman,
Mike Ricci, Ron Hextall, Chris Simon, and a pair of first-round
picks (Joceyln Thibault and Nolan Baumgartner). Yeow. At the time,
Lindros was 19 years old, touted as a Cup kingpin for 10-12 years.
Now he's 27, still without a Cup, and his long list of injuries
makes him a very questionable commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Yashin's shelf life is no more than 5-7 years now. He's not
going to bring Ottawa a Lindroslike ransom, but don't worry, the
bidding will be high. It would be even higher if Yashin's play were
as important to him as his pay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wrong number
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Roenick has one year remaining on his deal in Phoenix,
which puts him on target to be an unrestricted free agent July 1,
2001. His Boston-based agent, Neil Abbott, said Friday that Coyote
GM Bobby Smith called in December to get a general feel what it
would take to extend Roenick's deal. ``I gave him an idea,'' said
Abbott, ``and never heard back.'' No doubt Roenick will want
something similar to what the Red Wings recently handed Brendan
Shanahan: $26 million over four years, with a club option at $6.5
million for a fifth year. ``I wouldn't call that a stretch,'' said
Abbott. Don't be surprised if the Desert Dogs deal Roenick this
summer, if only because it may be impossible to find anyone to take
on Tkachuk's $8.3 million pact. They could wheel Roenick for a
young, cheap prospect and use the savings to bring back No. 1
goalie Nikolai Khabibulin . . . Bryan Lewis, the NHL's supervisor
of officials, estimates that referees Dan Marouelli and Rob Shick
each skated 14.2 miles in Philly's 2-1 victory over Pittsburgh
Thursday night, settled in the fifth OT. Asked what kind of
overtime compensation the two whistleblowers would receive, Lewis
said, ``Oh, about the same OT a writer gets in a game like that.''
. . . Count Bruins Hall of Fame goaltender Gerry Cheevers among
those who hold Boston University netminder Rick DePietro in high
regard. ``What I've seen of him, he's terrific,'' said Cheevers.
``He always seems to be in position. He handles the puck well. He's
confident. And he's got charisma up the ying-yang.'' DiPietro last
week signed the papers that make him eligible for next month's
entry draft, forfeiting his final three years at BU. Many scouts
figure he'll get grabbed in the top 10. ``Just about every team out
there would have to be interested,'' said Cheevers. ``Remember, if
you answer your goaltending situation with a 20-year-old, you've
taken away a big headache for a very long time.'' . . . How badly
do the Senators need grit? Their top trio, Radek Bonk-Magnus
Arvedson-Marian Hossa, was held without a point in the first-round
playoff loss to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pricing himself out
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for unrestricted free agent Tom Barrasso to be back
tending net in Ottawa. Overall, he did his job, but reports out of
Ottawa have him looking for a two-year deal worth about $3.5
million per year . . . The new GM in Calgary, replacing Al Coates,
most likely will be Mike Murphy, longtime pal of Flames president
Ron Bremner. This past season, Murphy has shared NHL discipline
duties with Colin Campbell . . . The Sabres have to figure out how
to protect both goalies, Dominik Hasek and Martin Biron, in the
expansion draft or risk losing a decent position player _ maybe
Richard Smehlik on defense or Erik Rasmussen up front. Unless, of
course, they wheel Hasek. But they wouldn't do that, would they? .
. . USA Hockey abruptly fired Jeff Jackson and his top aide, Bob
Mancini, a major shakeup for the national development team based in
Ann Arbor, Mich. Jackson, ex- of Lake Superior State, had been with
the program since its inception. One name to keep in mind as a
possible new coach: former NHL forward Mike Eaves, now back in
Minnesota after getting canned as one of Kevin Constantine's
assistants in Pittsburgh . . . Word around Montreal is that
ex-Buffalo goalie Bob Sauve could replace Rejean Houle as the
Canadiens general manager. Houle is still on the job, but has been
widely rumored for weeks to be headed out the door. Sauve and
Pierre Lacroix, the Avalanche GM, once were partners as player
agents, but Sauve took over the job in full when Lacroix was hired
away as the Nordiques boss. How about Habs coach Alain Vigneault
making it to the short list, along with Joel Quenneville (St.
Louis) and Ron Wilson, for the Jack Adams Award as Coach of the
Year? The Habs remained in the hunt for a playoff berth right to
the end, despite 500-plus man-games lost to injury. If he wins it,
it wouldn't be the Jack Adams, said Vigneault, ``It would be the
Patch Adams.'' . . . The Rangers gave Pittsburgh owner Mario
Lemieux a call for permission to speak to Craig Patrick about
returning to Manhattan for another stint as Blueshirts GM. A waste
of a call, said Patrick, because he's too happy doing the job in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   See you later
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, the Flyers said that Ulf Samuelsson's
sprained knee will keep him out of the remainder of the postseason.
That may explain the void you've been feeling this spring . . .
Deal of deals: The Tampa Bay Lightning next season will price 1,500
seats at $10 apiece and hundreds more at $8 a pop. This is a
franchise reported to have given away in excess of 100,000 tickets
last season . . . The Hurricanes believe they could have as many as
seven kids from their farm team, the Cincinnati Cyclones, playing
for them in 2000-01. That's just what the Bruins were thinking
about their crop of Baby B's last summer. Meanwhile defenseman Paul
Coffey is an unrestricted free agent. If he doesn't re-sign in
Raleigh, look for him to surface in Toronto, where the Leafs will
have to cover themselves if Bryan Berard can't make it back from
his eye injury . . . While he's been away fighting the World battle
in St. Petersburg, Bruins defenseman Hal Gill has slipped a notch
on Jaromir Jagr's belt. Jagr now says Philly's Chris Therien, 6-5,
230, is the toughest blue liner he faces . . . Look for Atlanta to
move netminder Norm Maracle and find someone to put the heat on No.
1 Damian Rhodes. The plan is for ex-UMass-Lowell netminder Scott
Fankhouser to spend at least a full year in the minors . . . Former
Bruin Dave Ellett won't be asked back to St. Louis. Look for
Stephane Richer and Bay Stater Jim Campbell also to get their
Bluenote pink slips . . . Now that Bill Ranford has retired, the
Oilers need someone to provide relief for Tommy Salo, who played in
70 games this season. Don't be surprised if Oiler boss Glen Sather
calls Boston and inquires about getting Rob Tallas . . . Edmonton's
chief scout out West, Lorne Davis, believes DiPietro is the best
goalie he's seen in the draft since Grant Fuhr (selected No. 8
overall by Edmonton in '81) . . . In his playing days, Cheevers was
known for his general disdain for practice. Asked recently how his
golf game was progressing, he said, ``Not bad. I've got some new
clubs, and I've got to get out there and practice. If you know me
and practice, I'll be done at 11.'' Time of the quote: 9:53 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
