<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-NASCAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CUTTING CORNERS ON NASCAR'S OVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are the barbarians at the gate. They are the ``outside
influences'' infecting the NASCAR Winston Cup Series with tempting
offers of performance-enhancing products that, they claim, are
invisible to NASCAR inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   They are the cheaters, the scofflaws, the bandits corrupting the
sport with promises of easy circumvention of NASCAR rules.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NASCAR sent a message when it hit driver Jeremy
Mayfield, car owner Michael Kranefuss, and crew chief Peter
Sospenzo with a series of severe penalties for using an illegal
fuel additive in an April 16 race at Talladega, Ala. Mayfield's No.
12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus won the pole position but finished 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors impounded the car following the race and detected the
additive _ or oxygenate _ that enriched the fuel mixture with
additional pure oxygen. It had been put in the tank, NASCAR
discovered, by an unidentified crew member during Mayfield's final
pit stop. Mayfield and Kranefuss were absolved of complicity in the
wrongdoing by Mike Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief
operating officer, but they were penalized nonetheless. Mayfield
was stripped of 151 Winston Cup points, dropping him from seventh
to 14th in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when my father used to do it, when he'd take off his
belt,'' said Helton. ``He'd give you two whacks for what you did,
and another so that you wouldn't do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield won last Sunday's NAPA 500 at California Speedway,
becoming NASCAR's 10th different winner this season. That victory
was allowed to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Kranefuss, who operates the team, co-owned by Roger Penske, also
was docked 151 owners' points and fined $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sospenzo was suspended for three races (until June 6) and hit
with an additional $25,000 fine Thursday when the roof of
Mayfield's winning car was found to be under the 51-inch minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a whole lot you can say under the circumstances,''
Kranefuss said in a statement. ``Mistakes were made and there were
certainly some grave errors in judgment. We won the pole at
Talladega by following the rules, which NASCAR confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, we accept the penalty, we have taken
disciplinary action within our team, and we apologize to our fans,
our sponsors, NASCAR and the other teams. We will make sure nothing
like this will ever happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can NASCAR prevent some snake oil salesman from offering
a team a ``wonder product''? These are independent schemers who
operate outside NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   Said Helton, ``After New Hampshire _ or `Tiregate' as a lot of
people called it a couple of years ago _ we circled back with all
the car owners and crew chiefs and explained to them what was
flying around out there, including a letter, quite frankly, that
began to get our attention on the bigger issue of people out there
making claims they could get around our rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what kind of started the process. The dilemma we face
is that our authority, basically, is limited to NASCAR members. So
we have a process where we work with NASCAR members. What we are
investigating is the possibility of NASCAR, as a company, going
after people who make erroneous allegations beyond being a member.
That's complicated and that's part of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent rules violations, Helton doesn't think there is a
cheating epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's massive or overwhelming at this point,'' he
said, ``but even the tire situation or the fuel situation that
we've had in the last 18 months is enough for NASCAR to pay serious
enough attention to it to do the right thing by the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happens, for the most part, the teams are smarter
than the sellers are. I think the teams understand that this really
can't happen, but if you hear it enough, then you start believing
in it, and our concern is people being that cavalier with the topic
and the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say in this particular incident with the 12 car that
there's a chain of reactions that leads us to understand that this
was not a case of someone coming by the shop selling snake oil and
making claims against NASCAR's rule-making process. This is a good
deal different situation that we found out during the
investigation, but it still brings to light a bigger issue that we
have a great deal of interest in following up on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fortunate to be alive
</P>
<P>
   Formula One driver David Coulthard will be back behind the wheel
for Sunday's Spanish Grand Prix in Barcelona after he, his fiancee
Heidi Wichlinski, and personal trainer Andy Matthews survived a
crash landing of their private jet in Lyon, France. The aircraft's
two pilots were killed in the crash. Coulthard, a 29-year-old
Scotsman, spoke Thursday about the harrowing crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish to express our heartfelt sympathies to the families of
the two pilots, David Saunders and Dan Worley, who behaved with the
utmost professionalism throughout the incident,'' said Coulthard,
who was traveling from England to Nice, France, when the Learjet
developed engine problems. ``During the flight the co-pilot
informed us that we had an engine problem and would have to make an
emergency landing at Lyon, which would be in about 10 minutes time.
Prior to the landing, we had time to prepare ourselves in the
`brace' position.
</P>
<P>
   ``On impact, a wing tank ruptured and there was a fire on the
right side of the aircraft. When the plane finally came to rest,
the front of the cockpit had broken free from the main fuselage. At
this point we established that the only way out was through the
front of the aircraft. Andy led the way through the debris, and as
this part of the aircraft was 3 or 4 feet above the ground, I
followed Andy out so that we could help Heidi get down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we were all clear of the plane, I returned to see whether
there was anything we could do for the pilots. But there was
nothing to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in driver's seat
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser Jr. ended a five-year drought in open-wheel racing when
he won the Vegas.com 500 April 22 at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
Unser, who was let go from his CART ride with Penske's outfit last
year, was reunited with former boss Rick Galles on the Northern
Lights Series Indy Racing League circuit. ``When Roger made the
announcement in Detroit about his two (new) drivers, Rick Galles
called me the next day,'' Unser said. ``There are people in this
world that never give up on you, and Rick Galles is one of those
people.'' Last week, Unser and Galles, who teamed to win the 1992
Indy 500, returned to the fabled Brickyard for an open test
session. It was Unser's first time in an open-wheel car at Indy
since his ill-fated qualifying attempt in 1995. ``When I pulled out
of the pits, it was great,'' Unser said. ``It was great to be back.
All the same feelings _ you know, the tradition, the heritage of
this place _ just came screaming back and it was wonderful.'' . . .
New Hampshire International Speedway will kick off its 2000 season
Saturday with a 200-lap Busch Series and 125-lap Busch North Series
doubleheader. Drivers will square off on the softball diamond in a
benefit game Thursday at 6:30 p.m. at Memorial Field in Concord,
N.H. An autograph session will take place at 5:30 . . . Jerry
Marquis, of East Windsor, Conn., will be juggling a hectic schedule
this season, attempting to campaign cars in the Busch North,
Featherlite Modified, and SK Modified Series at Stafford Motor
Speedway in Stafford Springs, Conn., where he is the reigning New
England Region Winston Weekly Racing Series champion. ``It makes it
more difficult to focus on one or the other, where you have to
actually concentrate on two different styles of open-wheel cars and
then your full-fendered car with the Busch North Series, so it
gives you three different kinds of scenarios in racing,'' said
Marquis, who also pulled triple duty in 1996 and parts of 1998.
``Basically, I'm kind of used to that and I was able to adjust my
driving style and adjust the tempos of both series by doing that on
a two-night-a-week basis. I think that actually physically trained
me to be prepared and be able to handle that kind of a challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
