<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-IBFCOURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBF TAKING BIGGEST HITS IN COURTROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While last week's heavyweight title fight between
undisputed champion Lennox Lewis and challenger Michael Grant
hogged the headlines in Manhattan, just down the Jersey Turnpike a
more important fight was going on in a Newark courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is fighting to lock the doors of the
International Boxing Federation and put its president, Robert Lee
Sr., and several accomplices behind bars for taking bribes and
selling ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Beavers, a former chairman of the IBF rating committee,
spent most of last week ratting out former accomplices, telling
stories of how he stuffed cash in his sock and delivered it to Lee
in a hotel room for ratings considerations. The FBI caught the
transaction on videotape, but the judge refused to allow the tape
as evidence, claiming Lee had a right to assume privacy in his
hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Bob Arum, among those who will testify to having paid
such bribes, told federal investigators he paid $100,000 to get
unrated Axel Schultz approved as an opponent for George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   During an HBO-sponsored symposium on the future of boxing,
Foreman denied that a bribe was paid. Anyone who knows how cheap
Foreman is wouldn't doubt it, but Arum admitted the money was for
that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   That the IBF was taking money hand over fist to sell its ratings
seems impossible to dispute. That the World Boxing Association and
World Boxing Council have conducted business in a similar fashion
may not be provable. What was significant in boxing last week was
really not the fight between Lewis and Grant but the fight between
the federal government and the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government loses this case, it's business as usual in
boxing,'' said Time Warner Sports president Seth Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other sport has some kind of apparatus to run it. It has
some kind of organization with a commissioner who has powers to
enforce the rules. Boxing is the closest thing to buccaneering left
in the world. If the government wins this case and begins to change
that, the sport will benefit greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very significant case,'' said Arum. ``The
resolution of this case, plus the enactment of the Muhammad Ali
Reform Act (championed by Arizona Sen. John McCain), bodes well for
the sport if the government wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sanctioning organizations have suffocated the growth of
boxing. So the question is not should those organizations disappear
but what to put in their place. With the proliferation of these
organizations there are now dozens of champions and no sense to any
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are strict rules in the sport but not in the business of
the sport. The rules all involve the ritualistic functions like the
weigh-in and the signing of contracts filed with the commissions
that turn out to be completely different from the real contracts
signed for a big fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, these local commissions don't have enough people
or money to police the sport. The reality is, where McCain is
moving will be a hybrid of state and federal regulation but on a
national basis. Not a federal commission but a national commission
using the association of state boxing commissions for an
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for any of that to happen, the government has to win this
case first.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum is probably right about that. So the big fight last weekend
was not really at Madison Square Garden; it was in a Newark
courthouse barely noticed by boxing fans. It's a fight that's long
from over . . . and long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   David Tua believes he has an advantage over Lewis, an advantage
most people would overlook. He's 6 inches shorter than the
6-foot-5-inch champion. Most people believe Lewis's size is his
biggest asset, but Tua has his doubts. ``Lewis for many years has
looked good against taller, bigger guys,'' Tua said after Lewis's
demolition of the 6-7 Grant. ``All he has to do is punch straight
at them. For me, he'll have to punch down. I'll slip punches, hit
him in the body, hit him in the chest. I'll see his body all night
in front of me.'' Tua, the IBF's top contender, will get his shot
at Lewis no later than November. Promoters are having preliminary
discussions for a Lewis-Tua fight, which should make for an
interesting negotiation. Kathy Duva's Main Events promotional
company represents Lewis and used to represent Tua before he jumped
to America Presents, the Dan Goossen-led promotional arm that also
represents Mike Tyson on a fight-by-fight basis. ``No disrespect,
but Lennox is tailor-made for me,'' said Tua (35-1, 30 KOs).
``Lennox doesn't have a problem when his punches are going straight
ahead to a man that is standing directly in front of him on the
same level. When he's punching down, the angle of his punches don't
work as well. Lennox can't box a smaller man on the inside. He'll
have to try to distance himself with a jab, which he will not be
able to do with my pressure. I'll be the one working on the inside.
His reach will be useless.'' . . . One person buying into Tua's
theory is a guy who looks a lot like him _ Tyson. He told a British
reporter, ``Tua's angry, mean, and hungry. He's got that look in
his eye like he's ready to kill someone. I hope it's not Lewis,
because I want to end Lewis.'' Tyson is supposed to be fighting in
June or July against Lou Savarese in Italy, but the fight has
already been postponed twice because Tyson wasn't ready . . . TVKO
reported a disappointing estimate of only 375,000 buys for the
Lewis-Grant fight. But TVKO senior vice president Mark Taffet
claimed the fight ``performed in the manner we expected,'' because
they didn't expect much. Lewis may be the undisputed champion, but
fans don't want to pay to watch him fight . . . Of a fight with
Tyson, Tua has a promotional suggestion. ``That fight should be on
Independence Day because it would be fireworks,'' Tua said. ``We're
both strong guys. One from a different era and one from the present
era but with the same style of fighting.'' . . . Junior Jones is
talking about retiring, less than a week after his TKO loss to IBF
featherweight champion Paul Ingle. Jones told friends his legs no
longer allow him to do what he used to do and that it is time to
stop. Jones fought bravely against Ingle but could not keep up with
the young Brit's relentless attack. Trainer Teddy Atlas got Jones
to the 11th round using a style that kept Jones in the fight early
and opened it up later when time was running out. It nearly worked.
Jones dropped Ingle in the ninth round, but when he didn't finish
him, Atlas knew the rest of the night would be difficult. One funny
moment in the fight occurred after Ingle was knocked down. Gary
Gittelson, Jones's manager, screamed at Atlas, ``You did it!'' When
he saw Ingle get up on sturdy legs, Atlas turned to Gittelson and
said calmly, ``This fight is far from over.'' . . . Undefeated
light heavyweight champion Darius Michalczewski was asked if he
might want to see his two sons, ages 8 and 13, become boxers. ``In
my mind, the environment is not appropriate for them to become
boxers,'' Michalczewski said. ``It's because they have such a great
life. I would like to see my son a world champion but I know how
hard it is. If I have the chance to advise him against doing it,
then I will. He can work out a bit, but he doesn't need to become a
boxer. One boxer in the family is enough. They should continue
learning and improve their mind. Not everybody must become an
athlete. Both are very intelligent boys. They are very good at
school. They have the chance to continue learning because they
don't have to worry about financial problems. I would love to have
a son who is a professional world champion, but I couldn't bear if
he would get knocked out. This would break my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Here's Sugar Ray Leonard's view of how people see the sport that
made him rich and famous. ``People have this misconception about
boxing and who does it,'' Leonard said. ``A lot of people think the
kids are bad, in gangs or something, but in reality, the sport
instills discipline, character, and there are a lot of good people
in boxing. I really wish it didn't have the image it has.'' . . .
According to Lewis, Evander Holyfield ``is a person that never
stuck by any rules. I don't need to call him a hypocrite once
again. We've already passed that stage. He knows what he's doing.''
. . . A book written by Ali's close friend Howard Bingham claims
Ali did not win the original Supreme Court vote on his draft
registration case. ``Muhammad Ali's Greatest Fight: Cassius Clay
vs. The United States of America'' claims the original vote was 5-3
to uphold his conviction but Justice John Harlan changed his mind
and then his vote, deadlocking it at 4-4. Harlan convinced others
to change their votes, and Ali ended up with a 8-0 victory and the
freedom to return to boxing . . . New York attorney Howard Sirota
is forming a new ranking organization, with boxing writers voting
online for the top 20 fighters in the various weight classes. The
theory is this will be a far less corruptive system than the IBF,
WBC, and WBA rankings. Backed by New York Post columnist Jack
Newfield, novelist and editor Pete Hamill, and Budd Schulberg, who
wrote ``On the Waterfront,'' the idea is based on the college
football and basketball rakings. They couldn't do any worse than
the present system . . . Cuban defector and former Olympic gold
medalist Joel Casamayor has dedicated his May 21 fight for the WBA
super featherweight title to Elian Gonzalez. ``I don't like to talk
about politics but I would like to see him stay here,'' Casamayor
said. ``This boy has touched my heart. I'm dedicating my fight to
the freedom of Elian Gonzalez.'' Casamayor, who defected along with
then-Cuban national teammate Ramon Garbey, left Miami to train and
live in Las Vegas because of ``too many distractions'' in a city in
which the local Cuban community remains rabidly anti-Castro . . .
Bernard Hopkins is back on the Roy Jones-Richard Hall undercard
after promoter Murad Muhammad dumped him. HBO would not allow
Muhammad's fighter, Brian Barbosa, to fight Hopkins because he had
suffered severe cuts in his last fight and had only six weeks to
heal. After weeks of negotiations, a settlement was reached and
Hopkins will fight Syd Vanderpool . . . Give Wladimir Klitschko
credit. Although it was his brother, Vitali, who quit in the ring
against Chris Byrd because of a torn rotator cuff, Wladimir
understands the problem it created for both of them. ``I understand
what happened,'' the younger Klitschko said. ``Vitali's career has
to start over again, and so does mine. I understand people's
perception.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local bleatings
</P>
<P>
   Micky Ward's representatives met with HBO senior vice president
Lou DiBella about getting the Lowell junior welterweight on an HBO
card. Nothing has been lined up but DiBella would like to use Ward
this summer . . . John Ruiz will be outfitted by Trained 2 Survive,
the one-year-old Salem-based sports apparel company, for his June
10 fight against Holyfield. ``John Ruiz embodies the spirit of our
company,'' said Dave Dunton, founder of Trained 2 Survive. ``He
more than exemplifies our philosophy that there are no excuses in
life and to believe in yourself. John liked our line, and we're
excited to be working with him on this marketing venture.
</P>
</TEXT>
