<HEADLINE>
BEATHARD MAKES A GRACIOUS EXIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just over a week ago, the NFL lost the kind of person it can ill
afford to lose. The kind of guy you find less and less in front
offices in these days of computer printouts, tight-fitting salary
caps, and bean counters making decisions based on salaries rather
than production.
</P>
<P>
   It lost a football guy. A real football guy.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why 63-year-old Bobby Beathard finally
decided to retire to his surfboard and his 12 grandchildren after
37 years in the NFL, but he still will be sorely missed. Not only
in San Diego, where he had been general manager since 1990 and
built a Super Bowl team in 1995, but throughout the insular world
of professional football.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a drafting guru, Beathard never got full of
himself when he was an integral part of building seven Super Bowl
teams _ in Kansas City, Miami, Washington, and San Diego. Because
of that, he never got too down the last few years when his drafting
acumen was called into question by people who knew far less than he
did and the Chargers failed to return to the Super Bowl, plagued by
more than a few drafting gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   The last big name he picked may prove to be his biggest bust, in
fact. Ryan Leaf has shown nothing but immaturity and a bad temper
since coming into the NFL. But even though he may be a bust, he was
not a mistake, and Beathard went out knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   Although he may have traded away his team's future to get Leaf
with the second pick of the 1998 draft, it was not a mistake. Leaf
was the wrong guy, but there was no other guy with his talent
except the guy taken ahead of him, Peyton Manning. Although he
never said it publicly, Beathard, had he had his druthers, would
have taken Manning, and had that happened, he'd probably still be
working in San Diego, but so what?
</P>
<P>
   Beathard did the right thing the day he traded up to grab Leaf,
just as he did the right thing most of the days he was running NFL
war rooms. He wasn't right all the time _ nobody is _ but he was
right most of the time, and few personnel men can claim that, so he
goes out with his head high and facing the sun and the waves he
still loves to ride.
</P>
<P>
   He also goes out the way he acted most of the time he was in
power _ with unerring grace.
</P>
<P>
   When asked at the March owners' meetings about Leaf _ as rumors
of Beathard's impending retirement were already circulating _
Beathard said, ``I'm rooting for him to pull it together. Not for
me. For himself and for the Chargers.''
</P>
<P>
   This was said about an infantile, petulant, 21-year-old
multimillionaire who hadn't done a thing for Beathard and the
Chargers but make them look foolish. This was typical of Beathard,
who was no Pollyanna but no Hannibal Lecter, either.
</P>
<P>
   So don't believe the stories that Leaf's failures and lousy
personality drove Beathard to despair. Don't believe the six No. 1s
he traded during his time in San Diego for players who seldom
worked out did it, either.
</P>
<P>
   It simply was his time for leaving, and so he left. Left with a
few tears in his eyes during his final press conference, but with
his head held high.
</P>
<P>
   As it should have been.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Charger in charge
</P>
<P>
   It figures that Beathard was not replaced by Billy Devaney, his
longtime assistant in personnel matters, but rather by Ed McGuire,
the Chargers' capologist. Devaney will head the scouting department
and run the draft but he will report to McGuire . . . How sick is
American society? Consider this. According to All Stretched Out
Limousine Service in Linthicum, Md., the Lincoln Navigator that
Baltimore Ravens linebacker Ray Lewis was using the night he
allegedly was involved in the murder of two men is now the hottest
car the company has. The stretch SUV that seats 14 is rented almost
every night, even though it costs $1,500 for eight hours. It also
was the featured car in the Ferndale (Md.) 2000 Day parade,
sandwiched between fire trucks and convertibles with Miss Anne
Arundel County inside. All bullet holes and bloodstains have been
cleaned up, so riders have to use their imagination when it comes
to what happened Super Bowl night in Atlanta. The car will reappear
in Atlanta in three weeks when the jury in the murder trial takes a
look at it . . . This story shouldn't surprise you. Denver bad boy
linebacker Bill Romanowski got into hot water with teammate Terrell
Davis last week when he slammed into the recovering running back
during a noncontact drill without pads. It was one of the first
days Davis had worked around other players since tearing his knee
apart a year ago, and he was less than pleased with Romanowski, who
has been fined by everybody else in football for his
extracurricular activities so why not his own team? ``Romo is
Romo,'' head coach Mike Shanahan said. ``He didn't even know what
he did.'' Well, Davis knew . . . The Miami Dolphins have altered
their defensive set and lineup to try to get more of a pass rush
out of quick but undersized linemen Jason Taylor and Lorenzo
Bromell. Head coach Dave Wannstedt has moved Bromell from tackle to
end on the opposite side of Taylor. Both will play farther outside
the offensive tackles to take advantage of their quickness and
minimize the problems that arise from their relative lack of size.
The 6-foot-6-inch Taylor weighs barely 250 and last year had only 2
1/2 sacks. The shift of Bromell also was insurance for the future,
because at the end of next season Taylor, Rich Owens, and Trace
Armstrong all can become free agents . . . Aug. 23 has been
declared Dan Marino Day in Miami, with an official celebration
scheduled for Pro Player Park to honor the retiring quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corner in a rich neighborhood
</P>
<P>
   Patriots cornerback Ty Law is a headache for the Dolphins even
in the offseason. Miami All-Pro cornerback Sam Madison has begun
negotiating a contract extension, and agent Gene Burroughs is using
as a standard Law's seven-year contract with its $14.2 million
signing bonus . . . He is filling big shoes, but Marcellus Wiley
believes his feet and his talent are big enough. The Buffalo Bills'
young defensive end has inherited Bruce Smith's position, a
position Smith filled well enough to be a lock for the Hall of
Fame. Wiley comes from an unlikely place for an NFL starter _
Columbia University _ but the former second-round draft choice
showed enough promise that general manager John Butler felt
comfortable letting Smith leave for Washington as a free agent.
Wiley doesn't seem uncomfortable with the idea, either. ``I didn't
want to be a 10-year veteran backup,'' Wiley said. ``I was going to
come into this camp challenging him anyway.'' Oh, really? Two years
ago, Wiley led the team with 27 quarterback pressures. Last year he
had 21, although he made only 8 1/2 sacks in the two seasons
combined. Coach Wade Phillips said that, in some pass rushing
situations, Wiley ``looks like Bruce,'' which is a bit much when
you're talking about one of the leading sackers in NFL history.
Although his goal is to exceed the seven sacks a slowed-down Smith
had last season, Wiley wouldn't make a specific prediction, he
said, because ``that's the Nostradamus effect.'' Sounds like he
went to Columbia; most guys in his position would be talking about
the Notre Damus effect. Wiley refuses to get into comparisons with
Smith because he knows the man he's replacing will only grow in
legend, but he did say confidently, ``It's going to be me this
year. It's going to be Marcellus.'' So the Bills hope . . . Only
the Oakland Raiders could lose money on attendance when the NFL is
not in season. A month ago, lawyers for team owner Al Davis claimed
he was owed $825 million in damages and lost revenue for an alleged
breach of contract by Alameda County and the city of Oakland
involving sellouts he was promised for moving the team from Los
Angeles. When those same attorneys finally appeared in Superior
Court in Sacramento last week, they claimed the figure was now $1.1
billion. According to them, the team is worth $400 million less
than it would have been with a string of sellouts, so they want
that money, too. Good luck making that argument. As it is, the deal
is already costing the citizens of Oakland and Alameda County $15
million a year in loan payments. The government contends the
contract never guaranteed the team any income, but Davis contends
public statements by government officials before the lease was
signed led him to believe he had such guarantees. If you've ever
spent five minutes talking to Davis, you know one thing. He wasn't
duped by anybody . . . Washington cornerback Champ Bailey got his
first exposure to offense during minicamp, but it amounted to only
one screen pass thrown to him by backup quarterback Jeff George.
Coach Norv Turner said he may try to get the former Georgia two-way
player the ball as a receiver, but he's not likely to let him
return kicks or punts. Although Turner claims he has return men who
handle the ball better, the fact is the Redskins learned their
lesson on such matters after watching the New York Giants lose Pro
Bowl cornerback Jason Sehorn two years ago on a punt return. In his
rookie season last year, Bailey started all 16 games and led the
team in passes defended (17) and had five interceptions . . . The
Philadelphia Eagles may have the biggest set of offensive tackles
in football with 6-8, 330-pound free agent acquisition Jon Runyan
and 6-8, 330-plus-pound Tra Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Realignment plan
</P>
<P>
   Like the Dolphins, the Eagles are also making a strategic change
in the way they line up on defense. Head coach Andy Reid has
decided to use outside linebacker Carlos Emmons on the tight end
regardless of what side he is on, making Barry Gardner the
weak-side linebacker full-time. They also plan to move their
linebackers off the line to allow them to play more in space and
use their speed to flow to the ball . . . Ex-Boston College lineman
Doug Brzezinski worked at center for the Eagles during a recent
minicamp. There is no plan to convert him, but with Steve Everitt's
release, they are looking for security at the position . . . The
Detroit Lions may find themselves in a bind in July. After signing
running back James Stewart to a huge free agent contract, they are
now being told in whispers that Barry Sanders intends to report to
training camp rather than repay the team millions. Sanders made the
initial payment of more than $88,000 last year, but this season's
installment would be well over $1 million, and word is he won't pay
it. Instead, he'll report and the Lions almost certainly will face
a huge salary cap hit, because they won't be able to get rid of
either Sanders or Stewart. For the time being, though, the Lions
are operating as if Sanders will not be back and Sanders is doing
what he always does _ saying nothing . . . Nothing will be official
until June 1, but it appears Randall Cunningham will be released by
the Minnesota Vikings, the team that helped him revive his career
two seasons ago, and likely sign an incentive-laden contract with
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers to back up second-year starter Shaun King.
Cunningham was not invited to a recent Vikings minicamp, so he
stayed in Las Vegas to work out on his own. Bubby Brister took
snaps behind No. 1 quarterback Daunte Culpepper in Minnesota, and
took them a lot cheaper than Cunningham would have because he
stands to earn $3.3 million this year . . . According to Keyshawn
Johnson, he's going to be on the leading edge of more than just
pass receiving this year. With the launch of Keyshawn.com, Johnson
says he will create a state-of-the-art Web site honoring himself
with ``a highlight show like ESPN, with live highlights.'' That
idea should last until Johnson is informed that he'll have to pay
to get the rights. Johnson spoke to that issue recently at an
Internet seminar in Santa Monica, Calif., when he claimed that
athletes should have some rights to the use of their own images.
Johnson acknowledged that the NFL would likely fight him over the
use of logos, but he had a quick retort to that: ``The NFL may own
them, but ultimately we wear 'em and in fact if we didn't wear 'em,
they wouldn't be much use to them anyway.'' Good point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No word from Young
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young caused a stir in San Francisco last week when he
made a brief appearance on the last day of minicamp. Young told
reporters he would not make a decision about playing again until
late this month. General manager Bill Walsh is opposed to the
return of Young or Jerry Rice, believing it's time to move on. But
it's difficult with such high-profile players. The 49ers seem to
have moved on, however. They drafted two quarterbacks in April,
Walsh told other coaches at the annual owners meetings that Young
would not be back, and head coach Steve Mariucci has said the team
would release Young if he asked out. Young had not talked directly
with Walsh about the issue until last week, and now calls that a
mistake. With Young's concussion history, the bigger mistake would
be coming back. But don't be surprised if he's in an NFL uniform in
September. Just not a 49er uniform . . . Rice's position is equally
uncomfortable. Rice, perhaps the greatest receiver in NFL history,
stands to earn $3.95 million this season, and the Niners don't want
to pay it. They want to slash his contract to bring down his cap
number. Rice says he's willing to do that but also calls it an
issue not about money but about ``respect.'' Whenever you hear that
word connected with a contract negotiation, you know it's going to
be a problem. A case in point was Johnson's problems with the Jets,
which were not about money of course but about respect _ about $7
million a year worth of ``respect,'' as I recall. Rice has said
he's ``at peace'' with the situation, in part because he watched
old friends Joe Montana and Ronnie Lott go through the same purging
in San Francisco . . . The future of Rice and Young was not the
main thing on the 49ers' minds during that minicamp. They had 21
defensive backs, which should make clear one area they are
addressing . . . Old friend Bill Kuharich landed on his feet as the
new pro personnel director of the Kansas City Chiefs. Kuharich, who
was fired as general manager of the New Orleans Saints after a 3-13
season, rejoins Chiefs president and GM Carl Peterson, for whom he
worked in his first pro football job with the USFL's Philadelphia
Stars . . . St. Louis Rams quarterback Kurt Warner may have done
more for the future of the Arena League than any other player in
history. Not only did his meteroic rise to Super Bowl MVP enhance
the indoor league's profile because he is an alumnus of the Iowa
Barnstormers, but he recently signed a deal with a video game
company to create a game called Kurt Warner's Arena Football
Unleashed. Despite hundreds of offseason offers of various types,
Warner is still the first player at the Rams' facility in the
offseason, according to head coach Mike Martz. ``He's 100 percent
in attendance,'' Martz said. Warner is already 11 pounds lighter
(205) than a year ago and has scheduled his off-field commitments
for weekends since the team's conditioning program began April 3 .
. . Cleveland Browns head coach Chris Palmer is about as good a guy
as there is, but that doesn't mean he's not the boss. At last
week's minicamp, he warned free agent linebacker Joey Mayo not to
hit offensive players when the team was working without pads. When
Mayo did it anyway, Palmer warned him not to let it happen again.
The next day it did, and Palmer ran him off the field as promised.
When Mayo at first refused to budge, Palmer sent equipment manager
Bobby Monica over to make it clear he meant business. ``I made it
very explicit if it happened again he was going home, so he went
home,'' Palmer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
