<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' WOES NO REASON FOR SOS TO DEION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Doug Melvin, you know it's not your day, your week, or maybe
even your season, when the lovely and talented Deioness is rumored
to be coming back to the Chicken-Fried Kingdom, yet Jerry Jones is
not remotely involved in the pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was only last week at the Cowboys' minicamp when
there was private talk of a sudden burst of fresh air engulfing the
Valley Ranch locker room, which had everything to do with the
removal of one large me-me-me fraud.
</P>
<P>
   So, just how desperate are the Rangers and Melvin? Have the
despair and the outfield injuries plunged this team to such a
gutter level, that trading for Nine-Toed Deion, as reported, was
actually a consideration last week?
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, it was. ``Consideration'' might be too
strong, and any inquiry about the Reds dealing Sanders came a month
ago, after Rusty Greer went on the disabled list, instead of last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But at some point, Melvin did do the unthinkable. He threw out
Deion's name to the Reds, one of about a dozen outfielders he has
discussed with various clubs. Nothing happened beyond that, and
adding Sanders is no longer even a remote thought by the Rangers.
Maybe owner Tom Hicks balked. Or manager Johnny Oates said no way
to having to deal with that clubhouse headache. Then again, Sanders
is hitting .200 at Triple A, so interest does tend to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of cool, Melvin has obviously lost his. If the normally
unflappable general manager had even a split-second thought about
obtaining that cargo ship full of soiled ego luggage, it's a sure
sign the Rangers' month of April sent Melvin into nuclear panic.
</P>
<P>
   If we don't watch this carefully, he might actually bring in
Ruben Sierra from the Mexican League minors and give Ruben a
Triple-A tryout. Is Darryl Strawberry out of rehab yet? What about
him? And because the Rangers' current record is directly connected
with the on-going failures in the bullpen, has Melvin contacted
Steve Howe?
</P>
<P>
   Why, Doug, why?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that same thing about looking at every option,'' he said.
``The player you wouldn't even consider last week may be the player
you are after this week. Things change in a hurry with injuries.
When Rusty got hurt, Deion's name came up. But it hasn't recently.
It's nothing we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin believes Cleveland could end up with Sanders, if the Reds
trade him. There is also desperation in Cleveland, where a slow
start has been combined with Kenny Lofton's injury. But the Indians
don't know Nine-Toed like we know Nine-Toed.
</P>
<P>
   Your job has to be on the line before a baseball team gives this
guy a second thought. Melvin's job isn't, based on what will
eventually happen this season. What tends to be worrisome is Melvin
acting and reacting as if the house note won't be paid beyond
October.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Doug, we understand injuries. Understand that the removal
of Greer, Frank Catalanotto and, lately, Rafael Palmeiro, took much
of the bite out of an already watered-down batting order. And when
Gabe Kapler also went out, even with his offensive struggles, the
outfield depth was reduced to nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, if key members of the bullpen had pitched anywhere close
to expectations, then the current record would be reversed. But Tim
Crabtree hasn't, and John Wetteland had the back-to-back blown
saves in April, which sent the Rangers into a lengthy funk. There
were several areas to second-guess going into the season, but
nobody listed the bullpen as anything except a team strength.
Unpleasant surprises do happen, however.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the April schedule: The Rangers were playing teams,
as it turned out, they weren't yet ready to compete against on even
terms. The Yankees, Red Sox and Indians will again be the best in
the league, despite the current struggles in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But there is always hope when the rotation is solid, and the
rotation has been just that, if not beyond. In addition, the
schedule in May suggests this is the month when the Rangers can
make up for what happened in April. If they don't, then Melvin
might have every right to panic. But why start so early?
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight says plenty at the moment: Todd Zeile's bat is missed
at third, but Melvin certainly made a valid attempt to re-sign him
last winter. It was Zeile's surprising decision to jump to the
Mets. The injury to Catalanotto put on hold Melvin's plan at second
base, which didn't include bringing back Mark McLemore. At the
moment, McLemore is missed, but a healthy Catalanotto could
eventually make that a forgotten issue.
</P>
<P>
   No question, the Lee Stevens trade for David Segui in late March
removed more firepower from the lineup than Melvin could afford to
give up. But even that opinion was fortified after all those
left-handed bats went down with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez? He was going to be missed, and he is. But that
trade is not even worth a debate. For financial and other reasons,
Juan had to go, and as stated at the time, it will be two years
before the total Detroit package received in the deal can be
properly judged. But clip-and-save this: I'd take that same deal
yesterday or tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, however, of the usually calm and deliberate Melvin,
here's a guy who in the past three or four weeks wasted a moment of
breath by uttering Deion's name to another general manager. The
laughing could be heard all the way over at Valley Ranch. But in
Arlington, there's nothing funny about panic.
</P>
<P>
   {Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
