<SLUG> BC-RAC-KENTUCKYDERBY-FUSAICHIPEGASUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINGED VICTORY FOR DERBY FAVORITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ It was a lesson we were all taught as
children: Good behavior will be rewarded. It turns out that those
words of wisdom are also true for racehorses, as Fusaichi Pegasus
behaved himself beautifully Saturday, and went on to dominate the
126th running of the Kentucky Derby at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With luck and health, he is capable of winning the Triple
Crown,'' said his rider, Kent Desormeaux, who hit his mount with
the whip only once (at the quarter-pole).
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, who was off at 2-1 ($6.60 to win), became the
first favorite to take the Kentucky Derby since Spectacular Bid in
1979, and the first son of legendary sire Mr. Prospector, who died
last year, to win the Derby. He scored with such ease that it
appears he has an excellent chance to become the first Triple Crown
winner since Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Noted for odd behavior, such as tossing exercise riders, falling
over, bucking, and standing stock still, Fusaichi Pegasus had
discouraged some potential backers. Saturday he stood briefly, then
bucked, on the way from the barn to the paddock, but he was docile
in the post parade, and loaded into the gate like a gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flies were on him,'' explained his trainer, Neil Drysdale.
``I attempted to put a fly net on him, and it upset him. We had
come with ice water, and we sponged him down in the paddock. He
cooled right off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first started, he would buck in the post parade. He
thought it was fun. As time went on, he has realized that this is
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus was 15th in the 19-horse field through the
opening quarter, but then he flew up the rail. To say he has a
fluid stride would be an understatement, and he began to pick off
the rivals in front of him. He swung out for the drive, split
horses, and forged ahead at the eighth-pole.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude and Alex Solis chased him home at 11-1, but as well as
the long shot ran, he was no match for the winner, as Fusaichi
Pegasus cruised home a length and a half in front. The time for the
1 1/4 miles, run over an extremely fast track, was 2:01, the
fourth-fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment, part of a four-horse entry, closed for third with
Craig Perret aboard, 4 lengths farther back. Second choice The
Deputy, off at 9-2, finished 14th with Chris McCarron aboard,
spoiling Jenine Sahadi's bid to become the first woman to train a
Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at Churchill Downs was 153,204, the second-largest
crowd in Derby history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a brilliant horse,'' said Desormeaux, who won the
Derby in 1998 aboard Real Quiet. ``This pretty horse can run. I
don't need wings, I feel like I can fly. I just gave him nudges,
and he began to accelerate. When he straightened away, I kissed at
him, and he took off. He has an awesome turn of foot. At this stage
of his career he is the best horse I've ever been associated
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale was named to the Hall of Fame last Tuesday, and, by
winning the Derby, he repeated the accomplishment of trainer D.
Wayne Lukas, who was named to the Hall on Derby week last year,
then won the race with Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very rewarding and humbling week,'' said Drysdale.
``The horses put you here . . . without the horses, there isn't a
sport. That's what makes you humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very talented horse. I'm so delighted for him. He
deserved it. I'm very, very proud of him. If he's all right, we'll
go to the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't concerned about the distance, I think the distance
helped him.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Fusao Sekiguchi, the venture capitalist who purchased
Fusaichi Pegasus for $4 million as a yearling, watched his horse
earn $1,038,400 Saturday, which included a $150,000 bonus for
winning both the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct (April 15) and the Derby
(Drysdale received a $100,000 bonus as well).
</P>
<P>
   ``I love challenges,'' said Sekiguchi through an interpreter.
``We were told many times that the favorite has not won in 21
years. I loved breaking the jinx. I have full faith in Mr.
Drysdale. I know he's a remarkable horseman. I know whatever he
wants to do, he can do. I can see in his eyes that he's happy with
the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that the horse does is something that comes through
his inquisitive temperament. It is nothing to get concerned
about.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Derby taught everyone a lesson. It's better to be
nice than naughty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
