<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH IS ENOUGH: STARS NEED TO DISPATCH SHARK PRETENDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's time that they end this, and the Stars know that.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Stars fans don't enjoy a good chortle, like the
one from watching Bryan Marchment stagger off the ice with a groin
injury. And it's not as if, any minute now, Eddie Belfour is likely
to kick out the windows on a police cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   No, they need to end this playoff series tonight because the
Stars know, deep down in their playoff-hardened hearts, that there
are bigger fish to fry than Steve Shields and the San Jose Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   The puck will drop tonight at 6:30, which means if all goes
according to the defending champs' plan, the Sharks can be home and
on the golf course tomorrow before lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   It's time the Stars end this. Maybe it's something in the San
Jose water. Maybe the Stars are distracted, wondering if Sharks
coach Darryl Sutter really does look like Chuck E. Cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the Stars need to dispose of these pretenders and get
on to the contenders. The Colorado Avalanche and Patrick Roy await.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade deadline, the Avalanche and the Stars have
loomed as the NHL's best matchup. Their Western Conference finals
series last year was laced with drama _ and even better hockey than
the six games with Buffalo for the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has Joe Sakic, Peter Forsberg and their 11th-hour trump
card, Ray Bourque. And there is also, it seems, this mildly
simmering Roy-versus-Belfour thing, wherein Eddie supposedly said
something somewhere that the proud Monsieur Roy took exception to.
</P>
<P>
   Or that's what the Denver papers are saying, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Roy-versus-Belfour is worthy of a Michael Buffer introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour-versus-Shields? Enough is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Shields is the same goaltender who had trouble beating out Mike
Vernon who, I think, broke in in Detroit with Gordie Howe. Vernon
was traded in December, and Shields immediately asserted himself by
winning exactly five of his first 16 starts.
</P>
<P>
   With the first-round series there for the taking in Game 6
against St. Louis, Shields gave up six stunningly soft and quick
goals to the Blues and was yanked. Shhhhh _ I think the guy falls
asleep. If the winning goal tonight goes in on a deflection off
Shields' head, remember where you read it first.
</P>
<P>
   As his own coach, Coach Cheese, said, ``I've said all along that
if you expect to beat Dallas, you've got to have great
goaltending.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks haven't. Which is why, for the Stars, it's time to
end this.
</P>
<P>
   Shields' counterpart, of course, Belfour, had his usual Crazy
Eddie reunion with the choir in San Jose. Belfour _ by all but The
Mansion standards, perhaps _ had an outstanding season.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Sharks' home ice, Belfour turned into the Eddie that
we've seen in those memorable TV promos, the
how-so-and-so-spent-his-day-with-the-Stanley-Cup spots. In the ad
Eddie is on a carnival Tilt-A-Whirl, the trophy beside him,
giggling crazily while the two Cup chaperones in suits appear on
the verge of throwing up.
</P>
<P>
   In Crazy Eddie, the Stars trust. At Reunion Arena, Sharks fans
might note, Belfour has yet to surrender a goal this series to the
San Joses.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says that if the home team can stay out of
the penalty box tonight, the Stars can put an end to this
best-of-seven series. Coach Ken Hitchcock's team has won seven
playoff contests in a row at noisy, Slurpee-iced Reunion. It would
be most uncharacteristic for a Hitchcock team to perform again as
it did in Game 4, which the coach termed ``a little comedic
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight it can't be comedy central, and the Stars know that.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Nolan and that handsome Mike Ricci have had their fun.
Stars fans are finished hyperventilating, watching Marchment wobble
off. And the Bay Area sports sections have used their last
``Yee-Haw'' joke.
</P>
<P>
   Enough is enough. Bigger fish await.
</P>
<P>
   {Gil LeBreton is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.}
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
