<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GET PUNCHED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The strikeouts flowed once again like vintage wine Saturday
afternoon from Pedro Martinez, who swallowed whatever bitter
aftertaste was left from being assessed a five-game suspension and
whiffed 17 Tampa Bay Devil Rays, matching his personal best.
</P>
<P>
   But the champagne at Fenway Park was delivered to the opposing
clubhouse after Devil Rays pitcher Steve Trachsel, an 18-game loser
last season, outdueled the Sox ace, 1-0, with a three-hitter in
which the former Cub fanned a career-high 11 batters.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay reserve shortstop Ozzie Guillen decided the moment
warranted a bottle of bubbly, and who could blame him? A Martinez
loss is a rare occasion. Greg Vaughn's two-out single on a
full-count breaking ball in the eighth inning scored Dave Martinez,
who had singled and stolen second, and sent Pedro the Younger to
his first loss in 13 starts since last Aug. 19. Two of his last
three defeats have come against the Devil Rays, even though their
first seven outs were whiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight survival,'' Vaughn said of his winning hit, which
came after three at-bats in which he struck out thrice on the
minimum nine pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give him credit,'' said Martinez, who had 15
strikeouts through seven innings, three more than at the same point
in his epic 17-K performance in Yankee Stadium last Sept. 10, but
had just one strikeout in each of the last two innings. ``I got him
three times. It's about time he did something. He's just a good
hitter, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Trachsel was anything but good last season in Chicago, losing
more games than anybody in the big leagues. He had 14 losses
entering August, and was spared a 20-loss season only by going 4-1
in September. But Saturday, he toyed with a lineup that was missing
Nomar Garciaparra, out with a pulled left hamstring. Trachsel gave
up a single to Troy O'Leary in the second, a single to Brian
Daubach in the third, and another single to Daubach in the sixth
before setting down the last 11 batters.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and Trachsel combined to strike out the most hitters in
any game, according to Sox researchers, since Kerry Wood of the
Cubs whiffed a record-tying 20 and Shane Reynolds of the Astros 10
two years ago to the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, when (Trachsel) took the mound, he knew he wasn't going
to give an inch out there,'' said Tampa Bay manager Larry
Rothschild, who also acknowledged that Martinez had stuff equal to
Kevin Brown and Al Leiter when they threw their no-hitters while he
was the Marlins' pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Like Martinez, Trachsel struck out the side in the first and had
an answer in the only two innings in which the Sox put two runners
on base. Carl Everett, who went 0 for 4, whiffed twice, and didn't
get the ball out of the infield while batting cleanup, tapped out
to second with runners on first and third in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had runners on the corners again in the sixth, when
Daubach led off with a single and took third when first baseman
Fred McGriff booted O'Leary's ground ball. But Mike Stanley struck
out, one of his three whiffs, and Jason Varitek, who had come into
the game with a career-best nine-game hitting streak, grounded out
to short.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing on our part,'' Varitek said. ``That's the
game we need to win, when we pitch well. But you've got to give
(Trachsel) credit. He threw everything. He had a real good split,
and he threw a changeup, slider, curveball, sinker, four-seamer.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Sox hit in the ninth, general manager Dan Duquette
made an appearance in the back of the press box and announced that
Martinez was dropping the appeal of the suspension he was given for
hitting Roberto Alomar of the Indians with a pitch last Sunday
following a warning from plate umpire Tim Tschida. Martinez will
begin to serve his penalty immediately, which has the effect of
pushing his next start back one day, to Friday night in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has yet to utter a word about the suspension _ a
posture recommended by club officials _ maintained his stance after
Saturday's game. Asked if he felt it important to show that his
performance would not be affected by the suspension, Martinez was
defiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about it,'' he said. ``I never will. I go
after my goals the same way, the same way I approach the game. I
won't think about it. It's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a hollowness, too, about losing a game in which he
struck out 15 or more batters for the seventh time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't score,'' said Red Sox manager Jimy Williams.
``The other guy pitched a great game. How many did Pedro strike
out? He had phenomenal stuff. Breaking ball, location, up and down,
in and out. We just couldn't score.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston right fielder Trot Nixon, whose drive to the warning
track in center was the hardest-hit ball of the day for the Sox,
could barely bring himself to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't going to say anything about (Trachsel),'' Nixon said.
``I had my pitches to hit. We all did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
