<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-DERBY-SAHADI-BOS &LR;      05-06 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-SAHADI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAHADI HAS THE KENTUCKY BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The sun shines bright on my old Kentucky home . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Long, long ago Stephen Foster wrote those
words about a home that wasn't even his but that of his cousin over
in Bardstown, Ky. Little matter. Kentucky had its state anthem.
</P>
<P>
   And on the first Saturday of every May, the sun always ``shines
bright on my old Kentucky home.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for an hour before Saturday's Kentucky Derby. The first
rumble of thunder was heard, rain pelted the horses running in the
race before the Derby, and Jenine Sahadi looked up to the sky, did
a little rain dance, and implored, ``Rain, rain go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi was just outside Barn 41 on the Churchill Downs
backstretch. Only a few raindrops were falling here, but no matter.
Down at the far end of the same barn, trainer Neil Drysdale was
tucked inside, under cover, his Fusaichi Pegasus only a few feet
away in his stall. Motionless. As Drysdale had been saying all
week, ``I'm not as concerned as you people in the media'' about his
temperamental colt.
</P>
<P>
   A group of women walked by the barn, some nine or 10 of them,
and each made a point of walking up to Sahadi and patting her
shoulder, wishing her luck or shaking her hand. The sisterhood all
had one wish, that Sahadi would be the first woman to train a
Kentucky Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   A fan walked by Barn 41 and shouted out, ``The Derby winner's
coming out of this barn; mark my words.''
</P>
<P>
   But which one? Sahadi's The Deputy or Drysdale's Fusaichi
Pegasus?
</P>
<P>
   ``T'is summer,'' Foster had written about the old Kentucky home
that wasn't his, ``and all the people are gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was spring and not all the people of Kentucky were
gay, certainly not Sahadi and Drysdale. Their springs were wound
very tight.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi had given her colt a bath in the morning and went back to
her hotel room ``where I tried to take a nap in between all the
phone calls; the phone rang all day. I just lay there, I didn't
sleep since the phone was ringing all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, too ill to make the trip, had called from California
``but he'll be watching on TV and I'm sure he'll be in floods of
tears when he sees me walking over.''
</P>
<P>
   The walk over? That short half-mile from the barns behind the
Churchill Downs backside, along the fence along the clubhouse turn,
thousands of fans screaming at human and horse, the wrong way past
the finish line until the left turn under the Twin Spires and into
the paddock.
</P>
<P>
   No other experience in American sports compares. Why, just
moments earlier, owner Bob Lewis had tried to minimize the anxiety
of the walk by doing what an Anheuser-Busch distributor in Los
Angeles does to pass the time _ trying to spot fans with cans of
Budweiser in their hands. ``It gets more thrilling each time,''
said Lewis, whose first walk was in 1997 when his Silver Charm won
the Derby. ``It doesn't get easier.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sahadi, though, it was her first walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already barfed,'' she said. ``I almost feel better when I
do that. I didn't do it before the Santa Anita Derby (won by The
Deputy), but I did it before both Breeders' Cups. I mean, I saddled
fast, I saddled as fast as I could and then I barely got to the
bathroom in time. Once you do it, you're much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi laughed. Then lit another cigarette. And paced and paced.
</P>
<P>
   It was so hard to ease the tension. Gary Barber, one of the
owners of The Deputy and the producer of the movie, ``The Sixth
Sense,'' had a cell phone to his ear just outside The Deputy's
stall in Barn 41 and Sahadi mocked him to lighten the heaviness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen these guys (Friday night at a dinner put
on by Team Valor, the other owners of the horse). ``Gary sees these
numbers . . . `00000063421' on his phone and you hear him make his
call, `I want a dime on the Lakers,' and `I want a dime on the
over' (a wager on the total points in the Lakers-Sacramento game)
and `I want a dime on this' and `I want a dime on that.' These guys
are sickos.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sahadi paced some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young folks roll on the little cabin floor,'' Foster had
written of his sweet Kentucky home. ``All merry, all happy and
bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale had two horses in the Derby, Fusaichi Pegasus and War
Chant. As if to show his lack of concern about the antics of
Fusaichi Pegasus, Drysdale chose to send War Chant first on the
track and follow that colt with his better (and more active) horse.
Every once in a while, though, Drysdale would peek behind him to
see if Pegasus was pulling another stunt of his.
</P>
<P>
   It was just after Fusaichi Pegasus made his turn from the mile
chute and onto the main track itself that the colt pulled his first
stunt. For no apparent reason, he pulled to a complete halt and
would not move. Drysdale scratched his head and waited. Nothing
else to do. Thirty-five seconds later, again for no apparent
reason, the colt began to walk again.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, one of those thousands of Kentucky ``young folks . .
. all merry, all happy and bright'' of Foster's could be heard
shouting through a chain link fence over to Fusaichi Pegasus,
``You're going down, Peggy.''
</P>
<P>
   And another one of those young Kentucky folks, all bright and
merry, shouted non-stop at Fusaichi Pegasus, but the colt never
even cocked an ear in his direction. ``You don't even turn around,
Peggy,'' the fan shouted in exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 'n by, hard times comes a knocking at the door,'' Foster
had written more than a century-and-a-half ago. Who could he know?
</P>
<P>
   Just past the finish line, with Enrique Lircios calmly keeping
his 6-year-old pony, Whistle, at the side of Fusaichi Pegasus to
keep the colt calm, Drysdale thought he saw some flies on the back
of his star. He reached over to an assistant and grabbed some
netting and draped it over Fusaichi Pegasus's back. Whoa, Nellie.
</P>
<P>
   The colt quickly came to a dead stop and begin frantically
kicking his back heels in frustration, kicking them high and
kicking them strong. All those behind the colt, media and handlers,
scattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting sticky,'' said the trainer. ``There were flies
on his back, so I attempted to put the net on him.'' But Fusaichi
Pegasus didn't appreciate it, ``and so I took the net off him
quickly.'' And the colt again began his walk to destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corn-top's ripe and the meadow's in the bloom,'' Foster
had sung of his sweet Kentucky, ``while the birds make music all
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   How could Foster have known? The birds? Pegasus? Flying so
gracefully?
</P>
<P>
   When all was done, when Fusaichi Pegasus had won the Kentucky
Derby as effortlessly as any horse since Seattle Slew in 1977, when
Fusaichi Pegasus had ran to the perfection of animal beauty that he
is, jockey Kent Desormeaux aptly summed up this awesome mix of
beauty and strength: ``This pretty boy can fly.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Sahadi's The Deputy had run a miserable 14th, another
one of those mysterious finishes that so many good horses have
suffered here in the Kentucky Derby, she was forlorn. Her husband,
trainer Ben Cecil, hugged her and gave her a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so happy, I feel so anxious, I feel so many things,''
she had said only an hour earlier. ``But most of all, I feel I want
this over.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weep no more, my lady, Oh! Weep no more today,'' Foster had
written. ``We will sing one song for my old Kentucky home, for the
old Kentucky home far away.''
</P>
<P>
   The tears were still flowing down Sahadi's cheeks nearly an hour
after the race when she and The Deputy had made it back to Barn 41.
Her horse ``was exhausted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And then the tears stopped. A lesson had been learned, for,
``The sun shines bright on my old Kentucky home,'' but on the first
Saturday in May, that warm Kentucky sun is most selective.
</P>
<P>
   It smiles on only one horse, one trainer and one jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weep no more, my lady. Oh! Weep no more today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
