<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GO FOR KO AGAINST SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so the last thing the Stars want or need to be thinking
about is the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they may be wise to keep in the back of their minds the
image of Peter Forsberg and Joe Sakic lounging around the house in
their boxer shorts. Because while the Stars and San Jose Sharks are
busy beating each other up tonight, that's what the Avs players
will be doing. Resting.
</P>
<P>
   They advanced to the Western Conference Finals by defeating
Detroit on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars could join the Avs if they defeat the Sharks in Game 5
at 6:30 tonight at Reunion Arena in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that lies in the back of your mind that right now they
are sitting there, waiting,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said,
before leaving San Jose. ``We have a chance to get a good rest
right now. Obviously, we don't want to come back here.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars don't win tonight, it's back to San Jose for Game
6, where a frenzied crowd and another punishing game awaits. Not to
mention Game 7 looms.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars want to get this series in the rearview mirror as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks, who had chances to win Game 4 but couldn't, look
ready to float to the surface. The Stars just need to push them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is blood and we smell it, then we go for it and try to
go for the throat and end it as soon as possible,'' Stars center
Mike Modano said. ``You don't want to give them any room, any air
to breathe. You want to eliminate them as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, to a man, say that if they're going to end this
sooner rather than later they're going to have to play better
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much better,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor added. ``That's
for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not a misprint. The stifling, smothering,
just-try-to-get-a-goal-on-us defense of the playoffs was a no-show
for Game 4 on Friday night. The Stars allowed four goals _ in 40
minutes _ which would be as if Pedro Martinez gave up 10 runs in
two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When was the last time we gave up four or five goals?'' Stars
winger Mike Keane asked rhetorically. ``That's just not us. It's
the little things we have to tighten up on.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of the little things is penalties. The Stars have
had 16 penalties in the past two games. Dumbs ones. Questionable
ones. Silly ones. Whatever the reason, there were too many of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars need to stay out of the penalty box or risk putting
the Sharks back into the series. The Sharks capitalized by scoring
a combined three power-play goals in Games 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, it was a little bit undisciplined on our part,'' Modano
said. ``If we are going to be better down the road, we have to
eliminate that retaliation and stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest offender for the Stars never served a minute in the
penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   When referees whistled Stars goalie Ed Belfour for roughing not
once but twice within a 40-second span in the third period, he had
to stay on the ice and help kill his own penalties. He did it, too:
The Sharks were scoreless on both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it fires him up,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said.
``But I think he has to be careful that you don't put our team in a
hole too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Because what's riding on tonight's game isn't merely closing out
the San Jose Sharks. The numbers say that will happen eventually.
When the Stars lead 3-1 in a series, they have gone on to win the
series all but once.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are down 3-1, it's tough. It's tough mentally,''
Hatcher said. ``The odds have it. When you are up 3-1, you have a
huge advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are playing to eliminate the couch factor in the
Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's extremely critical,'' Nieuwendyk said of closing
out the Sharks. ``We don't want to make that long trip back. ... We
have them in a very vulnerable position. We have to make sure we
capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, the Avs will be capitalizing on the couch.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
