</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-APTITUDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-GUESSING APTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ In every Kentucky Derby there is a moment _ a
split second, really _ that can make all the difference in the
world. In that snap of the fingers, the correct decision can mean
victory. The wrong one, defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus won the 126th Derby by a length and a half
Saturday but Bobby Frankel, trainer of runner-up Aptitude, felt the
result could easily have been closer or even different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desormeaux took the rail and got lucky,'' said Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux, riding the winner, was well back in the early
going, settled behind Aptitude and Alex Solis.
</P>
<P>
   On the far turn, Solis made a decision. He took Aptitude off the
rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved out into the middle a little so I would have the
choice to go inside or out,'' said Solis.
</P>
<P>
   With the rail clear, Desormeaux was free to move inside horses
and up into contention. In the last quarter-mile he pulled away and
Aptitude chased futilely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was in great shape,'' said Solis about that moment
when he moved off the rail. ``I thought I had a big chance to win
the race. But then (Fusaichi Pegasus) came galloping up and he was
doing it real easy. I knew he was going to be hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved to be the case, but Frankel, without being too
critical of his jockey, wondered what would have happened if Solis
had made a different decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my jock does what Desormeaux does, it was going to be real
close,'' he said. ``Desormeaux got real lucky and we only got beat
a length and a quarter (actually a length and a half). Maybe we
don't beat him, but it was going to be real close. They would have
been together at the 16th pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude will get another chance at Fusaichi Pegasus, but it
won't happen in the Preakness. Aptitude will stay at Churchill
Downs, where the West Coast-based Frankel has a small string of
horses, and prepare for the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too many hard races,'' said Frankel about running in the
Preakness and the Belmont. ``Why do it? We can't win the Triple
Crown now anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question the 1 1/2-mile Belmont, the longest of the
Triple Crown races, will suit Aptitude. ``He's bred for it, top and
bottom,'' said Frankel, referring to Aptitude's sire, A.P. Indy,
the winner of the 1992 Belmont, and his dam, Dokki, a daughter of
Northern Dancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' said Solis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
