</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-VANGUNDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDYS CAUGHT IN PARENT TRAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They know the drill by heart. Bill Van Gundy goes upstairs and
turns on the television, but mutes the sound. Downstairs, Cindy Van
Gundy watches with the sound on. The two do not communicate with
anyone, including each other, until the game is over.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that way for three years, and it will be that way
again this week. While many salivate over another Knicks-Heat
playoff series, it is, at best, a tough time for the Van Gundys of
Brockport, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   One son, Jeff, coaches the Knicks. Another son, Stan, is an
assistant with the Heat. This will be the fourth consecutive year
the parents go through this ritual at home while their sons go at
each other in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried going to the games once, but I guess we don't like
having our emotions on public display,'' said Cindy. ``It's just
easier this way. It's always so much easier when they play other
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill, a longtime high school and college coach, added, ``It
wasn't really fun when we went to the games in person. NBA fans
everywhere are less than pleasant to the visiting team. And no
matter where we go, we have someone on the visiting team.''
</P>
<P>
   So they don't go out in public. Or have friends over. On one
occasion, they allowed a local sportswriter to watch the games with
them, but only if he agreed to keep it civil in the newspaper. He
complied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a little nerve-wracking,'' said Cindy. ``I try to
look at the positive side, that one of them will win, that they are
both at the top of their profession, that they are both competitive
and doing what they want to do. I try to keep it in perspective.
There's so many things going on more important than the Heat and
the Knicks. I try. I really try.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then they throw up the ball and I become a wild woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill says he appreciates being alone so he can say what he wants
and not worry about anyone hearing him. He watches not only as a
father but also as a coach. He will wonder why such a play was run
and critique strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do anything I want,'' he said. ``That's the biggest
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But, to him, it all comes down to the same thing when the game
is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got one son happy and one son dejected,'' he said.
``Jeff tries to tell me that I should look at the positive, that
one son is going on. But that's always hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy said, ``Absolutely, we always feel more for the loser than
the winner. That's why it's so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Van Gundys did catch the Knicks clincher in person last
Sunday in Toronto. When they returned home, they discovered their
house, which was for sale, had been sold. In July, they will move
into an apartment in Miami, where they can be closer to Stan and
his four children. Jeff has one daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But they already have a problem of sorts. The new digs have no
second floor. What to do next year if the teams meet again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought of that,'' said Bill. ``I guess we'll have to
get two TVs and close the door to one of the rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cindy, ``He may just have to leave and drive around Miami
for a few hours.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five and fold?
</P>
<P>
   With both the Pacers and Lakers going to the five-game maximum
in the first round, it marked the second time both No. 1 seeds were
so extended since 1984, the year the 16-team format was instituted.
The other time was in 1994, when Western No. 1 Seattle was upset by
No. 8 Denver (which trailed, 0-2), and Eastern No. 1 Atlanta,
arguably the most fraudulent top seed in the last 16 years, ousted
Miami in five games (after trailing, 2-1). Since 1984, no No. 1
seed has been extended to five games in the first round and gone on
to win the NBA title. However, No. 6 Houston went five games with
Utah in the first round in 1995 and went on to win the title . . .
The Warriors have offered contract extensions to assistant coaches
Rod Higgins and Brian Winters, but they will not be the least bit
surprised if Higgins decides to leave for the Wizards . . .
Meanwhile, isn't it interesting that all these teams are interested
in Isiah Thomas as a head coach and the Pistons won't go near him?
. . . Winston Bennett lasted less than a year in Boston as Rick
Pitino's No. 2 assistant. Now, he's back in the biz, having just
been named head coach at Kentucky State. The Division 2 Thorobreds
were 13-14 last season. Since leaving the Celtics, Bennett had been
working in real estate in the Lexington, Ky., area and also doing
occasional scouting for Pitino . . . Now that the Spurs have been
put out of their misery, the team has some big offseason questions,
starting with the status of You Know Who. Tim Duncan is still
playing it cozy, although he does have a very solid relationship
with coach/general manager Gregg Popovich, who wisely did not rush
his franchise player back into the series with Phoenix. In addition
to Duncan, veteran Avery Johnson (who turned 35 in March) is a free
agent and wants to stick around. Given his age, the Spurs may
decide to give him a one-year balloon contract so as not to tie up
their cap down the road. The improving play of Antonio Daniels and
Samaki Walker has given the Spurs some hope, although all will be
lost if Duncan decides to go to Orlando. The Spurs are expected to
make a serious run at free agent Derek Anderson . . . From
Minnesota's postmortem _ four consecutive first-round exits _ comes
this gem from Kevin McHale on signing free agents: ``If you could
put a gun to a guy's head and make him sign a contract, we'd be
more successful. I've got more guns than most general managers.'' .
. . Celtics GM Chris Wallace tried to slip into Athens incognito,
but instead was treated like General Patton on the march to Messina
when he showed up at the big AEK-Panathinaikos game last Wednesday.
He was there to see, among others, big center Iakovos Tsakalidis of
AEK. How wild was it for Wallace? Well, in one Greek paper he had
to say that he hoped his presence had not taken away from the game
(which Panathinaikos won as Tsakalidis was limited to 8 points and
5 rebounds in 18 foul-plagued minutes). Another Greek paper claimed
to have seen his notes from the game and published them. ``I've
never seen anything like it,'' Wallace said. ``I kept telling them
that I was over here just to see the guy play.'' Tsakalidis said
before the game that, as far as he was concerned, he was a free
agent and planned to attend the NBA predraft camp next month in
Chicago. AEK may have other ideas. Wallace also stopped in Israel
on his junket, er, scouting mission to see Nate Huffman. He's the
7-footer from Central Michigan who plays for Maccabi Tel-Aviv and
is considered this year's John Amaechi, although smaller. Given the
Celtics' interior problems, anything is possible. There's their
likely draft pick (11th), free agency, and trades. One option might
be a deal with Toronto for the rights to Zeljko Rebraca, who is
considered the best player in Europe. He's 27 and probably will
play one more year overseas. But the Raptors apparently are open to
moving him, having elected not to sign him last year. Wallace saw
Rebraca play twice last week and had some discussions with
Rebraca's representatives. The Greek papers, however, seemed to
think the Celtics were homing in on Tsakalidis with their pick.
Wallace has tried to downplay any interest in European players, but
he can't do that anymore given the team's clandestine but fruitless
attempt to snag Dirk Nowitzki two years ago . . . A clarification
from last week on the subject of European players. Ethminios
Rentzias was drafted by Denver in 1996 and the Nuggets may well be
waiting for him. But not as badly as Atlanta. The Hawks acquired
his rights via trade. Rebraca was drafted in 1994 by Seattle and
his rights were acquired by the Raptors in a three-way trade last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The McGrady factor
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to Vince Carter, the most important
individual in the Raptors organization is Tracy McGrady. As he
goes, so goes the franchise, which only a couple of years ago was
at ground zero and could be there again if McGrady bolts. ``Vince
Carter is an outstanding player,'' said Knicks assistant Brendan
Malone. ``Unfortunately for Tracy McGrady, he has to play in
Vince's shadow. McGrady is an outstanding player. He has the long
arms. He's an outstanding offensive rebounder. He's good around the
basket. He's a good passer. He can score in the post, off the
dribble, or facing up. He's only 20 and he's going to be a star in
this league.'' But if that stardom materializes somewhere else,
like Orlando or Chicago, then Carter would be holding the bag and
you could start the Vince-to-America countdown. Antonio Davis has
an opt-out clause at the end of next season while fellow graybeards
Charles Oakley and Kevin Willis have a couple of years left, at
least contractually. Doug Christie, meanwhile, all but assured his
exodus with his comments about coach Butch Carter. He, too, has an
opt-out clause at the end of next season. McGrady tried last week
to put the onus on Vince Carter by saying he'd sign with Toronto
only if Vince did. But Vince can't do anything for two more years.
The Raptors need to re-sign McGrady. If they don't, the slide
begins again. Old friend Dee Brown has probably played his last
game as a Raptor and will enter free agency at 31 . . . The Celtics
should take a long, hard look at Adonal Foyle, who is a free agent.
He hasn't exactly dazzled in his three years at Golden State, but
he is a shot blocker and has an upside. The Warriors would like to
keep him and know that Foyle is unlikely to command anything more
than the $2.5 million exception. But Foyle seems like an ideal
Pitino candidate: an underachiever who could fill a need in Boston
. . . Here's another byproduct of the ridiculous first-round
playoff schedule (which the NBA defends). The Knicks will be the
hosts for Game 3 against the Heat Friday. That will mark a span of
16 days between home playoff games for New York. Miami, host Sunday
afternoon, has gone seven days without a game and 11 days between
home games _ and the Heat are division champions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 2322EDT &QL; 
