r s BC-RAC-DERBY-LEDE-TEX     05-06 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEGASUS TAKES FLIGHT AS FAVORITE WINS KENTUCKY DERBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ It's hard to fathom a wad of cash $4 million
thick. It's just as hard to fathom a horse with wings.
</P>
<P>
   But Fusaichi Pegasus, who cost $4 million as a yearling, moved
somewhat like the mythical Greek version when _ as jockey Kent
Desormeaux put it _ the colt ``floated around there today'' to win
the 126th Kentucky Derby in front of 153,204 people at Churchill
Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux rode his second Derby winner when he got Fusaichi
Pegasus to rally from 15th place early in the race. He reached a
prominent position nearing the stretch before powering through the
lane to win the Derby by 1 1/2 lengths over a game, but hapless,
Aptitude, the same horse who ran third behind him in the Wood
Memorial Stakes three weeks ago in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Fusao Sekiguchi, a Japanese venture capitalist, bid $4 million
to buy Fusaichi Pegasus at the Keeneland Summer Yearling Sale in
Lexington, Ky., in July 1998. Then he named him almost like a
vanity plate on a hot rod automobile. The first name is a
combination of Fusao and ``ichi,'' which means No. 1 in Japanese.
Pegasus is the name of the horse in Greek mythology that has wings.
</P>
<P>
   The name has fit through the four races leading up to the Derby,
all victories with an average winning margin of more than two
lengths. But it looked as if Desormeaux might be driving with an
expired plate when the horses were midway through the final turn.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux had to ease his horse around More Than Ready, who was
making a move from fourth to second. Desormeaux angled out even
more to the point that he was seven wide entering the stretch less
than a quarter-mile away from the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had faith that the traffic would break and he would have a
gap in front of him and he would make way,'' Sekiguchi said through
his interpreter, Mikki Tsuge. ``I knew he was going to bust out.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was a door in the way he might have broken it down. But
Fusaichi Pegasus got a break there, if he needed it. Straightening
for home, Captain Steve was vying for the lead under jockey Robby
Albarado. But Wheelaway veered in sharply toward the rail under
rider Richard Migliore and put the squeeze on Captain Steve.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he left a wide-open path for Desormeaux. Still
about seven wide, he shook up Fusaichi Pegasus with the reins and
moved to pop him with the whip. But he ended up giving the colt
three light taps. That's all he would need of the whip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took off,'' Desormeaux said, ``like the best horse I've
been involved with at this point of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty good animal. At this time two years ago,
Desormeaux was crossing the Churchill wire first with Real Quiet.
After winning the Derby, Real Quiet took the Preakness and missed
winning the Triple Crown at the Belmont by the smallest losing
margin in the history of the series.
</P>
<P>
   There are more positives to consider. The winning margin matches
the 1 1/2 lengths Real Quiet claimed. But there was another horse
gaining on Real Quiet that day. Yesterday, Fusaichi Pegasus was
home free in the final eighth of a mile and could have put on more
distance if Desormeaux wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner was in front of me all the way,'' said Aptitude
jockey Alex Solis, the runner-up. ``And he was running so easy.
He's obviously a very special horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The time of 2 minutes, 1 second is the sixth-fastest in Derby
history. It's the best since Grindstone covered the 1 1/4 miles in
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat still has the track and Derby record at 1:592/5.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Desormeaux saved some horse for the Preakness,
the next step in the Triple Crown that is a little less than two
weeks away on May 20 in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't do more than he had to from the start. Fusaichi
Pegasus was 15th after moving under the finish line for the first
time, leaving a little more than a mile to make up 13 1/2 lengths
to the lead. It's the farthest Fusaichi Pegasus has ever been
behind in his previous five starts (he was fifth, 2 1/2 lengths
back in his career debut, the only time he's lost).
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke keen,'' Desormeaux said. ``But his second step was
laggard. But Neil's words were bouncing in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Neil Drysdale, trainer of Fusaichi Pegasus and whose
election to horse racing's Hall of Fame was announced Tuesday. In
pre-race instructions, Drysdale told Desormeaux to move easily over
to the rail and save ground for the rest of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the colt settled onto the backstretch, until
Desormeaux wanted some action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to get contentious,'' Desormeaux said. ``I wasn't
just a pilot. There were some nudges.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't need a nudge coming down the stretch. Fusaichi
Pegasus pulled away, as if he were a horse with wings. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
