<HEADLINE>
QUIGLEY STILL ON STANDBY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His tee time was in Florence, S.C., last week, but his heart was
in Houston. This week he's in Knoxville, but he'd prefer New
Orleans. He keeps his travel plans open at all times and knows a
thing or two about airline routes, but he will drive the backroads
if that's what it takes.
</P>
<P>
   He is Brett Quigley, quite often located underneath the heading
of ``alternates.'' His uncle Dana, easily mistaken for an ATM
capable of drilling a 4-iron under the wind, is a weekly contender
on the Senior PGA Tour and riding an incredible wave of success. In
a heartbeat, though, the proud uncle would trade in one of his top
10s if he knew it would provide a break for his brother's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in Never-Never Land,'' said Dana, referring to Brett's
status on the exempt list. ``He has been for three years, but some
day it will come together for him. The kid can play. Believe me,
he's a player.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, he's biased, but the uncle happens to be telling the truth.
Brett Quigley, the 1987 US Junior Amateur champion, has been on the
edge of a breakthrough on the PGA Tour for a few years now. He was
128th on the money list in 1997, 127th the next year, 152d last
season. Nothing to be ashamed of, but in his line of work, falling
just outside the top 125 earns you a spot in the 29th category of
priority when it comes to exempt status. There's a traffic jam
ahead, but to get into it you have to negotiate a few rotaries.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you show up at an event, sit around for three days,
then go home because not enough players got sick. Sometimes you
choose to play somewhere else, though your exit is rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   Take last week, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a flight booked out of Florence Wednesday night,'' said
the 30-year-old graduate of the University of South Carolina, ``but
I had to cancel it.'' He had been seventh alternate in the Shell
Houston Open and got all the way to No. 1 when the withdrawals
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Deprived once again of a spot in a PGA Tour event _ he's gotten
into just three thus far _ Quigley stayed in Florence for the
BUY.com and made the most of it by finishing in a tie for second.
There was an opportunity to win, and even though it was not the big
leagues, ``It felt good to play with the pressure on,'' he said.
The $29,866 paycheck doesn't count toward his PGA Tour money
status, but it will help with some bills, and Quigley took great
comfort in the fact that he overcame a 1-over-par 73 to start.
</P>
<P>
   But, no, there is no thought of sticking full-time with the
BUY.com Tour and putting an end to this sort of dual citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much money out there,'' said Quigley. ``Just look
what happened to Mike Sposa.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Quigley, Sposa is an unheralded PGA Tour player who happens
to be waiting for a break. It came, in a small way, last week. As
the sixth alternate, he got into the field at Houston. Though he
had missed four cuts in six starts, Sposa proved grateful for
another chance and finished in a tie for seventh, good for an
$84,350 check.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see: $29,866 for finishing in a tie for second or $84,350
for finishing in a tie for seventh? Is it any wonder why Quigley
books those exit flights?
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when you're going to get it going,'' he said.
``All it takes is one good week, with the way the purses are.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another exit plan in the works this week, but Quigley
_ the fifth alternate for the Compaq Classic in New Orleans _ did
not get a chance to use it. So he stayed in Knoxville for his fifth
BUY.com start of the year and through two rounds (69-72) had
himself in position to threaten once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for my confidence,'' said Quigley, who is in
constant touch with his uncle. Last Sunday, Brett's chase for the
win in Florence was on the Golf Channel, while a short time later
Dana was on ESPN, in the hunt at the Bruno's Memorial Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Both Quigleys came up a bit short, but Dana vows that someday
things will change for Brett:
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll catch a break, and when he does, people will see how
good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going astray
</P>
<P>
   Things got a little sloppy in the final round of last Sunday's
Chick-Fil-A LPGA event in Stockbridge, Ga. Sophie Gustafson, who
would go on to win, slammed her tee shot out of bounds at the third
hole, and playing partner Laura Davies did the same at the fourth.
Michelle McGann, who was in position to win for the first time
since 1997, drove into the woods at the eighth, then punched out to
a steep bank, from where she swung and missed twice before settling
for a quadruple-bogey 8. Next to fall from contention was Kelly
Robbins, who won the first event of 1999 but has gone 31 since
without one. She drove into the water at the easy par-5 10th. All
of which left Gustafson to collect the top prize, though a serious
speech impediment led her to ask tournament host Nancy Lopez to
make the acceptance speech . . . Gary Nicklaus has requested a
sponsor's exemption into the upcoming Memorial. Officials usually
extend exemptions to the two Q-School graduates who have earned the
most money on the PGA Tour, which would be Matt Gogel (27th,
$535,482) and Nicklaus (48th, $355,260), but that could change. In
which case we are predicting that somehow, someway a sponsor's
exemption will fall into Nicklaus's lap . . . Congratulations to
Bob Lendzion, the longtime pro at Quechee, Vt., who used a 7-iron
to ace the 165-yard 14th hole during the final round of the Bruno's
Memorial Classic. It led to his best score (68) in 10 events on the
Senior PGA Tour this year, and he finished tied for 22d, his
highest finish since T-17 in the opening event of the year . . .
Earlier in the week, Tiger Woods said he would honor a strike by
the Screen Actors Guild and the American Federation of Television
and Radio Artists, so a Nike commercial had to be put on hold. But
unless the SAG and AFTRA put up a picket line at TPC at Las Colinas
in Irving, Texas, it's back to work in Woods's other pastime _ golf
_ as he ends a four-week vacation by playing in this week's GTE
Byron Nelson Classic. David Duval is also expected to return to
competition for the first time since his Masters heartache . . .
Busy week for World Golf Hall of Fame announcements. Judy Rankin
became the first LPGA Tour player voted in via the veterans
category, a move that was popular though it could be questioned;
Rankin won 26 times, but never a major. Donna Caponi, who probably
will be next to be voted in, counts four majors among her 24 wins.
On the men's side, no one was elected for induction _ not even Greg
Norman _ but Jack Burke Jr. was named in the veterans category, and
four others (Deane Beman, Sir Michael Bonallack, Neil Coles, and
John Jacobs) got the nod based on lifetime achievement. They will
join Beth Daniel and Juli Inkster at the induction ceremonies Nov.
20 in St. Augustine, Fla. . . . ``Byron Nelson: A Texas
Gentleman,'' a documentary on the life of the great champion, will
be on the Golf Channel at 9 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Graduate
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 33 years after his death, Francis Ouimet will be awarded
an honorary diploma from Brookline High School. It will be accepted
by his daughters, Jane Salvi and Barbara McLean, next Saturday at
Brookline Golf Course (Putterham Meadows). During the ceremonies, a
life-size statue of Ouimet and his caddie from the stunning 1913 US
Open, Eddie Lowery _ arguably the most famous likeness in golf
history _ will be dedicated. Lowery's daughter, Cynthia Wilcox,
also will be on hand, as will the sculptor, Bob Pack. The statue
originally was on display at The Country Club during last
September's Ryder Cup, but it has been donated to the town of
Brookline, which has chosen to relocate it to the course. Following
the ceremony, a scramble tournament will be held ($240 per
foursome), and interested players can call Brookline GC at
617-730-2078. In a few weeks, Ouimet will be inducted into BHS's
Hall of Fame . . . Olde Scotland Links in Bridgewater will provide
the challenge for some of the area's best professionals when the
New England PGA Pro-Pro Match Play Championship tees off Monday
morning. Kirk Hanefeld of the Ridge Club and Bob Green of Tedesco
CC will try to defend their title against 15 other teams. An
18-hole stroke-play qualifier will be held Monday, with the low
eight teams advancing to Tuesday's match-play format . . . With the
Cronin Memorial having wrapped up Saturday, the local amateur
spotlight swings to the MGA Four-ball Championship (May 15-16 at
Walpole CC), but right behind that comes the Norfolk County Classic
(May 20-21 at Presidents GC). It will be the 22d edition of the
NCC, and head professional Arthur Cicconi, as he has from the
outset, will oversee this popular attraction. Bill McInerney of
Charles River is the defending champion, and for players who did
not receive invitations, there will be a qualifying round May 17.
For information, call the pro shop at 617-328-3444, ext. 305 . . .
The Tucker Anthony Tournament is back for another season, and
MediaOne is televising this year's competition. Monday night at 8,
Cummaquid, led by 19-time club champ Barbara Fitzpatrick, takes on
Crumpin-Fox with Stacey Wolejko, recently crowned the MIAA girls'
champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
