<HEADER>
A8036 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-EWING-KNICKS-BOS &LR;      05-06 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-EWING-KNICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING STILL A PIVOTAL FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ He always wonders why, among his many roles,
the coach of the New York Knicks is also seen as the Defender of
Patrick Ewing. He doesn't avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be,'' said Jeff Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   But he also sees it as an unnecessary role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did (Larry) Bird need to be defended in Boston? Patrick needs
no defending, but that's the thought process here,'' Van Gundy said
as he prepared the Knicks for Sunday's opener against the Miami
Heat in the Eastern Conference semifinals. ``I've never sensed that
a guy who has done so much _ clearly, he's the best Knick player of
all time _ and still plays at such a high level needs to be
defended. So, I always wonder, why is it that people say I'm his
biggest defender? Why does he need defending? It's an amazing
phenomenon in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing will be front and center and, barring injury, front and
center for the rest of the Knicks' run in the playoffs. After three
years of battling wrist, rib, knee, and Achilles' tendon injuries,
the 37-year-old Knick flagship is as healthy as he has been in
years.
</P>
<P>
   He did miss the first 20 games of this season, allowing his
Achilles' tendinitis to heal. He returned and started the final 62
games, leading the Knicks in rebounding and shot-blocking. Over the
past three seasons, Ewing has missed 88 games because of injuries,
and the Knicks are a very revealing 46-42 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby might think that the Madison Square Garden fans are
tired of seeing the old dump-it-in-to-Patrick Knicks and prefer
instead the freewheeling style of Latrell Sprewell. That might be
what the fans want. That's most definitely not what Van Gundy
wants; nor does he suspect that he is alone in that line of
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 20 games he missed, we were 11-9,'' the coach said.
``We were an average team without Patrick. I think the guys
understand fully, even though they may have gotten more minutes and
more shots in those games, that we still were 11-9. They understand
that this guy is the most important player to our success.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is not the same player he was 10 years ago or even five
years ago. His shattered right wrist has mended, but has robbed him
of his position as the best jump-shooting big man in the game.
Defensively, he is not as agile laterally or getting back on
transition.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not lost anything where it matters the most: the
ability to compete at an elite level with the inner strength and
confidence that he is not only capable but indispensable. He
believes that. He really does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into the league 14 years ago with the Knicks and he was
the hardest-working player on our team then,'' said Knicks
assistant Brendan Malone. ``He still is the hardest-working player
on our team now. And he has not stopped believing that he is an
outstanding player. I think that's what carries him: his work ethic
and his tremendous belief in himself as a player. Everyone wants to
dismiss him and send him out to pasture. He refuses to listen to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's good that he does. There's been a lot of it, especially
with the arrival of the young pups and the inevitable deterioration
of Ewing's game to age and injuries. But Van Gundy is right.
Without him, they're Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always going to think what they want to think,
believe what they want to believe,'' Ewing said. ``I think I'm
still a great player, but I feel sometimes if I hadn't gotten hurt,
if I hadn't hurt my wrist . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``My Achilles' healed perfectly, my wrist will never be the
same. That was an adjustment. It still is an adjustment. But apart
from being hurt, I've accomplished a lot and I'm still playing
great. I'm surprising all of y'all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, never regarded as a go-to guy for reporters, even had
some fun with the media last week (which, with the league's
outright capitulation to television, came and went without a single
Knicks game). While Van Gundy was saying that Alonzo Mourning was
the best player this season in the Eastern Conference ``hands
down,'' Ewing was wondering how that could be.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Mourning was the best in the East, Ewing
smiled and said, ``Yeah.'' Then there was a long,
nine-months-pregnant pause. ``Next to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The tabloids, predictably, went nuts. ``Ewing: I'm Still The
Man,'' said the Daily News. The Post said, simply, ``I'm The Best:
Patrick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When he says he's the greatest, or believes he's a great
player, he really believes it,'' Malone said. ``It's not for
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing conceded that Mourning might disagree, but that was OK
with him. Neither has a championship ring and only Ewing has tasted
the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even talk about it,'' Ewing said. ``We don't need to
talk about that. He knows he's great, I know I'm great. The
objective is to go out and win.''
</P>
<P>
   He has put last year behind him. He has no choice. It tortured
him to watch the Knicks go up against the Spurs without a decent
big man. He doesn't know if he might have made a difference, but he
does know he can't undo what's already done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new series, a new year,'' he sniffed. ``Can't worry
about that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Spurs already are gone. The Knicks are getting
ready for what has become their annual tong war with Miami. The
Knicks, no longer the trendy underdog of last year, figure they
have as much of a chance as anyone of coming out of the East.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing also figures there's a lot of basketball left in his
banged-up body. He's under contract for next year and never has
remotely hinted when he might retire. Just this week, his former
coach, Pat Riley, now leading the hated Heat, said Ewing had aged
as well as any big man he has ever seen. Riley, in case you may
have forgotten, had Kareem Abdul-Jabbar until the age of 42.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, and even for years before that, Abdul-Jabbar was
trying to be what Ewing still can be: a factor and a force. He has
had a week to practice, prepare, and rest for the next round. That
might not be good news for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' he said. ``I feel pretty good. I'm healthy _
healthy as I'm going to be. I plan on going through the series
playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, just maybe, Van Gundy can drop the one role he never
really has come to understand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
