<HEADLINE>
THE DEPUTY STUMBLES TO A 14TH-PLACE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Possibly the most puzzling performance in the
Kentucky Derby yesterday came from The Deputy. The second favorite
in the wagering at 9-2, The Deputy finished 14th.
</P>
<P>
   He was ninth after the opening quarter-mile, but he never got
any closer. In his only other meeting with Fusaichi Pegasus, The
Deputy lost by less than a length in the San Felipe Stakes seven
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did his best,'' said Jenine Sahadi, who trains The Deputy.
``Chris \RMcCarron, the jockey\S, said that he didn't have any real
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't fire. Chris said he seemed to be struggling,
but we don't know why just yet. He looks like he came out of the
race OK.'' \Nsubheds:St. Julien's trip Marlon St. Julien, the first
African-American to ride in the Kentucky Derby in 79 years,
finished seventh aboard Curule. Coupled in the wagering with the
Godolphin-owned China Visit, Curule was a longshot at 23 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien won the first race at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie
and was the track's leading rider the first two years until he
moved to the Kentucky circuit last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great trip,'' St. Julien said. ``He broke well, and
we were able to drop in and save ground. He ran better than
expected, and the Godolphin people seem pleased. That makes me
happy.'' \Nsubheds:Derby crowd The crowd of 153,204 people marked
the second-largest crowd in Churchill history. The record
attendance stands at 163,628 for the centennial running of the race
in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   A record total of $65 million was wagered at Churchill and
off-track locations. It's a preliminary number because some
off-track locations had not reported immediately after the race.
\Nsubheds:Captain Steve injury Trainers for Captain Steve, who
finished eighth after getting pinched back behind More Than Ready
when Wheelaway veered in sharply in midstretch, discovered a slight
injury to the horse when he returned to the barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got slammed pretty good,'' said April Mayberry, who assists
Captain Steve trainer Bob Baffert at Churchill. ``He came out of
the race with a grabbed quarter behind, but other than that he's
OK. He cooled out fine.''
</P>
<P>
   A grabbed quarter on a horse is when the skin around the hoof is
cut by another hoof. It's unclear when the injury occurred.
\Nsubheds:Dubai try For the second consecutive year, Sheikh
Mohammed al Maktoum has come away from the Derby without a victory
despite spending millions. The Sheikh, the crown prince of Dubai
emirate in the United Arab Emirates, had to settle for a
sixth-place finish from China Visit and seventh from Curule.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the three-sixteenths pole, I really thought we were going
to win,'' China Visit jockey Frankie Dettori said. ``He was in the
bridle. But he ran out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep getting closer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sheikh spent a reported $4 million on Worldly Manner prior
to the colt's seventh-place Derby finish last year. He spent
another $5 million on Chief Seattle after that colt finished second
in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile last year, but he wasn't training
properly and did not make the trip from Dubai. \Nsubheds:Hal's Hope
ends Hal's Hope, trained by 88-year-old Harold Rose, battled Trippi
through the opening three-quarters of a mile before tiring and
finishing 16th.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw those fractions, I got nervous,'' said Rose, who
endured quadruple bypass heart surgery last year. ``You just can't
go that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening three quarters went in 1:09 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we go back home with him,'' Rose said. ``I don't know
what's next now.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly Danny Pish, a trainer based at
Lone Star Park, was represented by First Attraction in the $121,000
WHAS-11 Stakes for 2-year-olds on the Derby undercard. She is the
winner of the Jean Lafitte Futurity, but she was the only filly in
the field of the WHAS, and she finished last among 12. There's talk
that Heritage Of Gold might be the best older mare in the country
after she won Friday's Grade III Louisville Breeders' Cup Handicap
over a field that included Keeper Hill and Silverbulletday.
Heritage Of Gold was the Horse of the Meet last year at Lone Star.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
