<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT MAPLE LEAFS, 4-3 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A brilliant goal by Patrik Elias, another by John
Madden and two marvelous passes by Scott Gomez for goals by Sergei
Nemchinov and Vladimir Malakhov led the New Jersey Devils to a 4-3
triumph over the Toronto Maple Leafs Saturday night at the Air
Canada Center.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Devils a 3-2 lead in the four-of-seven-game
Eastern Conference semifinal series. The Devils can advance to the
conference finals when play resumes Monday night at Continental
Arena in New Jersey for the sixth game of a series dominated for
the most part by the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto took the lead twice on goals by Garry Valk and Jeff
Farkas, but the Devils rallied with three unanswered goals before
Sergei Berezin narrowed the gap for the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   A melee erupted at the end of the game, after the Devils had
played the final seconds while killing a penalty to their captain,
Scott Stevens. The players from both teams stood in front of their
benches and barked at each other before the officials escorted them
to the tunnels for the dressing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Devils coach Larry Robinson came up with the right matchups for
the most part. The Devils took 32 shots at Curtis Joseph, while
Martin Brodeur, playing on his 28th birthday, faced 25 shots to
earn his seventh victory in these playoffs and the 41st of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson surprised no one by bringing Sergei Brylin back into
the lineup in place of Steve Kelly. Brylin had missed six games, or
since the second game of the opening-round series against Florida,
with a bruised right knee. He simply returned to his place at left
wing with Bobby Holik his center and Randy McKay the other wing.
</P>
<P>
   Brylin was the Devils' best forward last year when they were
eliminated by the Pittsburgh Penguins. He has always raised his
level of intensity in the playoffs, and his superb efforts were
noticed in the days when Jacques Lemaire was the head coach and
Robinson was his assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Brylin was a spark plug in the Florida series,
which the Devils swept. He not only scored a goal in that series,
but he also played effectively against Pavel Bure, the league's
leading goal scorer during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Brylin's role Saturday night was to be on the ice as much as
possible against the Maple Leafs' top forwards, but he did not get
that many chances because Toronto coach Pat Quinn had the last
change and avoided that matchup.
</P>
<P>
   For the biggest part of the game, Quinn sent out his top line of
Mats Sundin centering for right wing Steve Thomas and left wing
Jonas Hoglund when the line of Madden centering for Jay Pandolfo on
the left and Claude Lemieux on the right was on the ice for the
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Quinn also matched the Sundin line against the
Devils' top line of Jason Arnott centering for Elias on the left
and Petr Sykora on the right.
</P>
<P>
   It was the speedy and elusive Elias who made the play of the
night with 3 minutes 19 seconds left in the first period, matching
Valk's goal that opened the scoring nine minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a pass from Scott Niedermayer in the neutral zone down
the right flank, Elias entered Toronto's zone with plenty of speed.
Just when it looked as if Darcy Tucker had him figured in the right
circle, Elias dropped his left shoulder to get behind Tucker, and
put the puck in the upper far corner of the net from a sharp angle
at a time when he appeared to be headed around the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Elias' goal, his third in the playoffs, came on the second power
play of the game for the Devils, who could have fallen behind by
more than a goal after Valk's redirection from the slot of
Aleksandr Karpovtsev's shot from the right circle beat Brodeur over
the glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs pressed for several minutes after Valk's goal,
but they failed to convert their opportunities, with Thomas and
Hoglund missing from good position on the left.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas regained the lead for the Maple Leafs with his first
National Hockey League goal, 2:19 into the middle period, when he
took advantage of Arnott's failure to clear a rebound from a shot
by Berezin and beat Brodeur from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   The next goal, with 4:01 to play in the second, came on a
mistake by Toronto defenseman Greg Andrusak, who allowed Gomez to
pass to Nemchinov in the slot. With plenty of time and space,
Nemchinov beat Joseph with a low shot for his third goal of the
playoffs to send the teams into the third period tied at two goals
apiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
