<HEADLINE>
SHIELDS TAKES THE HEAT AFTER SHARKS' DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sharks coach Darryl Sutter directed his harshest criticism of
the playoffs toward goalie Steve Shields after the Stars' 5-4
victory in Friday's Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Shields served up the Stars' first shot of the game from Mike
Modano 68 seconds in and never allowed his teammates a chance for
momentum. They resiliently erased four Dallas leads, but the
longest Shields could ever keep the game tied was 4 minutes, 1
second.
</P>
<P>
   He will try to redeem himself tonight, much the way he did last
series against St. Louis, in do-or-die Game 5 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along,'' Sutter said, ``if we're going to beat
Dallas, we need great goaltending. And for us, that's ...''
</P>
<P>
   Sutter stopped and motioned with his hands as if he were
flipping a coin.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter used ``bad goal'' to describe Sergei Zubov's short-handed
goal that put the Stars ahead, 3-2, just 56 seconds into the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost set your watch to a Shields meltdown. It has been
the same pattern throughout the playoffs. After a couple of
confident outings, inexplicable collapses follow. He has allowed 26
goals in six playoff losses and seven goals in five playoff
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 ran at a frenetic pace, with both teams' forwards flying
and launching scoring chances. Shields was not responsible for all
five goals, but, to quote him from after his Game 1 misadventure,
he wasn't ``the difference maker.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Sharks are to get back in this series, Shields _ whose
2-0 record in Game 7s can't be overlooked _ will have to be the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have big saves,'' Sutter said.
 &LR; subheds:Marchment sidelined Sharks defenseman Bryan Marchment did
not return to the game after pulling a groin muscle during the
first period Friday. He was injured while the Sharks were on the
power play, and the injury indirectly led to Guy Carbonneau's
short-handed goal. It also left the Sharks' defense short-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had a huge impact on our game,'' Sutter said. ``It gets
us away from our matchups.''
</P>
<P>
   If Marchment is sidelined for Game 5, Andy Sutton and rookie
Scott Hannan are available. Neither has seen playoff action. Sutton
played 40 games in the regular season, and Hannan played 30.
 &LR; subheds:Nolan a leader Owen Nolan's unassisted short-handed goal
at 7:48 of the second period Friday, tying the game at 3-3, tied
him for the lead in NHL playoff goals with eight. He is tied with
Pittsburgh Penguins players Jaromir Jagr and Martin Straka.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan and Mike Ricci, who has five playoff goals, have half of
the team's 26 goals.  &LR; subheds:Briefly The Sharks have three
power-play goals in the series. Two are by virtue of five-on-three
advantages. Otherwise, the lethargic Sharks' power play is
1-for-23.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks are 5-4 all-time in elimination games.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jeff Norton called Friday's wild 5-4 contest ``the
craziest playoff game I've ever been involved in.'' He has played
in 55 career playoff games.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
