<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KUPCHAK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS INTERESTED IN LAKERS' KUPCHAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The New Jersey Nets, searching for a new director
of basketball operations, are pursuing Los Angeles Lakers general
manager Mitch Kupchak, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Nets officials recently asked for permission to speak with
Kupchak about the opening, and the team granted their request,
Lakers spokesman John Black confirmed. Kupchak wasn't immediately
available for comment, and Black declined to say if the parties had
spoken yet.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak, a member of the Lakers' front office since 1986, was
pursued by the Denver Nuggets two years ago. Shortly thereafter,
the Lakers gave him a long-term contract extension, putting Kupchak
in position to eventually succeed executive vice president Jerry
West as head of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   That deal still has at least three years remaining, but the
Lakers' decision to grant the Nets permission to speak with Kupchak
means they probably would let him out of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak is a coveted basketball mind around the league, and he
has made no secret of wanting to hold the top personnel position
with an NBA club. It has been assumed he would wait for that
opportunity here, once West retires.
</P>
<P>
   According to The New York Times, the Nets are also interested in
Lenny Wilkens, John Thompson and Isiah Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak, who turns 46 later this month, has East Coast roots. He
was born in Hicksville, N.Y. and was a standout at Brentwood High
on Long Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0272 </DOCNO>
