<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8043 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     05-06 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 14)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; INCUBUS &LR;  By Ann Arensberg. Ballantine, $14. In this postmodern
Gothic novel, wilted crops, bizarre weather, monstrous births among
farm animals and especially the arrival of a bodiless force that
ravishes women become metaphors for the sexual and social problems
of a small Maine town. ``Arensberg is particularly good at
depicting the itch and ache of human relations,'' Janet Burroway
wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIND OF THE RAVEN: Investigations and Adventures With
Wolf-Birds &LR;  By Bernd Heinrich. Cliff Street/HarperPerennial, $13. A
biologist examines the social relationships and mischievous
behavior of the common raven to determine whether these uncannily
intelligent birds learn tricks by chance or consciously analyze
problems. ``The mind of Bernd Heinrich is a big, antic thing, like
a raven, and meant to live outdoors,'' David Quammen wrote in The
New York Times Book Review in 1999. ``He has a rare ability to
embed dense scientific explications within graceful, light-footed
nature writing.''
</P>
<P>
   According to  &UR; LIVING ON THE WIND: Across the Hemisphere With
Migratory Birds &LR; , by Scott Weidensaul (North Point/Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $15), an estimated 5 billion birds migrate throughout the
Western Hemisphere every year, often in journeys of amazing length
and duration. Last year one critic called this account of migratory
habits ``fulfilling for birders and nonbirders alike.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERRA INFIRMA: A Memoir of My Mother's Life in Mine &LR;  By Rodger
Kamenetz. Schocken, $11. The author's unsparing meditation on his
mother, who died at 54 from cancer, examines the inspiring yet
destructive force of her love, and probes the mystery of one
woman's jagged, willful character and the way it imprints itself on
her son. Last year in The New York Times, Richard Bernstein called
this ``an impressively intelligent, maturely perceptive and
learned'' book that is both ``strange and moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; A GOOD ENOUGH DAUGHTER: A
Memoir &LR; , by Alix Kates Shulman ($13), in which an independent New
York writer returns to suburban Cleveland to care for her aging
parents and discovers their vigorous inner lives, including her
mother's impassioned pursuit of a literary career in later life.
``Her portrayal is refreshingly upbeat, infused with insight,
affection and respect,'' Leslie Chess Feller wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRACE &LR; , by Robert Ward (St. Martin's Griffin, $12.95), is a
fictional account of the author's complex relationship with his
grandmother, with whom he spent part of his childhood in postwar
Baltimore, and her life as a social activist. The result is ``a
book-length valentine written for and about a woman he clearly
adored,'' Ruth Coughlin said in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; WHITE OLEANDER &LR; , by Janet Fitch (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
$13.95), a lovely but poisonous plant is a metaphor for motherhood.
This novel follows the harrowing coming of age of a girl who is
forced into the California foster-care system after her mother, a
footloose poet, is imprisoned for the murder of a lover. Fitch's
``startlingly apt language relates a story that is both intelligent
and gripping,'' Gretchen Holbrook Gerzina wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARIS TRANCE: A Romance &LR;  By Geoff Dyer. North Point/Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux, $13. Luke Barnes is a young Englishman who travels
to Paris to write a novel, only to hook up with a beautiful Serbian
student and another couple, and to discover how contentment can
curdle into inertia and failure. ``I can't think of a recent novel
that better describes the scarily charged beginning of a love
affair,'' Daniel Mendelsohn wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE &LR;  By Thomas L. Friedman. Anchor,
$15. A columnist for The New York Times deploys a torrent of
anecdotes and vignettes to probe the causes and effects of
globalization and the transforming power of technology. ``Friedman
knows how to cut through the arcana of high tech and high finance
with vivid images,'' Josef Joffe wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A VIEW FROM THE MANGROVE &LR;  By Antonio Bentez-Rojo. University of
Massachusetts, $16.95. The final work of a trilogy by the
expatriate Cuban author exploring the history of the Caribbean is a
collection of tales of slave trading, invasions, murders and other
events in which the characters exist only in extremis. ``His
stories are dense with disaster and rich in description,'' Barbara
Fisher wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T LOOK BACK: Satchel Paige in the Shadows of Baseball &LR;  By
Mark Ribowsky. Da Capo, $16. According to this biography, Leroy
Robert ``Satchel'' Paige, the most famous player in the history of
the Negro leagues, was both a brilliant pitcher and a shrewd
self-promoter. The author ``has done enough digging into Paige's
life and career to separate the historical record from the
pitcher's own gauzy, entertaining recollections,'' Warren Goldstein
said in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE POND &LR;  By Ha Jin. Vintage International, $11. In this
first novel by the winner of last year's National Book Award, a
factory worker in a Chinese village unleashes satirical cartoons
and clever letters of complaint in a crusade against his superiors.
The result is a ``naughty, lusty, raucously entertaining''
screwball comedy, Mei Chin wrote in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0273 </DOCNO>
