<HEADER>
A8060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIAMI-DEMONSTRATE-1ST     05-06 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-DEMONSTRATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA REBUTTAL OF PROTESTS OVER CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert new 3rd graf; rewrites start of 4th graf; adds
sentence to story's final quote.)   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Responding to the numerous protests Cuban-Americans here
have mounted since federal agents seized custody of Elian Gonzalez
last month, thousands of residents turned out for a demonstration
of their own Saturday, lining sidewalks and filling vacant lots in
southern Dade County to support the American government.
</P>
<P>
   The counterdemonstrators, waving American flags and some
Confederate battle flags, and carrying signs reading ``Reno for
president,'' said they had been angered and insulted by the way
Cuban-Americans had protested the seizure of Elian, 6, from his
Miami relatives' home in Little Havana two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   While the sometimes heated protests that greeted the
government's action took place largely in Miami proper, Saturday's
demonstrations occurred in a conservative area of Miami-Dade County
that is home to farms, factories and thousands of whites who feel
little affinity for the city. About 20 people displayed Confederate
battle flags, but the demonstration also attracted more than 100
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters said they had cringed while watching
Cuban-Americans burn the American flag and parade it upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen the utmost disrespect for this country in the last
couple of weeks,'' said Robert Milton, a construction worker from
Homestead, a suburb south of Miami. ``It's like these people have
forgotten which country took them in and gave them freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Iget sick to my stomach,'' he added. ``Someone needs to tell
them to show some respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Saturday's demonstrators, whom the authorities put at
more than 5,000, said they were still more angered by the attitudes
of local leaders who openly supported Elian's relatives in Miami.
The family had defied the federal government by refusing to turn
over the boy after his father asked that he be returned to his
custody in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   They also said they were disgusted at the public squabbling
between city officials.
</P>
<P>
   After the federal raid, Mayor Joe Carollo of Miami denounced the
police chief for not telling him in advance about the raid and
fired City Manager Donald Warshaw.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the police chief, William O'Brien, resigned, saying
he wanted no part of Carollo's administration. Warshaw remains in
office, after a judge temporarily halted his dismissal.
Demonstrators asserted Saturday in this conservative part of the
county that city and county officials had turned their backs on the
rest of the community. They carried signs with slogans like ``Crazy
Joe must go'' and ``I want a new county.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of what is happening in this city,'' said Kristen
Markovich, 31, of Perrine, another suburb south of Miami. ``The
politicians are making fools of themselves and the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Hartwell, an organizer of the demonstration, said the
protesters' message had been effective, because of the strong
turnout. ``Miami was a one-sided city until now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators also accused Cuban-Americans of intimidating
anyone who did not share their hatred of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you disagree with the majority, you fear for your life, for
your family and for your job,'' said Marlene Kay, of Homestead.
``Freedom of speech doesn't apply in Miami-Dade County anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-00 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000506.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-06 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HARVARD-LABOR-RALLY-1     05-06 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-LABOR-RALLY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT RALLY FOR LOW-PAID WORKERS, PROTESTERS REJECT HARVARD PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert number of workers in 3rd graf.)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Three days after Harvard University released
a long-awaited report on how it would improve compensation for its
lowest-paid employees, several hundred students and their
supporters, including the actors Matt Damon and Ben Affleck,
denounced the report Saturday at a rally on campus.
</P>
<P>
   It was a noisy sign that despite what the administration called
a ``very progressive'' program of education and benefits that would
cost the university over $2.3 million per year, the protesters were
not backing down from their demand for a $10.25 per hour minimum
wage for all university employees.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has centered on the university's more than 3,000
part-time, temporary and contract workers, some of whom make about
$6.50 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from the granite steps of Harvard's columned Littauer
Hall, in front of a banner that read ``Workers can't eat
prestige,'' Affleck and Damon told the crowd about growing up in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   They said the disparity between the wealth of Harvard's
endowment and the pay of its blue-collar workers inspired them to
write the 1997 film ``Good Will Hunting.'' In the film, Damon
played a janitor at another distinguished Cambridge school, the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The two saw both sides of university life. Damon, who attended
Harvard, said he was embarrassed by his alma mater's pay rates.
Affleck said his stepmother, who scrubbed toilets for $5.75 an
hour, and his father, who handed out vacuums and brooms, were part
of the ``low-skilled'' work force at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was often treated brusquely and with little respect,
although not by the students,'' Affleck said of his father.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``This is honest work, and there is honor in doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Students began organized demonstrations here in 1998, calling
for a ``living wage'' for the university's workers. Other
universities, including Stanford, Brown and Johns Hopkins, have
started similar campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In response, a faculty committee spent 15 months studying
Harvard's labor policies, finally deciding against raising
take-home pay.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in a proposal released on Wednesday, the committee
recommended that the university give health benefits to employees
who work at least 16 hours a week (the previous threshold was 20
hours) and that Harvard contract only with companies that subsidize
health care for their workers. It also called for more continuing
education and worker training programs.
</P>
<P>
   The committee argued that pay scales are negotiated through
employee unions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
