<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENTION POST STIRS RE
 SENTMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY KRIS MAYES 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If John McCain has his way, the leader of the Arizona delegation
to the Republican National Convention will be his companion on the
cam paign trail, Cindy McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator's efforts to install his wife at the head of the
delegation have rekindled anger among support ers of Gov. Jane
Hull, who last month agreed to give up the gover nor's traditional
prerogative of serv ing as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total snub to Jane, and it's a distraction from what we
ought to be doing right now, which is talking about the issues that
are going to help us beat Al Gore,'' said state Sen. Scott
Bundgaard, R-Phoenix. ``We shouldn't be engaging in this petty
bickering and infighting.''
</P>
<P>
   So much bad blood has been spilled in the battle for the
chairmanship of the convention delegation that last week,
negotiations between the two sides broke down.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership question will be decided next Saturday in
Scottsdale by delegates to state GOP conven tion.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy, who had previously made a point of avoiding involvement
in state and national politics, is step ping into the spotlight in
her hus band's behalf. She has asked to address the state
convention because the senator will be giving a com mencement
speech out of state, according to state party officials.
</P>
<P>
   John's aides have made it clear behind the scenes that the
decision that his wife lead the state's GOP activists into the
national convention in Philadelphia is not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull backers see an effort to punish Hull for supporting
Texas Gov. George W. Bush during the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Arizona GOP, Mike Minnaugh, said that
tapping Cindy to head the delegation is a good compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, (John) McCain won the state, and who knows
whether he will run again,'' Minnaugh said. ``I think it's another
opportunity to show some additional respect for Senator McCain and
what he has done for the state and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hull withdrew from the race to lead the delegation
after McCain, on national television, laughingly dismissed the idea
of her filling the post. Nevertheless, friends say, Hull had hoped
to have some say in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the struggle over the leadership of the state
delegation has mirrored the national negotiations between Bush and
McCain over a Tuesday ``summit'' between the two men in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In a week and a half of negotiations between McCain and Hull's
staffs, no detail has been too obscure to raise hackles. McCain was
reportedly angered after a handful of Hull loyalists applied to be
delegates. And Hull was thrown off guard by the move to place Cindy
McCain at the helm of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, as it became clear that John McCain would not budge
on having his wife lead the delegation, the negotiations trailed
off. A sched uled meeting Thursday between the two sides was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Bundgaard blames McCain for cast ing a shadow over the efforts
to craft a slate of delegates and wonders whether a plot is brewing
to keep Bush supporters out of the conven tion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, they want a lot of McCain insiders, people
that are predictable and unwavering support ers for McCain, and it
gives every appearance that Senator McCain is trying to wage some
sort of floor fight or challenge to Governor Bush for the
nomination,'' Bundgaard said.
</P>
<P>
   According to several sources close to both Hull and McCain, the
Bush campaign has been monitoring the developments from Austin,
hopeful that the bad blood will not poison relations at the
national level.
</P>
<P>
   Mal Barrett, a GOP party official from Prescott who is running
to be a delegate, said the matter of who will make up the
delegation will not be a bitter fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be a floor fight or some kind of
acrimonious thing,'' Barrett said of making Cindy McCain the
chairman. ``If the dele gates don't want to do it, they won't do
it, but I don't think it's going to be a nasty thing, by any
means.`
</P>
<P>
   Competition for a seat in the delega tion has not turned ugly,
but has become as intense as the last few moments of a furious game
of musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 200 party activists, elected officials and party leaders
have applied for the 30 available slots. Compounding the problem is
the fact that the delegation has shrunk from its 1996 size of 39
delegation, a reduction that occurred under Re publican National
Committee rules after the state voted for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, party leaders are having to make tough choices as
they put together the recommended slate to present to the state
convention. They want ethnic diversity, but they also need to
reward the party activists, who most of the year toil in relative
obscurity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
