<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-SANJOSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SHAKE UP EARTHQUAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ There was good reason for the Revolution to
celebrate Saturday night. They scored more than one goal in
regulation for the first time since April 1 and they took over
first place in the Eastern Division with a 2-1 win over San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have 10 points in eight games and are leading the
division for the first time at this point in the season. Even more
significantly, the Revolution seem to have uncovered a midfield
choreographer in Bolivian Mauricio Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos and Wolde Harris combined for both goals. Ramos scored
first, capitalizing on an unforced San Jose turnover, in the 55th
minute, then played a give-and-go with Harris, who converted in the
59th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution survived an Abdul Thompson Conteh counter in the
72d minute and a disallowed goal by Ian Russell, which appeared to
have beaten the offside trap four minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some good combination play and we played a lot faster
than in past games,'' Harris said. ``We kept possession, and we
kept possession going forward, so we kept the attack flowing. We
took a little risk because we were attacking, but it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos took command just behind strikers Harris and Johnny
Torres, with Leonel Alvarez and Carlos Parra in support. Alvarez
(left foot tendon strain) departed in the second half, but Parra,
replacing John Harkes (calf) was a steadying influence in his first
start. The Revolution remained active and sufficiently composed
with a young lineup in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some of the same problems in the first half,'' coach
Fernando Clavijo said. ``We kept possession and we created chances,
but we were not able to finish. In the second half, we were able to
get a couple of goals and we missed a couple more. They have
experienced players and they put pressure on us, we lost Leo
(Alvarez) and Carlos Parra was tired, but we managed to keep them
out of the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   A Ryan Tinsley giveaway led to Ramos converting an inspired
drive into the far upper corner of the net in the 55th minute, four
minutes after Khodadad Azizi hit the crossbar for San Jose.
Tinsley, under no apparent pressure, scuffed a pass to Harris in
the Revolution attacking zone. Harris laid off a perfectly-weighted
ball for Ramos, running into the penalty area, to convert his first
goal for the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, Harris took on three defenders in the
penalty area, played a give-and-go with Ramos, and finished a
wide-open shot.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez appeared on the verge of increasing the lead, carrying
to the end line on the edge of the goal area, but his foot caught
in the turf and he was replaced by Shaker Asad in the 67th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The game opened in the second half, allowing the Revolution's
Asad, Ramos, and William Sunsing to display their skill, but also
left the Revolution in jeopardy. In the 88th minute, Jeff Causey
blocked a point-blank drive by Wojtek Krakowiak. And the match
ended in bizarre fashion as referee Rich Grady blew the final
whistle as Sunsing avoided Cannon and was about to go in alone on
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Earthquakes struggled to find an offensive rhythm in the
first half, but were secure at the back thanks to the strength of
John Doyle and the elegance of Mauricio Wright. But Azizi had
little impact until midway in the second half, when he moved to
midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Azizi launched a perfect pass to Conteh, who outmaneuvered Brian
Dunseth and lofted a shot over Causey to cut the deficit to 2-1.
Russell appeared to beat the offside trap, finishing a pass from
Wright, but the goal was disallowed in the 76th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone makes mistakes, including referees and linesmen,''
San Jose coach Lothar Osiander said. ``New England deserved to win
over the 90 minutes. And those things are supposed to balance out
by the end of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
